urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.146#or you yourself, son of Peleus, most terrifying of all men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.147#to reconcile by accomplishing sacrifice the archer.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.148#Then looking darkly at him Achilleus of the swift feet spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.149#'O wrapped in shamelessness, with your mind forever on profit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.150#how shall any one of the Achaians readily obey you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.151#either to go on a journey or to fight men strongly in battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.152#I for my part did not come here for the sake of the Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.153#spearmen to fight against them, since to me they have done nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.154#Never yet have they driven away my cattle or my horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.155#never in Phthia where the soil is rich and men grow great did they
