urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.169#Now I am returning to Phthia, since it is much better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.170#to go home again with my curved ships, and I am minded no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.171#to stay here dishonoured and pile up your wealth and your luxury.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.172#Then answered him in turn the lord of men Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.173#'Run away by all means if your heart drives you. I will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.174#entreat you to stay here for my sake. There are others with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.175#who will do me honour, and above all Zeus of the counsels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.176#To me you are the most hateful of all the kings whom the gods love.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.177#Forever quarrelling is dear to your heart, and wars and battles;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.178#and if you are very strong indeed, that is a god's gift.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.179#Go home then with your own ships and your own companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.180#be king over the Myrmidons. I care nothing about you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.181#I take no account of your anger. But here is my threat to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.182#Even as Phoibos Apollo is taking away my Chryseis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.183#I shall convey her back in my own ship, with my own
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.184#followers; but I shall take the fair-cheeked Briseis,
