urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.186#how much greater I am than you, and another man may shrink back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.187#from likening himself to me and contending against me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.188#So he spoke. And the anger came on Peleus' son, and within
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.189#his shaggy breast the heart was divided two ways, pondering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.190#whether to draw from beside his thigh the sharp sword, driving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.191#away all those who stood between and kill the son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.192#or else to check the spleen within and keep down his anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.193#Now as he weighed in mind and spirit these two courses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.194#and was drawing from its scabbard the great sword, Athene descended
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.195#from the sky. For Hera the goddess of the white arms sent her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.196#who loved both men equally in her heart and cared for them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.197#The goddess standing behind Peleus' son caught him by the fair hair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.198#appearing to him only, for no man of the others saw her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.199#Achilleus in amazement turned about, and straightway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.200#knew Pallas Athene and the terrible eyes shining.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.201#He uttered winged words and addressed her: 'Why have you come now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.202#o child of Zeus of the aegis, once more? Is it that you may see
