urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.223#But Peleus' son once again in words of derision
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.224#spoke to Atreides, and did not yet let go of his anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.225#'You wine sack, with a dog's eyes, with a deer's heart. Never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.226#once have you taken courage in your heart to arm with your people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.227#for battle, or go into ambuscade with the best of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.228#No, for in such things you see death. Far better to your mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.229#is it, all along the widespread host of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.230#to take away the gifts of any man who speaks up against you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.231#King who feed on your people, since you rule nonentities;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.232#otherwise, son of Atreus, this were your last outrage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.233#But I will tell you this and swear a great oath upon it:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.234#in the name of this sceptre, which never again will bear leaf nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:1.235#branch, now that it has left behind the cut stump in the mountains,
