urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.333#So he spoke, and the Argives shouted aloud, and about them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.334#the ships echoed terribly to the roaring Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.335#as they cried out applause to the word of godlike Odysseus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.336#Now among them spoke the Gerenian horseman, Nestor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.337#'Oh, for shame! You are like children when you hold assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.338#infant children, to whom the works of war mean nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.339#Where then shall our covenants go, and the oaths we have taken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.340#Let counsels and the meditations of men be given to the flames then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.341#with the unmixed wine poured and the right hands we trusted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.342#We do our fighting with words only, and can discover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.343#no remedy, though we have stayed here a long time. Son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.344#do you still as before hold fast to your counsel unshaken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.345#and be the leader of the Argives through the strong encounters;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.346#let them go perish, these one or two, who think apart from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.347#the rest of the Achaians, since there will be no use in them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.348#until they get back again to Argos without ever learning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.349#whether Zeus of the aegis promises false or truly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.350#For I say to you, the son of all-powerful Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.351#promised, on that day when we went in our fast-running vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.352#we of Argos, carrying blood and death to the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.353#He flashed lightning on our right, showing signs of favour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.354#Therefore let no man be urgent to take the way homeward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.355#until after he has lain in bed with the wife of a Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.356#to avenge Helen's longing to escape and her lamentations.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.357#But if any man is terribly desirous to go home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.358#let him only lay his hands on his well-benched black ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.359#that before all others he may win death and destruction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.360#Come, my lord: yourself be careful, and listen to another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.361#This shall not be a word to be cast away that I tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.362#Set your men in order by tribes, by clans, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.363#and let clan go in support of clan, let tribe support tribe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.364#If you do it this way, and the Achaians obey you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.365#you will see which of your leaders is bad, and which of your people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.366#and which also is brave, since they will fight in divisions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.367#and might learn also whether by magic you fail to take this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.368#city, or by men's cowardice and ignorance of warfare.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.369#Then in answer again spoke powerful Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.370#'Once again, old sir, you surpass the sons of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.371#in debate. O father Zeus, Athene, Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.372#would that among the Achaians I had ten such counsellors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.373#Then perhaps the city of lord Priam would be bent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.374#underneath our hands, captured and sacked. But instead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.375#Zeus of the aegis, son of Kronos, has given me bitterness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.376#who drives me into unprofitable abuse and quarrels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.377#For I and Achilleus fought together for a girl's sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.378#in words' violent encounter, and I was the first to be angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.379#If ever we can take one single counsel, then no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.380#shall the Trojans' evil be put aside, not even for a small time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.381#Now go back, take your dinner, and let us gather our warcraft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.382#Let a man put a good edge to his spear, and his shield in order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.383#let each put good fodder before his swift-footed horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.384#and each man look well over his chariot, careful of his fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.385#that all day long we may be in the division of hateful Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.386#There will not even for a small time be any respite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.387#unless darkness come down to separate the strength of the fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.388#There will be a man's sweat on the shield-strap binding the breast to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.389#the shield hiding the man's shape, and the hand on the spear grow weary.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.390#There will be sweat on a man's horse straining at the smoothed chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.391#But any man whom I find trying, apart from the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.392#to hang back by the curved ships, for him no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.393#will there be any means to escape the dogs and the vultures.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.394#So he spoke, and the Argives shouted aloud, as surf crashing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.395#against a sheerness, driven by the south wind descending,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.396#some cliff out-jutting, left never alone by the waves from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.397#all the winds that blow, as they rise one place and another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.398#They stood up scattering and made for the ships; they kindled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.399#the fires' smoke along the shelters, and took their dinner,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.400#each man making a sacrifice to some one of the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.401#gods, in prayer to escape death and the grind of Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.402#But Agamemnon the lord of men dedicated a fat ox
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.403#five years old to Zeus, all-powerful son of Kronos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.404#and summoned the nobles and the great men of all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.405#Nestor before all others, and next the lord Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.406#next the two Aiantes and Tydeus' son Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.407#and sixth Odysseus, a man like Zeus himself for counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.408#Of his own accord came Menelaos of the great war cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.409#who knew well in his own mind the cares of his brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.410#They stood in a circle about the ox and took up the scattering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.411#barley; and among them powerful Agamemnon spoke in prayer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.412#'Zeus, exalted and mightiest, sky-dwelling in the dark mist:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.413#let not the sun go down and disappear into darkness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.414#until I have hurled headlong the castle of Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.415#blazing, and lit the castle gates with the flames' destruction;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.416#not till I have broken at the chest the tunic of Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.417#torn with the bronze blade, and let many companions about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.418#go down headlong into the dust, teeth gripping the ground soil.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.419#He spoke, but none of this would the son of Kronos accomplish,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.420#who accepted the victims, but piled up the unwished-for hardship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.421#Now when all had made prayer and flung down the scattering barley,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.422#first they drew back the victim's head, cut his throat and skinned him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.423#and cut away the meat from the thighs and wrapped them in fat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.424#making a double fold, and laid shreds of flesh above them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.425#Placing these on sticks cleft and peeled they burned them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.426#and spitted the vitals and held them over the flame of Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.427#But when they had burned the thigh pieces and tasted the vitals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.428#they cut all the remainder into pieces and spitted them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.429#and roasted all carefully and took off the pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.430#Then after they had finished the work and got the feast ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.431#they feasted, nor was any man's hunger denied a fair portion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.432#But when they had put away their desire for eating and drinking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.433#the Gerenian horseman Nestor began speaking among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.434#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.435#let us talk no more of these things, nor for a long time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.436#set aside the action which the god puts into our hands now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.437#Come then, let the heralds of the bronze-armoured Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.438#make proclamation to the people and assemble them by the vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.439#and let us together as we are go down the wide host
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.440#of the Achaians, to stir more quickly the fierce war god.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.441#He spoke, nor did the lord of men Agamemnon neglect him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.442#but straightway commanded the clear-voiced heralds to summon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.443#by proclamation to battle the flowing-haired Achaians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.444#and the heralds made their cry and the men were assembled swiftly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.445#And they, the god-supported kings, about Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.446#ran marshalling the men, and among them grey-eyed Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.447#holding the dear treasured aegis, ageless, immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.448#from whose edges float a hundred all-golden tassels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.449#each one carefully woven, and each worth a hundred oxen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.450#With this fluttering she swept through the host of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.451#urging them to go forward. She kindled the strength in each man's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.452#heart to take the battle without respite and keep on fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.453#And now battle became sweeter to them than to go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.454#in their hollow ships to the beloved land of their fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.455#As obliterating fire lights up a vast forest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.456#along the crests of a mountain, and the flare shows far off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.457#so as they marched, from the magnificent bronze the gleam went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.458#dazzling all about through the upper air to the heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.459#These, as the multitudinous nations of birds winged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.460#of geese, and of cranes, and of swans long-throated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.461#in the Asian meadow beside the Kaïstrian waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.462#this way and that way make their flights in the pride of their wings, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.463#settle in clashing swarms and the whole meadow echoes with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.464#so of these the multitudinous tribes from the ships and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.465#shelters poured to the plain of Skamandros, and the earth beneath their
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.466#feet and under the feet of their horses thundered horribly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.467#They took position in the blossoming meadow of Skamandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.468#thousands of them, as leaves and flowers appear in their season.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.469#Like the multitudinous nations of swarming insects
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.470#who drive hither and thither about the stalls of the sheepfold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.471#in the season of spring when the milk splashes in the milk pails:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.472#in such numbers the flowing-haired Achaians stood up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.473#through the plain against the Trojans, hearts burning to break them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.474#These, as men who are goatherds among the wide goatflocks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.475#easily separate them in order as they take to the pasture,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.476#thus the leaders separated them this way and that way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.477#toward the encounter, and among them powerful Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.478#with eyes and head like Zeus who delights in thunder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.479#like Ares for girth, and with the chest of Poseidon;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.480#like some ox of the herd pre-eminent among the others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.481#a bull, who stands conspicuous in the huddling cattle;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.482#such was the son of Atreus as Zeus made him that day,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.483#conspicuous among men, and foremost among the fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.484#Tell me now, you Muses who have your homes on Olympos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.485#For you, who are goddesses, are there, and you know all things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.486#and we have heard only the rumour of it and know nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.487#Who then of those were the chief men and the lords of the Danaans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.488#I could not tell over the multitude of them nor name them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.489#not if I had ten tongues and ten mouths, not if I had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.490#a voice never to be broken and a heart of bronze within me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.491#not unless the Muses of Olympia, daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.492#of Zeus of the aegis, remembered all those who came beneath Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.493#I will tell the lords of the ships, and the ships numbers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.494#Leïtos and Peneleos were leaders of the Boiotians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.495#with Arkesilaos and Prothoenor and Klonios;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.496#they who lived in Hyria and in rocky Aulis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.497#in the hill-bends of Eteonos, and Schoinos, and Skolos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.498#Thespeia and Graia, and in spacious Mykalessos;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.499#they who dwelt about Harma and Eilesion and Erythrai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.500#they who held Eleon and Hyle and Peteon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.501#with Okalea and Medeon, the strong-founded citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.502#Kopai, and Eutresis, and Thisbe of the dove-cotes;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.503#they who held Koroneia, and the meadows of Haliartos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.504#they who held Plataia, and they who dwelt about Glisa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.505#they who held the lower Thebes, the strong-founded citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.506#and Onchestos the sacred, the shining grove of Poseidon;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.507#they who held Arne of the great vineyards, and Mideia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.508#with Nisa the sacrosanct and uttermost Anthedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.509#Of these there were fifty ships in all, and on board
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.510#each of these a hundred and twenty sons of the Boiotians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.511#But they who lived in Aspledon and Orchomenos of the Minyai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.512#Askalaphos led these, and Ialmenos, children of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.513#whom Astyoche bore to him in the house of Aktor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.514#Azeus' son, a modest maiden; she went into the chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.515#with strong Ares, who was laid in bed with her secretly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.516#With these two there were marshalled thirty hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.517#Schedios and Epistrophos led the men of Phokis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.518#children of Iphitos, who was son of great-hearted Naubolos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.519#These held Kyparissos, and rocky Pytho, and Krisa
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.520#the sacrosanct together with Daulis and Panopeus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.521#they who lived about Hyampolis and Anamoreia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.522#they who dwelt about Kephisos, the river immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.523#they who held Lilaia beside the well springs of Kephisos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.524#Following along with these were forty black ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.525#and the leaders marshalling the ranks of the Phokians set them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.526#in arms on the left wing of the host beside the Boiotians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.527#Swift Aias son of Oïleus led the men of Lokris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.528#the lesser Aias, not great in size like the son of Telamon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.529#but far slighter. He was a small man armoured in linen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.530#yet with the throwing spear surpassed all Achaians and Hellenes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.531#These were the dwellers in Kynos and Opoeis and Kalliaros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.532#and in Bessa, and Skarphe, and lovely Augeiai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.533#in Thronion and Tarphe and beside the waters of Boagrios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.534#Following along with him were forty black ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.535#of the Lokrians, who dwell across from sacred Euboia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.536#They who held Euboia, the Abantes, whose wind was fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.537#Chalkis, and Eretria, the great vineyards of Histiaia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.538#and seaborne Kerinthos and the steep stronghold of Dion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.539#they who held Karystos and they who dwelt about Styra,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.540#of these the leader was Elephenor, scion of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.541#son of Chalkodon and lord of the great-hearted Abantes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.542#And the running Abantes followed with him, their hair grown
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.543#long at the back, spearmen furious with the out-reached ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.544#to rip the corselets girt about the chests of their enemies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.545#Following along with him were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.546#But the men who held Athens, the strong-founded citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.547#the deme of great-hearted Erechtheus, whom once Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.548#Zeus' daughter tended after the grain-giving fields had born him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.549#and established him to be in Athens in her own rich temple;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.550#there as the circling years go by the sons of the Athenians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.551#make propitiation with rams and bulls sacrificed;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.552#of these men the leader was Peteos' son Menestheus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.553#Never on earth before had there been a man born like him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.554#for the arrangement in order of horses and shielded fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.555#Nestor alone could challenge him, since he was far older.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.556#Following along with him were fifty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.557#Out of Salamis Aias brought twelve ships and placed them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.558#next to where the Athenian battalions were drawn up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.559#They who held Argos and Tiryns of the huge walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.560#Hermione and Asine lying down the deep gulf,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.561#Troizen and Eïonai, and Epidauros of the vineyards,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.562#they who held Aigina and Mases, sons of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.563#of these the leader was Diomedes of the great war cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.564#with Sthenelos, own son to the high-renowned Kapaneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.565#and with them as a third went Euryalos, a man godlike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.566#son of Mekisteus the king, and scion of Talaos;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.567#but the leader of all was Diomedes of the great war cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.568#Following along with these were eighty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.569#But the men who held Mykenai, the strong-founded citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.570#Korinth the luxurious, and strong-founded Kleonai;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.571#they who dwelt in Orneai and lovely Araithyrea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.572#and Sikyon, where of old Adrestos had held the kingship;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.573#they who held Hyperesia and steep Gonoëssa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.574#they who held Pellene and they who dwelt about Aigion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.575#all about the sea-shore and about the wide headland of Helike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.576#of their hundred ships the leader was powerful Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.577#Atreus' son, with whom followed far the best and bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.578#people; and among them he himself stood armoured in shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.579#bronze, glorying, conspicuous among the great fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.580#since he was greatest among them all, and led the most people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.581#They who held the swarming hollow of Lakedaimon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.582#Pharis, and Sparta, and Messe of the dove-cotes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.583#they who dwelt in Bryseiai and lovely Augeiai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.584#they who held Amyklai and the seaward city of Helos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.585#they who held Laas, and they who dwelt about Oitylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.586#of these his brother Menelaos of the great war cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.587#was leader, with sixty ships marshalled apart from the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.588#He himself went among them in the confidence of his valour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.589#driving them battleward, since above all his heart was eager
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.590#to avenge Helen's longing to escape and her lamentations.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.591#They who dwelt about Pylos and lovely Arene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.592#and Thryon, the Alpheios crossing, and strong-built Aipy;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.593#they who lived in Kyparisseeis and Amphigeneia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.594#Pteleos and Helos and Dorion, where the Muses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.595#encountering Thamyris the Thracian stopped him from singing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.596#as he came from Oichalia and Oichalian Eurytos;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.597#for he boasted that he would surpass, if the very Muses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.598#daughters of Zeus who holds the aegis, were singing against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.599#and these in their anger struck him maimed, and the voice of wonder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.600#they took away, and made him a singer without memory;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.601#of these the leader was the Gerenian horseman, Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.602#in whose command were marshalled ninety hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.603#They who held Arkadia under the sheer peak, Kyllene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.604#beside the tomb of Aipytos, where men fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.605#they who dwelt in Orchomenos of the flocks, and Pheneos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.606#about Rhipe and Stratia and windy Enispe;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.607#they who held Tegea and Mantineia the lovely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.608#they who held Stymphalos, and dwelt about Parrhasia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.609#their leader was Angkaios' son, powerful Agapenor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.610#Sixty was the number of their ships, and in each ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.611#went many men of Arkadia, well skilled in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.612#Agamemnon the lord of men himself had given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.613#these for the crossing of the wine-blue sea their strong-benched vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.614#Atreus' son, since the work of the sea was nothing to these men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.615#They who lived in Bouprasion and brilliant Elis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.616#all as much as Hyrmine and Myrsinos the uttermost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.617#and the Olenian rock and Alesion close between them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.618#of these there were four chieftains, and with each man ten swift
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.619#vessels followed, with many Epeian men on board them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.620#Of two tens Thalpios and Amphimachos were leaders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.621#of Aktor's seed, sons one of Kteatos, one of Eurytos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.622#Ten more were led by Amaryngkeus' son, strong Diores,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.623#and of the fourth ten godlike Polyxeinos was leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.624#son of lord Agasthenes, of the race of Augeias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.625#They who came from Doulichion and the sacred Echinai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.626#islands, where men live across the water from Elis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.627#Meges was the leader of these, a man like Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.628#Phyleus' son, whom the rider dear to Zeus had begotten,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.629#Phyleus, who angered with his father had settled Doulichion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.630#Following along with him were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.631#But Odysseus led the high-hearted men of Kephallenia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.632#those who held Ithaka and leaf-trembling Neriton,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.633#those who dwelt about Krokyleia and rigged Aigilips,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.634#those who held Zakynthos and those who dwelt about Samos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.635#those who held the mainland and the places next to the crossing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.636#All these men were led by Odysseus, like Zeus in counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.637#Following with him were twelve ships with bows red painted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.638#Thoas son of Andraimon was leader of the Aitolians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.639#those who dwelt in Pleuron and Olenos and Pylene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.640#Kalydon of the rocks and Chalkis beside the sea-shore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.641#since no longer were the sons of high-hearted Oineus living,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.642#nor Oineus himself, and fair-haired Meleagros had perished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.643#So all the lordship of the Aitolians was given to Thoas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.644#Following along with him were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.645#Idomeneus the spear-famed was leader of the Kretans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.646#those who held Knosos and Gortyna of the great walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.647#Lyktos and Miletos and silver-shining Lykastos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.648#and Phaistos and Rhytion, all towns well established,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.649#and others who dwelt beside them in Krete of the hundred cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.650#Of all these Idomeneus the spear-famed was leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.651#with Meriones, a match for the murderous Lord of Battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.652#Following along with these were eighty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.653#Herakles' son Tlepolemos the huge and mighty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.654#led from Rhodes nine ships with the proud men of Rhodes aboard them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.655#those who dwelt about Rhodes and were ordered in triple division,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.656#Ialysos and Lindos and silver-shining Kameiros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.657#Of all these Tlepolemos the spear-famed was leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.658#he whom Astyocheia bore to the strength of Herakles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.659#Herakles brought her from Ephyra and the river Selleëis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.660#after he sacked many cities of strong, god-supported fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.661#Now when Tlepolemos was grown in the strong-built mansion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.662#he struck to death his own father's beloved uncle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.663#Likymnios, scion of Ares, a man already ageing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.664#At once he put ships together and assembled a host of people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.665#and went fugitive over the sea, since the others threatened,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.666#the rest of the sons and the grandsons of the strength of Herakles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.667#And he came to Rhodes a wanderer, a man of misfortune,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.668#and they settled there in triple division by tribes, beloved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.669#of Zeus himself, who is lord over all gods and all men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.670#Kronos' son, who showered the wonder of wealth upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.671#Nireus from Syme led three balanced vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.672#Nireus son of Aglaia and the king Charopos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.673#Nireus, the most beautiful man who came beneath Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.674#beyond the rest of the Danaans next after perfect Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.675#But he was a man of poor strength and few people with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.676#They who held Nisyros and Krapathos and Kasos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.677#and Kos, Eurypylos' city, and the islands called Kalydnai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.678#of these again Pheidippos and Antiphos were the leaders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.679#sons both of Thessalos who was born to the lord Herakles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.680#In their command were marshalled thirty hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.681#Now all those who dwelt about Pelasgian Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.682#those who lived by Alos and Alope and at Trachis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.683#those who held Phthia and Hellas the land of fair women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.684#who were called Myrmidons and Hellenes and Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.685#of all these and their fifty ships the lord was Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.686#But these took no thought now for the grim clamour of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.687#since there was no one who could guide them into close order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.688#since he, swift-footed brilliant Achilleus, lay where the ships were,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.689#angered over the girl of the lovely hair, Briseis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.690#whom after much hard work he had taken away from Lyrnessos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.691#after he had sacked Lyrnessos and the walls of Thebe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.692#and struck down Epistrophos and Mynes the furious spearmen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.693#children of Euenos, king, and son of Selepios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.694#For her sake he lay grieving now, but was soon to rise up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.695#They who held Phylake and Pyrasos of the flowers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.696#the precinct of Demeter, and Iton, mother of sheepflocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.697#Antron by the sea-shore, and Pteleos deep in the meadows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.698#of these in turn fighting Protesilaos was leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.699#while he lived; but now the black earth had closed him under,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.700#whose wife, cheeks torn for grief, was left behind in Phylake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.701#and a marriage half completed; a Dardanian man had killed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.702#as he leapt from his ship, far the first of all the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.703#Yet these, longing as they did for their leader, did not go leaderless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.704#but Podarkes, scion of Ares, set them in order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.705#child of Iphikles, who in turn was son to Phylakos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.706#rich in flocks, full brother of high-hearted Protesilaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.707#younger born; but the elder man was braver also,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.708#Protesilaos, a man of battle; yet still the people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.709#lacked not a leader, though they longed for him and his valour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.710#Following along with Podarkes were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.711#They who lived by Pherai beside the lake Boibeis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.712#by Boibe and Glaphyrai and strong-founded Iolkos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.713#of their eleven ships the dear son of Admetos was leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.714#Eumelos, born to Admetos by the beauty among women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.715#Alkestis, loveliest of all the daughters of Pelias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.716#They who lived about Thaumakia and Methone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.717#they who held Meliboia and rugged Olizon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.718#of their seven ships the leader was Philoktetes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.719#skilled in the bow's work, and aboard each vessel were fifty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.720#oarsmen, each well skilled in the strength of the bow in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.721#Yet he himself lay apart in the island, suffering strong pains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.722#in Lemnos the sacrosanct, where the sons of the Achaians had left him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.723#in agony from the sore bite of the wicked water snake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.724#There he lay apart in his pain; yet soon the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.725#beside their ships were to remember lord Philoktetes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.726#Yet these, longing as they did for their leader, did not go leaderless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.727#but Medon, the bastard son of Oileus, set them in order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.728#whom Rhene bore to Oïleus the sacker of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.729#They who held Trikke and the terraced place of Ithome,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.730#and Oichalia, the city of Oichalian Eurytos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.731#of these in turn the leaders were two sons of Asklepios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.732#good healers both themselves, Podaleirios and Machaon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.733#In their command were marshalled thirty hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.734#They who held Ormenios and the spring Hypereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.735#they who held Asterion and the pale peaks of Titanos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.736#Eurypylos led these, the shining son of Euaimon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.737#Following along with him were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.738#They who held Argissa and dwelt about Gyrtone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.739#Orthe and Elone and the white city Oloösson,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.740#of these the leader was Polypoites, stubborn in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.741#son of Peirithoös whose father was Zeus immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.742#he whom glorious Hippodameia bore to Peirithoös
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.743#on that day when he wreaked vengeance on the hairy beast men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.744#and drove them from Pelion and hurled them against the Aithikes;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.745#not by himself, for Leonteus was with him, scion of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.746#Leonteus, son of high-hearted Koronos the son of Kaineus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.747#Following in the guidance of these were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.748#Gouneus from Kyphos led two and twenty vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.749#and the Enienes and the Perrhaibians stubborn in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.750#followed him, they who made their homes by wintry Dodona,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.751#and they who by lovely Titaressos held the tilled acres,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.752#Titaressos, who into Peneios casts his bright current:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.753#yet he is not mixed with the silver whirls of Peneios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.754#but like oil is floated along the surface above him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.755#since he is broken from the water of Styx, the fearful oath-river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.756#Prothoös son of Tenthredon was leader of the Magnesians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.757#those who dwelt about Peneios and leaf-trembling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.758#Pelion. Of these Prothoös the swift-footed was leader.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.759#Following along with him were forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.760#These then were the leaders and the princes among the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.761#Tell me then, Muse, who of them all was the best and bravest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.762#of the men, and the men's horses, who went with the sons of Atreus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.763#Best by far among the horses were the mares of Eumelos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.764#Pheres' son, that he drove, swift-moving like birds, alike in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.765#texture of coat, in age, both backs drawn level like a plumb-line.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.766#These Apollo of the silver bow had bred in Pereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.767#mares alike, who went with the terror of the god of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.768#Among the men far the best was Telamonian Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.769#while Achilleus stayed angry, since he was far best of all of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.770#and the horses also, who carried the blameless son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.771#But Achilleus lay apart among his curved sea-wandering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.772#vessels, raging at Agamemnon, the shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.773#Atreus' son; and his men beside the break of the sea-beach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.774#amused themselves with discs and with light spears for throwing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.775#and bows; and the horses, standing each beside his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.776#champed their clover and the parsley that grows in wet places,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.777#resting, while the chariots of their lords stood covered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.778#in the shelters, and the men forlorn of their warlike leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.779#wandered here and there in the camp, and did no fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.780#But the rest went forward, as if all the earth with flame were eaten,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.781#and the ground echoed under them, as if Zeus who delights in thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.782#were angry, as when he batters the earth about Typhoeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.783#in the land of the Arimoi, where they say Typhoeus lies prostrate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.784#Thus beneath their feet the ground re-echoed loudly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.785#to men marching, who made their way through the plain in great speed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.786#Now to the Trojans came as messenger wind-footed Iris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.787#in her speed, with the dark message from Zeus of the aegis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.788#These were holding assembly in front of the doors of Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.789#gathered together in one place, the elders and the young men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.790#Standing close at hand swift-running Iris spoke to them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.791#and likened her voice to that of the son of Priam, Polites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.792#who confident in the speed of his feet kept watch for the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.793#aloft the ancient burial mound of ancient Aisyetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.794#waiting for the time when the Achaians should move from their vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.795#In this man's likeness Iris the swift-running spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.796#'Old sir, dear to you forever are words beyond number
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.797#as once, when there was peace; but stintless war has arisen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.798#In my time I have gone into many battles among men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.799#yet never have I seen a host like this, not one so numerous.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.800#These look terribly like leaves, or the sands of the sea-shore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.801#as they advance across the plain to fight by the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.802#Hektor, on you beyond all I urge this, to do as I tell you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.803#all about the great city of Priam are many companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.804#but multitudinous is the speech of the scattered nations:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.805#let each man who is their leader give orders to these men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.806#and let each set his citizens in order, and lead them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.807#She spoke, nor did Hektor fail to mark the word of the goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.808#Instantly he broke up the assembly; they ran to their weapons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.809#All the gates were opened and the people swept through them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.810#on foot, and with horses, and a clamour of shouting rose up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.811#Near the city but apart from it there is a steep hill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.812#in the plain by itself, so you pass one side or the other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.813#This men call the Hill of the Thicket, but the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.814#gods have named it the burial mound of dancing Myrina.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.815#There the Trojans and their companions were marshalled in order.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.816#Tall Hektor of the shining helm was leader of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.817#Priam's son; and with him far the best and the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.818#fighting men were armed and eager to fight with the spear's edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.819#The strong son of Anchises was leader of the Dardanians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.820#Aineias, whom divine Aphrodite bore to Anchises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.821#in the folds of Ida, a goddess lying in love with a mortal:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.822#not Aineias alone, but with him were two sons of Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.823#Archelochos and Akamas, both skilled in all fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.824#They who lived in Zeleia below the foot of Mount Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.825#men of wealth, who drank the dark water of Aisepos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.826#Trojans: of these the leader was the shining son of Lykaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.827#Pandaros, with the bow that was actual gift of Apollo.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.828#They who held Adresteia and the countryside of Apaisos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.829#they who held Pityeia and the sheer hill of Tereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.830#these were led by Adrestos and Amphios armoured in linen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.831#sons both of Merops of Perkote, who beyond all men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.832#knew the art of prophecy, and tried to prevent his two sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.833#from going into the battle where men die. Yet these would not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.834#listen, for the spirits of dark death were driving them onward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.835#They who dwelt in the places about Perkote and Praktion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.836#who held Sestos and Abydos and brilliant Arisbe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.837#their leader was Asios, Hyrtakos' son, a prince of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.838#Asios, son of Hyrtakos, whom huge and shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.839#horses carried from Arisbe and the river Selleëis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.840#Hippothoös led the tribes of spear-fighting Pelasgians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.841#they who dwelt where the soil is rich about Larissa;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.842#Hippothoös and Pylaios, scion of Ares, led these,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.843#sons alike of Pelasgian Lethos, son of Teutamos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.844#Akamas led the men of Thrace with the fighter Peiroös,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.845#all the Thracians held within the hard stream of the Hellespont.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.846#Euphemos was leader of the Kikonian spearmen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.847#son of Troizenos, Keas' son, the king whom the gods loved.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.848#Pyraichmes in turn led the Paionians with their curved bows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.849#from Amydon far away and the broad stream of Axios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.850#Axios, whose stream on all earth is the loveliest water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.851#Pylaimenes the wild heart was leader of the Paphlagones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.852#from the land of the Enetoi where the wild mules are engendered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.853#those who held Kytoros and those who dwelt about Sesamos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.854#those whose renowned homes were about Parthenios river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.855#and Kromna and Aigialos and high Erythinoi.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.856#Odios and Epistrophos led the Halizones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.857#from Alybe far away, where silver was first begotten.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.858#Chromis, with Ennomos the augur, was lord of the Mysians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.859#yet his reading of birds could not keep off dark destruction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.860#but he went down under the hands of swift-running Aiakides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.861#in the river, as he slew other Trojans beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.862#Phorkys and godlike Askanios were lords of the Phrygians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.863#from Askania far away, eager to fight in the onfall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.864#Mesthles and Antiphos were leaders of the Maionians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.865#sons of Talaimenes, who was born of the lake Gygaian:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.866#these led the Maionian men whose home was beneath Mount Tmolos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.867#The Karians of the outland speech were led by Nastes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.868#they who held Miletos and the leaf-deep mountain of Phthiron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.869#the waters of Maiandros and the headlong peaks of Mykale;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.870#of these the two leaders were Amphimachos and Nastes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.871#Nastes and Amphimachos, the shining sons of Nomion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.872#Nastes came like a girl to the fighting in golden raiment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.873#poor fool, nor did this avail to keep dismal death back;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.874#but he went down under the hands of swift-running Aiakides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.875#in the river, and fiery Achilleus stripped the gold from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.876#Sarpedon with unfaulted Glaukos was lord of the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:2.877#from Lykia far away, and the whirling waters of Xanthos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.1#Now when the men of both sides were set in order by their leaders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.2#the Trojans came on with clamour and shouting, like wildfowl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.3#as when the clamour of cranes goes high to the heavens,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.4#when the cranes escape the winter time and the rains unceasing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.5#and clamorously wing their way to the streaming Ocean,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.6#bringing to the Pygmaian men bloodshed and destruction:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.7#at daybreak they bring on the baleful battle against them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.8#But the Achaian men went silently, breathing valour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.9#stubbornly minded each in his heart to stand by the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.10#As on the peaks of a mountain the south wind scatters the thick mist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.11#no friend to the shepherd, but better than night for the robber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.12#and a man can see before him only so far as a stone cast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.13#so beneath their feet the dust drove up in a stormcloud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.14#of men marching, who made their way through the plain in great speed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.15#Now as these in their advance had come close together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.16#Alexandros the godlike leapt from the ranks of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.17#as challenger wearing across his shoulders the hide of a leopard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.18#curved bow and sword; while in his hands shaking two javelins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.19#pointed with bronze, he challenged all the best of the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.20#to fight man to man against him in bitter combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.21#Now as soon as Menelaos the warlike caught sight of him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.22#making his way with long strides out in front of the army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.23#he was glad, like a lion who comes on a mighty carcass,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.24#in his hunger chancing upon the body of a horned stag
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.25#or wild goat; who eats it eagerly, although against him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.26#are hastening the hounds in their speed and the stalwart young men:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.27#thus Menelaos was happy finding godlike Alexandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.28#there in front of his eyes, and thinking to punish the robber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.29#straightway in all his armour he sprang to the ground from his chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.30#But Alexandros the godlike when he saw Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.31#showing among the champions, the heart was shaken within him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.32#to avoid death he shrank into the host of his own companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.33#As a man who has come on a snake in the mountain valley
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.34#suddenly steps back, and the shivers come over his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.35#and he draws back and away, cheeks seized with a green pallor;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.36#so in terror of Atreus' son godlike Alexandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.37#lost himself again in the host of the haughty Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.38#But Hektor saw him and in words of shame rebuked him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.39#'Evil Paris, beautiful, woman-crazy, cajoling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.40#better had you never been born, or killed unwedded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.41#Truly I could have wished it so; it would be far better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.42#than to have you with us to our shame, for others to sneer at.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.43#Surely now the flowing-haired Achaians laugh at us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.44#thinking you are our bravest champion, only because your
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.45#looks are handsome, but there is no strength in your heart, no courage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.46#Were you like this that time when in sea-wandering vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.47#assembling oarsmen to help you you sailed over the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.48#and mixed with the outlanders, and carried away a fair woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.49#from a remote land, whose lord's kin were spearmen and fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.50#to your father a big sorrow, and your city, and all your people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.51#to yourself a thing shameful but bringing joy to the enemy?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.52#And now you would not stand up against warlike Menelaos?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.53#Thus you would learn of the man whose blossoming wife you have taken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.54#The lyre would not help you then, nor the favours of Aphrodite,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.55#nor your locks, when you rolled in the dust, nor all your beauty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.56#No, but the Trojans are cowards in truth, else long before this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.57#you had worn a mantle of flying stones for the wrong you did us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.58#Then in answer Alexandros the godlike spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.59#'Hektor, seeing you have scolded me rightly, not beyond measure--
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.60#still, your heart forever is weariless, like an axe-blade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.61#driven by a man's strength through the timber, one who, well skilled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.62#hews a piece for a ship, driven on by the force of a man's strength:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.63#such is the heart in your breast, unshakable: yet do not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.64#bring up against me the sweet favours of golden Aphrodite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.65#Never to be cast away are the gifts of the gods, magnificent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.66#which they give of their own will, no man could have them for wanting them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.67#Now though, if you wish me to fight it out and do battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.68#make the rest of the Trojans sit down, and all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.69#and set me in the middle with Menelaos the warlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.70#to fight together for the sake of Helen and all her possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.71#That one of us who wins and is proved stronger, let him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.72#take the possessions fairly and the woman, and lead her homeward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.73#But the rest of you, having cut your oaths of faith and friendship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.74#dwell, you in Troy where the soil is rich, while those others return home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.75#to horse-pasturing Argos, and Achaia the land of fair women.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.76#So he spoke, and Hektor hearing his word was happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.77#and went into the space between and forced back the Trojan battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.78#holding his spear by the middle until they were all seated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.79#But the flowing-haired Achaians kept pointing their bows at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.80#with arrows and with flung stones striving ever to strike him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.81#until Agamemnon lord of men cried out in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.82#'Argives, hold: cast at him no longer, o sons of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.83#Hektor of the shining helm is trying to tell us something.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.84#So he spoke, and they stopped fighting and suddenly all fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.85#silent; but Hektor between them spoke now to both sides:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.86#'Hear from me, Trojans and strong-greaved Achaians, the word
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.87#of Alexandros, for whose sake this strife has arisen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.88#He would have all the rest of the Trojans and all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.89#lay aside on the bountiful earth their splendid armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.90#while he himself in the middle and warlike Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.91#fight alone for the sake of Helen and all her possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.92#That one of them who wins and is proved stronger, let him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.93#take the possessions fairly and the woman, and lead her homeward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.94#while the rest of us cut our oaths of faith and friendship.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.95#So he spoke, and all of them stayed stricken to silence;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.96#but among them spoke out Menelaos of the great war cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.97#'Listen now to me also; since beyond all others this sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.98#comes closest to my heart, and I think the Argives and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.99#can go free of each other at last. You have suffered much evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.100#for the sake of this my quarrel since Alexandros began it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.101#As for that one of us two to whom death and doom are given,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.102#let him die: the rest of you be made friends with each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.103#Bring two lambs: let one be white and the other black for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.104#Earth and the Sun God, and for Zeus we will bring yet another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.105#Bring, that he may seal the pledges, the strength of Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.106#Priam himself, for his sons are outrageous, not to be trusted;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.107#lest some man overstep Zeus' oaths, and make them be nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.108#Always it is, that the hearts in the younger men are frivolous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.109#but when an elder man is among them, he looks behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.110#and in front, so that all comes out far better for both sides.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.111#So he spoke, and the Trojans and Achaians were joyful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.112#hoping now to be rid of all the sorrow of warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.113#They pulled their chariots into line, and themselves dismounted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.114#and stripped off their armour which was laid on the ground beside them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.115#close together, so there was little ground left between them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.116#Hektor sent away to the citadel two heralds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.117#lightly to bring down the lambs, and to summon Priam;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.118#and powerful Agamemnon in turn sent Talthybios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.119#to go down to the hollow ships, with orders to bring two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.120#lambs: he did not disobey the order of great Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.121#Now to Helen of the white arms came a messenger, Iris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.122#in the likeness of her sister-in-law, the wife of Antenor's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.123#son, whom strong Helikaon wed, the son of Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.124#Laodike, loveliest looking of all the daughters of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.125#She came on Helen in the chamber; she was weaving a great web,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.126#a red folding robe, and working into it the numerous struggles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.127#of Trojans, breakers of horses, and bronze-armoured Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.128#struggles that they endured for her sake at the hands of the war god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.129#Iris of the swift feet stood beside her and spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.130#'Come with me, dear girl, to behold the marvellous things done
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.131#by Trojans, breakers of horses, and bronze-armoured Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.132#who just now carried sorrowful war against each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.133#in the plain, and all their desire was for deadly fighting;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.134#now they are all seated in silence, the fighting has ended;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.135#they lean on their shields, the tall spears stuck in the ground beside them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.136#But Menelaos the warlike and Alexandros will fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.137#with long spears against each other for your possession.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.138#You shall be called beloved wife of the man who wins you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.139#Speaking so the goddess left in her heart sweet longing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.140#after her husband of time before, and her city and parents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.141#And at once, wrapping herself about in shimmering garments,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.142#she went forth from the chamber, letting fall a light tear;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.143#not by herself, since two handmaidens went to attend her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.144#Aithre, Pitteus' daughter, and Klymene of the ox eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.145#Rapidly they came to the place where the Skaian gates stood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.146#Now those who sat with Priam: Panthoös and Thymoites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.147#Lampos and Klytios, Hiketaon, scion of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.148#with Antenor and Oukalegon, both men of good counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.149#these were seated by the Skaian gates, elders of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.150#Now through old age these fought no longer, yet were they excellent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.151#speakers still, and clear, as cicadas who through the forest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.152#settle on trees, to issue their delicate voice of singing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.153#Such were they who sat on the tower, chief men of the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.154#And these, as they saw Helen along the tower approaching,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.155#murmuring softly to each other uttered their winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.156#'Surely there is no blame on Trojans and strong-greaved Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.157#if for long time they suffer hardship for a woman like this one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.158#Terrible is the likeness of her face to immortal goddesses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.159#Still, though she be such, let her go away in the ships, lest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.160#she be left behind, a grief to us and our children.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.161#So they spoke: but Priam aloud called out to Helen:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.162#'Come over where I am, dear child, and sit down beside me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.163#to look at your husband of time past, your friends and your people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.164#I am not blaming you: to me the gods are blameworthy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.165#who drove upon me this sorrowful war against the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.166#So you could tell me the name of this man who is so tremendous;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.167#who is this Achaian man of power and stature?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.168#Though in truth there are others taller by a head than he is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.169#yet these eyes have never yet looked on a man so splendid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.170#nor so lordly as this: such a man might well be royal.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.171#Helen, the shining among women, answered and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.172#'Always to me, beloved father, you are feared and respected;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.173#and I wish bitter death had been what I wanted, when I came hither
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.174#following your son, forsaking my chamber, my kinsmen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.175#my grown child, and the loveliness of girls my own age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.176#It did not happen that way: and now I am worn with weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.177#This now I will tell you in answer to the question you asked me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.178#That man is Atreus' son Agamemnon, widely powerful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.179#at the same time a good king and a strong spearfighter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.180#once my kinsman, slut that I am. Did this ever happen?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.181#This she said, and the old man spoke again, wondering at him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.182#'O son of Atreus, blessed, child of fortune and favour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.183#many are these beneath your sway, these sons of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.184#Once before this time I visited Phrygia of the vineyards.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.185#There I looked on the Phrygian men with their swarming horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.186#so many of them, the people of Otreus and godlike Mygdon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.187#whose camp was spread at that time along the banks of Sangarios:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.188#and I myself, a helper in war, was marshalled among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.189#on that day when the Amazon women came, men's equals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.190#Yet even they were not so many as these glancing-eyed Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.191#Next again the old man asked her, seeing Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.192#'Tell me of this one also, dear child; what man can he be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.193#shorter in truth by a head than Atreus' son Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.194#but broader, it would seem, in the chest and across the shoulders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.195#Now as his armour lies piled on the prospering earth, still he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.196#ranges, like some ram, through the marshalled ranks of the fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.197#Truly, to some deep-fleeced ram would I liken him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.198#who makes his way through the great mass of the shining sheep-flocks.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.199#Helen, the daughter descended of Zeus, spoke then in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.200#'This one is Laertes' son, resourceful Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.201#who grew up in the country, rough though it be, of Ithaka,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.202#to know every manner of shiftiness and crafty counsels.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.203#In his turn Antenor of the good counsel answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.204#'Surely this word you have spoken, my lady, can be no falsehood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.205#Once in the days before now brilliant Odysseus came here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.206#with warlike Menelaos, and their embassy was for your sake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.207#To both of these I gave in my halls kind entertainment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.208#and I learned the natural way of both, and their close counsels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.209#Now when these were set before the Trojans assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.210#and stood up, Menelaos was bigger by his broad shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.211#but Odysseus was the more lordly when both were seated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.212#Now before all when both of them spun their speech and their counsels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.213#Menelaos indeed spoke rapidly, in few words
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.214#but exceedingly lucid, since he was no long speaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.215#nor one who wasted his words though he was only a young man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.216#But when that other drove to his feet, resourceful Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.217#he would just stand and stare down, eyes fixed on the ground beneath him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.218#nor would he gesture with the staff backward and forward, but hold it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.219#clutched hard in front of him, like any man who knows nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.220#Yes, you would call him a sullen man, and a fool likewise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.221#But when he let the great voice go from his chest, and the words came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.222#drifting down like the winter snows, then no other mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.223#man beside could stand up against Odysseus. Then we
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.224#wondered less beholding Odysseus' outward appearance.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.225#Third in order, looking at Aias, the old man asked her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.226#'Who then is this other Achaian of power and stature
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.227#towering above the Argives by head and broad shoulders?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.228#Helen with the light robes and shining among women answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.229#'That one is gigantic Aias, wall of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.230#and beyond him there is Idomeneus like a god standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.231#among the Kretans, and the lords of Krete are gathered about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.232#Many a time warlike Menelaos would entertain him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.233#in our own house when he came over from Krete. And I see them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.234#all now, all the rest of the glancing-eyed Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.235#all whom I would know well by sight, whose names I could tell you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.236#yet nowhere can I see those two, the marshals of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.237#Kastor, breaker of horses, and the strong boxer, Polydeukes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.238#my own brothers, born with me of a single mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.239#Perhaps these came not with the rest from Lakedaimon the lovely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.240#or else they did come here in their sea-wandering ships, yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.241#now they are reluctant to go with the men into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.242#dreading the words of shame and all the reproach that is on me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.243#So she spoke, but the teeming earth lay already upon them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.244#away in Lakedaimon, the beloved land of their fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.245#Now through the town the heralds brought the symbols of oaths pledged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.246#two young rams, and cheerful wine, the yield of the tilled land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.247#in a goatskin wine sack, while another carried the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.248#mixing bowl (the herald Idaios) and the golden wine-cups.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.249#Standing beside the aged man he spoke words to arouse him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.250#'Son of Laomedon, rise up: you are called by the chief men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.251#of Trojans, breakers of horses, and bronze-armoured Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.252#to come down into the plain that you may seal the oaths pledged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.253#For warlike Menelaos and Alexandros are to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.254#with long spears against each other for the sake of the woman.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.255#Let the woman go to the winner, and all the possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.256#Let the rest of them, cutting their oaths of faith and friendship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.257#dwell, we in Troy where the soil is rich, while those others return home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.258#to horse-pasturing Argos and Achaia the land of fair women.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.259#So he spoke, and the old man shuddered, but called his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.260#to yoke the horses to the car, and they promptly obeyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.261#And Priam mounted into the car and gathered the reins back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.262#as Antenor beside him stepped into the fair-wrought chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.263#Through the Skaian gates to the plain they steered the swift horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.264#Now when these had come among the Trojans and Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.265#they stepped down on the prospering earth from their car with horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.266#and made their way striding among the Achaians and Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.267#On the other side rose up the lord of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.268#and the resourceful Odysseus rose up. Meanwhile the proud heralds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.269#led up the victims for the gods' oaths, and in a great wine-bowl
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.270#mixed the wine, and poured water over the hands of the princes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.271#Atreus' son laid hands upon his work-knife, and drew it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.272#from where it hung ever beside the mighty sheath of his war sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.273#and cut off hairs from the heads of the lambs; and the heralds thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.274#passed these about to all the princes of the Trojans and Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.275#Atreus' son uplifting his hands then prayed in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.276#'Father Zeus, watching over us from Ida, most high, most honoured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.277#and Helios, you who see all things, who listen to all things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.278#earth, and rivers, and you who under the earth take vengeance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.279#on dead men, whoever among them has sworn to falsehood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.280#you shall be witnesses, to guard the oaths of fidelity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.281#If it should be that Alexandros slays Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.282#let him keep Helen for himself, and all her possessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.283#and we in our seafaring ships shall take our wayhomeward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.284#But if the fair-haired Menelaos kills Alexandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.285#then let the Trojans give back Helen and all her possessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.286#and pay also a price to the Argives which will be fitting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.287#which among people yet to come shall be as a standard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.288#Then if Priam and the sons of Priam are yet unwilling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.289#after Alexandros has fallen to pay me the penalty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.290#I myself shall fight hereafter for the sake of the ransom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.291#here remaining, until I have won to the end of my quarrel.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.292#So he spoke, and with pitiless bronze he cut the lambs' throats,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.293#letting them fall gasping again to the ground, the life breath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.294#going away, since the strength of the bronze had taken it from them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.295#Drawing the wine from the mixing bowls in the cups, they poured it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.296#forth, and made their prayer to the gods who live everlasting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.297#And thus would murmur any man, Achaian or Trojan:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.298#'Zeus, exalted and mightiest, and you other immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.299#let those, whichever side they may be, who do wrong to the oaths sworn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.300#first, let their brains be spilled on the ground as this wine is spilled now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.301#theirs and their sons', and let their wives be the spoil of others.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.302#They spoke, but none of this would the son of Kronos accomplish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.303#Now among them spoke Priam descended of Dardanos also:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.304#'Listen to me, you Trojans and you strong-greaved Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.305#Now I am going away to windy Ilion, homeward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.306#since I cannot look with these eyes on the sight of my dear son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.307#fighting against warlike Menelaos in single combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.308#Zeus knows--maybe he knows--and the rest of the gods immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.309#for which of the two death is appointed to end this matter.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.310#He spoke, a godlike man, and laid the lambs in the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.311#and mounted into it himself, and pulled the reins backward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.312#Antenor beside him stepped up into the fair-wrought chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.313#These two took their way backward and made for Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.314#Hektor now, the son of Priam, and brilliant Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.315#measured out the distance first, and thereafter picked up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.316#two lots, and put them in a brazen helmet, and shook them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.317#to see which one of the two should be first to cast with his bronze spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.318#and the people on each side held up their hands to the gods, and prayed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.319#to them. Thus would murmur any man, Achaian or Trojan:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.320#'Father Zeus, watching over us from Ida, most high, most honoured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.321#whichever man has made what has happened happen to both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.322#grant that he be killed and go down to the house of Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.323#Let the friendship and the sworn faith be true for the rest of us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.324#So they spoke, and tall Hektor of the shining helm shook
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.325#the lots, looking backward, and at once Paris' lot was outshaken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.326#All the rest sat down in their ranks on the ground, at the place where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.327#the glittering armour of each was piled by his light-footed horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.328#while one of them put about his shoulders his splendid armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.329#brilliant Alexandros, the lord of lovely-haired Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.330#First he placed along his legs the fair greaves linked with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.331#silver fastenings to hold the greaves at the ankles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.332#Afterwards he girt on about his chest the corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.333#of Lykaon his brother since this fitted him also.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.334#Across his shoulders he slung the sword with the nails of silver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.335#a bronze sword, and above it the great shield, huge and heavy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.336#Over his powerful head he set the well-fashioned helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.337#with the horse-hair crest, and the plumes nodded terribly above it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.338#He took up a strong-shafted spear that fitted his hand's grip.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.339#In the same way warlike Menelaos put on his armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.340#Now when these two were armed on either side of the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.341#they strode into the space between the Achaians and Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.342#looking terror at each other; and amazement seized the beholders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.343#Trojans, breakers of horses, and strong-greaved Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.344#They took their stand in the measured space not far from each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.345#raging each at the other man and shaking their spearshafts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.346#First of the two Alexandros let go his spear far-shadowing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.347#and struck the shield of Atreus' son on its perfect circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.348#nor did the bronze point break its way through, but the spearhead bent back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.349#in the strong shield. And after him Atreus' son, Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.350#was ready to let go the bronze spear, with a prayer to Zeus father:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.351#'Zeus, lord, grant me to punish the man who first did me injury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.352#brilliant Alexandros, and beat him down under my hands' strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.353#that any one of the men to come may shudder to think of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.354#doing evil to a kindly host, who has given him friendship.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.355#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far-shadowed, and threw it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.356#and struck the shield of Priam's son on its perfect circle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.357#All the way through the glittering shield went the heavy spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.358#and smashed its way through the intricately worked corselet;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.359#straight ahead by the flank the spearhead shore through his tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.360#yet he bent away to one side and avoided the dark death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.361#Drawing his sword with the silver nails, the son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.362#heaving backward struck at the horn of his helmet; the sword-blade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.363#three times broken and four times broken fell from his hand's grip.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.364#Groaning, the son of Atreus lifted his eyes to the wide sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.365#'Father Zeus, no God beside is more baleful than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.366#Here I thought to punish Alexandros for his wickedness;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.367#and now my sword is broken in my hands, and the spear flew vainly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.368#out of my hands on the throw before, and I have not hit him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.369#He spoke, and flashing forward laid hold of the horse-haired helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.370#and spun him about, and dragged him away toward the strong-greaved Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.371#for the broidered strap under the softness of his throat strangled Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.372#fastened under his chin to hold on the horned helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.373#Now he would have dragged him away and won glory forever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.374#had not Aphrodite daughter of Zeus watched sharply.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.375#She broke the chinstrap, made from the hide of a slaughtered bullock,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.376#and the helmet came away empty in the heavy hand of Atreides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.377#The hero whirled the helmet about and sent it flying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.378#among the strong-greaved Achaians, and his staunch companions retrieved it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.379#He turned and made again for his man, determined to kill him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.380#with the bronze spear. But Aphrodite caught up Paris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.381#easily, since she was divine, and wrapped him in a thick mist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.382#and set him down again in his own perfumed bedchamber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.383#She then went away to summon Helen, and found her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.384#on the high tower, with a cluster of Trojan women about her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.385#She laid her hand upon the robe immortal, and shook it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.386#and spoke to her, likening herself to an aged woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.387#a wool-dresser who when she was living in Lakedaimon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.388#made beautiful things out of wool, and loved her beyond all others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.389#Likening herself to this woman Aphrodite spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.390#'Come with me: Alexandros sends for you to come home to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.391#He is in his chamber now, in the bed with its circled pattern,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.392#shining in his raiment and his own beauty; you would not think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.393#that he came from fighting against a man; you would think he was going
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.394#rather to a dance, or rested and had been dancing lately.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.395#So she spoke, and troubled the spirit in Helen's bosom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.396#She, as she recognized the round, sweet throat of the goddess
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.397#and her desirable breasts and her eyes that were full of shining,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.398#she wondered, and spoke a word and called her by name, thus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.399#'Strange divinity! Why are you still so stubborn to beguile me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.400#Will you carry me further yet somewhere among cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.401#fairly settled? In Phrygia or in lovely Maionia?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.402#Is there some mortal man there also who is dear to you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.403#Is it because Menelaos has beaten great Alexandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.404#and wishes, hateful even as I am, to carry me homeward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.405#is it for this that you stand in your treachery now beside me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.406#Go yourself and sit beside him, abandon the gods' way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.407#turn your feet back never again to the path of Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.408#but stay with him forever, and suffer for him, and look after him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.409#until he makes you his wedded wife, or makes you his slave girl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.410#Not I. I am not going to him. It would be too shameful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.411#I will not serve his bed, since the Trojan women hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.412#would laugh at me, all, and my heart even now is confused with sorrows.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.413#Then in anger Aphrodite the shining spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.414#'Wretched girl, do not tease me lest in anger I forsake you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.415#and grow to hate you as much as now I terribly love you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.416#lest I encompass you in hard hate, caught between both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.417#Danaans and Trojans alike, and you wretchedly perish.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.418#So she spoke, and Helen daughter of Zeus was frightened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.419#and went, shrouding herself about in the luminous spun robe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.420#silent, unseen by the Trojan women, and led by the goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.421#When they had come to Alexandros' splendidly wrought house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.422#the rest of them, the handmaidens went speedily to their own work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.423#but she, shining among women, went to the high-vaulted bedchamber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.424#Aphrodite the sweetly laughing drew up an armchair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.425#carrying it, she, a goddess, and set it before Alexandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.426#and Helen, daughter of Zeus of the aegis, took her place there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.427#turning her eyes away, and spoke to her lord in derision:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.428#'So you came back from fighting. Oh, how I wish you had died there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.429#beaten down by the stronger man, who was once my husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.430#There was a time before now you boasted that you were better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.431#than warlike Menelaos, in spear and hand and your own strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.432#Go forth now and challenge warlike Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.433#once again to fight you in combat. But no: I advise you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.434#rather to let it be, and fight no longer with fair-haired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.435#Menelaos, strength against strength in single combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.436#recklessly. You might very well go down before his spear.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.437#Paris then in turn spoke to her thus and answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.438#'Lady, censure my heart no more in bitter reprovals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.439#This time Menelaos with Athene's help has beaten me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.440#another time I shall beat him. We have gods on our side also.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.441#Come, then, rather let us go to bed and turn to love-making.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.442#Never before as now has passion enmeshed my senses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.443#not when I took you the first time from Lakedaimon the lovely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.444#and caught you up and carried you away in seafaring vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.445#and lay with you in the bed of love on the island Kranae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.446#not even then, as now, did I love you and sweet desire seize me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.447#Speaking, he led the way to the bed; and his wife went with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.448#So these two were laid in the carven bed. But Atreides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.449#ranged like a wild beast up and down the host, to discover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.450#whether he could find anywhere godlike Alexandros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.451#Yet could none of the Trojans nor any renowned companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.452#show Alexandros then to warlike Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.453#These would not have hidden him for love, if any had seen him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.454#since he was hated among them all as dark death is hated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.455#Now among them spoke forth the lord of men Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.456#'Listen to me, o Trojans, Dardanians and companions:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.457#clearly the victory is with warlike Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.458#Do you therefore give back, with all her possessions, Helen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.459#of Argos, and pay a price that shall be befitting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.460#which among people yet to come shall be as a standard.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:3.461#So spoke Atreus' son, and the other Achaians applauded him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.1#Now the gods at the side of Zeus were sitting in council
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.2#over the golden floor, and among them the goddess Hebe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.3#poured them nectar as wine, while they in the golden drinking-cups
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.4#drank to each other, gazing down on the city of the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.5#Presently the son of Kronos was minded to anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.6#Hera, if he could, with words offensive, speaking to cross her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.7#'Two among the goddesses stand by Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.8#Hera of Argos, and Athene who stands by her people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.9#Yet see, here they are sitting apart, looking on at the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.10#and take their pleasure. Meanwhile laughing Aphrodite forever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.11#stands by her man and drives the spirits of death away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.12#Even now she has rescued him when he thought he would perish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.13#So, the victory now is with warlike Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.14#Let us consider then how these things shall be accomplished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.15#whether again to stir up grim warfare and the terrible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.16#fighting, or cast down love and make them friends with each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.17#If somehow this way could be sweet and pleasing to all of us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.18#the city of lord Priam might still be a place men dwell in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.19#and Menelaos could take away with him Helen of Argos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.20#So he spoke; and Athene and Hera muttered, since they were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.21#sitting close to each other, devising evil for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.22#Still Athene stayed silent and said nothing, but only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.23#sulked at Zeus her father, and savage anger took hold of her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.24#But the heart of Hera could not contain her anger, and she spoke forth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.25#'Majesty, son of Kronos, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.26#How can you wish to make wasted and fruitless all this endeavour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.27#the sweat that I have sweated in toil, and my horses worn out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.28#gathering my people, and bringing evil to Priam and his children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.29#Do it then; but not all the rest of us gods will approve you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.30#Deeply troubled, Zeus who gathers the clouds answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.31#'Dear lady, what can be all the great evils done to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.32#by Priam and the sons of Priam, that you are thus furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.33#forever to bring down the strong-founded city of Ilion?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.34#If you could walk through the gates and through the towering ramparts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.35#and eat Priam and the children of Priam raw, and the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.36#Trojans, then, then only might you glut at last your anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.37#Do as you please then. Never let this quarrel hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.38#be between you and me a bitterness for both of us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.39#And put away in your thoughts this other thing that I tell you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.40#whenever I in turn am eager to lay waste some city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.41#as I please, one in which are dwelling men who are dear to you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.42#you shall not stand in the way of my anger, but let me do it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.43#since I was willing to grant you this with my heart unwilling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.44#For of all the cities beneath the sun and the starry heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.45#dwelt in by men who live upon earth, there has never been one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.46#honoured nearer to my heart than sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.47#and Priam, and the people of Priam of the strong ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.48#Never yet has my altar gone without fair sacrifice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.49#the libation and the savour, since this is our portion of honour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.50#Then the goddess the ox-eyed lady Hera answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.51#'Of all cities there are three that are dearest to my own heart:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.52#Argos and Sparta and Mykenai of the wide ways. All these,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.53#whenever they become hateful to your heart, sack utterly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.54#I will not stand up for these against you, nor yet begrudge you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.55#Yet if even so I bear malice and would not have you destroy them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.56#in malice I will accomplish nothing, since you are far stronger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.57#Yet my labour also should not be let go unaccomplished;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.58#I am likewise a god, and my race is even what yours is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.59#and I am first of the daughters of devious-devising Kronos,
