urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.219#that Cheiron in friendship long ago had given his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.220#While they were working over Menelaos of the great war cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.221#all this time came on the ranks of the armoured Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.222#The Achaians again put on their armour, and remembered their warcraft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.223#Then you would not have seen brilliant Agamemnon asleep nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.224#skulking aside, nor in any way a reluctant fighter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.225#but driving eagerly toward the fighting where men win glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.226#He left aside his chariot gleaming with bronze, and his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.227#and these, breathing hard, were held aside by a henchman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.228#Eurymedon, born to Ptolemaios, the son of Peiraios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.229#Agamemnon told him to keep them well in hand, till the time came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.230#when weariness might take hold of his limbs, through marshalling so many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.231#Then he, on foot as he was, ranged through the ranks of his fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.232#Those of the fast-mounted Danaans he found eager, he would
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.233#stand beside these and urge them harder on with words spoken:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.234#'Argives, do not let go now of this furious valour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.235#Zeus the father shall not be one to give aid to liars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.236#but these, who were the first to do violence over the oaths sworn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.237#vultures shall feed upon the delicate skin of their bodies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.238#while we lead away their beloved wives and innocent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.239#children, in our ships, after we have stormed their citadel.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.240#Any he might see hanging back from the hateful conflict
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.241#these in words of anger he would reproach very bitterly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.242#'Argives, you arrow-fighters, have you no shame, you abuses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.243#Why are you simply standing there bewildered, like young deer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.244#who after they are tired from running through a great meadow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.245#stand there still, and there is no heart of courage within them?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.246#Thus are you standing still bewildered and are not fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.247#Or are you waiting for the Trojans to come close, where the strong-sterned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.248#ships have been hauled up along the strand of the grey sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.249#so you may know if Kronos' son will hold his hand over you?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.250#Thus he ranged through the ranks of his men and set them in order.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.251#On his way through the thronging men he came to the Kretans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.252#who about valiant Idomeneus were arming for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.253#Idomeneus, like a boar in his strength, stood among the champions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.254#while Meriones still urged along the last battalions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.255#Agamemnon the lord of men was glad as he looked at them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.256#and in words of graciousness at once spoke to Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.257#'I honour you, Idomeneus, beyond the fast-mounted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.258#Danaans whether in battle, or in any action whatever,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.259#whether it be at the feast, when the great men of the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.260#blend in the mixing bowl the gleaming wine of the princes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.261#Even though all the rest of the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.262#drink out their portion, still your cup stands filled forever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.263#even as mine, for you to drink when the pleasure takes you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.264#Rise up then to battle, be such as you claimed in time past.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.265#Then in turn Idomeneus lord of the Kretans answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.266#'Son of Atreus, I will in truth be a staunch companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.267#in arms, as first I promised you and bent my head to it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.268#Rouse up rather the rest of the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.269#so that we may fight in all speed, since the Trojans have broken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.270#their oaths: a thing that shall be death and sorrow hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.271#to them, since they were the first to do violence over the oaths sworn.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.272#So he spoke, and Atreides, cheerful at heart, went onward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.273#On his way through the thronging men he came to the Aiantes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.274#These were armed, and about them went a cloud of foot-soldiers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.275#As from his watching place a goatherd watches a cloud move
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.276#on its way over the sea before the drive of the west wind;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.277#far away though he be he watches it, blacker than pitch is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.278#moving across the sea and piling the storm before it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.279#and as he sees it he shivers and drives his flocks to a cavern;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.280#so about the two Aiantes moved the battalions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.281#close-compacted of strong and god-supported young fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.282#black, and jagged with spear and shield, to the terror of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.283#Agamemnon the lord of men was glad when he looked at them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.284#and he spoke aloud to them and addressed them in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.285#'Aiantes, o leaders of the bronze-armoured Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.286#to you two I give no orders; it would not become me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.287#to speed you, now that yourselves drive your people on to fight strongly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.288#Father Zeus, and Athene, and Apollo, if only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.289#such a spirit were in the hearts of all of my people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.290#Then perhaps the city of lord Priam would be bent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.291#underneath our hands, captured and utterly taken.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.292#So he spoke, and left them there, and went among others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.293#There he came upon Nestor, the lucid speaker of Pylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.294#setting in order his own companions and urging them to battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.295#tall Pelagon with those about him, Alastor and Chromios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.296#Haimon the powerful, and Bias, shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.297#First he ranged the mounted men with their horses and chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.298#and stationed the brave and numerous foot-soldiers behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.299#to be the bastion of battle, and drove the cowards to the centre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.300#so that a man might be forced to fight even though unwilling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.301#First he gave orders to the drivers of horses, and warned them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.302#to hold their horses in check and not be fouled in the multitude:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.303#'Let no man in the pride of his horsemanship and his manhood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.304#dare to fight alone with the Trojans in front of the rest of us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.305#neither let him give ground, since that way you will be weaker.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.306#When a man from his own car encounters the enemy chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.307#let him stab with his spear, since this is the stronger fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.308#So the men before your time sacked tower and city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.309#keeping a spirit like this in their hearts, and like this their purpose.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.310#Thus the old man wise in fighting from of old encouraged them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.311#Agamemnon the lord of men was glad when he looked at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.312#and he spoke aloud to him and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.313#'Aged sir, if only, as the spirit is in your bosom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.314#so might your knees be also and the strength stay steady within you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.315#but age weakens you which comes to all; if only some other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.316#of the fighters had your age and you were one of the young men!'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.317#Nestor the Gerenian horseman spoke and answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.318#'Son of Atreus, so would I also wish to be that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.319#man I was, when I cut down brilliant Ereuthalion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.320#But the gods give to mortals not everything at the same time;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.321#if I was a young man then, now in turn old age is upon me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.322#Yet even so I shall be among the riders, and command them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.323#with word and counsel; such is the privilege of the old men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.324#The young spearmen shall do the spear-fighting, those who are born
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.325#of a generation later than mine, who trust in their own strength.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.326#So he spoke, and Atreides, cheerful at heart, went onward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.327#He came on the son of Peteos, Menestheus, driver of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.328#standing still, and about him the Athenians, urgent for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.329#Next to these resourceful Odysseus had taken position,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.330#and beside him the Kephallenian ranks, no weak ones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.331#were standing, since the men had not heard the clamour of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.332#but even now fresh set in motion moved the battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.333#of Achaians and Trojans, breakers of horses; so these standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.334#waited, until some other mass of Achaians advancing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.335#might crash against the Trojans, and the battle be opened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.336#Seeing these the lord of men Agamemnon scolded them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.337#and spoke aloud to them and addressed them in winged words, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.338#'Son of Peteos, the king supported of God: and you, too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.339#you with your mind forever on profit and your ways of treachery,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.340#why do you stand here skulking aside, and wait for the others?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.341#For you two it is becoming to stand among the foremost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.342#fighters, and endure your share of the blaze of battle;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.343#since indeed you two are first to hear of the feasting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.344#whenever we Achaians make ready a feast of the princes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.345#There it is your pleasure to eat the roast flesh, to drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.346#as much as you please the cups of the wine that is sweet as honey.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.347#Now, though, you would be pleased to look on though ten battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.348#of Achaians were to fight with the pitiless bronze before you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.349#Then looking at him darkly resourceful Odysseus spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.350#'What is this word that broke through the fence of your teeth, Atreides?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.351#How can you say that, when we Achaians waken the bitter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.352#war god on Trojans, breakers of horses, I hang back from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.353#fighting? Only watch, if you care to and if it concerns you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.354#the very father of Telemachos locked with the champion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.355#Trojans, breakers of horses. Your talk is wind, and no meaning.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.356#Powerful Agamemnon in turn answered him, laughing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.357#seeing that he was angered and taking back the word spoken:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.358#'Son of Laertes and seed of Zeus, resourceful Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.359#I must not be niggling with you, nor yet give you orders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.360#since I know how the spirit in your secret heart knows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.361#ideas of kindness only; for what you think is what I think.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.362#Come now, I will make it good hereafter, if anything evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.363#has been said; let the gods make all this come to nothing.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.364#So he spoke, and left him there, and went among others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.365#He came on the son of Tydeus, high-spirited Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.366#standing among the compacted chariots and by the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.367#and Kapaneus' son, Sthenelos, was standing beside him. At sight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.368#of Diomedes the lord of men Agamemnon scolded him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.369#and spoke aloud to him and addressed him in winged words, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.370#'Ah me, son of Tydeus, that daring breaker of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.371#why are you skulking and spying out the outworks of battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.372#Such was never Tydeus' way, to lurk in the background,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.373#but to fight the enemy far ahead of his own companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.374#So they say who had seen him at work, since I never saw nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.375#encountered him ever; but they say he surpassed all others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.376#Once on a time he came, but not in war, to Mykenai
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.377#with godlike Polyneikes, a guest and a friend, assembling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.378#people, since these were attacking the sacred bastions of Thebe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.379#and much they entreated us to grant him renowned companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.380#And our men wished to give them and were assenting to what they asked for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.381#but Zeus turned them back, showing forth portents that crossed them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.382#Now as these went forward and were well on their way, and came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.383#to the river Asopos, and the meadows of grass and the deep rushes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.384#from there the Achaians sent Tydeus ahead with a message.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.385#He went then and came on the Kadmeians in their numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.386#feasting all about the house of mighty Eteokles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.387#There, stranger though he was, the driver of horses, Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.388#was not frightened, alone among so many Kadmeians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.389#but dared them to try their strength with him, and bested all of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.390#easily, such might did Pallas Athene give him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.391#The Kadmeians who lash their horses, in anger compacted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.392#an ambuscade of guile on his way home, assembling together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.393#fifty fighting men, and for these there were two leaders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.394#Maion, Haimon's son, in the likeness of the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.395#with the son of Autophonos, Polyphontes stubborn in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.396#On these men Tydeus let loose a fate that was shameful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.397#He killed them all, except that he let one man get home again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.398#letting Maion go in obedience to the god's signs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.399#This was Tydeus, the Aitolian; yet he was father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.400#to a son worse than himself at fighting, better in conclave.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.401#So he spoke, and strong Diomedes gave no answer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.402#in awe before the majesty of the king's rebuking;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.403#but the son of Kapaneus the glorious answered him, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.404#'Son of Atreus, do not lie when you know the plain truth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.405#We two claim we are better men by far than our fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.406#We did storm the seven-gated foundation of Thebe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.407#though we led fewer people beneath a wall that was stronger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.408#We obeyed the signs of the gods and the help Zeus gave us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.409#while those others died of their own headlong stupidity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.410#Therefore, never liken our fathers to us in honour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.411#Then looking at him darkly strong Diomedes spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.412#'Friend, stay quiet rather and do as I tell you; I will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.413#find no fault with Agamemnon, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.414#for stirring thus into battle the strong-greaved Achaians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.415#this will be his glory to come, if ever the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.416#cut down the men of Troy and capture sacred Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.417#If the Achaians are slain, then his will be the great sorrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.418#Come, let you and me remember our fighting courage.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.419#He spoke and leapt in all his gear to the ground from the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.420#and the bronze armour girt to the chest of the king clashed terribly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.421#as he sprang. Fear would have gripped even a man stout-hearted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.422#As when along the thundering beach the surf of the sea strikes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.423#beat upon beat as the west wind drives it onward; far out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.424#cresting first on the open water, it drives thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:4.425#to smash roaring along the dry land, and against the rock jut
