urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.85#but you could not have told on which side Tydeus' son was fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.86#whether he were one with the Trojans or with the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.87#since he went storming up the plain like a winter-swollen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.88#river in spate that scatters the dikes in its running current,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.89#one that the strong-compacted dikes can contain no longer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.90#neither the mounded banks of the blossoming vineyards hold it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.91#rising suddenly as Zeus' rain makes heavy the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.92#and many lovely works of the young men crumble beneath it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.93#Like these the massed battalions of the Trojans were scattered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.94#by Tydeus' son, and many as they were could not stand against him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.95#Now as the shining son of Lykaon, Pandaros, watched him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.96#storming up the plain scattering the battalions before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.97#at once he strained the bent bow against the son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.98#and shot, and hit him as he charged forward, in the right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.99#at the hollow of the corselet; and the bitter arrow went straight through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.100#holding clean to its way, and the corselet was all blood-spattered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.101#And the shining son of Lykaon cried aloud in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.102#'Rise up, Trojans, o high-hearted, lashers of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.103#Now the best of the Achaians is hit, and I think that he will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.104#long hold up under the strong arrow, if truly Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.105#lord and son of Zeus stirred me to come forth from Lykia.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.106#So he spoke, vaunting, but the swift arrow had not broken him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.107#only he drew back again to his chariot and horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.108#and stood there, speaking to Sthenelos, son of Kapaneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.109#'Come, dear friend, son of Kapaneus, step down from the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.110#so that you may pull out from my shoulder this bitter arrow.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.111#So he spoke, and Sthenelos sprang to the ground from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.112#and standing beside him pulled the sharp arrow clean through his shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.113#and the blood shot up spurting through the delicate tunic.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.114#Now Diomedes of the great war cry spoke aloud, praying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.115#'Hear me now, Atrytone, daughter of Zeus of the aegis:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.116#if ever before in kindliness you stood by my father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.117#through the terror of fighting, be my friend now also, Athene;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.118#grant me that I may kill this man and come within spearcast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.119#who shot me before I could see him, and now boasts over me, saying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.120#I cannot live to look much longer on the shining sunlight.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.121#So he spoke in prayer, and Pallas Athene heard him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.122#She made his limbs light again, and his feet, and his hands above them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.123#and standing close beside him she spoke and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.124#'Be of good courage now, Diomedes, to fight with the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.125#since I have put inside your chest the strength of your father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.126#untremulous, such as the horseman Tydeus of the great shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.127#had; I have taken away the mist from your eyes, that before now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.128#was there, so that you may well recognize the god and the mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.129#Therefore now, if a god making trial of you comes hither
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.130#do you not do battle head on with the gods immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.131#not with the rest; but only if Aphrodite, Zeus' daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.132#comes to the fighting, her at least you may stab with the sharp bronze.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.133#She spoke thus, grey-eyed Athene, and went, while Tydeus'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.134#son closed once again with the champions, taking his place there;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.135#raging as he had been before to fight with the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.136#now the strong rage tripled took hold of him, as of a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.137#whom the shepherd among his fleecy flocks in the wild lands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.138#grazed as he leapt the fence of the fold, but has not killed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.139#but only stirred up the lion's strength, and can no more fight him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.140#off, but hides in the steading, and the frightened sheep are forsaken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.141#and these are piled pell-mell on each other in heaps, while the lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.142#raging still leaps out again over the fence of the deep yard;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.143#such was the rage of strong Diomedes as he closed with the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.144#Next he killed Astynoös and Hypeiron, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.145#striking one with the bronze-heeled spear above the nipple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.146#and cutting the other beside the shoulder through the collar-bone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.147#with the great sword, so that neck and back were hewn free of the shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.148#He left these men, and went on after Polyidos and Abas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.149#sons of the aged dream-interpreter, Eurydamas;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.150#yet for these two as they went forth the old man did not answer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.151#their dreams, but Diomedes the powerful slew them. Now he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.152#went after the two sons of Phainops, Xanthos and Thoön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.153#full grown both, but Phainops was stricken in sorrowful old age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.154#nor could breed another son to leave among his possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.155#There he killed these two and took away the dear life from them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.156#both, leaving to their father lamentation and sorrowful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.157#affliction, since he was not to welcome them home from the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.158#alive still; and remoter kinsmen shared his possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.159#Next he killed two children of Dardanian Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.160#who were in a single chariot, Echemmon and Chromios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.161#As among cattle a lion leaps on the neck of an ox or
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.162#heifer, that grazes among the wooded places, and breaks it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.163#so the son of Tydeus hurled both from their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.164#hatefully, in spite of their struggles, then stripped their armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.165#and gave the horses to his company to drive to their vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.166#Now as Aineias saw him wrecking the ranks of warriors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.167#he went on his way through the fighting and the spears' confusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.168#looking to see if he could find Pandaros the godlike;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.169#and he came upon the strong and blameless son of Lykaon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.170#He stood before him face to face and spoke a word to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.171#'Pandaros, where now are your bow and your feathered arrows;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.172#where your fame, in which no man here dare contend with you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.173#nor can any man in Lykia claim he is better?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.174#Come then, hold up your hands to Zeus, and let go an arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.175#at this strong man, whoever he be, who does so much evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.176#to the Trojans, since many and great are those whose knees he has broken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.177#Unless this be some god who in wrath with the Trojans for offerings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.178#failed afflicts them. The wrath of a god is hard to deal with.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.179#Then in answer the shining son of Lykaon spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.180#'Aineias, charged with the counsels of the bronze-armoured Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.181#I liken him in all ways to the valiant son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.182#going by his shield and the hollow eyes of his helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.183#and by the look of his horses; but it may be a god, I am not sure;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.184#and if this is a man, as I think, and the valiant son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.185#of Tydeus, yet not without god does he rage so, but some one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.186#of the immortals, mantling in mist his shoulders, stands close beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.187#who turned my flying arrow as it struck, elsewhere, away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.188#For I have shot my shaft already, and hit him in the shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.189#the right one, hard driven through the hollow of his corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.190#and I said to myself I had hurled him down to meet Aidoneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.191#yet still I have not beaten him; now this is some god who is angered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.192#But I have no horses nor chariot I could mount in, and yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.193#somewhere in the great house of Lykaon are eleven chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.194#beauties, all new made, just finished, and over them blankets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.195#lie spread, and beside each chariot one brace of horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.196#stand there, champing their white barley and oats. But Lykaon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.197#the aged spearman spoke to me over and over, as I was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.198#on my way from the house well compacted, advising me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.199#he told me to take my horses and chariots, and riding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.200#there to be lord among the Trojans in the strong encounters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.201#I did not let him persuade me, and that would have been far better,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.202#sparing my horses, who had grown accustomed to eating all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.203#they wished, from going hungry where the men were penned in a small place.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.204#So I left them and made my way on foot to Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.205#trusting my bow, a thing that was to profit me nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.206#For now I have drawn it against two of their best men, Tydeus'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.207#son, and the son of Atreus, and both of these I hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.208#and drew visible blood, yet only wakened their anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.209#So it was in bad luck that I took from its peg the curved bow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.210#on that day when I carried it to lovely Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.211#at the head of my Trojans, bringing delight to brilliant Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.212#Now if ever I win home again and lay eyes once more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.213#on my country, and my wife, and the great house with the high roof,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.214#let some stranger straightway cut my head from my shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.215#if I do not break this bow in my hands and throw it in the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.216#fire, since as a wind and nothing I have taken it with me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.217#Then in turn Aineias, lord of the Trojans, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.218#'Speak no more this way; there will be no time for changing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.219#before you and I must face this man with horses and chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.220#and strength against strength fight it out with our weapons. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.221#mount rather into my chariot, so that you may see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.222#what the Trojan horses are like, how they understand their
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.223#plain, and how to traverse it in rapid pursuit and withdrawal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.224#These two will bring us safe to the city again, if once more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.225#Zeus grants glory to Diomedes the son of Tydeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.226#Come then, taking into your hands the goad and the glittering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.227#reins, while I dismount from my chariot and carry the fighting;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.228#or else yourself encounter this man, while I handle the horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.229#Then in answer the shining son of Lykaon spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.230#'Keep yourself, Aineias, the reins and your horses. These will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.231#carry better the curved chariot under the driver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.232#they know best, if we must give way before the son of Tydeus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.233#for fear they might go wild with terror and not be willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.234#to carry us out of the fighting, as they listen and long for your voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.235#for fear the son of high-hearted Tydeus charging upon us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.236#might kill us both and drive away the single-foot horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.237#Rather drive yourself your own horses and your own chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.238#while with my sharp spear I encounter this man as he comes on.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.239#They spoke so, and mounting the wrought chariot held
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.240#their fast-running horses against the son of Tydeus, in fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.241#And Sthenelos the shining son of Kapaneus seeing them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.242#swiftly uttered his winged words to the son of Tydeus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.243#'Son of Tydeus, you who delight my heart, Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.244#look, I see two mighty men furious to fight with you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.245#Their strength is enormous, one of them well skilled in the bow's work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.246#Pandaros, who claims his right as son of Lykaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.247#and the other Aineias, who claims he was born as son to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.248#Anchises the blameless, but his mother was Aphrodite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.249#Come then, let us give way with our horses; no longer storm on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.250#so far among the champions, for fear you destroy your heart's life.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.251#Then looking at him darkly strong Diomedes spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.252#'Argue me not toward flight, since I have no thought of obeying you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.253#No, for it would be ignoble for me to shrink back in the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.254#or to lurk aside, since my fighting strength stays steady forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.255#I shrink indeed from mounting behind the horses, but as I am
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.256#now, I will face these. Pallas Athene will not let me run from them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.257#These two men, their fast-running horses shall never carry them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.258#both back away from us, even though one man may escape us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.259#And put away in your thoughts this other thing I tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.260#If Athene of the many counsels should grant me the glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.261#to kill both, then do you check here these fast-running horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.262#ours, tethering them with the reins tied to the chariot's rail and thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.263#remember to make a dash against the horses of Aineias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.264#and drive them away from the Trojans among the strong-greaved Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.265#These are of that strain which Zeus of the wide brows granted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.266#once to Tros, recompense for his son Ganymedes, and therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.267#are the finest of all horses beneath the sun and the daybreak;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.268#and the lord of men Anchises stole horses from this breed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.269#without the knowledge of Laomedon putting mares under them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.270#From these there was bred for him a string of six in his great house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.271#Four of these, keeping them himself, he raised at his mangers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.272#but these two he gave to Aineias, two horses urgent of terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.273#If we might only take these we should win ourselves excellent glory.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.274#Now as these were speaking things like this to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.275#the two came fast upon them driving their swift-running horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.276#First to Diomedes called out the shining son of Lykaon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.277#'Valiant and strong-spirited, o son of proud Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.278#you were not beaten then by the bitter arrow, my swift shot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.279#Now I will try with the throwing-spear to see if I can hit you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.280#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far-shadowed, and threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.281#and struck the son of Tydeus in the shield, and the flying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.282#bronze spearhead was driven clean through and into the corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.283#and the shining son of Lykaon cried aloud in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.284#'Now are you struck clean through the middle, and I think that you will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.285#hold up for much longer; you have given me great claim to glory.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.286#Then strong Diomedes answered, not frightened before him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.287#'You did not hit me, you missed, but I do not think that you two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.288#will go free until one or the other of you has fallen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.289#to glut with his blood Ares the god who fights under the shield's guard.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.290#He spoke, and threw; and Pallas Athene guided the weapon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.291#to the nose next to the eye, and it cut on through the white teeth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.292#and the bronze weariless shore all the way through the tongue's base
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.293#so that the spearhead came out underneath the jawbone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.294#He dropped then from the chariot and his armour clattered upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.295#dazzling armour and shining, while those fast-running horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.296#shied away, and there his life and his strength were scattered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.297#But Aineias sprang to the ground with shield and with long spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.298#for fear that somehow the Achaians might haul off the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.299#and like a lion in the pride of his strength stood over him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.300#holding before him the perfect circle of his shield and the spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.301#and raging to cut down any man who might come to face him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.302#crying a terrible cry. But Tydeus' son in his hand caught
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.303#up a stone, a huge thing which no two men could carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.304#such as men are now, but by himself he lightly hefted it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.305#He threw, and caught Aineias in the hip, in the place where the hip-bone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.306#turns inside the thigh, the place men call the cup-socket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.307#It smashed the cup-socket and broke the tendons both sides of it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.308#and the rugged stone tore the skin backward, so that the fighter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.309#dropping to one knee stayed leaning on the ground with his heavy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.310#hand, and a covering of black night came over both eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.311#Now in this place Aineias lord of men might have perished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.312#had not Aphrodite, Zeus' daughter, been quick to perceive him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.313#his mother, who had borne him to Anchises the ox-herd;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.314#and about her beloved son came streaming her white arms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.315#and with her white robe thrown in a fold in front she shielded him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.316#this keeping off the thrown weapons lest some fast-mounted Danaan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.317#strike the bronze spear through his chest and strip the life from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.318#She then carried her beloved son out of the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.319#Nor did Sthenelos son of Kapaneus forget the commandments
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.320#that Diomedes of the great war cry had laid upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.321#but he held where they were their own single-foot horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.322#with their reins tied to the chariot rail, apart from the confusion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.323#and making a dash for the fluttering-maned horses of Aineias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.324#drove them away from the Trojans among the strong-greaved Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.325#and gave them to Deïpylos, his close friend, whom beyond all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.326#others of his own age he prized, for their hearts were intimate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.327#to drive away to the hollow ships; meanwhile the warrior
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.328#mounted behind his own horses and caught up the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.329#reins, and held the strong-footed team toward the son of Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.330#headlong; and he swung the pitiless bronze at the lady of Kypros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.331#knowing her for a god without warcraft, not of those who,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.332#goddesses, range in order the ranks of men in the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.333#not Athene and not Enyo, sacker of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.334#Now as, following her through the thick crowd, he caught her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.335#lunging in his charge far forward the son of high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.336#Tydeus made a thrust against the soft hand with the bronze spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.337#and the spear tore the skin driven clean on through the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.338#robe that the very Graces had woven for her carefully,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.339#over the palm's base; and blood immortal flowed from the goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.340#ichor, that which runs in the veins of the blessed divinities;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.341#since these eat no food, nor do they drink of the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.342#wine, and therefore they have no blood and are called immortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.343#She gave a great shriek and let fall her son she was carrying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.344#but Phoibos Apollo caught him up and away in his own hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.345#in a dark mist, for fear that some fast-mounted Danaan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.346#might strike the bronze spear through his chest and strip the life from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.347#But Diomedes of the great war cry shouted after her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.348#'Give way, daughter of Zeus, from the fighting and the terror. It is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.349#not then enough that you lead astray women without warcraft?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.350#Yet, if still you must haunt the fighting, I think that now you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.351#will shiver even when you hear some other talking of battles.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.352#So he spoke, and the goddess departed in pain, hurt badly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.353#and Iris wind-footed took her by the hand and led her away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.354#from the battle, her lovely skin blood-darkened, wounded and suffering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.355#There to the left of the fighting she found Ares the violent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.356#sitting, his spear leaned into the mist, and his swift horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.357#Dropping on one knee before her beloved brother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.358#in deep supplication she asked for his gold-bridled horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.359#'Beloved brother, rescue me and give me your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.360#so I may come to Olympos where is the place of the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.361#I am in too much pain from the wound of a mortal's spear-stroke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.362#Tydeus' son's, who would fight now even against Zeus father.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.363#So she spoke, and Ares gave her the gold-bridled horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.364#and, still grieved in the inward heart, she mounted the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.365#and beside her entering Iris gathered the reins up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.366#and whipped them into a run, and they winged their way unreluctant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.367#Now as they came to sheer Olympos, the place of the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.368#there swift Iris the wind-footed reined in her horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.369#and slipped them from the yoke and threw fodder immortal before them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.370#and now bright Aphrodite fell at the knees of her mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.371#Dione, who gathered her daughter into the arms' fold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.372#and stroked her with her hand and called her by name and spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.373#'Who now of the Uranian gods, dear child, has done such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.374#things to you, rashly, as if you were caught doing something wicked?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.375#Aphrodite the sweetly laughing spoke then and answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.376#'Tydeus' son Diomedes, the too high-hearted, stabbed me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.377#as I was carrying my own beloved son out of the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.378#Aineias, who beyond all else in the world is dear to me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.379#so now this is no horrible war of Achaians and Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.380#but the Danaans are beginning to fight even with the immortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.381#Then Dione the shining among divinities answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.382#'Have patience, my child, and endure it, though you be saddened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.383#For many of us who have our homes on Olympos endure things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.384#from men, when ourselves we inflict hard pain on each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.385#Ares had to endure it when strong Ephialtes and Otos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.386#sons of Aloeus, chained him in bonds that were too strong for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.387#and three months and ten he lay chained in the brazen cauldron;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.388#and now might Ares, insatiable of fighting, have perished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.389#had not Eëriboia, their stepmother, the surpassingly lovely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.390#brought word to Hermes, who stole Ares away out of it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.391#as he was growing faint and the hard bondage was breaking him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.392#Hera had to endure it when the strong son of Amphitryon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.393#struck her beside the right breast with a tri-barbed arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.394#so that the pain he gave her could not be quieted. Hades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.395#the gigantic had to endure with the rest the flying arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.396#when this self-same man, the son of Zeus of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.397#struck him among the dead men at Pylos, and gave him to agony;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.398#but he went up to the house of Zeus and to tall Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.399#heavy at heart, stabbed through and through with pain, for the arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.400#was driven into his heavy shoulder, and his spirit was suffering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.401#But Paiëon, scattering medicines that still pain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.402#healed him, since he was not made to be one of the mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.403#Brute, heavy-handed, who thought nothing of the bad he was doing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.404#who with his archery hurt the gods that dwell on Olympos!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.405#It was the goddess grey-eyed Athene who drove on this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.406#against you; poor fool, the heart of Tydeus' son knows nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.407#of how that man who fights the immortals lives for no long time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.408#his children do not gather to his knees to welcome their father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.409#when he returns home after the fighting and the bitter warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.410#Then, though he be very strong indeed, let the son of Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.411#take care lest someone even better than he might fight with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.412#lest for a long time Aigialeia, wise child of Adrastos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.413#mourning wake out of sleep her household's beloved companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.414#longing for the best of the Achaians, her lord by marriage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.415#she, the strong wife of Diomedes, breaker of horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.416#She spoke, and with both hands stroked away from her arm the ichor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.417#so that the arm was made whole again and the strong pains rested.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.418#But Hera and Athene glancing aside at her began
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.419#to tease the son of Kronos, Zeus, in words of mockery:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.420#and the goddess grey-eyed Athene began the talk among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.421#'Father Zeus, would you be angry with me if I said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.422#something? It must be the lady of Kypros, moving some woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.423#of Achaia to follow after those Trojans she loves so hopelessly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.424#laying hold on the fair dresses of the Achaian women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.425#tore the tenderness of her hand on a golden pin's point.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.426#So she spoke, and the father of gods and men smiled on her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.427#and spoke to Aphrodite the golden, calling her to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.428#'No, my child, not for you are the works of warfare. Rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.429#concern yourself only with the lovely secrets of marriage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.430#while all this shall be left to Athene and sudden Ares.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.431#Now as these were talking in this way with each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.432#Diomedes of the great war cry made for Aineias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.433#Though he saw how Apollo himself held his hands over him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.434#he did not shrink even from the great god, but forever forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.435#drove, to kill Aineias and strip his glorious armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.436#Three times, furious to cut him down, he drove forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.437#and three times Apollo battered aside the bright shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.438#but as a fourth time, like more than man, he charged, Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.439#who strikes from afar cried out to him in the voice of terror:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.440#'Take care, give back, son of Tydeus, and strive no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.441#to make yourself like the gods in mind, since never the same is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.442#the breed of gods, who are immortal, and men who walk groundling.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.443#He spoke, and Tydeus' son gave backward, only a little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.444#avoiding the anger of him who strikes from afar, Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.445#who caught Aineias now away from the onslaught, and set him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.446#in the sacred keep of Pergamos where was built his own temple.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.447#There Artemis of the showering arrows and Leto within
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.448#the great and secret chamber healed his wound and cared for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.449#But he of the silver bow, Appollo, fashioned an image
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.450#in the likeness of Aineias himself and in armour like him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.451#and all about this image brilliant Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.452#hewed at each other, and at the ox-hide shields strong circled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.453#guarding men's chests, and at the fluttering straps of the guard-skins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.454#But Phoibos Apollo spoke now to violent Ares:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.455#'Ares, Ares, manslaughtering, blood-stained, stormer of strong walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.456#is there no way you can go and hold back this man from the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.457#Tydeus' son, who would now do battle against Zeus father?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.458#Even now he stabbed in her hand by the wrist the lady
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.459#of Kypros, and again, like more than a man, charged even against me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.460#So he spoke, and himself alighted on the peak of Pergamos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.461#while stark Ares went down to stir the ranks of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.462#in the likeness of the lord of the Thracians, swift-footed Akamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.463#and urged onward the god-supported children of Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.464#'O you children of Priam, the king whom the gods love, how long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.465#will you allow the Achaians to go on killing your people?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.466#Until they fight beside the strong-builded gates? A man lies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.467#fallen whom we honoured as we honour Hektor the brilliant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.468#Aineias, who is son of great-hearted Anchises.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.469#Come then, let us rescue our good companion from the carnage.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.470#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit and the strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.471#Then Sarpedon spoke in abuse to brilliant Hektor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.472#'Where now, Hektor, has gone that strength that was yours? You said once
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.473#that without companions and without people you could hold this city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.474#alone, with only your brothers and the lords of your sisters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.475#I can see not one of these men now, I know not where they are;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.476#no, but they slink away like hounds who circle the lion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.477#while we, who are here as your companions, carry the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.478#I have come, a companion to help you, from a very far place;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.479#Lykia lies far away, by the whirling waters of Xanthos;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.480#there I left behind my own wife and my baby son, there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.481#I left my many possessions which the needy man eyes longingly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.482#Yet even so I drive on my Lykians, and myself have courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.483#to fight my man in battle, though there is nothing of mine here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.484#that the Achaians can carry away as spoil or drive off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.485#But you: you stand here, not even giving the word to the rest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.486#of your people to stand fast and fight in defence of their own wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.487#Let not yourselves, caught as in the sweeping toils of the spun net,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.488#be taken as war-spoil and plunder by the men who hate you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.489#men who presently will storm your strong-founded citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.490#All these things should lie night and day on your mind, forever,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.491#supplication to the lords of your far-renowned companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.492#to fight unwearying and hold off the strength of an insult.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.493#Sarpedon spoke, and his word bit into the heart of Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.494#Straightway in all his armour he sprang to the ground from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.495#and shaking two sharp spears ranged everywhere through the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.496#stirring men up to fight and waking the hateful warfare;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.497#and these pulled themselves about and stood to face the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.498#while the Argives held in their close order and would not be broken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.499#As when along the hallowed threshing floors the wind scatters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.500#chaff, among men winnowing, and fair-haired Demeter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.501#in the leaning wind discriminates the chaff and the true grain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.502#and the piling chaff whitens beneath it, so now the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.503#turned white underneath the dust the feet of the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.504#drove far into the brazen sky across their faces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.505#as they rapidly closed and the charioteers wheeled back again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.506#They drove the strength of their hands straight on, as violent Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.507#defending the Trojans mantled in dark night the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.508#and passed everywhere, since he was carrying out the commandments
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.509#of Phoibos Apollo, him of the golden sword, who had bidden him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.510#wake the heart in the Trojans as he saw that Pallas Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.511#was gone away now, she who stood to defend the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.512#And out of the rich secret chamber Apollo sent forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.513#Aineias, and dropped strength in the heart of the people's shepherd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.514#So Aineias stood among his friends, who were happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.515#as they saw him coming back, still alive, and unwounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.516#and full of brave spirit; yet they asked him no question,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.517#for the rest of their fighting work would not let them, that the silver-bow god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.518#woke, and manslaughtering Ares, and Hate, whose wrath is relentless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.519#Now the two Aiantes and Odysseus and Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.520#stirred the Danaans to fight these; since themselves they did not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.521#fear the force of the men of Troy nor their charges onward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.522#but stayed where they were, like clouds, which the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.523#stops in the windless weather on the heights of the towering mountains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.524#motionless, when the strength of the north wind sleeps, and the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.525#tearing winds, those winds that when they blow into tempests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.526#high screaming descend upon the darkening clouds and scatter them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.527#So the Danaans stood steady against the Trojans, nor gave way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.528#And Atreus' son ranged through the masses with his many orders:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.529#'Be men now, dear friends, and take up the heart of courage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.530#and have consideration for each other in the strong encounters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.531#since more come through alive when men consider each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.532#and there is no glory when they give way, nor warcraft either.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.533#He spoke, and made a swift cast with his spear, and struck down a great man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.534#Deïkoön, companion of high-hearted Aineias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.535#Pergasos' son, whom the Trojans honoured as they honoured Priam's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.536#children, since he was a swift man to fight in the foremost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.537#Powerful Agamemnon struck his shield with spear, nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.538#could the shield hold off the spear, but the bronze smashed clean through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.539#and was driven on through the belt to the deep of the belly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.540#He fell, thunderously, and his armour clattered upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.541#Now Aineias killed two great men of the Danaans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.542#the sons of Diokles, Orsilochos and Krethon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.543#men whose father dwelt in Phere the strong-founded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.544#rich in substance, and his generation was of the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.545#Alpheios, who flows wide through the country of the Pylians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.546#and who got a son, Ortilochos, to be lord over many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.547#men, but the son of Ortilochos was high-hearted Diokles;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.548#and to Diokles in his turn were two twin sons born,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.549#Orsilochos and Krethon, both well skilled in all fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.550#These two as they were grown to young manhood followed along with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.551#the Argives in their black ships to Ilion, land of good horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.552#winning honour for the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.553#and Menelaos; now fulfilment of death was a darkness upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.554#These, as two young lions in the high places of the mountains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.555#had been raised by their mother in the dark of the deep forest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.556#lions which as they prey upon the cattle and the fat sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.557#lay waste the steadings where there are men, until they also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.558#fall and are killed under the cutting bronze in the men's hands;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.559#such were these two who beaten under the hands of Aineias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.560#crashed now to the ground as if they were two tall pine trees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.561#As these fell warlike Menelaos took pity on them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.562#and he strode out among the champions, helmed in bright bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.563#shaking his spear, and the fury of Ares drove him onward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.564#minded that he might go down under the hands of Aineias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.565#But Antilochos, son of high-hearted Nestor, watched him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.566#and he strode among the champions in fear for the shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.567#lest he be hurt, and all their labour slip away into nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.568#So as Aineias and Menelaos raised hand and sharp spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.569#standing to face each other and furious to do battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.570#Antilochos took his stand close beside the shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.571#Nor did Aineias hold his ground, though yet a swift fighter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.572#as he saw two men staying with each other against him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.573#These, when they had dragged back the bodies among the Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.574#people, dropped the poor youths into the hands of their company,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.575#and themselves wheeled about once more to fight among the foremost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.576#There these killed Pylaimenes the equal of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.577#lord of the Paphlagonian men in armour, high-hearted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.578#Menelaos the spear-famed, son of Atreus, stabbed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.579#with the spear as he stood his ground, and struck the collar-bone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.580#while Antilochos struck down Mydon, his charioteer and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.581#henchman, Atymnios' brave son, as he wheeled the single-foot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.582#horses about, with a stone striking mid-elbow, and from his
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.583#hands the reins pale with ivory dropped in the dust groundling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.584#Antilochos charging drove the sword into his temple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.585#so that gasping he dropped from the carefully wrought chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.586#headlong, driven deep in the dust his neck and shoulders;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.587#and there, since he chanced to light in a depth of sand, he stuck fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.588#while his horses trampled him into the dust with their feet. These
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.589#Antilochos lashed and drove back into the host of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.590#Hektor saw them across the ranks, and drove on against them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.591#crying aloud, and with him followed the Trojan battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.592#in their strength; and Ares led them with the goddess Enyo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.593#she carrying with her the turmoil of shameless hatred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.594#while Ares made play in his hands with the spear gigantic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.595#and ranged now in front of Hektor and now behind him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.596#Diomedes of the great war cry shivered as he saw him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.597#and like a man in his helplessness who, crossing a great plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.598#stands at the edge of a fast-running river that dashes seaward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.599#and watches it thundering into white water, and leaps a pace backward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.600#so now Tydeus' son gave back, and spoke to his people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.601#'Friends, although we know the wonder of glorious Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.602#to be a fighter with the spear and a bold man of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.603#yet there goes ever some god beside him, who beats off destruction,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.604#and now, in the likeness of a man mortal, Ares goes with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.605#Come then, keeping your faces turned to the Trojans, give ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.606#backward, nor be we eager to fight in strength with divinities.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.607#He spoke, and now the Trojans had come very close upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.608#There Hektor cut down two men, well skilled in warcraft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.609#Anchialos and Menesthes both in a single chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.610#As these fell great Telamonian Aias pitied them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.611#and stood close in and made a cast with the shining javelin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.612#and struck Amphios, Selagos' son, who rich in possessions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.613#and rich in cornland had lived in Paisos, but his own destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.614#brought him companion in arms to Priam and the children of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.615#Now Telamonian Aias struck him beneath the war belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.616#and the far-shadowing spear was fixed in the lower belly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.617#and he fell, thunderously, and shining Aias ran forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.618#to strip his armour, but the Trojans showered spears upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.619#sharp spears and glittering, and the great shield caught many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.620#Setting his heel on the chest of the corpse he pulled out the brazen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.621#spear, yet could no longer strip the rest of the glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.622#armour from his shoulders, since he was battered with spears thrown,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.623#and he dreaded the strong circle made by the haughty Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.624#who many and valiant stood over him, gripping their great spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.625#and though he was a mighty man and a strong and a proud one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.626#thrust him away from them so that he gave ground backward staggering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.627#So they went at their work all about the strong encounter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.628#But Herakles' son Tlepolemos the huge and mighty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.629#was driven by his strong destiny against godlike Sarpedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.630#Now as these in their advance had come close together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.631#the own son, and the son's son of Zeus cloud-gathering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.632#it was Tlepolemos of the two who spoke the first word:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.633#'Man of counsel of the Lykians, Sarpedon, why must you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.634#be skulking here, you who are a man unskilled in the fighting?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.635#They are liars who call you issue of Zeus, the holder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.636#of the aegis, since you fall far short in truth of the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.637#who were begotten of Zeus in the generations before us:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.638#such men as, they say, was the great strength of Herakles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.639#my own father, of the daring spirit, the heart of a lion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.640#he came here on a time for the sake of Laomedon's horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.641#with six vessels only and the few men needed to man them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.642#and widowed the streets of Ilion and sacked the city;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.643#but yours is the heart of a coward and your people are dying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.644#And I think that now, though you are come from Lykia, you will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.645#bring no help to the Trojans even though you be a strong man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.646#but beaten down by my hands will pass through the gates of Hades.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.647#In turn the lord of the Lykians, Sarpedon, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.648#'In truth, Tlepolemos, he did destroy Ilion the sacred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.649#through the senselessness of one man, the haughty Laomedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.650#who gave Herakles an evil word in return for good treatment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.651#and would not give up the horses for whose sake he had come from far off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.652#But I tell you, what you will win from me here will be death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.653#and black destruction; and broken under my spear you will give me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.654#glory, and give your soul to Hades of the famed horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.655#So spoke Sarpedon, while the other lifted his ash spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.656#Tlepolemos; and in a single moment the long shafts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.657#shot from their hands, Sarpedon striking him in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.658#of the throat, and the agonizing spear drove clean through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.659#and over his eyes was mantled the covering mist of darkness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.660#But Tlepolemos in turn had struck Sarpedon with the long spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.661#in the left thigh, and the spear smashed on through in fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.662#scraping the bone, but his father fended destruction away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.663#But his brilliant companions carried godlike Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.664#out of the fighting, weighted down as he was by the long spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.665#which dragged, yet not one of them noticed nor took thought,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.666#in their urgency, to pull out of his thigh the ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.667#so he might stand, such hard work did they have attending him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.668#On the other side the strong-greaved Achaians carried Tlepolemos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.669#out of the fighting; but brilliant Odysseus, who held a hardy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.670#spirit, saw what had happened, and his heart within was stirred up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.671#but now he pondered two ways within, in mind and in spirit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.672#whether first to go after the son of Zeus the loud-thundering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.673#or whether he should strip the life from more of the Lykians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.674#Yet, as it was not the destiny of great-hearted Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.675#to kill with sharp bronze the strong son of Zeus, therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.676#Athene steered his anger against the host of the Lykians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.677#And there he killed Koiranos, and Chromios, and Alastor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.678#Halios and Alkandros, and Prytanis and Noemon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.679#And now might brilliant Odysseus have killed yet more of the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.680#had not tall Hektor of the shining helmet sharply perceived him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.681#who strode out among the champions helmed in the bright bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.682#bringing terror to the Danaans; but Zeus' son, Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.683#was glad as he saw him come up, and piteously bespoke him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.684#'Son of Priam, do not leave me lying for the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.685#to prey upon, but protect me, since otherwise in your city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.686#my life must come to an end, since I could return no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.687#back to my own house and the land of my fathers, bringing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.688#joy to my own beloved wife and my son, still a baby.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.689#He spoke, but Hektor of the shining helm did not answer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.690#but swept on past him in his eagerness with all speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.691#to push back the Argives and strip the life out of many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.692#Meanwhile his brilliant companions laid godlike Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.693#under a lovely spreading oak of Zeus of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.694#and strong Pelagon, one of his beloved companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.695#pushed perforce through and out of his thigh the shaft of the ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.696#And the mist mantled over his eyes, and the life left him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.697#but he got his breath back again, and the blast of the north wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.698#blowing brought back to life the spirit gasped out in agony.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.699#But the Argives under the strength of Ares and bronze-armoured Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.700#did not ever turn their backs and make for their black ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.701#nor yet stand up to them in fighting, but always backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.702#gave way, as they saw how Ares went with the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.703#Who then was the first and who the last that they slaughtered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.704#Hektor, Priam's son, and Ares the brazen? Godlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.705#Teuthras first, and next Orestes, driver of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.706#Trechos the spearman of Aitolia and Oinomaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.707#Helenos son of Oinops and Oresbios of the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.708#guard, who had lived in Hyle much concerned with his property
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.709#in a place hard on the Kephisian mere, and beside him other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.710#men of Boiotia lived and held the fine fertile country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.711#Now as the goddess Hera of the white arms perceived how
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.712#the Argives were perishing in the strong encounter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.713#immediately she spoke to Pallas Athene her winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.714#'For shame, now, Atrytone, daughter of Zeus of the aegis:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.715#nothing then meant the word we promised to Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.716#to go home after sacking the strong-walled city of Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.717#if we are to let cursed Ares be so furious.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.718#Come then, let us rather think of our own stark courage.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.719#So she spoke, nor did the goddess grey-eyed Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.720#disobey her. But Hera, high goddess, daughter of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.721#the mighty, went away to harness the gold-bridled horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.722#Then Hebe in speed set about the chariot the curved wheels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.723#eight-spoked and brazen, with an axle of iron both ways.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.724#Golden is the wheel's felly imperishable, and outside it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.725#is joined, a wonder to look upon, the brazen running-rim,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.726#and the silver naves revolve on either side of the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.727#whereas the car itself is lashed fast with plaiting of gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.728#and silver, with double chariot rails that circle about it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.729#and the pole of the chariot is of silver, to whose extremity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.730#Hebe made fast the golden and splendid yoke, and fastened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.731#the harness, golden and splendid, and underneath the yoke Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.732#furious for hate and battle, led the swift-running horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.733#Now in turn Athene, daughter of Zeus of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.734#beside the threshold of her father slipped off her elaborate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.735#dress which she herself had wrought with her hands' patience,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.736#and now assuming the war tunic of Zeus who gathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.737#the clouds, she armed in her gear for the dismal fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.738#And across her shoulders she threw the betasselled, terrible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.739#aegis, all about which Terror hangs like a garland,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.740#and Hatred is there, and Battle Strength, and heart-freezing Onslaught
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.741#and thereon is set the head of the grim gigantic Gorgon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.742#a thing of fear and horror, portent of Zeus of the aegis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.743#Upon her head she set the golden helm with its four sheets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.744#and two horns, wrought with the fighting men of a hundred cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.745#She set her feet in the blazing chariot and took up a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.746#heavy, huge, thick, wherewith she beats down the battalions of fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.747#men, against whom she of mighty father is angered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.748#Hera laid the lash swiftly on the horses; and moving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.749#of themselves groaned the gates of the sky that the Hours guarded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.750#those Hours to whose charge is given the huge sky and Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.751#to open up the dense darkness or again to close it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.752#Through the way between they held the speed of their goaded horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.753#They found the son of Kronos sitting apart from the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.754#gods, upon the highest peak of rugged Olympos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.755#There the goddess of the white arms, Hera, stopping her horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.756#spoke to Zeus, high son of Kronos, and asked him a question:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.757#'Father Zeus, are you not angry with Ares for his violent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.758#acts, for killing so many and such good Achaian warriors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.759#for no reason, and out of due order, to grieve me? And meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.760#Kypris and Apollo of the silver bow take their ease and their pleasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.761#having let loose this maniac who knows nothing of justice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.762#Father Zeus, would you be angry with me if I were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.763#to smite Ares with painful strokes and drive him out of the fighting?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.764#Then in turn the father of gods and men made answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.765#'Go to it then, and set against him the spoiler Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.766#who beyond all others is the one to visit harsh pains upon him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.767#So he spoke, nor did the goddess of the white arms, Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.768#disobey, but lashed on the horses, and they winged their way unreluctant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.769#through the space between the earth and the starry heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.770#As far as into the hazing distance a man can see with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.771#his eyes, who sits in his eyrie gazing on the wine-blue water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.772#as far as this is the stride of the gods' proud neighing horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.773#Now as they came to Troy land and the two running rivers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.774#where Simoeis and Skamandros dash their waters together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.775#there the goddess of the white arms, Hera, stayed her horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.776#slipping them from the chariot, and drifting close mist about them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.777#and Simoeis grew as grass ambrosia for them to graze on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.778#Now these two walked forward in little steps like shivering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.779#doves, in their eagerness to stand by the men of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.780#after they had come to the place where the most and the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.781#stood close huddled about the great strength of the breaker of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.782#Diomedes; in the likeness of lions who rend their meat raw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.783#or wild pigs, boars, in whom the strength diminishes never,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.784#there standing the goddess of the white arms, Hera, shouted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.785#likening herself to high-hearted, bronze-voiced Stentor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.786#who could cry out in as great a voice as fifty other men:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.787#'Shame, you Argives, poor nonentities splendid to look on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.788#In those days when brilliant Achilleus came into the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.789#never would the Trojans venture beyond the Dardanian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.790#gates, so much did they dread the heavy spear of that man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.791#Now they fight by the hollow ships and far from the city.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.792#So she spoke, and stirred the spirit and strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.793#But the goddess grey-eyed Athene made straight for Tydeus'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.794#son, and found the king standing by his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.795#cooling the wound that Pandaros made with the cast of his arrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.796#For the sweat made him sore underneath the broad strap of the circled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.797#shield; this made him sore, and his arm was tired. He held up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.798#the shield-strap, and wiped the dark blot of blood away from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.799#The goddess laid hold of the harnessed horses and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.800#'Tydeus got him a son who is little enough like him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.801#since Tydeus was a small man for stature, but he was a fighter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.802#Even on that time when I would not consent to his fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.803#nor drawing men's eyes, when he went by himself without the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.804#as a messenger to Thebe among all the Kadmeians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.805#then I invited him to feast at his ease in their great halls;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.806#even so, keeping that heart of strength that was always within him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.807#he challenged the young men of the Kadmeians, and defeated all of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.808#easily; such a helper was I who stood then beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.809#Now beside you also I stand and ever watch over you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.810#and urge you to fight confidently with the Trojans. And yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.811#the weariness has entered your limbs from many encounters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.812#or else it is some poor-spirited fear that holds you. If so,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.813#you are no issue then of the son of wise Oineus, Tydeus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.814#Then in answer powerful Diomedes spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.815#'Daughter of Zeus who holds the aegis, goddess, I know you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.816#and therefore will speak confidently to you, and hide nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.817#It is no poor-spirited fear nor shrinking that holds me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.818#Rather I remember the orders you yourself gave me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.819#when you would not let me fight in the face of the blessed immortals--
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.820#the rest of them, except only if Aphrodite, Zeus' daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.821#went into the fighting, I might stab at her with the sharp bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.822#Therefore now have I myself given way, and I ordered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.823#the rest of the Argives all to be gathered in this place beside me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.824#since I see that this who is lord of the fighting is Ares.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.825#Then in turn the goddess grey-eyed Athene answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.826#'Son of Tydeus, you who delight my heart, Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.827#no longer be thus afraid of Ares, nor of any other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.828#immortal; such a helper shall I be standing beside you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.829#Come then, first against Ares steer your single-foot horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.830#and strike him from close. Be not afraid of violent Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.831#that thing of fury, evil-wrought, that double-faced liar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.832#who even now protested to Hera and me, promising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.833#that he would fight against the Trojans and stand by the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.834#Now, all promises forgotten, he stands by the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.835#So speaking she pushed Sthenelos to the ground from the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.836#driving him back with her hand, and he leapt away from it lightly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.837#and she herself, a goddess in her anger, stepped into the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.838#beside brilliant Diomedes, and the oaken axle groaned aloud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.839#under the weight, carrying a dread goddess and a great man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.840#Pallas Athene then took up the whip and the reins, steering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.841#first of all straight on against Ares the single-foot horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.842#Ares was in the act of stripping gigantic Periphas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.843#shining son of Ochesios, far the best of the men of Aitolia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.844#Blood-stained Ares was in the act of stripping him. But Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.845#put on the helm of Death, that stark Ares might not discern her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.846#Now as manslaughtering Ares caught sight of Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.847#the brilliant, he let gigantic Periphas lie in the place where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.848#he had first cut him down and taken the life away from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.849#and made straight against Diomedes, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.850#Now as they in their advance had come close together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.851#Ares lunged first over the yoke and the reins of his horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.852#with the bronze spear, furious to take the life from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.853#But the goddess grey-eyed Athene in her hand catching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.854#the spear pushed it away from the car, so he missed and stabbed vainly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.855#After him Diomedes of the great war cry drove forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.856#with the bronze spear; and Pallas Athene, leaning in on it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.857#drove it into the depth of the belly where the war belt girt him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.858#Picking this place she stabbed and driving it deep in the fair flesh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.859#wrenched the spear out again. Then Ares the brazen bellowed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.860#with a sound as great as nine thousand men make, or ten thousand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.861#when they cry as they carry into the fighting the fury of the war god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.862#And a shivering seized hold alike on Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.863#in their fear at the bellowing of battle-insatiate Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.864#As when out of the thunderhead the air shows darkening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.865#after a day's heat when the stormy wind uprises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.866#thus to Tydeus' son Diomedes Ares the brazen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.867#showed as he went up with the clouds into the wide heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.868#Lightly he came to the gods' citadel, headlong Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.869#and sat down beside Kronian Zeus, grieving in his spirit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.870#and showed him the immortal blood dripping from the spear cut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.871#So in sorrow for himself he addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.872#'Father Zeus, are you not angry looking on these acts of violence?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.873#We who are gods forever have to endure the most horrible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.874#hurts, by each other's hatred, as we try to give favour to mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.875#It is your fault we fight, since you brought forth this maniac daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.876#accursed, whose mind is fixed forever on unjust action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.877#For all the rest, as many as are gods on Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.878#are obedient to you, and we all have rendered ourselves submissive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.879#Yet you say nothing and you do nothing to check this girl, letting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.880#her go free, since yourself you begot this child of perdition.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.881#See now, the son of Tydeus, Diomedes the haughty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.882#she has egged on to lash out in fury against the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.883#gods. First he stabbed the Kyprian in the arm by the wrist. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.884#like something more than human he swept on even against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.885#But my swift feet took me out of the way. Otherwise I should
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.886#long be lying there in pain among the stark dead men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.887#or go living without strength because of the strokes of the bronze spear.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.888#Then looking at him darkly Zeus who gathers the clouds spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.889#'Do not sit beside me and whine, you double-faced liar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.890#To me you are most hateful of all gods who hold Olympos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.891#Forever quarrelling is dear to your heart, was and battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.892#Truly the anger of Hera your mother is grown out of all hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.893#nor gives ground; and try as I may I am broken by her arguments,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.894#and it is by her impulse, I think, you are suffering all this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.895#And yet I will not long endure to see you in pain, since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.896#you are my child, and it was to me that your mother bore you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.897#But were you born of some other god and proved so ruinous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.898#long since you would have been dropped beneath the gods of the bright sky.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.899#So he spoke, and told Paiëon to heal him; and scattering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.900#medicines to still pain upon him Paiëon rendered him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.901#well again, since he was not made to be one of the mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.902#As when the juice of the fig in white milk rapidly fixes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.903#that which was fluid before and curdles quickly for one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.904#stirs it; in such speed as this he healed violent Ares;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.905#and Hebe washed him clean and put delicate clothing upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.906#And rejoicing in the glory of his strength he sat down beside Kronion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.907#Meanwhile, the two went back again to the house of great Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.908#Hera of Argos, with Athene who stands by her people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:5.909#after they stopped the murderous work of manslaughtering Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.1#So the grim encounter of Achaians and Trojans was left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.2#to itself, and the battle veered greatly now one way, now in another,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.3#over the plain as they guided their bronze spears at each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.4#in the space between the waters of Xanthos and Simoeis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.5#First Telamonian Aias, that bastion of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.6#broke the Trojan battalions and brought light to his own company,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.7#striking down the man who was far the best of the Thracians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.8#Akamas, the huge and mighty, the son of Eussoros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.9#Throwing first, he struck the horn of the horse-haired helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.10#and the bronze spear-point fixed in his forehead and drove inward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.11#through the bone; and a mist of darkness clouded both eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.12#Diomedes of the great war cry cut down Axylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.13#Teuthras' son, who had been a dweller in strong-founded Arisbe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.14#a man rich in substance and a friend to all humanity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.15#since in his house by the wayside he entertained all comers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.16#Yet there was none of these now to stand before him and keep off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.17#the sad destruction, and Diomedes stripped life from both of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.18#Axylos and his henchman Kalesios, who was the driver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.19#guiding his horses; so down to the underworld went both men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.20#Now Euryalos slaughtered Opheltios and Dresos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.21#and went in pursuit of Aisepos and Pedasos, those whom the naiad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.22#nymph Abarbare had born to blameless Boukolion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.23#Boukolion himself was the son of haughty Laomedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.24#eldest born, but his mother conceived him in darkness and secrecy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.25#While shepherding his flocks he lay with the nymph and loved her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.26#and she conceiving bore him twin boys. But now Mekistios'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.27#son unstrung the strength of these and the limbs in their glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.28#Euryalos, and stripped the armour away from their shoulders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.29#Polypoites the stubborn in battle cut down Astyalos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.30#while Odysseus slaughtered one from Perkote, Pidytes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.31#with the bronze spear, and great Aretaon was killed by Teukros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.32#Nestor's son Antilochos with the shining shaft killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.33#Ableros; the lord of men, Agamemnon, brought death to Elatos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.34#whose home had been on the shores of Satnioeis' lovely waters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.35#sheer Pedasos. And Leitos the fighter caught Phylakos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.36#as he ran away; and Eurypylos made an end of Melanthios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.37#Now Menelaos of the great war cry captured Adrestos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.38#alive; for his two horses bolting over the level land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.39#got entangled in a tamarisk growth, and shattered the curving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.40#chariot at the tip of the pole; so they broken free went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.41#on toward the city, where many beside stampeded in terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.42#So Adrestos was whirled beside the wheel from the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.43#headlong into the dust on his face; and the son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.44#Menelaos, with the far-shadowed spear in his hand, stood over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.45#But Adrestos, catching him by the knees, supplicated:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.46#'Take me alive, son of Atreus, and take appropriate ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.47#In my rich father's house the treasures lie piled in abundance;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.48#bronze is there, and gold, and difficultly wrought iron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.49#and my father would make you glad with abundant repayment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.50#were he to hear that I am alive by the ships of the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.51#So he spoke, and moved the spirit inside Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.52#And now he was on the point of handing him to a henchman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.53#to lead back to the fast Achaian ships; but Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.54#came on the run to join him and spoke his word of argument:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.55#'Dear brother, o Menelaos, are you concerned so tenderly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.56#with these people? Did you in your house get the best of treatment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.57#from the Trojans? No, let not one of them go free of sudden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.58#death and our hands; not the young man child that the mother carries
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.59#still in her body, not even he, but let all of Ilion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.60#people perish, utterly blotted out and unmourned for.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.61#The hero spoke like this, and bent the heart of his brother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.62#since he urged justice. Menelaos shoved with his hand Adrestos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.63#the warrior back from him, and powerful Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.64#stabbed him in the side and, as he writhed over, Atreides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.65#setting his heel upon the midriff, wrenched out the ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.66#Nestor in a great voice cried out to the men of Argos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.67#'O beloved Danaan fighters, henchmen of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.68#let no man any more hang back with his eye on the plunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.69#designing to take all the spoil he can gather back to the vessels;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.70#let us kill the men now, and afterwards at your leisure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.71#all along the plain you can plunder the perished corpses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.72#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit and strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.73#Then once more would the Trojans have climbed back into Ilion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.74#wall, subdued by terror before the warlike Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.75#had not Priam's son, Helenos, best by far of the augurs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.76#stood beside Aineias and Hektor and spoken a word to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.77#'Hektor and Aineias, on you beyond others is leaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.78#the battle-work of Trojans and Lykians, since you are our greatest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.79#in every course we take, whether it be in thought or in fighting:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.80#stand your ground here; visit your people everywhere; hold them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.81#fast by the gates, before they tumble into their women's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.82#arms, and become to our enemies a thing to take joy in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.83#Afterwards, when you have set all the battalions in motion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.84#the rest of us will stand fast here and fight with the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.85#though we are very hard hit indeed; necessity forces us;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.86#but you, Hektor, go back again to the city, and there tell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.87#your mother and mine to assemble all the ladies of honour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.88#at the temple of grey-eyed Athene high on the citadel;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.89#there opening with a key the door to the sacred chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.90#let her take a robe, which seems to her the largest and loveliest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.91#in the great house, and that which is far her dearest possession,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.92#and lay it along the knees of Athene the lovely haired. Let her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.93#promise to dedicate within the shrine twelve heifers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.94#yearlings, never broken, if only she will have pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.95#on the town of Troy, and the Trojan wives, and their innocent children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.96#So she might hold back from sacred Ilion the son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.97#that wild spear-fighter, the strong one who drives men to thoughts of terror,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.98#who I say now is become the strongest of all the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.99#For never did we so fear Achilleus even, that leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.100#of men, who they say was born of a goddess. This man has gone clean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.101#berserk, so that no one can match his warcraft against him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.102#So he spoke, and Hektor did not disobey his brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.103#but at once in all his armour leapt to the ground from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.104#and shaking two sharp spears in his hands ranged over the whole host
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.105#stirring them up to fight and waking the ghastly warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.106#So they whirled about and stood their ground against the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.107#and the Argives gave way backward and stopped their slaughtering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.108#and thought some one of the immortals must have descended
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.109#from the starry sky to stand by the Trojans, the way they rallied.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.110#But Hektor lifted his voice and cried aloud to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.111#'You high-hearted Trojans and far-renowned companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.112#be men now, dear friends, and remember your furious valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.113#until I can go back again to Ilion, and there tell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.114#the elder men who sit as counsellors, and our own wives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.115#to make their prayer to the immortals and promise them hecatombs.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.116#So spoke Hektor of the shining helm, and departed;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.117#and against his ankles as against his neck clashed the dark ox-hide,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.118#the rim running round the edge of the great shield massive in the midd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.119#Now Glaukos, sprung of Hippolochos, and the son of Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.120#came together in the space between the two armies, battle-bent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.121#Now as these advancing came to one place and encountered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.122#first to speak was Diomedes of the great war cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.123#'Who among mortal men are you, good friend? Since never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.124#before have I seen you in the fighting where men win glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.125#yet now you have come striding far out in front of all others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.126#in your great heart, who have dared stand up to my spear far-shadowing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.127#Yet unhappy are those whose sons match warcraft against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.128#But if you are some one of the immortals come down from the bright sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.129#know that I will not fight against any god of the heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.130#since even the son of Dryas, Lykourgos the powerful, did not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.131#live long; he who tried to fight with the gods of the bright sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.132#who once drove the fosterers of rapturous Dionysos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.133#headlong down the sacred Nyseian hill, and all of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.134#shed and scattered their wands on the ground, stricken with an ox-goad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.135#by murderous Lykourgos, while Dionysos in terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.136#dived into the salt surf, and Thetis took him to her bosom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.137#frightened, with the strong shivers upon him at the man's blustering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.138#But the gods who live at their ease were angered with Lykourgos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.139#and the son of Kronos struck him to blindness, nor did he live long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.140#afterwards, since he was hated by all the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.141#Therefore neither would I be willing to fight with the blessed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.142#gods; but if you are one of those mortals who eat what the soil yields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.143#come nearer, so that sooner you may reach your appointed destruction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.144#Then in turn the shining son of Hippolochos answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.145#'High-hearted son of Tydeus, why ask of my generation?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.146#As is the generation of leaves, so is that of humanity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.147#The wind scatters the leaves on the ground, but the live timber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.148#burgeons with leaves again in the season of spring returning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.149#So one generation of men will grow while another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.150#dies. Yet if you wish to learn all this and be certain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.151#of my genealogy: there are plenty of men who know it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.152#There is a city, Ephyre, in the corner of horse-pasturing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.153#Argos; there lived Sisyphos, that sharpest of all men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.154#Sisyphos, Aiolos' son, and he had a son named Glaukos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.155#and Glaukos in turn sired Bellerophontes the blameless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.156#To Bellerophontes the gods granted beauty and desirable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.157#manhood; but Proitos in anger devised evil things against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.158#and drove him out of his own domain, since he was far greater,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.159#from the Argive country Zeus had broken to the sway of his sceptre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.160#Beautiful Anteia the wife of Proitos was stricken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.161#with passion to lie in love with him, and yet she could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.162#beguile valiant Bellerophontes, whose will was virtuous.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.163#So she went to Proitos the king and uttered her falsehood:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.164#"Would you be killed, o Proitos? Then murder Bellerophontes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.165#who tried to lie with me in love, though I was unwilling."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.166#So she spoke, and anger took hold of the king at her story.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.167#He shrank from killing him, since his heart was awed by such action,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.168#but sent him away to Lykia, and handed him murderous symbols,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.169#which he inscribed in a folding tablet, enough to destroy life,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.170#and told him to show it to his wife's father, that he might perish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.171#Bellerophontes went to Lykia in the blameless convoy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.172#of the gods; when he came to the running stream of Xanthos, and Lykia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.173#the lord of wide Lykia tendered him full-hearted honour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.174#Nine days he entertained him with sacrifice of nine oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.175#but afterwards when the rose fingers of the tenth dawn showed, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.176#he began to question him, and asked to be shown the symbols,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.177#whatever he might be carrying from his son-in-law, Proitos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.178#Then after he had been given his son-in-law's wicked symbols
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.179#first he sent him away with orders to kill the Chimaira
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.180#none might approach; a thing of immortal make, not human,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.181#lion-fronted and snake behind, a goat in the middle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.182#and snorting out the breath of the terrible flame of bright fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.183#He killed the Chimaira, obeying the portents of the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.184#Next after this he fought against the glorious Solymoi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.185#and this he thought was the strongest battle with men that he entered;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.186#but third he slaughtered the Amazons, who fight men in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.187#Now as he came back the king spun another entangling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.188#treachery; for choosing the bravest men in wide Lykia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.189#he laid a trap, but these men never came home thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.190#since all of them were killed by blameless Bellerophontes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.191#Then when the king knew him for the powerful stock of the god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.192#he detained him there, and offered him the hand of his daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.193#and gave him half of all the kingly privilege. Thereto
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.194#the men of Lykia cut out a piece of land, surpassing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.195#all others, fine ploughland and orchard for him to administer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.196#His bride bore three children to valiant Bellerophontes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.197#Isandros and Hippolochos and Laodameia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.198#Laodameia lay in love beside Zeus of the counsels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.199#and bore him godlike Sarpedon of the brazen helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.200#But after Bellerophontes was hated by all the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.201#he wandered alone about the plain of Aleios, eating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.202#his heart out, skulking aside from the trodden track of humanity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.203#As for Isandros his son, Ares the insatiate of fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.204#killed him in close battle against the glorious Solymoi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.205#while Artemis of the golden reins killed the daughter in anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.206#But Hippolochos begot me, and I claim that he is my father;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.207#he sent me to Troy, and urged upon me repeated injunctions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.208#to be always among the bravest, and hold my head above others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.209#not shaming the generation of my fathers, who were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.210#the greatest men in Ephyre and again in wide Lykia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.211#Such is my generation and the blood I claim to be born from.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.212#He spoke, and Diomedes of the great war cry was gladdened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.213#He drove his spear deep into the prospering earth, and in winning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.214#words of friendliness he spoke to the shepherd of the people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.215#'See now, you are my guest friend from far in the time of our fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.216#Brilliant Oineus once was host to Bellerophontes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.217#the blameless, in his halls, and twenty days he detained him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.218#and these two gave to each other fine gifts in token of friendship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.219#Oineus gave his guest a war belt bright with the red dye,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.220#Bellerophontes a golden and double-handled drinking-cup,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.221#a thing I left behind in my house when I came on my journey.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.222#Tydeus, though, I cannot remember, since I was little
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.223#when he left me, that time the people of the Achaians perished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.224#in Thebe. Therefore I am your friend and host in the heart of Argos;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.225#you are mine in Lykia, when I come to your country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.226#Let us avoid each other's spears, even in the close fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.227#There are plenty of Trojans and famed companions in battle for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.228#to kill, whom the god sends me, or those I run down with my swift feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.229#many Achaians for you to slaughter, if you can do it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.230#But let us exchange our armour, so that these others may know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.231#how we claim to be guests and friends from the days of our fathers.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.232#So they spoke, and both springing down from behind their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.233#gripped each other's hands and exchanged the promise of friendship;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.234#but Zeus the son of Kronos stole away the wits of Glaukos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.235#who exchanged with Diomedes the son of Tydeus armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.236#of gold for bronze, for nine oxen's worth the worth of a hundred.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.237#Now as Hektor had come to the Skaian gates and the oak tree,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.238#all the wives of the Trojans and their daughters came running about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.239#to ask after their sons, after their brothers and neighbours,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.240#their husbands; and he told them to pray to the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.241#all, in turn; but there were sorrows in store for many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.242#Now he entered the wonderfully built palace of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.243#This was fashioned with smooth-stone cloister walks, and within it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.244#were embodied fifty sleeping chambers of smoothed stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.245#built so as to connect with each other; and within these slept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.246#each beside his own wedded wife, the sons of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.247#In the same inner court on the opposite side, to face these,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.248#lay the twelve close smooth-stone sleeping chambers of his daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.249#built so as to connect with each other; and within these slept,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.250#each by his own modest wife, the lords of the daughters of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.251#There there came to meet Hektor his bountiful mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.252#with Laodike, the loveliest looking of all her daughters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.253#She clung to his hand and called him by name and spoke to him: 'Why then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.254#child, have you come here and left behind the bold battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.255#Surely it is these accursed sons of the Achaians who wear you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.256#out, as they fight close to the city, and the spirit stirred you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.257#to return, and from the peak of the citadel lift your hands, praying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.258#to Zeus. But stay while I bring you honey-sweet wine, to pour out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.259#a libation to father Zeus and the other immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.260#first, and afterwards if you will drink yourself, be strengthened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.261#In a tired man, wine will bring back his strength to its bigness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.262#in a man tired as you are tired, defending your neighbours.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.263#Tall Hektor of the shining helm spoke to her answering:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.264#'My honoured mother, lift not to me the kindly sweet wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.265#for fear you stagger my strength and make me forget my courage;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.266#and with hands unwashed I would take shame to pour the glittering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.267#wine to Zeus; there is no means for a man to pray to the dark-misted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.268#son of Kronos, with blood and muck all spattered upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.269#But go yourself to the temple of the spoiler Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.270#assembling the ladies of honour, and with things to be sacrificed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.271#and take a robe, which seems to you the largest and loveliest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.272#in the great house, and that which is far your dearest possession.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.273#Lay this along the knees of Athene the lovely haired. Also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.274#promise to dedicate within the shrine twelve heifers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.275#yearlings, never broken, if only she will have pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.276#on the town of Troy, and the Trojan wives, and their innocent children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.277#if she will hold back from sacred Ilion the son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.278#that wild spear-fighter, the strong one who drives men to thoughts of terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.279#So go yourself to the temple of the spoiler Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.280#while I go in search of Paris, to call him, if he will listen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.281#to anything I tell him. How I wish at this moment the earth might
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.282#open beneath him. The Olympian let him live, a great sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.283#to the Trojans, and high-hearted Priam, and all of his children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.284#If only I could see him gone down to the house of the Death God,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.285#then I could say my heart had forgotten its joyless affliction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.286#So he spoke, and she going into the great house called out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.287#to her handmaidens, who assembled throughout the city the highborn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.288#women; while she descended into the fragrant store-chamber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.289#There lay the elaborately wrought robes, the work of Sidonian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.290#women, whom Alexandros himself, the godlike, had brought home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.291#from the land of Sidon, crossing the wide sea, on that journey
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.292#when he brought back also gloriously descended Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.293#Hekabe lifted out one and took it as gift to Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.294#that which was the loveliest in design and the largest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.295#and shone like a star. It lay beneath the others. She went on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.296#her way, and a throng of noble women hastened about her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.297#When these had come to Athene's temple on the peak of the citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.298#Theano of the fair cheeks opened the door for them, daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.299#of Kisseus, and wife of Antenor, breaker of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.300#she whom the Trojans had established to be Athene's priestess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.301#With a wailing cry all lifted up their hands to Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.302#and Theano of the fair cheeks taking up the robe laid it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.303#along the knees of Athene the lovely haired, and praying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.304#she supplicated the daughter of powerful Zeus: 'O lady,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.305#Athene, our city's defender, shining among goddesses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.306#break the spear of Diomedes, and grant that the man be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.307#hurled on his face in front of the Skaian gates; so may we
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.308#instantly dedicate within your shrine twelve heifers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.309#yearlings, never broken, if only you will have pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.310#on the town of Troy, and the Trojan wives, and their innocent children.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.311#She spoke in prayer, but Pallas Athene turned her head from her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.312#So they made their prayer to the daughter of Zeus the powerful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.313#But Hektor went away to the house of Alexandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.314#a splendid place he had built himself, with the men who at that time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.315#were the best men for craftsmanship in the generous Troad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.316#who had made him a sleeping room and a hall and a courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.317#near the houses of Hektor and Priam, on the peak of the citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.318#There entered Hektor beloved of Zeus, in his hand holding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.319#the eleven-cubit-long spear, whose shaft was tipped with a shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.320#bronze spearhead, and a ring of gold was hooped to hold it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.321#He found the man in his chamber busy with his splendid armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.322#the corselet and the shield, and turning in his hands the curved bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.323#while Helen of Argos was sitting among her attendant women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.324#directing the magnificent work done by her handmaidens.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.325#But Hektor saw him, and in words of shame he rebuked him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.326#'Strange man! It is not fair to keep in your heart this coldness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.327#The people are dying around the city and around the steep wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.328#as they fight hard; and it is for you that this war with its clamour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.329#has flared up about our city. You yourself would fight with another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.330#whom you saw anywhere hanging back from the hateful encounter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.331#Up then, to keep our town from burning at once in the hot fire.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.332#Then in answer the godlike Alexandros spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.333#'Hektor, seeing you have scolded me rightly, not beyond measure,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.334#therefore I will tell, and you in turn understand and listen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.335#It was not so much in coldness and bitter will toward the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.336#that I sat in my room, but I wished to give myself over to sorrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.337#But just now with soft words my wife was winning me over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.338#and urging me into the fight, and that way seems to me also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.339#the better one. Victory passes back and forth between men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.340#Come then, wait for me now while I put on my armour of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.341#or go, and I will follow, and I think I can overtake you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.342#He spoke, but Hektor of the shining helm gave him no answer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.343#but Helen spoke to him in words of endearment: 'Brother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.344#by marriage to me, who am a nasty bitch evil-intriguing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.345#how I wish that on that day when my mother first bore me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.346#the foul whirlwind of the storm had caught me away and swept me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.347#to the mountain, or into the wash of the sea deep-thundering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.348#where the waves would have swept me away before all these things had happened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.349#Yet since the gods had brought it about that these vile things must be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.350#I wish I had been the wife of a better man than this is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.351#one who knew modesty and all things of shame that men say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.352#But this man's heart is no steadfast thing, nor yet will it be so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.353#ever hereafter; for that I think he shall take the consequence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.354#But come now, come in and rest on this chair, my brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.355#since it is on your heart beyond all that the hard work has fallen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.356#for the sake of dishonoured me and the blind act of Alexandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.357#us two, on whom Zeus set a vile destiny, so that hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.358#we shall be made into things of song for the men of the future.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.359#Then tall Hektor of the shining helm answered her: 'Do not, Helen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.360#make me sit with you, though you love me. You will not persuade me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.361#Already my heart within is hastening me to defend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.362#the Trojans, who when I am away long greatly to have me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.363#Rather rouse this man, and let himself also be swift to action
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.364#so he may overtake me while I am still in the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.365#For I am going first to my own house, so I can visit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.366#my own people, my beloved wife and my son, who is little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.367#since I do not know if ever again I shall come back this way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.368#or whether the gods will strike me down at the hands of the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.369#So speaking Hektor of the shining helm departed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.370#and in speed made his way to his own well-established dwelling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.371#but failed to find in the house Andromache of the white arms;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.372#for she, with the child, and followed by one fair-robed attendant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.373#had taken her place on the tower in lamentation, and tearful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.374#When he saw no sign of his perfect wife within the house, Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.375#stopped in his way on the threshold and spoke among the handmaidens:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.376#'Come then, tell me truthfully as you may, handmaidens:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.377#where has Andromache of the white arms gone? Is she
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.378#with any of the sisters of her lord or the wives of his brothers?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.379#Or has she gone to the house of Athene, where all the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.380#lovely-haired women of Troy propitiate the grim goddess?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.381#Then in turn the hard-working housekeeper gave him an answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.382#'Hektor, since you have urged me to tell you the truth, she is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.383#with any of the sisters of her lord or the wives of his brothers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.384#nor has she gone to the house of Athene, where all the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.385#lovely-haired women of Troy propitiate the grim goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.386#but she has gone to the great bastion of Ilion, because she heard that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.387#the Trojans were losing, and great grew the strength of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.388#Therefore she has gone in speed to the wall, like a woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.389#gone mad, and a nurse attending her carries the baby.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.390#So the housekeeper spoke, and Hektor hastened from his home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.391#backward by the way he had come through the well-laid streets. So
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.392#as he had come to the gates on his way through the great city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.393#the Skaian gates, whereby he would issue into the plain, there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.394#at last his own generous wife came running to meet him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.395#Andromache, the daughter of high-hearted Eëtion;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.396#Eëtion, who had dwelt underneath wooded Plakos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.397#in Thebe below Plakos, lord over the Kilikian people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:6.398#It was his daughter who was given to Hektor of the bronze helm.
