urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.28#But if you might only do as I say, it would be far better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.29#For this day let us put an end to the hatred and the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.30#now; they shall fight again hereafter, till we witness the finish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.31#they make of Ilion, since it is dear to the heart of you, who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.32#are goddesses immortal, that this city shall be made desolate.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.33#Then in answer the goddess grey-eyed Athene spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.34#'Worker from afar, thus let it be. These were my thoughts also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.35#as I came down from Olympos among the Achaians and Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.36#Tell me then, how are you minded to stop these men in their fighting?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.37#Now in turn the son of Zeus, lord Apollo, addressed her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.38#'Let us rouse up the strong heart in Hektor, breaker of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.39#if he might call forth some Danaan to do battle against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.40#single man against single man, in bitter combat;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.41#and let the strong-greaved Achaians, stirred into admiration,
