urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.61#taking their ease and watching these men whose ranks, dense-settled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.62#shuddered into a bristle of spears, of shields and of helmets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.63#As when the shudder of the west wind suddenly rising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.64#scatters across the water, and the water darkens beneath it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.65#so darkening were settled the ranks of Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.66#in the plain. And now Hektor spoke forth between them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.67#'Listen to me, you Trojans and strong-greaved Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.68#while I speak forth what the heart within my breast urges.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.69#Zeus, son of Kronos, who sits on high, would not bring to fulfilment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.70#our oaths, but is found to be of evil intention toward both sides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.71#until that day when you storm Troy of the strong towers, or that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.72#when you yourselves are broken beside your seafaring vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.73#Seeing now that among you are the bravest of all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.74#let one of you, whose heart stirs him to combat against me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.75#stand forth before all to fight by himself against brilliant Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.76#Behold the terms that I make, let Zeus be witness upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.77#If with the thin edge of the bronze he takes my life, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.78#let him strip my armour and carry it back to the hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.79#but give my body to be taken home again, so that the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.80#and the wives of the Trojans may give me in death my rite of burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.81#But if I take his life, and Apollo grants me the glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.82#I will strip his armour and carry it to sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.83#and hang it in front of the temple of far-striking Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.84#but his corpse I will give back among the strong-benched vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.85#so that the flowing-haired Achaians may give him due burial
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.86#and heap up a mound upon him beside the broad passage of Helle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.87#And some day one of the men to come will say, as he sees it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.88#one who in his benched ship sails on the wine-blue water:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.89#"This is the mound of a man who died long ago in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.90#who was one of the bravest, and glorious Hektor killed him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.91#So will he speak some day, and my glory will not be forgotten.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.92#So he spoke, and all of them stayed stricken to silence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.93#in shame of refusing him, and in fear to take up his challenge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.94#But now at long last Menelaos stood forth and addressed them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.95#in scorn and reproach, and stirred within the heart to great sorrow:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.96#'Ah me! You brave in words, you women, not men, of Achaia!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.97#This will be a defilement upon us, shame upon shame piled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.98#if no one of the Danaans goes out to face Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.99#No, may all of you turn to water and earth, all of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.100#who sit by yourselves with no life in you, utterly dishonoured.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.101#I myself will arm against this man. While above us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.102#the threads of victory are held in the hands of the immortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.103#So he spoke, and began to put on his splendid armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.104#And there, o Menelaos, would have shown forth the end of your life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.105#under the hands of Hektor, since he was far stronger than you were,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.106#had not the kings of the Achaians leapt up and caught you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.107#and the son of Atreus himself, powerful Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.108#caught you by the right hand, and called you by name, and spoke to you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.109#'Menelaos, beloved of God, you are mad; you have no need
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.110#to take leave of your senses thus. Hold fast, though it hurts you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.111#nor long in your pride to fight with a man who is better than you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.112#with Hektor, Priam's son. There are others who shudder before him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.113#Even Achilleus, in the fighting where men win glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.114#trembles to meet this man, and he is far better than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.115#Go back now and sit down in the throng of your own companions;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.116#the Achaians will set up another to fight against this man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.117#and even though he is without fear, and can never be glutted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.118#with rough work, I think he will be glad to leave off, even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.119#if he comes off whole from the hateful fighting and bitter combat.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.120#The hero spoke like this and bent the heart of his brother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.121#since he urged wisely. And Menelaos obeyed him; his henchmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.122#joyfully thereupon took off the armour from his shoulders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.123#Nestor among the Argives now stood forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.124#'Oh, for shame. Great sorrow settles on the land of Achaia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.125#Surely he would groan aloud, Peleus, the aged horseman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.126#the great man of counsel among the Myrmidons, and their speaker.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.127#Once, as he questioned me in his house, he was filled with great joy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.128#as he heard the generation and blood of all of the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.129#Now if he were to hear how all cringe away before Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.130#many a time he would lift up his very hands to the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.131#and the life breath from his limbs would go down into the house of Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.132#If only, o father Zeus, Athene, Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.133#I were in my youth as when the Pylians assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.134#and the spear-fighting Arkadians battled by swirling Keladon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.135#by the streams of Iardanos and before the ramparts of Pheia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.136#Their champion stood forth, Ereuthalion, a man godlike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.137#wearing upon his shoulders the armour of lord Areïthoös,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.138#Areïthoös the brilliant, given by the men of that time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.139#and the fair-girdled women the name club-fighter, because he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.140#went into battle armed neither with the bow nor the long spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.141#but with a great bar clubbed of iron broke the battalions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.142#Lykourgos killed this man by craft, not strength, for he met him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.143#in the narrow pass of the way, where the iron club served not to parry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.144#destruction, for Lykourgos, too quick with a stab beneath it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.145#pinned him through the middle with the spear, so he went down backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.146#to the ground; and he stripped the armour brazen Ares had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.147#and wore the armour thereafter himself through the grind of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.148#But when Lykourgos was grown an old man in his halls, he gave it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.149#to his beloved henchman, Ereuthalion, to carry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.150#Wearing this armour he called forth all the bravest to fight him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.151#but they were all afraid and trembling: none had the courage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.152#only I, for my hard-enduring heart in its daring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.153#drove me to fight him. I in age was the youngest of all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.154#And I fought with him, and Pallas Athene gave me the glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.155#Of all the men I have killed this was the tallest and strongest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.156#For he sprawled in his great bulk this way and that way. If only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.157#I were young now, as then, and the strength still steady within me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.158#Hektor of the glancing helm would soon find his battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.159#But you, now, who are the bravest of all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.160#are not minded with a good will to go against Hektor.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.161#So the old man scolded them, and nine in all stood forth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.162#Far the first to rise up was the lord of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.163#and rose after him the son of Tydeus, strong Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.164#and next the two Aiantes rose, their fierce strength upon them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.165#and after these Idomeneus, and Idomeneus' companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.166#Meriones, a match for the murderous Lord of Battles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.167#and after these Eurypylos, the glorious son of Euaimon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.168#and Thoas rose up, Andraimon's son, and brilliant Odysseus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.169#All of these were willing to fight against brilliant Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.170#Now before them again spoke the Gerenian horseman, Nestor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.171#'Let the lot be shaken for all of you, to see who wins it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.172#He shall be the one to gladden the strong-greaved Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.173#and to be glad within his own heart, if he can come off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.174#whole again from the hateful battle and bitter combat.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.175#So he spoke, and each of them marked a lot as his own one lot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.176#They threw them in the helmet of Atreus' son, Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.177#and the people, holding up their hands to the gods, prayed to them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.178#Then would murmur any man, gazing into the wide sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.179#'Father Zeus, let Aias win the lot, or else Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.180#Tydeus' son, or the king himself of golden Mykenai.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.181#So they spoke, and Nestor the Gerenian horseman shook the lots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.182#and a lot leapt from the helmet, that one that they all had wished for,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.183#the lot of Aias; and a herald carrying it all through the great throng
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.184#showed it from left to right to the great men of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.185#all of them. Each man knew not the mark, and denied it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.186#but as carrying it all through the great throng he showed it to that one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.187#who had marked it as his, and thrown it in the helmet, glorious Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.188#he held forth his hand, and the herald stood by him, and put the lot in it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.189#and he saw his mark on the lot, and knew it, and his heart was gladdened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.190#He threw it down on the ground beside his foot, and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.191#'See, friends, the lot is mine, and I myself am made happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.192#in my heart, since I think I can win over brilliant Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.193#Do this, then: while I put on my armour of fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.194#all of you be praying to the lord Zeus, the son of Kronos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.195#in silence and each to himself, let none of the Trojans hear you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.196#or openly out loud, since we have nothing to be afraid of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.197#at all, since no man by force will beat me backward unwilling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.198#as he wills, nor by craft either, since I think that the man who was born
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.199#and raised in Salamis, myself, is not such a novice.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.200#So he spoke, and they prayed to the lord Zeus, the son of Kronos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.201#And then would murmur any man, gazing into the wide sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.202#'Father Zeus, watching over us from Ida, most high, most honoured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.203#grant that Aias win the vaunt of renown and the victory;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.204#but if truly you love Hektor and are careful for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.205#give to both of them equal strength, make equal their honour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.206#So they spoke, and meanwhile Aias armed him in shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.207#bronze. Then when he had girt his body in all its armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.208#he strode on his way, as Ares the war god walks gigantic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.209#going into the fighting of men whom the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.210#has driven to fight angrily in heart-perishing hatred.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.211#Such was Aias as he strode gigantic, the wall of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.212#smiling under his threatening brows, with his feet beneath him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.213#taking huge strides forward, and shaking the spear far-shadowing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.214#And the Argives looking upon him were made glad, while the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.215#were taken every man in the knees with trembling and terror,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.216#and for Hektor himself the heart beat hard in his breast, but he could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.217#any more find means to take flight and shrink back into
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.218#the throng of his men, since he in his pride had called him to battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.219#Now Aias came near him, carrying like a wall his shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.220#of bronze and sevenfold ox-hide which Tychios wrought him with much toil;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.221#Tychios, at home in Hyle, far the best of all workers in leather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.222#who had made him the great gleaming shield of sevenfold ox-hide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.223#from strong bulls, and hammered an eighth fold of bronze upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.224#Telamonian Aias, carrying this to cover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.225#his chest, came near to Hektor and spoke to him in words of menace:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.226#'Hektor, single man against single man you will learn now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.227#for sure what the bravest men are like among the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.228#even after Achilleus the lion-hearted who breaks men in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.229#He lies now apart among his own beaked seafaring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.230#ships, in anger at Agamemnon, the shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.231#But here are we; and we are such men as can stand up against you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.232#there are plenty of us; so now begin your fight and your combat.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.233#Tall Hektor of the glancing helm answered him: 'Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.234#son of Telamon, seed of Zeus, o lord of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.235#do not be testing me as if I were some ineffectual
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.236#boy, or a woman, who knows nothing of the works of warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.237#I know well myself how to fight and kill men in battle;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.238#I know how to turn to the right, how to turn to the left the ox-hide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.239#tanned into a shield which is my protection in battle;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.240#I know how to storm my way into the struggle of flying horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.241#I know how to tread my measures on the grim floor of the war god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.242#Yet great as you are I would not strike you by stealth, watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.243#for my chance, but openly, so, if perhaps I might hit you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.244#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far-shadowed, and threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.245#and struck the sevenfold-ox-hide terrible shield of Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.246#in the uttermost bronze, which was the eighth layer upon it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.247#and the unwearying bronze spearhead shore its way through six folds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.248#but was stopped in the seventh ox-hide. Then after him Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.249#the illustrious in turn cast with his spear far-shadowing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.250#and struck the shield of Priam's son on its perfect circle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.251#All the way through the glittering shield went the heavy spearhead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.252#and crashed its way through the intricately worked corselet;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.253#straight ahead by the flank the spearhead shore through his tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.254#yet he bent away to one side and avoided the dark death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.255#Both now gripping in their hands the long spears pulled them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.256#out, and went at each other like lions who live on raw meat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.257#or wild boars, whose strength is no light thing. The son of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.258#Priam stabbed then with his spear into the shield's centre,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.259#nor did the bronze point break its way through, but the spearhead bent back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.260#Now Aias plunging upon him thrust at the shield, and the spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.261#passed clean through, and pounded Hektor back in his fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.262#and tore at his neck passing so that the dark blood broke. Yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.263#even so Hektor of the shining helmet did not stop fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.264#but gave back and in his heavy hand caught up a stone that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.265#lay in the plain, black and rugged and huge. With this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.266#he struck the sevenfold-ox-hide terrible shield of Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.267#in the knob of the centre so that the bronze clashed loud about it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.268#After him Aias in turn lifting a stone far greater
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.269#whirled it and threw, leaning into the cast his strength beyond measure,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.270#and the shield broke inward under the stroke of the rock like a millstone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.271#and Hektor's very knees gave, so that he sprawled backward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.272#shield beaten upon him, but at once Apollo lifted him upright.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.273#And now they would have been stabbing with their swords at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.274#had not the heralds, messengers of Zeus and of mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.275#come up, one for the bronze-armoured Achaians, one for the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.276#Idaios and Talthybios, both men of good counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.277#They held their staves between the two men, and the herald Idaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.278#out of his knowledge of prudent advices spoke a word to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.279#'Stop the fight, dear children, nor go on with this battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.280#To Zeus who gathers the clouds both of you are beloved,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.281#and both of you are fighters; this thing all of us know surely.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.282#Night darkens now. It is a good thing to give way to the night-time.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.283#Aias the son of Telamon spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.284#'Bid Hektor answer this, Idaios, since it was he who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.285#in his pride called forth all our bravest to fight him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.286#Let him speak first; and I for my part shall do as he urges.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.287#Tall Hektor of the glancing helm answered him: 'Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.288#seeing that God has given you strength, stature and wisdom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.289#also, and with the spear you surpass the other Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.290#let us now give over this fighting and hostility
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.291#for today; we shall fight again, until the divinity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.292#chooses between us, and gives victory to one or the other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.293#Night darkens now. It is a good thing to give way to the night-time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.294#Thus you may bring joy to all the Achaians beside their
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.295#ships, and above all to those who are your own kindred and company;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.296#and I in the great city of lord Priam will gladden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.297#the Trojans, and the women of Troy with their trailing robes, who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.298#will go before the divine assembly in thanksgiving for my sake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.299#Come then, let us give each other glorious presents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.300#so that any of the Achaians or Trojans may say of us:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.301#"These two fought each other in heart-consuming hate, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.302#joined with each other in close friendship, before they were parted."'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.303#So he spoke, and bringing a sword with nails of silver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.304#gave it to him, together with the sheath and the well-cut sword belt,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.305#and Aias gave a war belt coloured shining with purple.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.306#So separating, Aias went among the Achaian people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.307#and Hektor went back to the thronging Trojans, who were made happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.308#when they saw him coming alive and unwounded out of the combat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.309#escaping the strength and the unconquerable hands of Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.310#and they, who had not hoped to see him alive, escorted him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.311#back to the town. On the other side the strong-greaved Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.312#led Aias, happy in his victory, to great Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.313#When these had come to the shelters of the son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.314#Agamemnon the lord of men dedicated an ox among them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.315#a five-year-old male, to Zeus, all-powerful son of Kronos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.316#They skinned the victim and put it in order, and butchered the carcass,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.317#and cut up the meat expertly into small pieces, and spitted them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.318#and roasted all carefully, and took off the pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.319#Then after they had finished the work and got the feast ready,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.320#they feasted, nor was any man's hunger denied a fair portion;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.321#and Atreus' son, the hero wide-ruling Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.322#gave to Aias in honour the long cuts of the chine's portion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.323#But when they had put away their desire for eating and drinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.324#the aged man began to weave his counsel before them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.325#first, Nestor, whose advice had shown best before this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.326#He in kind intention toward all stood forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.327#'Son of Atreus, and you other great men of all the Achaians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.328#seeing that many flowing-haired Achaians have died here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.329#whose dark blood has been scattered beside the fair waters of Skamandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.330#by the fierce war god, while their souls went down into the house of Hades;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.331#therefore with the dawn we should set a pause to the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.332#of Achaians, and assembling them wheel back the bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.333#with mules and oxen; then must we burn them a little apart from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.334#the ships, so that each whose duty it is may carry the bones back
