urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.336#And let us gather and pile one single mound on the corpse-pyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.337#indiscriminately from the plain, and build fast upon it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.338#towered ramparts, to be a defence of ourselves and our vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.339#And let us build into these walls gates strongly fitted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.340#that there may be a way through them for the driving of horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.341#and on the outer side, and close, we must dig a deep ditch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.342#circling it, so as to keep off their people and horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.343#that we may not be crushed under the attack of these proud Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.344#So he spoke, and all the kings gave him their approval.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.345#Now there was an assembly of Trojans high on the city of Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.346#fiercely shaken to tumult before the doors of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.347#and among these Antenor the thoughtful began to address them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.348#'Trojans and Dardanians and companions in arms: hear me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.349#while I speak forth what the heart within my breast urges.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.350#Come then: let us give back Helen of Argos and all her possessions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.351#to the sons of Atreus to take away, seeing now we fight with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.352#our true pledges made into lies; and I see no good thing's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.353#accomplishment for us in the end, unless we do this.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.354#He spoke thus and sat down again, and among them rose up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.355#brilliant Alexandros, the lord of lovely-haired Helen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.356#who spoke to him in answer and addressed them in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.357#'Antenor, these things that you argue please me no longer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.358#Your mind knows how to contrive a saying better than this one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.359#But if in all seriousness this is your true argument; then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.360#it is the very gods who ruined the brain within you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.361#I will speak out before the Trojans, breakers of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.362#I refuse, straight out. I will not give back the woman.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.363#But of the possessions I carried away to our house from Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.364#I am willing to give all back, and to add to these from my own goods.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.365#He spoke thus and sat down again, and among them rose up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.366#Priam, son of Dardanos, equal of the gods in counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.367#who in kind intention toward all stood forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.368#'Trojans and Dardanians and companions in arms: hear me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.369#while I speak forth what the heart within my breast urges.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.370#Take now your supper about the city, as you did before this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.371#and remember your duty of the watch, and be each man wakeful;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.372#and at dawn let Idaios go to the hollow ships, and speak with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.373#the sons of Atreus, Menelaos and Agamemnon, giving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.374#the word of Alexandros, for whose sake this strife has arisen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.375#and to add this solid message, and ask them if they are willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.376#to stop the sorrowful fighting until we can burn the bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.377#of our dead. We shall fight again until the divinity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.378#chooses between us, and gives victory to one or the other.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.379#So he spoke, and they listened to him with care, and obeyed him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.380#and so took their supper, watch succeeding watch, through the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.381#Then at dawn Idaios went down to the hollow ships, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.382#he found the Danaans, henchmen of the war god, in assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.383#beside the stern of Agamemnon's ship; the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.384#with the great voice took his stand in their midst, and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.385#'Son of Atreus, and you other great men of all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.386#Priam and the rest of the haughty Trojans have bidden me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.387#give you, if this message be found to your pleasure and liking,
