urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.389#All those possessions that Alexandros carried in his hollow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.390#ships to Troy, and I wish that he had perished before then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.391#he is willing to give all back, and to add to these from his own goods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.392#But the very wedded wife of glorious Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.393#he says that he will not give, though the Trojans would have him do it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.394#They told me to give you this message also, if you are willing;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.395#to stop the sorrowful fighting until we can burn the bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.396#of our dead. We shall fight again afterwards, until the divinity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.397#chooses between us, and gives victory to one or the other.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.398#So he spoke, and all of them stayed quiet in silence;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.399#but now at long last Diomedes of the great war cry addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.400#'Now let none accept the possessions of Alexandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.401#nor take back Helen; one who is very simple can see it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.402#that by this time the terms of death hang over the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.403#So he spoke, and all sons of the Achaians shouted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.404#acclaim for the word of Diomedes, breaker of horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.405#and now powerful Agamemnon spoke to Idaios:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.406#'Idaios, you hear for yourself the word of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.407#how they are answering you; and such is my pleasure also.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.408#But about the burning of the dead bodies I do not begrudge you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.409#no, for there is no sparing time for the bodies of the perished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.410#once they have died, to give them swiftly the pity of burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.411#Let Zeus, high-thundering lord of Hera, witness our pledges.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.412#He spoke, and held up the sceptre in the sight of all the gods. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.413#Idaios made his way back once more to sacred Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.414#The Trojans and Dardanians were in session of assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.415#all gathered in one place, awaiting Idaios when he might come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.416#back; and he returned to them and delivered his message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.417#standing there in their midst, and they made their swift preparations,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.418#for two things, some to gather the bodies, and the others firewood;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.419#while the Argives on the other side from their strong-benched vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.420#went forward, some to gather the bodies, and others firewood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.421#Now the sun of a new day struck on the ploughlands, rising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.422#out of the quiet water and the deep stream of the ocean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.423#to climb the sky. The Trojans assembled together. They found
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.424#it hard to recognize each individual dead man;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.425#but with water they washed away the blood that was on them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.426#and as they wept warm tears they lifted them on to the wagons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.427#But great Priam would not let them cry out; and in silence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.428#they piled the bodies upon the pyre, with their hearts in sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.429#and burned them upon the fire, and went back to sacred Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.430#In the same way on the other side the strong-greaved Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.431#piled their own slain upon the pyre, with their hearts in sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.432#and burned them upon the fire, and went-back to their hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.433#But when the dawn was not yet, but still the pallor of night's edge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.434#a chosen body of the Achaians formed by the pyre;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.435#and they gathered together and piled one single mound all above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.436#indiscriminately from the plain, and built a fort on it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.437#with towered ramparts, to be a defence for themselves and their vessels;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.438#and they built within these walls gates strongly fitted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.439#that there might be a way through them for the driving of horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.440#and on the outer side and against it they dug a deep ditch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.441#making it great and wide, and fixed the sharp stakes inside it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.442#So the flowing-haired Achaians laboured, and meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.443#the gods in session at the side of Zeus who handles the lightning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.444#watched the huge endeavour of the bronze-armoured Achaians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.445#and the god Poseidon who shakes the earth began speaking among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.446#'Father Zeus, is there any mortal left on the wide earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.447#who will still declare to the immortals his mind and his purpose?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.448#Do you not see how now these flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.449#have built a wall landward of their ships, and driven about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.450#a ditch, and not given to the gods any grand sacrifice?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.451#Now the fame of this will last as long as dawnlight is scattered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.452#and men will forget that wall which I and Phoibos Apollo
