urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.454#Deeply troubled, Zeus who gathers the clouds answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.455#'What a thing to have said, earth-shaker of the wide strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.456#Some other one of the gods might fear such a thought, one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.457#is a god far weaker of his hands and in anger than you are;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.458#but the fame of you shall last as long as dawnlight is scattered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.459#Come then! After once more the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.460#are gone back with their ships to the beloved land of their fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.461#break their wall to pieces and scatter it into the salt sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.462#and pile again the beach deep under the sands and cover it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.463#so let the great wall of the Achaians go down to destruction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.464#As these two were talking thus together, the sun went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.465#down, and the work of the Achaians was finished. They slaughtered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.466#oxen then beside their shelters, and took their supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.467#The ships came over to them from Lemnos bringing them wine, ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.468#sent over to them in numbers by the son of Jason, Euneos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.469#whom Hypsipyle had borne to the shepherd of the people, Jason.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.470#Apart to the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon and Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.471#Jason's son had given wine as a gift, a thousand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.472#measures; and thence the rest of the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.473#bought wine, some for bronze and others for shining iron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.474#some for skins and some for the whole oxen, while others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.475#paid slaves taken in war; and they made their feasting abundant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.476#All night long thereafter the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:7.477#feasted, and the Trojans and their companions in arms in the city;
