urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.197#might embark this very night on their fast-running vessels.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.198#So he spoke, boasting, and the lady Hera was angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.199#and started upon her throne, and tall Olympos was shaken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.200#and she spoke straight out to the great god Poseidon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.201#'For shame, now, far-powerful shaker of the earth. In your breast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.202#the heart takes no sorrow for the Danaans who are dying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.203#they who at Helike and at Aigai bring you offerings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.204#numerous and delightful. Do you then plan that they conquer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.205#For if all of us who stand by the Danaans only were willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.206#to hurl back the Trojans and hold off Zeus of the broad brows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.207#he would be desperate, there where he sits by himself on Ida.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.208#Deeply troubled, the powerful shaker of the earth answered her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.209#'Hera, reckless of word, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.210#I would not be willing that all the rest of us fight with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.211#Zeus, the son of Kronos, since he is so much the greater.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.212#Now as these two were talking thus to each other, meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.213#for those others, all that space which the ditch of the wall held
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.214#off from the ships was filled with armoured men and with horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.215#penned there; and he who penned them was a man like the rapid war god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.216#Hektor, Priam's son, since Zeus was giving him glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.217#And now he might have kindled their balanced ships with the hot flame,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.218#had not the lady Hera set it in Agamemnon's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.219#heart to rush in with speed himself and stir the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.220#He went on his way beside the Achaians' ships and their shelters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.221#holding up in his heavy hand the great coloured mantle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.222#and stood beside the black huge-hollowed ship of Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.223#which lay in the midmost, so that he could call out to both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.224#either toward the shelters of Telamonian Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.225#or toward Achilleus, since these two had drawn their balanced ships up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.226#at the utter ends, sure of the strength of their hands and their courage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.227#He lifted his voice and called in a piercing cry to the Danaans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.228#'Shame, you Argives, poor nonentities splendid to look on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.229#Where are our high words gone, when we said that we were the bravest?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.230#those words you spoke before all in hollow vaunting at Lemnos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.231#when you were filled with abundant meat of the high-horned oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.232#and drank from the great bowls filled to the brim with wine, how each man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.233#could stand up against a hundred or even two hundred Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.234#in the fighting; now we together cannot match one of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.235#Hektor, who must presently kindle our ships with the hot fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.236#Father Zeus, is it one of our too strong kings you have stricken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.237#in this disaster now, and stripped him of his high honour?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.238#For I say that never did I pass by your fair-wrought altar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.239#in my benched ships when I came here on this desperate journey;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.240#but on all altars I burned the fat and the thighs of oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.241#in my desire to sack the strong-walled city of the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.242#Still, Zeus, bring to pass at least this thing that I pray for.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.243#Let our men at least get clear and escape, and let not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.244#the Achaians be thus beaten down at the hands of the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.245#He spoke thus, and as he wept the father took pity upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.246#and bent his head, that the people should stay alive, and not perish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.247#Straightway he sent down the most lordly of birds, an eagle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.248#with a fawn, the young of the running deer, caught in his talons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.249#who cast down the fawn beside Zeus' splendid altar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.250#where the Achaians wrought their devotions to Zeus of the Voices.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.251#They, when they saw the bird and knew it was Zeus who sent it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.252#remembered once again their warcraft, and turned on the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.253#Then, many as the Danaans were, there was no man among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.254#could claim he held his fast horses ahead of the son of Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.255#to drive them once more across the ditch and fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.256#but he was far the first to kill a chief man of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.257#Phradmon's son, Agelaos, as he turned his team to escape him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.258#For in his back even as he was turning the spear fixed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.259#between the shoulders and was driven on through the chest beyond it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.260#He fell from the chariot, and his armour clattered upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.261#After him came the Atreidai, Menelaos and Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.262#and the two Aiantes gathering their fierce strength about them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.263#and with them Idomeneus and Idomeneus' companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.264#Meriones, a match for the murderous lord of battles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.265#and after these Eurypylos, the glorious son of Euaimon;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.266#and ninth came Teukros, bending into position the curved bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.267#and took his place in the shelter of Telamonian Aias'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.268#shield, as Aias lifted the shield to take him. The hero
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.269#would watch, whenever in the throng he had struck some man with an arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.270#and as the man dropped and died where he was stricken, the archer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.271#would run back again, like a child to the arms of his mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.272#to Aias, who would hide him in the glittering shield's protection.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.273#Then which of the Trojans first did Teukros the blameless strike down?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.274#Orsilochos first of all, and Ormenos, and Ophelestes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.275#Daitor and Chromios, and Lykophontes the godlike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.276#and Amopaon, Polyaimon's son, and Melanippos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.277#All these he felled to the bountiful earth in close succession.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.278#Agamemnon the lord of men was glad as he watched him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.279#laying waste from the strong bow the Trojan battalions;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.280#he went over and stood beside him and spoke a word to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.281#'Telamonian Teukros, dear heart, o lord of your people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.282#strike so; thus you may be a light given to the Danaans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.283#and to Telamon your father, who cherished you when you were little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.284#and, bastard as you were, looked after you in his own house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.285#Bring him into glory, though he is far away; and for my part,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.286#I will tell you this, and it will be a thing accomplished:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.287#if ever Zeus who holds the aegis and Athene grant me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.288#to sack outright the strong-founded citadel of Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.289#first after myself I will put into your hands some great gift
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.290#of honour; a tripod, or two horses and the chariot with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.291#or else a woman, who will go up into the same bed with you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.292#Then in answer to him again spoke Teukros the blameless:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.293#'Son of Atreus, most lordly: must you then drive me, who am eager
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.294#myself, as it is? Never, so far as the strength is in me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.295#have I stopped, since we began driving the Trojans back upon Ilion;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.296#since then I have been lurking here with my bow, to strike down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.297#fighters. And by this I have shot eight long-flanged arrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.298#and all of them were driven into the bodies of young men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.299#fighters; yet still I am not able to hit this mad dog.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.300#He spoke, and let fly another shaft from the bowstring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.301#straight for Hektor, and all his heart was straining to hit him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.302#but missed his man, and struck down instead a strong son of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.303#Gorgythion the blameless, hit in the chest by an arrow;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.304#Gorgythion whose mother was lovely Kastianeira,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.305#Priam's bride from Aisyme, with the form of a goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.306#He bent drooping his head to one side, as a garden poppy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.307#bends beneath the weight of its yield and the rains of springtime;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.308#so his head bent slack to one side beneath the helm's weight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.309#But Teukros now let fly another shaft from the bowstring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.310#straight for Hektor, and all his heart was straining to hit him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.311#yet missed his man once again as Apollo faltered his arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.312#and struck Archeptolemos, bold charioteer of Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.313#in the chest next to the nipple as he charged into the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.314#He fell out of the chariot, and the fast-footed horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.315#shied away. And there his life and his strength were scattered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.316#And bitter sorrow closed over Hektor's heart for his driver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.317#yet grieving as he did for his friend he left him to lie there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.318#and called to his brother Kebriones who stood near to take up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.319#the reins of the horses, nor did he disobey him. But Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.320#himself vaulted down to the ground from the shining chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.321#crying a terrible cry and in his hand caught up a great stone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.322#and went straight for Teukros, heart urgent to hit him. Now Teukros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.323#had drawn a bitter arrow out of his quiver, and laid it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.324#along the bowstring, but as he drew the shaft by his shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.325#there where between neck and chest the collar-bone interposes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.326#and this is a spot most mortal; in this place shining-helmed Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.327#struck him in all his fury with the jagged boulder, smashing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.328#the sinew, and all his arm at the wrist was deadened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.329#He dropped to one knee and stayed, and the bow fell from his hand. Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.330#was not forgetful of his fallen brother, but running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.331#stood bestriding him and covered him under the great shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.332#Thereon Mekisteus, son of Echios, and brilliant Alastor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.333#two staunch companions, stooping beneath it, caught up Teukros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.334#and carried him, groaning heavily, to the hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.335#Now once again the Olympian filled the Trojans with fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.336#and they piled the Achaians straight backward against the deep ditch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.337#as Hektor ranged in their foremost ranks in the pride of his great strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.338#As when some hunting hound in the speed of his feet pursuing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.339#a wild boar or a lion snaps from behind at his quarters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.340#or flanks, but watches for the beast to turn upon him, so Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.341#followed close on the heels of the flowing-haired Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.342#killing ever the last of the men; and they fled in terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.343#But after they had crossed back over the ditch and the sharp stakes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.344#in flight, and many had gone down under the hands of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.345#they reined in and stood fast again beside their ships, calling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.346#aloud upon each other, and to all of the gods uplifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.347#their hands each man of them cried out his prayers in a great voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.348#while Hektor, wearing the stark eyes of a Gorgon, or murderous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.349#Ares, wheeled about at the edge his bright-maned horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.350#Now seeing them the goddess of the white arms, Hera, took pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.351#and immediately she spoke to Pallas Athene her winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.352#'For shame, daughter of Zeus who wears the aegis! no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.353#shall we care for the Danaans in their uttermost hour of destruction?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.354#These must then fill out an evil destiny, and perish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.355#in the wind of one man's fury where none can stand now against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.356#Hektor, Priam's son, who has wrought so much evil already.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.357#Then in turn the goddess grey-eyed Athene answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.358#'Yet even this man would have his life and strength taken from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.359#dying under the hands of the Argives in his own country;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.360#but it is my father who is so furious in his heart of evil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.361#He is hard, and forever wicked; he crosses my high hopes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.362#nor remembers at all those many times I rescued his own son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.363#Herakles, when the tasks of Eurystheus were too much for his strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.364#And time and again he would cry out aloud to the heavens,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.365#and Zeus would send me down in speed from the sky to help him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.366#If in the wiliness of my heart I had had thoughts like his,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.367#when Herakles was sent down to Hades of the Gates, to hale back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.368#from the Kingdom of the Dark the hound of the grisly death god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.369#never would he have got clear of the steep-dripping Stygian water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.370#Yet now Zeus hates me, and is bent to the wishes of Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.371#who kissed his knees and stroked his chin in her hand, and entreated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.372#that he give honour to Achilleus, the sacker of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.373#Yet time shall be when he calls me again his dear girl of the grey eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.374#So then: do you put under their harness our single-foot horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.375#while I go back into the house of Zeus, the lord of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.376#and arm me in my weapons of war. So shall I discover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.377#whether the son of Priam, Hektor of the shining helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.378#will feel joy to see us apparent on the outworks of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.379#or see if some Trojan give the dogs and the birds their desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.380#with fat and flesh, struck down beside the ships of the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.381#She spoke, nor failed to persuade the goddess Hera of the white arms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.382#And she, Hera, exalted goddess, daughter of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.383#the mighty, went away to harness the gold-bridled horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.384#Now in turn Athene, daughter of Zeus of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.385#beside the threshold of her father slipped off her elaborate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.386#dress which she herself had wrought with her hands' patience,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.387#and now assuming the war tunic of Zeus who gathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.388#the clouds, she armed herself in her gear for the dismal fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.389#She set her feet in the blazing chariot, and took up a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.390#heavy, huge, thick, wherewith she beats down the battalions of fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.391#men, against whom she of the mighty father is angered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.392#Hera laid the lash swiftly on the horses; and moving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.393#of themselves groaned the gates of the sky that the Hours guarded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.394#those Hours to whose charge is given the huge sky and Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.395#to open up the dense darkness or again to close it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.396#Through the way between they held the speed of their goaded horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.397#But Zeus father, watching from Ida, was angered terribly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.398#and stirred Iris of the golden wings to run with his message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.399#'Go forth, Iris the swift, turn them back again, let them not reach me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.400#since we would close in fighting thus that would be unseemly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.401#For I will say this straight out, and it will be a thing accomplished:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.402#I will lame beneath the harness their fast-running horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.403#and hurl the gods from the driver's place, and smash their chariot;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.404#and not in the circle of ten returning years shall they be whole
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.405#of the wounds where the stroke of the lightning hits them; so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.406#the grey-eyed goddess may know when it is her father she fights with.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.407#Yet with Hera I am not so angry, neither indignant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.408#since it is ever her way to cross the commands that I give her.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.409#He spoke, and Iris, storm-footed, rose with his message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.410#and took her way from the peaks of Ida to tall Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.411#and at the utmost gates of many-folded Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.412#met and stayed them, and spoke the word that Zeus had given her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.413#'Where so furious? How can your hearts so storm within you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.414#The son of Kronos will not let you stand by the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.415#Since Zeus has uttered this threat and will make it a thing accomplished:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.416#that he will lame beneath the harness your fast-running horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.417#and hurl yourselves from the driver's place, and smash your chariot;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.418#and not in the circle of ten returning years would you be whole
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.419#of the wounds where the stroke of the lightning hits you; so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.420#you may know, grey-eyed goddess, when it is your father you fight with.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.421#Yes, you, bold brazen wench, are audacious indeed, if truly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.422#you dare to lift up your gigantic spear in the face of your father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.423#Yet with Hera he is not so angry, neither indignant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.424#since it is ever her way to cross the commands he gives her.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.425#So Iris the swift-footed spoke and went away from them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.426#and now Hera spoke a word to Pallas Athene:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.427#'Alas, daughter of Zeus of the aegis: I can no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.428#let us fight in the face of Zeus for the sake of mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.429#Let one of them perish then, let another live, as their fortune
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.430#wills; let him, as is his right and as his heart pleases,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.431#work out whatever decrees he will on Danaans and Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.432#So she spoke, and turned back again her single-foot horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.433#and the Hours set free their flowing-maned horses from the harness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.434#and tethered them at their mangers that were piled with ambrosia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.435#and leaned the chariot against the shining inward wall. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.436#the goddesses themselves took their place on the golden couches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.437#among the other immortals, their hearts deep grieving within them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.438#Now father Zeus steered back from Ida his strong-wheeled chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.439#and horses to Olympos, and came among the gods' sessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.440#while for him the famed shaker of the earth set free his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.441#and put the chariot on its stand, with a cloth spread over it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.442#Then Zeus himself of the wide brows took his place on the golden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.443#throne, as underneath his feet tall Olympos was shaken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.444#These two alone, Hera and Athene, stayed seated apart aside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.445#from Zeus, and would not speak to him, nor ask him a question;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.446#but he knew the whole matter within his heart, and spoke to them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.447#'Why then are you two sorrowful, Athene and Hera?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.448#Surely in the battle where men win glory you were not wearied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.449#out, destroying those Trojans on whom you have set your grim wrath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.450#In the whole account, such is my strength and my hand so invincible,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.451#not all the gods who are on Olympos could turn me backward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.452#but before this the trembling took hold of your shining bodies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.453#before you could look upon the fighting and war's work of sorrow;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.454#for I will say straight out, and it would now be a thing accomplished:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.455#once hit in your car by the lightning stroke you could never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.456#have come back to Olympos, where is the place of the immortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.457#So he spoke; and Athene and Hera muttered, since they were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.458#sitting close to each other, devising evil for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.459#Still Athene stayed silent and said nothing, but only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.460#sulked at Zeus her father, and savage anger took hold of her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.461#But the heart of Hera could not contain her anger, and she spoke forth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.462#'Majesty, son of Kronos, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.463#We know well already your strength, how it is no small thing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.464#Yet even so we are sorrowful for the Danaan spearmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.465#who must fill out an unhappy destiny, and perish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.466#Still we shall keep out of the fighting, as you command us;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.467#yet we will put good counsel in the Argives, if it may help them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.468#so that not all of them will die because of your anger.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.469#Zeus who gathers the clouds spoke to her again in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.470#'Tomorrow at the dawning, lady Hera of the ox eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.471#you will see, if you have the heart, a still mightier son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.472#perishing the ranged numbers of Argive spearmen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.473#For Hektor the huge will not sooner be stayed from his fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.474#until there stirs by the ships the swift-footed son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.475#on that day when they shall fight by the sterns of the beached ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.476#in the narrow place of necessity over fallen Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.477#This is the way it is fated to be; and for you and your anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.478#I care not; not if you stray apart to the undermost limits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.479#of earth and sea, where Iapetos and Kronos seated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.480#have no shining of the sun god Hyperion to delight them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.481#nor winds' delight, but Tartaros stands deeply about them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.482#not even if you reach that place in your wandering shall I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.483#care for your sulks; since there is nothing more shameless than you are.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.484#So he spoke, and Hera of the white arms gave him no answer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.485#And now the shining light of the sun was dipped in the Ocean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.486#trailing black night across the grain-giving land. For the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.487#the daylight sank against their will, but for the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.488#sweet and thrice-supplicated was the coming on of the dark night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.489#Now glorious Hektor held an assembly of all the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.490#taking them aside from the ships, by a swirling river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.491#on clean ground, where there showed a space not cumbered with corpses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.492#They stepped to the ground from behind their horses and listened to Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.493#the loved of Zeus, and the words he spoke to them. He in his hand held
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.494#the eleven-cubit-long spear, whose shaft was tipped with a shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.495#bronze spearhead, and a ring of gold was hooped to hold it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.496#Leaning upon this spear he spoke his words to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.497#'Trojans and Dardanians and companions in arms: hear me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.498#Now I had thought that, destroying the ships and all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.499#we might take our way back once more to windy Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.500#but the darkness came too soon, and this beyond all else rescued
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.501#the Argives and their vessels along the beach where the sea breaks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.502#But now let us give way to black night's persuasion; let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.503#make ready our evening meal, and as for your flowing-maned horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.504#set them free from their harness, and cast down fodder before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.505#And lead forth also out of the city oxen and fat sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.506#in all speed, and convey out also the kindly sweet wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.507#with food out of our houses. And heap many piles of firewood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.508#so that all night long and until the young dawn appears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.509#we may burn many fires, and the glare go up into heaven;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.510#so that not in the night-time the flowing-haired Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.511#may set out to run for home over the sea's wide ridges.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.512#No: not thus in their own good time must they take to their vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.513#but in such a way that a man of them at home will still nurse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.514#his wound, the place where he has been hit with an arrow or sharp spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.515#springing to his ship; so that another may shrink hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.516#from bringing down fearful war on the Trojans, breakers of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.517#And let the heralds Zeus loves give orders about the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.518#for the boys who are in their first youth and the grey-browed elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.519#to take stations on the god-founded bastions that circle the city;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.520#and as for the women, have our wives, each one in her own house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.521#kindle a great fire; let there be a watch kept steadily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.522#lest a sudden attack get into the town when the fighters have left it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.523#Let it be thus, high-hearted men of Troy, as I tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.524#Let that word that has been spoken now be a strong one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.525#with that which I speak at dawn to the Trojans, breakers of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.526#For in good hope I pray to Zeus and the other immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.527#that we may drive from our place these dogs swept into destruction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.528#whom the spirits of death have carried here on their black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.529#Now for the night we shall keep watch on ourselves, and tomorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.530#early, before dawn shows, shall arm ourselves in our weapons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.531#and beside their hollow vessels waken the bitter war god;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.532#and I shall know if the son of Tydeus, strong Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.533#will force me back from the ships against the wall, or whether I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.534#shall cut him down with the bronze and take home the blooded war-spoils.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.535#Tomorrow he will learn his own strength, if he can stand up to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.536#my spear's advance; but sooner than this, I think, in the foremost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.537#he will go down under the stroke, and many companions about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.538#as the sun goes up into tomorrow. Oh, if I only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.539#could be as this in all my days immortal and ageless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.540#and be held in honour as Athene and Apollo are honoured
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.541#as surely as this oncoming day brings evil to the Argives.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.542#So Hektor spoke among them, and the Trojans shouted approval.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.543#And they set free their sweating horses from under the harness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.544#and tethered them by the reins, each one by his own chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.545#They led forth also out of the city oxen and fat sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.546#in all speed, and conveyed out also the kindly sweet wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.547#with food out of their houses, and heaped many piles of firewood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.548#They accomplished likewise full sacrifices before the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.549#and the winds wafted the savour aloft from the plain to the heavens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.550#in its fragrance; and yet the blessed gods took no part of it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.551#They would not; so hateful to them was sacred Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.552#and Priam, and the city of Priam of the strong ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.553#So with hearts made high these sat night-long by the outworks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.554#of battle, and their watchfires blazed numerous about them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.555#As when in the sky the stars about the moon's shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.556#are seen in all their glory, when the air has fallen to stillness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.557#and all the high places of the hills are clear, and the shoulders out-jutting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.558#and the deep ravines, as endless bright air spills from the heavens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.559#and all the stars are seen, to make glad the heart of the shepherd;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.560#such in their numbers blazed the watchfires the Trojans were burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.561#between the waters of Xanthos and the ships, before Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.562#A thousand fires were burning there in the plain, and beside each
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.563#one sat fifty men in the flare of the blazing firelight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.564#And standing each beside his chariot, champing white barley
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:8.565#and oats, the horses waited for the dawn to mount to her high place.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.1#So the Trojans held their night watches. Meanwhile immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.2#Panic, companion of cold Terror, gripped the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.3#as all their best were stricken with grief that passes endurance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.4#As two winds rise to shake the sea where the fish swarm, Boreas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.5#and Zephyros, north wind and west, that blow from Thraceward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.6#suddenly descending, and the darkened water is gathered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.7#to crests, and far across the salt water scatters the seaweed;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.8#so the heart in the breast of each Achaian was troubled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.9#And the son of Atreus, stricken at heart with the great sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.10#went among his heralds the clear-spoken and told them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.11#to summon calling by name each man into the assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.12#but with no outcry, and he himself was at work with the foremost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.13#They took their seats in assembly, dispirited, and Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.14#stood up before them, shedding tears, like a spring dark-running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.15#that down the face of a rock impassable drips its dim water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.16#So, groaning heavily, Agamemnon spoke to the Argives:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.17#'Friends, who are leaders of the Argives and keep their counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.18#Zeus son of Kronos has caught me badly in bitter futility.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.19#He is hard: who before this time promised me and consented
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.20#that I might sack strong-walled Ilion and sail homeward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.21#Now he has devised a vile deception and bids me go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.22#to Argos in dishonour having lost many of my people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.23#Such is the way it will be pleasing to Zeus, who is too strong,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.24#who before now has broken the crests of many cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.25#and will break them again, since his power is beyond all others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.26#Come then, do as I say, let us all be won over; let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.27#run away with our ships to the beloved land of our fathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.28#since no longer now shall we capture Troy of the wide ways.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.29#So he spoke, and all of them stayed stricken to silence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.30#For some time the sons of the Achaians said nothing in sorrow;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.31#but at long last Diomedes of the great war cry addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.32#'Son of Atreus: I will be first to fight with your folly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.33#as is my right, lord, in this assembly; then do not be angered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.34#I was the first of the Danaans whose valour you slighted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.35#and said I was unwarlike and without courage. The young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.36#of the Argives know all these things, and the elders know it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.37#The son of devious-devising Kronos has given you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.38#gifts in two ways: with the sceptre he gave you honour beyond all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.39#but he did not give you a heart, and of all power this is the greatest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.40#Sir, sir, can you really believe the sons of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.41#are so unwarlike and so weak of their hearts as you call them?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.42#But if in truth your own heart is so set upon going,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.43#go. The way is there, and next to the water are standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.44#your ships that came--so many of them!--with you from Mykenai,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.45#and yet the rest of the flowing-haired Achaians will stay here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.46#until we have sacked the city of Troy; let even these also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.47#run away with their ships to the beloved land of their fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.48#still we two, Sthenelos and I, will fight till we witness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.49#the end of Ilion; for it was with God that we made our way hither.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.50#So he spoke, and all the sons of the Achaians shouted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.51#acclaim for the word of Diomedes, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.52#And now Nestor the horseman stood forth among them and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.53#'Son of Tydeus, beyond others you are strong in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.54#and in counsel also are noblest among all men of your own age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.55#Not one man of all the Achaians will belittle your words nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.56#speak against them. Yet you have not made complete your argument,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.57#since you are a young man still and could even be my own son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.58#and my youngest born of all; yet still you argue in wisdom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.59#with the Argive kings, since all you have spoken was spoken fairly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.60#But let me speak, since I can call myself older than you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.61#and go through the whole matter, since there is none who can dishonour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.62#the thing I say, not even powerful Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.63#Out of all brotherhood, outlawed, homeless shall be that man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.64#who longs for all the horror of fighting among his own people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.65#But now let us give way to the darkness of night, and let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.66#make ready our evening meal; and let the guards severally
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.67#take their stations by the ditch we have dug outside the ramparts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.68#This I would enjoin upon our young men; but thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.69#do you, son of Atreus, take command, since you are our kingliest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.70#Divide a feast among the princes; it befits you, it is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.71#unbecoming. Our shelters are filled with wine that the Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.72#ships carry day by day from Thrace across the wide water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.73#All hospitality is for you; you are lord over many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.74#When many assemble together follow him who advises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.75#the best counsel, for in truth there is need for all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.76#of good close counsel, since now close to our ships the enemy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.77#burn their numerous fires. What man could be cheered to see this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.78#Here is the night that will break our army, or else will preserve it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.79#So he spoke, and they listened hard to him, and obeyed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.80#and the sentries went forth rapidly in their armour, gathering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.81#about Nestor's son Thrasymedes, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.82#and about Askalaphos and Ialmenos, sons both of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.83#about Meriones and Aphareus and Deïpyros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.84#and about the son of Kreion, Lykomedes the brilliant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.85#There were seven leaders of the sentinels, and with each one a hundred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.86#fighting men followed gripping in their hands the long spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.87#They took position in the space between the ditch and the rampart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.88#and there they kindled their fires and each made ready his supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.89#But the son of Atreus led the assembled lords of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.90#to his own shelter, and set before them the feast in abundance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.91#They put their hands to the good things that lay ready before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.92#But when they had put away their desire for eating and drinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.93#the aged man began to weave his counsel before them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.94#first, Nestor, whose advice had shown best before this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.95#He in kind intention toward all stood forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.96#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.97#with you I will end, with you I will make my beginning, since you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.98#are lord over many people, and Zeus has given into your hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.99#the sceptre and rights of judgment, to be king over the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.100#It is yours therefore to speak a word, yours also to listen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.101#and grant the right to another also, when his spirit stirs him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.102#to speak for our good. All shall be yours when you lead the way. Still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.103#I will speak in the way it seems best to my mind, and no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.104#shall have in his mind any thought that is better than this one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.105#that I have in my mind either now or long before now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.106#ever since that day, illustrious, when you went from the shelter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.107#of angered Achilleus, taking by force the girl Briseis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.108#against the will of the rest of us, since I for my part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.109#urged you strongly not to, but you, giving way to your proud heart's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.110#anger, dishonoured a great man, one whom the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.111#honour, since you have taken his prize and keep it. But let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.112#even now think how we can make this good and persuade him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.113#with words of supplication and with the gifts of friendship.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.114#Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.115#'Aged sir, this was no lie when you spoke of my madness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.116#I was mad, I myself will not deny it. Worth many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.117#fighters is that man whom Zeus in his heart loves, as now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.118#he has honoured this man and beaten down the Achaian people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.119#But since I was mad, in the persuasion of my heart's evil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.120#I am willing to make all good, and give back gifts in abundance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.121#Before you all I will count off my gifts in their splendour:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.122#seven unfired tripods; ten talents' weight of gold; twenty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.123#shining cauldrons; and twelve horses, strong, race-competitors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.124#who have won prizes in the speed of their feet. That man would not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.125#poor in possessions, to whom were given all these have won me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.126#nor be unpossessed of dearly honoured gold, were he given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.127#all the prizes these single-foot horses have won for me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.128#I will give him seven women of Lesbos, the work of whose hands is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.129#blameless, whom when he himself captured strong-founded Lesbos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.130#I chose, and who in their beauty surpassed the races of women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.131#I will give him these, and with them shall go the one I took from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.132#the daughter of Briseus. And to all this I will swear a great oath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.133#that I never entered into her bed and never lay with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.134#as is natural for human people, between men and women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.135#All these gifts shall be his at once; but again, if hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.136#the gods grant that we storm and sack the great city of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.137#let him go to his ship and load it deep as he pleases
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.138#with gold and bronze, when we Achaians divide the war spoils,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.139#and let him choose for himself twenty of the Trojan women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.140#who are the loveliest of all after Helen of Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.141#And if we come back to Achaian Argos, pride of the tilled land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.142#he may be my son-in-law; I will honour him with Orestes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.143#my growing son, who is brought up there in abundant luxury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.144#Since, as I have three daughters there in my strong-built castle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.145#Chrysothemis and Laodike and Iphianassa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.146#let him lead away the one of these that he likes, with no bride-price,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.147#to the house of Peleus, and with the girl I will grant him as dowry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.148#many gifts, such as no man ever gave with his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.149#I will grant to him seven citadels, strongly settled:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.150#Kardamyle, and Enope, and Hire of the grasses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.151#Pherai the sacrosanct, and Antheia deep in the meadows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.152#with Aipeia the lovely and Pedasos of the vineyards.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.153#All these lie near the sea, at the bottom of sandy Pylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.154#and men live among them rich in cattle and rich in sheepflocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.155#who will honour him as if he were a god with gifts given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.156#and fulfil his prospering decrees underneath his sceptre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.157#All this I will bring to pass for him, if he changes from his anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.158#Let him give way. For Hades gives not way, and is pitiless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.159#and therefore he among all the gods is most hateful to mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.160#And let him yield place to me, inasmuch as I am the kinglier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.161#and inasmuch as I can call myself born the elder.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.162#Thereupon the Gerenian horseman Nestor answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.163#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.164#none could scorn any longer these gifts you offer to Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.165#the king. Come, let us choose and send some men, who in all speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.166#will go to the shelter of Achilleus, the son of Peleus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.167#or come, the men on whom my eye falls, let these take the duty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.168#First of all let Phoinix, beloved of Zeus, be their leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.169#and after him take Aias the great, and brilliant Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.170#and of the heralds let Odios and Eurybates go with them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.171#Bring also water for their hands, and bid them keep words of good omen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.172#so we may pray to Zeus, son of Kronos, if he will have pity.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.173#So he spoke, and the word he spoke was pleasing to all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.174#And the heralds brought water at once, and poured it over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.175#their hands, and the young men filled the mixing-bowl with pure wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.176#and passed it to all, pouring first a libation in goblets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.177#Then when they had poured out wine, and drunk as much as their hearts wished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.178#they set out from the shelter of Atreus' son, Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.179#And the Gerenian horseman Nestor gave them much instruction,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.180#looking eagerly at each, and most of all at Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.181#to try hard, so that they might win over the blameless Peleion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.182#So these two walked along the strand of the sea deep-thundering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.183#with many prayers to the holder and shaker of the earth, that they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.184#might readily persuade the great heart of Aiakides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.185#Now they came beside the shelters and ships of the Myrmidons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.186#and they found Achilleus delighting his heart in a lyre, clear-sounding,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.187#splendid and carefully wrought, with a bridge of silver upon it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.188#which he won out of the spoils when he ruined Eëtion's city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.189#With this he was pleasuring his heart, and singing of men's fame,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.190#as Patroklos was sitting over against him, alone, in silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.191#watching Aiakides and the time he would leave off singing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.192#Now these two came forward, as brilliant Odysseus led them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.193#and stood in his presence. Achilleus rose to his feet in amazement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.194#holding the lyre as it was, leaving the place where he was sitting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.195#In the same way Patroklos, when he saw the men come, stood up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.196#And in greeting Achilleus the swift of foot spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.197#'Welcome. You are my friends who have come, and greatly I need you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.198#who even to this my anger are dearest of all the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.199#So brilliant Achilleus spoke, and guided them forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.200#and caused them to sit down on couches with purple coverlets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.201#and at once called over to Patroklos who was not far from him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.202#'Son of Menoitios, set up a mixing-bowl that is bigger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.203#and mix us stronger drink, and make ready a cup for each man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.204#since these who have come beneath my roof are the men that I love best.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.205#So he spoke, and Patroklos obeyed his beloved companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.206#and tossed down a great chopping-block into the firelight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.207#and laid upon it the back of a sheep, and one of a fat goat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.208#with the chine of a fatted pig edged thick with lard, and for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.209#Automedon held the meats, and brilliant Achilleus carved them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.210#and cut it well into pieces and spitted them, as meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.211#Menoitios' son, a man like a god, made the fire blaze greatly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.212#But when the fire had burned itself out, and the flames had died down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.213#he scattered the embers apart, and extended the spits across them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.214#lifting them to the andirons, and sprinkled the meats with divine salt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.215#Then when he had roasted all, and spread the food on the platters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.216#Patroklos took the bread and set it out on a table
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.217#in fair baskets, while Achilleus served the meats. Thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.218#he himself sat over against the godlike Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.219#against the further wall, and told his companion, Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.220#to sacrifice to the gods; and he threw the firstlings in the fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.221#They put their hands to the good things that lay ready before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.222#But when they had put aside their desire for eating and drinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.223#Aias nodded to Phoinix, and brilliant Odysseus saw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.224#and filled a cup with wine, and lifted it to Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.225#'Your health, Achilleus. You have no lack of your equal portion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.226#either within the shelter of Atreus' son, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.227#nor here now in your own. We have good things in abundance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.228#to feast on; here it is not the desirable feast we think of,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.229#but a trouble all too great, beloved of Zeus, that we look on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.230#and are afraid. There is doubt if we save our strong-benched vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.231#or if they will be destroyed, unless you put on your war strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.232#The Trojans in their pride, with their far-renowned companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.233#have set up an encampment close by the ships and the rampart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.234#and lit many fires along their army, and think no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.235#of being held, but rather to drive in upon the black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.236#And Zeus, son of Kronos, lightens upon their right hand, showing them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.237#portents of good, while Hektor in the huge pride of his strength rages
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.238#irresistibly, reliant on Zeus, and gives way to no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.239#neither god nor man, but the strong fury has descended upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.240#He prays now that the divine Dawn will show most quickly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.241#since he threatens to shear the uttermost horns from the ship-sterns,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.242#to light the ships themselves with ravening fire, and to cut down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.243#the Achaians themselves as they stir from the smoke beside them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.244#All this I fear terribly in my heart, lest immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.245#accomplish all these threats, and lest for us it be destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.246#to die here in Troy, far away from horse-pasturing Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.247#Up, then! if you are minded, late though it be, to rescue
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.248#the afflicted sons of the Achaians from the Trojan onslaught.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.249#It will be an affliction to you hereafter, there will be no remedy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.250#found to heal the evil thing when it has been done. No, beforehand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.251#take thought to beat the evil day aside from the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.252#Dear friend, surely thus your father Peleus advised you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.253#that day when he sent you away to Agamemnon from Phthia:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.254#"My child, for the matter of strength, Athene and Hera will give it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.255#if it be their will, but be it yours to hold fast in your bosom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.256#the anger of the proud heart, for consideration is better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.257#Keep from the bad complication of quarrel, and all the more for this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.258#the Argives will honour you, both their younger men and their elders."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.259#So the old man advised, but you have forgotten. Yet even now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.260#stop, and give way from the anger that hurts the heart. Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.261#offers you worthy recompense if you change from your anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.262#Come then, if you will, listen to me, while I count off for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.263#all the gifts in his shelter that Agamemnon has promised:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.264#Seven unfired tripods; ten talents' weight of gold; twenty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.265#shining cauldrons; and twelve horses, strong, race-competitors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.266#who have won prizes in the speed of their feet. That man would not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.267#poor in possessions, to whom were given all these have won him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.268#nor be unpossessed of dearly honoured gold, were he given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.269#all the prizes Agamemnon's horses won in their speed for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.270#He will give you seven women of Lesbos, the work of whose hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.271#is blameless, whom when you yourself captured strong-founded Lesbos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.272#he chose, and who in their beauty surpassed the races of women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.273#He will give you these, and with them shall go the one he took from you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.274#the daughter of Briseus. And to all this he will swear a great oath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.275#that he never entered into her bed and never lay with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.276#as is natural for human people, between men and women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.277#All these gifts shall be yours at once; but again, if hereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.278#the gods grant that we storm and sack the great city of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.279#you may go to your ship and load it deep as you please with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.280#gold and bronze, when we Achaians divide the war spoils,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.281#and you may choose for yourself twenty of the Trojan women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.282#who are the loveliest of all after Helen of Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.283#And if we come back to Achaian Argos, pride of the tilled land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.284#you could be his son-in-law; he would honour you with Orestes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.285#his growing son, who is brought up there in abundant luxury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.286#Since, as he has three daughters there in his strong-built castle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.287#Chrysothemis and Laodike and Iphianassa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.288#you may lead away the one of these that you like, with no bride-price,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.289#to the house of Peleus; and with the girl he will grant you as dowry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.290#many gifts, such as no man ever gave with his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.291#He will grant you seven citadels, strongly settled:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.292#Kardamyle and Enope and Hire of the grasses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.293#Pherai the sacrosanct, and Antheia deep in the meadows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.294#with Aipeia the lovely, and Pedasos of the vineyards.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.295#All these lie near the sea, at the bottom of sandy Pylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.296#and men live among them rich in cattle and rich in sheepflocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.297#who will honour you as if you were a god with gifts given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.298#and fulfil your prospering decrees underneath your sceptre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.299#All this he will bring to pass for you, if you change from your anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.300#But if the son of Atreus is too much hated in your heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.301#himself and his gifts, at least take pity on all the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.302#Achaians, who are afflicted along the host, and will honour you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.303#as a god. You may win very great glory among them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.304#For now you might kill Hektor, since he would come very close to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.305#with the wicked fury upon him, since he thinks there is not his equal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.306#among the rest of the Danaans the ships carried hither.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.307#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.308#'Son of Laertes and seed of Zeus, resourceful Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.309#without consideration for you I must make my answer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.310#the way I think, and the way it will be accomplished, that you may not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.311#come one after another, and sit by me, and speak softly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.312#For as I detest the doorways of Death, I detest that man, who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.313#hides one thing in the depths of his heart, and speaks forth another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.314#But I will speak to you the way it seems best to me: neither
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.315#do I think the son of Atreus, Agamemnon, will persuade me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.316#nor the rest of the Danaans, since there was no gratitude given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.317#for fighting incessantly forever against your enemies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.318#Fate is the same for the man who holds back, the same if he fights hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.319#We are all held in a single honour, the brave with the weaklings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.320#A man dies still if he has done nothing, as one who has done much.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.321#Nothing is won for me, now that my heart has gone through its afflictions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.322#in forever setting my life on the hazard of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.323#For as to her unwinged young ones the mother bird brings back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.324#morsels, wherever she can find them, but as for herself it is suffering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.325#such was I, as I lay through all the many nights unsleeping,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.326#such as I wore through the bloody days of the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.327#striving with warriors for the sake of these men's women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.328#But I say that I have stormed from my ships twelve cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.329#of men, and by land eleven more through the generous Troad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.330#From all these we took forth treasures, goodly and numerous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.331#and we would bring them back, and give them to Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.332#Atreus' son; while he, waiting back beside the swift ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.333#would take them, and distribute them little by little, and keep many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.334#All the other prizes of honour he gave the great men and the princes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.335#are held fast by them, but from me alone of all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.336#he has taken and keeps the bride of my heart. Let him lie beside her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.337#and be happy. Yet why must the Argives fight with the Trojans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.338#And why was it the son of Atreus assembled and led here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.339#these people? Was it not for the sake of lovely-haired Helen?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.340#Are the sons of Atreus alone among mortal men the ones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.341#who love their wives? Since any who is a good man, and careful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.342#loves her who is his own and cares for her, even as I now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.343#loved this one from my heart, though it was my spear that won her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.344#Now that he has deceived me and taken from my hands my prize of honour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.345#let him try me no more. I know him well. He will not persuade me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.346#Let him take counsel with you, Odysseus, and the rest of the princes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.347#how to fight the ravening fire away from his vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.348#Indeed, there has been much hard work done even without me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.349#he has built himself a wall and driven a ditch about it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.350#making it great and wide, and fixed the sharp stakes inside it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.351#Yet even so he cannot hold the strength of manslaughtering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.352#Hektor; and yet when I was fighting among the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.353#Hektor would not drive his attack beyond the wall's shelter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.354#but would come forth only so far as the Skaian gates and the oak tree.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.355#There once he endured me alone, and barely escaped my onslaught.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.356#But, now I am unwilling to fight against brilliant Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.357#tomorrow, when I have sacrificed to Zeus and to all gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.358#and loaded well my ships, and rowed out on to the salt water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.359#you will see, if you have a mind to it and if it concerns you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.360#my ships in the dawn at sea on the Hellespont where the fish swarm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.361#and my men manning them with good will to row. If the glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.362#shaker of the earth should grant us a favouring passage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.363#on the third day thereafter we might raise generous Phthia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.364#I have many possessions there that I left behind when I came here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.365#on this desperate venture, and from here there is more gold, and red bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.366#and fair-girdled women, and grey iron I will take back;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.367#all that was allotted to me. But my prize: he who gave it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.368#powerful Agamemnon, son of Atreus, has taken it back again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.369#outrageously. Go back and proclaim to him all that I tell you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.370#openly, so other Achaians may turn against him in anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.371#if he hopes yet one more time to swindle some other Danaan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.372#wrapped as he is forever in shamelessness; yet he would not,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.373#bold as a dog though he be, dare look in my face any longer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.374#I will join with him in no counsel, and in no action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.375#He cheated me and he did me hurt. Let him not beguile me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.376#with words again. This is enough for him. Let him of his own will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.377#be damned, since Zeus of the counsels has taken his wits away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.378#I hate his gifts. I hold him light as the strip of a splinter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.379#Not if he gave me ten times as much, and twenty times over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.380#as he possesses now, not if more should come to him from elsewhere,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.381#or gave all that is brought in to Orchomenos, all that is brought in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.382#to Thebes of Egypt, where the greatest possessions lie up in the houses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.383#Thebes of the hundred gates, where through each of the gates two hundred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.384#fighting men come forth to war with horses and chariots;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.385#not if he gave me gifts as many as the sand or the dust is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.386#not even so would Agamemnon have his way with my spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.387#until he had made good to me all this heartrending insolence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.388#Nor will I marry a daughter of Atreus' son, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.389#not if she challenged Aphrodite the golden for loveliness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.390#not if she matched the work of her hands with grey-eyed Athene;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.391#not even so will I marry her; let him pick some other Achaian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.392#one who is to his liking and is kinglier than I am.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.393#For if the gods will keep me alive, and I win homeward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.394#Peleus himself will presently arrange a wife for me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.395#There are many Achaian girls in the land of Hellas and Phthia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.396#daughters of great men who hold strong places in guard. And of these
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.397#any one that I please I might make my beloved lady.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.398#And the great desire in my heart drives me rather in that place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.399#to take a wedded wife in marriage, the bride of my fancy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.400#to enjoy with her the possessions won by aged Peleus. For not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.401#worth the value of my life are all the possessions they fable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.402#were won for Ilion, that strong-founded citadel, in the old days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.403#when there was peace, before the coming of the sons of the Achaians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.404#not all that the stone doorsill of the Archer holds fast within it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.405#of Phoibos Apollo in Pytho of the rocks. Of possessions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.406#cattle and fat sheep are things to be had for the lifting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.407#and tripods can be won, and the tawny high heads of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.408#but a man's life cannot come back again, it cannot be lifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.409#nor captured again by force, once it has crossed the teeth's barrier.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.410#For my mother Thetis the goddess of the silver feet tells me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.411#I carry two sorts of destiny toward the day of my death. Either,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.412#if I stay here and fight beside the city of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.413#my return home is gone, but my glory shall be everlasting;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.414#but if I return home to the beloved land of my fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.415#the excellence of my glory is gone, but there will be a long life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.416#left for me, and my end in death will not come to me quickly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.417#And this would be my counsel to others also, to sail back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.418#home again, since no longer shall you find any term set
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.419#on the sheer city of Ilion, since Zeus of the wide brows has strongly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.420#held his own hand over it, and its people are made bold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.421#Do you go back therefore to the great men of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.422#and take them this message, since such is the privilege of the princes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.423#that they think out in their minds some other scheme that is better,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.424#which might rescue their ships, and the people of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.425#who man the hollow ships, since this plan will not work for them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.426#which they thought of by reason of my anger. Let Phoinix
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.427#remain here with us and sleep here, so that tomorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.428#he may come with us in our ships to the beloved land of our fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.429#if he will; but I will never use force to hold him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.430#So he spoke, and all of them stayed stricken to silence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.431#in amazement at his words. He had spoken to them very strongly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.432#But at long last Phoinix the aged horseman spoke out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.433#in a stormburst of tears, and fearing for the ships of the Achaians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.434#'If it is going home, glorious Achilleus, you ponder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.435#in your heart, and are utterly unwilling to drive the obliterating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.436#fire from the fast ships, since anger has descended on your spirit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.437#how then shall I, dear child, be left in this place behind you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.438#all alone? Peleus the aged horseman sent me forth with you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.439#on that day when he sent you from Phthia to Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.440#a mere child, who knew nothing yet of the joining of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.441#nor of debate where men are made pre-eminent. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.442#he sent me along with you to teach you of all these matters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.443#to make you a speaker of words and one who accomplished in action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.444#Therefore apart from you, dear child, I would not be willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.445#to be left behind, not were the god in person to promise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.446#he would scale away my old age and make me a young man blossoming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.447#as I was that time when I first left Hellas, the land of fair women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.448#running from the hatred of Ormenos' son Amyntor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.449#my father; who hated me for the sake of a fair-haired mistress.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.450#For he made love to her himself, and dishonoured his own wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.451#my mother; who was forever taking my knees and entreating me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.452#to lie with this mistress instead so that she would hate the old man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.453#I was persuaded and did it; and my father when he heard of it straightway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.454#called down his curses, and invoked against me the dreaded furies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.455#that I might never have any son born of my seed to dandle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.456#on my knees; and the divinities, Zeus of the underworld
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.457#and Persephone the honoured goddess, accomplished his curses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.458#Then I took it into my mind to cut him down with the sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.459#but some one of the immortals checked my anger, reminding me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.460#of rumour among the people and men's maledictions repeated,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.461#that I might not be called a parricide among the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.462#But now no more could the heart in my breast be ruled entirely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.463#to range still among these halls when my father was angered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.464#Rather it was the many kinsmen and cousins about me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.465#who held me closed in the house, with supplications repeated,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.466#and slaughtered fat sheep in their numbers, and shambling horn-curved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.467#cattle, and numerous swine with the fat abundant upon them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.468#were singed and stretched out across the flame of Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.469#and much wine was drunk that was stored in the jars of the old man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.470#Nine nights they slept nightlong in their places beside me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.471#and they kept up an interchange of watches, and the fire was never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.472#put out; one below the gate of the strong-closed courtyard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.473#and one in the ante-chamber before the doors of the bedroom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.474#But when the tenth night had come to me in its darkness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.475#then I broke the close-compacted doors of the chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.476#and got away, and overleapt the fence of the courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.477#lightly, unnoticed by the guarding men and the women servants.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.478#Then I fled far away through the wide spaces of Hellas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.479#and came as far as generous Phthia, mother of sheepflocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.480#and to lord Peleus, who accepted me with a good will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.481#and gave me his love, even as a father loves his own son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.482#who is a single child brought up among many possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.483#He made me a rich man, and granted me many people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.484#and I lived, lord over the Dolopes, in remotest Phthia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.485#and, godlike Achilleus, I made you all that you are now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.486#and loved you out of my heart, for you would not go with another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.487#out to any feast, nor taste any food in your own halls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.488#until I had set you on my knees, and cut little pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.489#from the meat, and given you all you wished, and held the wine for you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.490#And many times you soaked the shirt that was on my body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.491#with wine you would spit up in the troublesomeness of your childhood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.492#So I have suffered much through you, and have had much trouble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.493#thinking always how the gods would not bring to birth any children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.494#of my own; so that it was you, godlike Achilleus, I made
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.495#my own child, so that some day you might keep hard affliction from me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.496#Then, Achilleus, beat down your great anger. It is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.497#yours to have a pitiless heart. The very immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.498#can be moved; their virtue and honour and strength are greater than ours are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.499#and yet with sacrifices and offerings for endearment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.500#with libations and with savour men turn back even the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.501#in supplication, when any man does wrong and transgresses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.502#For there are also the spirits of Prayer, the daughters of great Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.503#and they are lame of their feet, and wrinkled, and cast their eyes sidelong,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.504#who toil on their way left far behind by the spirit of Ruin:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.505#but she, Ruin, is strong and sound on her feet, and therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.506#far outruns all Prayers, and wins into every country
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.507#to force men astray; and the Prayers follow as healers after her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.508#If a man venerates these daughters of Zeus as they draw near,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.509#such a man they bring great advantage, and hear his entreaty;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.510#but if a man shall deny them, and stubbornly with a harsh word
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.511#refuse, they go to Zeus, son of Kronos, in supplication
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.512#that Ruin may overtake this man, that he be hurt, and punished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.513#So, Achilleus: grant, you also, that Zeus' daughters be given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.514#their honour, which, lordly though they be, curbs the will of others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.515#Since, were he not bringing gifts and naming still more hereafter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.516#Atreus' son; were he to remain still swollen with rancour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.517#even I would not bid you throw your anger aside, nor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.518#defend the Argives, though they needed you sorely. But see now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.519#he offers you much straightway, and has promised you more hereafter;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.520#he has sent the best men to you to supplicate you, choosing them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.521#out of the Achaian host, those who to yourself are the dearest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.522#of all the Argives. Do not you make vain their argument
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.523#nor their footsteps, though before this one could not blame your anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.524#Thus it was in the old days also, the deeds that we hear of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.525#from the great men, when the swelling anger descended upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.526#The heroes would take gifts; they would listen, and be persuaded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.527#For I remember this action of old, it is not a new thing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.528#and how it went; you are all my friends, I will tell it among you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.529#The Kouretes and the steadfast Aitolians were fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.530#and slaughtering one another about the city of Kalydon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.531#the Aitolians in lovely Kalydon's defence, the Kouretes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.532#furious to storm and sack it in war. For Artemis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.533#she of the golden chair, had driven this evil upon them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.534#angered that Oineus had not given the pride of the orchards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.535#to her, first fruits; the rest of the gods were given due sacrifice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.536#but alone to this daughter of great Zeus he had given nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.537#He had forgotten, or had not thought, in his hard delusion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.538#and in wrath at his whole mighty line the Lady of Arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.539#sent upon them the fierce wild boar with the shining teeth, who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.540#after the way of his kind did much evil to the orchards of Oineus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.541#For he ripped up whole tall trees from the ground and scattered them headlong
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.542#roots and all, even to the very flowers of the orchard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.543#The son of Oineus killed this boar, Meleagros, assembling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.544#together many hunting men out of numerous cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.545#with their hounds; since the boar might not have been killed by a few men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.546#so huge was he, and had put many men on the sad fire for burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.547#But the goddess again made a great stir of anger and crying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.548#battle, over the head of the boar and the bristling boar's hide,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.549#between Kouretes and the high-hearted Aitolians. So long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.550#as Meleagros lover of battle stayed in the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.551#it went the worse for the Kouretes, and they could not even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.552#hold their ground outside the wall, though they were so many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.553#But when the anger came upon Meleagros, such anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.554#as wells in the hearts of others also, though their minds are careful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.555#he, in the wrath of his heart against his own mother, Althaia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.556#lay apart with his wedded bride, Kleopatra the lovely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.557#daughter of sweet-stepping Marpessa, child of Euenos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.558#and Idas, who was the strongest of all men upon earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.559#in his time; for the even took up the bow to face the King's onset,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.560#Phoibos Apollo, for the sake of the sweet-stepping maiden;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.561#a girl her father and honoured mother had named in their palace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.562#Alkyone, sea-bird, as a by-name, since for her sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.563#her mother with the sorrow-laden cry of a sea-bird
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.564#wept because far-reaching Phoibos Apollo had taken her;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.565#with this Kleopatra he lay mulling his heart-sore anger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.566#raging by reason of his mother's curses, which she called down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.567#from the gods upon him, in deep grief for the death of her brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.568#and many times beating with her hands on the earth abundant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.569#she called on Hades and on honoured Persephone, lying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.570#at length along the ground, and the tears were wet on her bosom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.571#to give death to her son; and Erinys, the mist-walking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.572#she of the heart without pity, heard her out of the dark places.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.573#Presently there was thunder about the gates, and the sound rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.574#of towers under assault, and the Aitolian elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.575#supplicated him, sending their noblest priests of the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.576#to come forth and defend them; they offered him a great gift:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.577#wherever might lie the richest ground in lovely Kalydon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.578#there they told him to choose out a piece of land, an entirely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.579#good one, of fifty acres, the half of it to be vineyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.580#and the half of it unworked ploughland of the plain to be furrowed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.581#And the aged horseman Oineus again and again entreated him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.582#and took his place at the threshold of the high-vaulted chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.583#and shook against the bolted doors, pleading with his own son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.584#And again and again his honoured mother and his sisters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.585#entreated him, but he only refused the more; then his own friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.586#who were the most honoured and dearest of all entreated him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.587#but even so they could not persuade the heart within him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.588#until, as the chamber was under close assault, the Kouretes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.589#were mounting along the towers and set fire to the great city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.590#And then at last his wife, the fair-girdled bride, supplicated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.591#Meleagros, in tears, and rehearsed in their numbers before him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.592#all the sorrows that come to men when their city is taken:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.593#they kill the men, and the fire leaves the city in ashes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.594#and strangers lead the children away and the deep-girdled women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.595#And the heart, as he listened to all this evil, was stirred within him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.596#and he rose, and went, and closed his body in shining armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.597#So he gave way in his own heart, and drove back the day of evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.598#from the Aitolians; yet these no longer would make good
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.599#their many and gracious gifts; yet he drove back the evil from them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.600#Listen, then; do not have such a thought in your mind; let not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.601#the spirit within you turn you that way, dear friend. It would be worse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.602#to defend the ships after they are burning. No, with gifts promised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.603#go forth. The Achaians will honour you as they would an immortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.604#But if without gifts you go into the fighting where men perish,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.605#your honour will no longer be as great, though you drive back the battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.606#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.607#'Phoinix my father, aged, illustrious, such honour is a thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.608#I need not. I think I am honoured already in Zeus' ordinance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.609#which will hold me here beside my curved ships as long as life's wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.610#stays in my breast, as long as my knees have their spring beneath me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.611#And put away in your thoughts this other thing I tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.612#Stop confusing my heart with lamentation and sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.613#for the favour of great Atreides. It does not become you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.614#to love this man, for fear you turn hateful to me, who love you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.615#It should be your pride with me to hurt whoever shall hurt me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.616#Be king equally with me; take half of my honour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.617#These men will carry back the message; you stay here and sleep here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.618#in a soft bed, and we shall decide tomorrow, as dawn shows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.619#whether to go back home again or else to remain here.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.620#He spoke, and, saying nothing, nodded with his brows to Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.621#to make up a neat bed for Phoinix, so the others might presently
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.622#think of going home from his shelter. The son of Telamon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.623#Aias the godlike, saw it, and now spoke his word among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.624#'Son of Laertes and seed of Zeus, resourceful Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.625#let us go. I think that nothing will be accomplished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.626#by argument on this errand; it is best to go back quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.627#and tell this story, though it is not good, to the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.628#who sit there waiting for us to come back, seeing that Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.629#has made savage the proud-hearted spirit within his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.630#He is hard, and does not remember that friends' affection
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.631#wherein we honoured him by the ships, far beyond all others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.632#Pitiless. And yet a man takes from his brother's slayer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.633#the blood price, or the price for a child who was killed, and the guilty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.634#one, when he has largely repaid, stays still in the country,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.635#and the injured man's heart is curbed, and his pride, and his anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.636#when he has taken the price; but the gods put in your breast a spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.637#not to be placated, bad, for the sake of one single
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.638#girl. Yet now we offer you seven, surpassingly lovely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.639#and much beside these. Now make gracious the spirit within you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.640#Respect your own house; see, we are under the same roof with you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.641#from the multitude of the Danaans, we who desire beyond all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.642#others to have your honour and love, out of all the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.643#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.644#'Son of Telamon, seed of Zeus, Aias, lord of the people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.645#all that you have said seems spoken after my own mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.646#Yet still the heart in me swells up in anger, when I remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.647#the disgrace that he wrought upon me before the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.648#the son of Atreus, as if I were some dishonoured vagabond.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.649#Do you then go back to him, and take him this message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.650#that I shall not think again of the bloody fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.651#until such time as the son of wise Priam, Hektor the brilliant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.652#comes all the way to the ships of the Myrmidons, and their shelters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.653#slaughtering the Argives, and shall darken with fire our vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.654#But around my own shelter, I think, and beside my black ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.655#Hektor will be held, though he be very hungry for battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.656#He spoke, and they taking each a two-handled cup poured out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.657#a libation, then went back to their ships, and Odysseus led them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.658#Now Patroklos gave the maids and his followers orders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.659#to make up without delay a neat bed for Phoinix.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.660#And these obeyed him and made up the bed as he had commanded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.661#laying fleeces on it, and a blanket, and a sheet of fine linen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.662#There the old man lay down and waited for the divine Dawn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.663#But Achilleus slept in the inward corner of the strong-built shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.664#and a woman lay beside him, one he had taken from Lesbos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.665#Phorbas' daughter, Diomede of the fair colouring.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.666#In the other corner Patroklos went to bed; with him also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.667#was a girl, Iphis the fair-girdled, whom brilliant Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.668#gave him, when he took sheer Skyros, Enyeus' citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.669#Now when these had come back to the shelters of Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.670#the sons of the Achaians greeted them with their gold cups
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.671#uplifted, one after another, standing, and asked them questions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.672#And the first to question them was the lord of men, Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.673#'Tell me, honoured Odysseus, great glory of the Achaians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.674#is he willing to fight the ravening fire away from our vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.675#or did he refuse, and does the anger still hold his proud heart?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.676#Then long-suffering great Odysseus spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.677#'Son of Atreus, most lordly, king of men, Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.678#That man will not quench his anger, but still more than ever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.679#is filled with rage. He refuses you and refuses your presents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.680#He tells you yourself to take counsel among the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.681#how to save your ships, and the people of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.682#And he himself has threatened that tomorrow as dawn shows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.683#he will drag down his strong-benched, oarswept ships to the water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.684#He said it would be his counsel to others also, to sail back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.685#home again, since no longer will you find any term set
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.686#on the sheer city of Ilion, since Zeus of the wide brows has strongly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.687#held his own hand over it, and its people are made bold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.688#So he spoke. There are these to attest it who went there with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.689#also, Aias, and the two heralds, both men of good counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.690#But aged Phoinix stayed there for the night, as Achilleus urged him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.691#so he might go home in the ships to the beloved land of his fathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.692#if Phoinix will; but he will never use force to persuade him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.693#So he spoke, and all of them stayed stricken to silence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.694#in amazement at his words. He had spoken to them very strongly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.695#For a long time the sons of the Achaians said nothing, in sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.696#but at long last Diomedes of the great war cry spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.697#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.698#I wish you had not supplicated the blameless son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.699#with innumerable gifts offered. He is a proud man without this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.700#and now you have driven him far deeper into his pride. Rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.701#we shall pay him no more attention, whether he comes in with us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.702#or stays away. He will fight again, whenever the time comes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.703#that the heart in his body urges him to, and the god drives him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.704#Come then, do as I say, and let us all be won over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.705#Go to sleep, now that the inward heart is made happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.706#with food and drink, for these are the strength and courage within us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.707#But when the lovely dawn shows forth with rose fingers, Atreides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.708#rapidly form before our ships both people and horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.709#stirring them on, and yourself be ready to fight in the foremost.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.710#So he spoke, and all the kings gave him their approval,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.711#acclaiming the word of Diomedes, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.712#Then they poured a libation, and each man went to his shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:9.713#where they went to their beds and took the blessing of slumber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.1#Now beside their ships the other great men of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.2#slept night long, with the soft bondage of slumber upon them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.3#but the son of Atreus, Agamemnon, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.4#was held by no sweet sleep as he pondered deeply within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.5#As when the lord of Hera the lovely-haired flashes his lightning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.6#as he brings on a great rainstorm, or a hail incessant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.7#or a blizzard, at such time when the snowfall scatters on ploughlands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.8#or drives on somewhere on earth the huge edge of tearing battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.9#such was Agamemnon, with the beating turmoil in his bosom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.10#from the deep heart, and all his wits were shaken within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.11#Now he would gaze across the plain to the Trojan camp, wondering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.12#at the number of their fires that were burning in front of Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.13#toward the high calls of their flutes and pipes, the murmur of people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.14#Now as he would look again to the ships and the Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.15#people, he would drag the hair by its roots from his head, looking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.16#toward Zeus on high, and his proud heart was stricken with lamentation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.17#Now to his mind this thing appeared to be the best counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.18#first among men to seek out Nestor, the son of Neleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.19#to see if Nestor with him could work out a plan that would not fail,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.20#and one that might drive the evil away from all the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.21#He stood upright, and slipped the tunic upon his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.22#and underneath his shining feet he bound the fair sandals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.23#and thereafter slung across him the tawny hide of a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.24#glowing and huge, that swung to his feet, and took up a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.25#So likewise trembling seized Menelaos, neither on his eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.26#had sweet slumber descending settled, for fear that the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.27#might suffer some hurt, they who for his sake over much water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.28#had come to Troy, bearing their bold attack to the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.29#First of all he mantled his broad back in a leopard's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.30#spotted hide, then lifting the circle of a brazen helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.31#placed it upon his head, and took up a spear in his big hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.32#and went on his way to waken his brother, who was the great king
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.33#of all Argives, one honoured in his own land as a god is.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.34#He found him putting the splendid armour about his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.35#beside the stern of his ship, and was welcomed as he came up to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.36#It was Menelaos of the great war cry who spoke first:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.37#'Why this arming, my brother? Is it some one of your companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.38#you are stirring to go and spy on the Trojans? Yet I fear sadly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.39#there will not be any man to undertake this endeavour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.40#going against enemy fighters to spy on them, alone, through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.41#the immortal night. Such a man will have to be very bold-hearted.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.42#Then in turn powerful Agamemnon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.43#'You and I, illustrious, o Menelaos, have need now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.44#of crafty counsel, if any man is to defend and rescue
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.45#the Argives and their ships, since the heart of Zeus is turned from us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.46#For the sacrifices of Hektor have stirred his heart more than ours have.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.47#No, for I never saw nor heard from the lips of another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.48#of a single man in a day imagining so much evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.49#as Hektor, beloved of Zeus, has wrought on the sons of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.50#alone, being called true son neither of a god nor a goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.51#He has done things I think the Argives will remember with sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.52#long into the future, such harm has he devised the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.53#But go now, running lightly beside the ships, and call to us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.54#Idomeneus and Aias, while I shall go after Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.55#the brilliant, and waken him to rise, if he might be willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.56#to approach the sacred duty of the guards, or give orders to them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.57#Above all, these would listen to him, seeing that his own son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.58#commands the pickets, and with him the follower of Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.59#Meriones. To these above all we entrusted the duty.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.60#Then in turn Menelaos of the great war cry answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.61#'How then do you intend this order that you have given me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.62#Shall I wait where I am, with them, and watch for your coming,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.63#or run after you, when I have properly given the order?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.64#Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.65#'Better wait here, so there will be no way we can miss one another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.66#as we come and go. There are many paths up and down the encampment.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.67#Call out wherever you go, and waken each man to give him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.68#your orders, naming him by descent with the name of his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.69#Give each man due respect. Let not your spirit be haughty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.70#but let it be you and I ourselves who do the work, seeing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.71#that Zeus cast on us as we were born this burden of evil.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.72#So he spoke and with careful orders sent off his brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.73#and he himself went in search of Nestor, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.74#and came on him beside his own shelter and his own black ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.75#in a soft bed, and his bright gear was lying beside him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.76#the shield, and the two spears, and the glittering helmet, and by him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.77#lay in all its shining the war belt, in which the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.78#girt himself, when he armed for the fighting where men die, leading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.79#his own people, since he gave no ground to sorrowful old age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.80#He straightened up and raised his head, leaning on one elbow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.81#and spoke to the son of Atreus, and asked him a question:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.82#'Who are you, who walk alone through the ships and the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.83#and through the darkness of night when other mortals are sleeping?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.84#Are you looking for one of your mules, or looking for some companion?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.85#Speak, do not come upon me in silence. What would you of me?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.86#Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.87#'Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.88#you will know Atreus' son Agamemnon, whom beyond others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.89#Zeus has involved in hard work forever, as long as life's wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.90#stays in my breast, as long as my knees have their spring beneath me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.91#I am driven thus, because the ease of sleep will not settle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.92#on my eyes, but fighting and the cares of the Achaians perplex me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.93#Terribly I am in dread for the Danaans, nor does my pulse beat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.94#steadily, but I go distracted, and my heart is pounding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.95#through my chest, and my shining limbs are shaken beneath me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.96#But if you are for action, since sleep comes neither upon you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.97#let us both go out to the pickets, so that we may see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.98#if they might not have found weariness too much for them, and fallen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.99#asleep, and altogether forgotten their duty, to keep watch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.100#There are men who hate us sitting nearby, nor do we know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.101#that they might not be pondering an attack on us in the darkness.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.102#Thereupon the Gerenian horseman Nestor answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.103#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.104#Zeus of the counsels, I think, will not accomplish for Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.105#all his designs and all he hopes for now; I think rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.106#he will have still more hardships to wrestle, if ever Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.107#turns again the heart within him from its wearisome anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.108#Surely, I will go with you, and let us also awaken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.109#others, the son of Tydeus the spear-famed, and Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.110#and Aias the swift-footed, and the powerful son of Phyleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.111#But if one were to go also and call these others I speak of,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.112#Aias the great, the godlike one, and the lord Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.113#why, their ships lie farthest from us, and are not at all close.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.114#But, beloved as he is and respected, I will still blame
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.115#Menelaos, even though you be angry, and I will not hide it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.116#for the way he sleeps and has given to you alone all the hard work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.117#For now he ought to be hard at work going to all the great men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.118#in supplication. This need that has come is no more endurable.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.119#Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.120#'Aged sir, other times I also would tell you to blame him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.121#since often he hangs back and is not willing to work hard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.122#not that he shrinks from it and gives way, nor in the mind's dullness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.123#but because he looks to me, and waits till I make a beginning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.124#But this time he woke far before me, and came to rouse me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.125#and I sent him on to call those you ask after. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.126#let us go. We shall find those others there with the sentries
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.127#before the gates, where I told them to form and assemble.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.128#Thereupon the Gerenian horseman Nestor answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.129#'Thus no man of the Argives can disobey him nor find fault
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.130#with him, whenever he stirs up any of them and gives orders.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.131#With this speech, he slipped the tunic upon his body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.132#and underneath his shining feet he bound the fair sandals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.133#and pinned about him a great vermilion mantle sweeping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.134#in a double fold, with a thick fleece of wool upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.135#Then he caught up a powerful spear, edged with sharp bronze,
