urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.338#Now when he had left behind the throng of men and of horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.339#he went on his way, eagerly, but illustrious Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.340#was aware of him coming and spoke to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.341#'This is some man, Diomedes, on his way from the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.342#I do not know whether he comes to spy on our vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.343#or to strip some one of the perished corpses, but we must let him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.344#first go on past us a little way in the open
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.345#and afterwards we will make a rush and fasten upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.346#suddenly. But if in the speed of his feet he eludes us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.347#then keep him crowded upon the ships, and away from the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.348#always, feinting with the spear, nor let him escape to the city.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.349#So they spoke, and bent aside from their way, through the corpses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.350#while he in the thoughtlessness of his heart ran swiftly by them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.351#But when he was gone from them as far as the range of a plough yoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.352#of mules, since these are better beasts than oxen for dragging
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.353#the wrought ploughshare through the depth of the harvest land, these two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.354#ran after him, and he heard the thudding of their feet and stopped still.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.355#He thought in his heart these would be friends from among the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.356#to turn him back, and that Hektor had sped them to summon him again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.357#But when they got to a spear's throw from him, or less even,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.358#he saw that these were enemy men, and moved his knees rapidly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.359#to run away, and these set out in rapid chase of him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.360#And, as when two rip-fanged hounds have sighted a wild beast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.361#a young deer, or a hare, and go after it, eagerly always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.362#through the spaces of the woods, and the chase runs crying before them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.363#so the son of Tydeus, and Odysseus, sacker of cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.364#kept always hard on his heels and cut him off from his people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.365#But when he was on the point of reaching the Achaian pickets,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.366#as he fled toward the vessels, then Athene put great power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.367#in Tydeus' son, so that no other bronze-armoured Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.368#might win the glory of striking him down, and he come in second.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.369#Powerful Diomedes threatening with the spear spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.370#'Either wait, or my spear will catch you. I think that you will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.371#thus get clear from my hands for long, and sudden destruction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.372#He spoke, and let fly with his spear, but missed, on purpose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.373#his man, as the point of the polished spear went over his right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.374#and stuck fast in the earth. And Dolon stood still in terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.375#gibbering, as through his mouth came the sound of his teeth's chatter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.376#in green fear; and these two, breathing hard, came up to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.377#and caught him by the hands, and he broke into tears and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.378#'Take me alive, and I will pay my ransom: in my house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.379#there is bronze, and gold, and difficultly wrought iron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.380#and my father would make you glad with abundant ransom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.381#were he to hear that I am alive by the ships of the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.382#Then resourceful Odysseus spoke in turn, and answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.383#'Do not fear, and let no thought of death be upon you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.384#But come, tell me this thing and recite it to me accurately:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.385#where is it that you walk alone to the ships from the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.386#through the darkness of night when other mortals are sleeping?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.387#Is it to strip some one of the perished corpses, or is it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.388#that Hektor sent you out to spy with care upon each thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.389#beside our hollow ships? Or did your own spirit drive you?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.390#Then Dolon answered him, but his legs were shaking beneath him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.391#'Hektor has led my mind astray with many deceptions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.392#He promised me the single-foot horses of proud Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.393#Peleus' son, and the chariot bright with bronze, for my gift,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.394#and gave me an order, to go through the running black night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.395#and get close to the enemy men, and find out for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.396#whether the swift ships are guarded, as they were before this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.397#or whether now the Achaians who are broken under our hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.398#are planning flight among themselves, and no longer are willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.399#to guard them by night, now that stark weariness has broken them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.400#Then Odysseus the resourceful smiled and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.401#'Surely now, these were mighty gifts that your heart longed after,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.402#the horses of valiant Aiakides. They are difficult horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.403#for mortal men to manage, or even to ride behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.404#for all except Achilleus, who was born of an immortal mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.405#But come, tell me this thing and recite it to me accurately.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.406#Where did you leave Hektor, the people's shepherd, when you came here?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.407#Where is his gear of war lying? Where are his horses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.408#How are the rest of the Trojans disposed, the guards and the sleepers?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.409#What do they deliberate among themselves? Do they purpose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.410#to stay where they are, close to the ships? Or else to withdraw back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.411#into the city, now that they have beaten the Achaians?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.412#Then in turn Dolon the son of Eumedes spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.413#'See, I will accurately recite all these things to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.414#Hektor is now among those who are the men of counsel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.415#and they hold their deliberations by the barrow of godlike Ilos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.416#apart from the confusion. But those guards that you ask of, hero--
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.417#there is no detail that protects the army and guards it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.418#As for the watchfire hearths of the Trojans, those who must do it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.419#keep awake by the fires and pass on the picket duty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.420#to each other, but their far-assembled companions in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.421#are sleeping, and pass on to the Trojans the duty of watching,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.422#since their own children do not lie nearby, nor their women.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.423#Then resourceful Odysseus spoke in turn, and answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.424#'How, then, are these sleeping? And are they mixed with the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.425#breakers of horses, or apart? Tell me, so I may be clear.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.426#Then in turn Dolon the son of Eumedes answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.427#'See, I will accurately recite all these things to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.428#Next the sea are the Karians, and Paionians with their curved bows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.429#the Leleges and Kaukonians and the brilliant Pelasgians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.430#By Thymbre are stationed the Lykians and the proud Mysians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.431#with the Phrygians who fight from horses, and Maionians, lords of chariots.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.432#But why do you question me on all this, each thing in detail?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.433#For if you are minded to get among the mass of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.434#here are the Thracians, new come, separate, beyond all others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.435#in place, and among them Rhesos their king, the son of Eïoneus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.436#And his are the finest horses I ever saw, and the biggest;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.437#they are whiter than snow, and their speed of foot is the winds' speed;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.438#his chariot is fairly ornate with gold and with silver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.439#and the armour is golden and gigantic, a wonder to look on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.440#that he brought here with him. It is not like armour for mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.441#men to carry, but for the immortal gods. And therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.442#take me with you to some place by the fast-running vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.443#or else tie me fast here in a pitiless bond, and leave me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.444#until you can make your venture, and try out the truth of my story,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.445#whether I have told you this fairly, or whether I have not.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.446#But powerful Diomedes looked darkly at him and spoke then:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.447#'Do not, Dolon, have in your mind any thought of escape
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.448#now you have got in our hands, though you brought us an excellent message.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.449#For if we let you get away now, or set you free, later
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.450#you will come back again to the fast ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.451#either to spy on us once more, or to fight strongly with us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.452#But if, beaten down under my hands, you lose your life now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.453#then you will nevermore be an affliction upon the Argives.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.454#He spoke, and the man was trying to reach his chin with his strong hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.455#and cling, and supplicate him, but he struck the middle of his neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.456#with a sweep of the sword, and slashed clean through both tendons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.457#and Dolon's head still speaking dropped in the dust. They took off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.458#his cap of marten's hide from his head, and stripped off also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.459#the wolf's pelt, and the back-strung bow, and the long spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.460#Brilliant Odysseus held these up to Athene the Spoiler
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.461#high in his hand, and spoke a word, and prayed to Athene:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.462#'Hail, goddess. These are yours. To you first of all the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.463#on Olympos we will give your due share. Only guide us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.464#once again to where the Thracians sleep, and their horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.465#So he spoke, and lifting the spoils high from him he placed them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.466#upon a tamarisk bush, and piled a clear landmark beside them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.467#pulling reeds together and the long branches of tamarisk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.468#that they might not miss them on their way back through the running black night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.469#These two went ahead on their way through war gear and dark blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.470#and came suddenly to the Thracians for whom they were looking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.471#These were asleep, worn out with weariness, and their armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.472#lay in splendour and good order on the ground beside them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.473#in three rows, and beside each man stood his team of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.474#Rhesos slept in the centre with his fast horses about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.475#tethered by the reins to the outer rail of the chariot. Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.476#was the first to see him and pointed him out to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.477#'Here is our man, see, Diomedes, and here are his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.478#those that Dolon, the man we killed, pointed out to us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.479#Come then, put forward your great strength. Here is no matter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.480#for standing by idle in your weapons. Untie the horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.481#or else let me look after them, while you kill the people.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.482#He spoke, and grey-eyed Athene breathed strength into Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.483#and he began to kill them one after another. Grim sounds rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.484#from there as they were stricken with the sword, and the ground reddened with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.485#As a lion advancing on the helpless herds unshepherded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.486#of sheep or goats pounces upon them with wicked intention,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.487#so the son of Tydeus attacked the Thracian people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.488#until he had killed twelve. Meanwhile resourceful Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.489#as Tydeus' son stood over each man with the sword, and struck him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.490#would catch each dead man by the foot from behind, and drag him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.491#away, with this thought in his mind, that the bright-maned horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.492#might pass easily through and not be shaken within them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.493#at stepping on dead men. These horses were not yet used to them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.494#But when the son of Tydeus came to the king, and this was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.495#the thirteenth man, he stripped the sweetness of life from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.496#as he lay heavily breathing--since a bad dream stood by his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.497#in the night--no dream, but Oineus' son, by device of Athene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.498#Meanwhile patient Odysseus was untying the single-foot horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.499#and pulled them together with the reins, and drove them from the confusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.500#and whipped them with his bow, since he had not noticed nor taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.501#in his hands the glittering whip that was in the elaborate chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.502#He whistled to brilliant Diomedes as a signal to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.503#But he waited, divided in his mind as to what he would best do,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.504#whether to seize the chariot, wherein lay the bright armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.505#and draw it away by the pole, or lift it and carry it off with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.506#or strip the life from still more of the Thracians. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.507#as he was pondering all this in his heart, Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.508#came and stood beside him, and spoke to great Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.509#'Think now, son of great-hearted Tydeus, of getting back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.510#to the hollow ships; else you might go back with men pursuing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.511#if there should be some other god to waken the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.512#So she spoke, and he knew the voice of the goddess speaking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.513#and lightly mounted behind the horses. Odysseus whipped them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.514#with his bow, and they ran for the rapid ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.515#Neither did Apollo of the silver bow keep blind watch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.516#since he saw Athene attending the son of Tydeus. Angered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.517#with her he plunged into the great multitude of the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.518#and roused a man of counsel among the Thracians, Hippokoön
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.519#the lordly cousin of Rhesos; and he, starting out of his sleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.520#when he saw the place left empty where the fast horses had been standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.521#and his men in the shambles of slaughter gasping their lives out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.522#he groaned, and called aloud by name his beloved companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.523#And a clamour rose up from the Trojans and a vast turmoil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.524#as they swept together in confusion and stared at the ghastly work done
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.525#by these two men, before they went back to their hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.526#But when these had come back to the place where they killed Hektor's scout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.527#Odysseus beloved of Zeus reined in his running horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.528#while Tydeus' son leaping to the ground took the bloody war spoils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.529#and handed them to Odysseus, and got up behind the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.530#Odysseus lashed them on, and they winged their way unreluctant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.531#back to the hollow ships, since this was the way he desired it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.532#Nestor was the first to hear their thunder, and spoke forth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.533#'Friends, who are leaders of the Argives and keep their counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.534#shall I be wrong, or am I speaking the truth? My heart tells me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.535#The thunder is beating against my ears of fast-running horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.536#Might this only be Odysseus and strong Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.537#driving rapidly away from the Trojans their single-foot horses!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.538#Yet terribly I fear in my heart that these bravest Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.539#might have suffered some disaster from the loud host of the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.540#Yet he had not spoken all his words, and they came. The two men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:10.541#dismounted to the ground, and their companions rejoicing
