urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.382#So the Trojans, who shudder before you as bleating goats do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.383#before a lion, would have got their wind again after disaster.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.384#Then not at all frightened strong Diomedes answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.385#'You archer, foul fighter, lovely in your locks, eyer of young girls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.386#If you were to make trial of me in strong combat with weapons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.387#your bow would do you no good at all, nor your close-showered arrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.388#Now you have scratched the flat of my foot, and even boast of this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.389#I care no more than if a witless child or a woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.390#had struck me; this is the blank weapon of a useless man, no fighter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.391#But if one is struck by me only a little, that is far different,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.392#the stroke is a sharp thing and suddenly lays him lifeless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.393#and that man's wife goes with cheeks torn in lamentation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.394#and his children are fatherless, while he staining the soil with his red blood
