urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.396#He spoke, and Odysseus the spear-famed coming up from nearby
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.397#stood in front; so he sat down behind him and pulled out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.398#the sharp arrow from his foot, and the hard pain came over his flesh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.399#He sprang back into the car and called to his charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.400#to drive him back to the hollow ships, since his heart was heavy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.401#Now Odysseus the spear-famed was left alone, nor did any
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.402#of the Argives stay beside him, since fear had taken all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.403#And troubled, he spoke then to his own great-hearted spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.404#'Ah me, what will become of me? It will be a great evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.405#if I run, fearing their multitude, yet deadlier if I am caught
