urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.772#Achilleus beside you, and Peleus the aged horseman was burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.773#the fat thigh pieces of an ox to Zeus who delights in the thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.774#in the garth of the courtyard. He was holding a golden beaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.775#and pouring the bright wine over the burning dedications. You two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.776#were over the meat of the ox attending to it, and we came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.777#and stood in the forecourt, and Achilleus sprang up wondering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.778#and took us by the hand and led us in, and told us to sit down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.779#and set hospitality properly before us, as is the stranger's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.780#right. Now when we had taken our pleasure of eating and drinking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.781#I began to talk, and invited you both to come with us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.782#and you were altogether willing, and your fathers spoke to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.783#And Peleus the aged was telling his own son, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.784#to be always best in battle and pre-eminent beyond all others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.785#but for you, Menoitios, Aktor's son, had this to say to you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.786#"My child, by right of blood Achilleus is higher than you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.787#but you are the elder. Yet in strength he is far the greater.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.788#You must speak solid words to him, and give him good counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.789#and point his way. If he listens to you it will be for his own good."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.790#This is what the old man told you, you have forgotten. Yet even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.791#now you might speak to wise Achilleus, he might be persuaded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.792#Who knows if, with God helping, you might trouble his spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.793#by entreaty, since the persuasion of a friend is a strong thing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.794#But if he is drawing back from some prophecy known in his own heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.795#and by Zeus' will his honoured mother has told him of something,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.796#let him send you out, at least, and the rest of the Myrmidon people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.797#follow you, and you may be a light given to the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.798#And let him give you his splendid armour to wear to the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.799#if perhaps the Trojans might think you are he, and give way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.800#from their attack, and the fighting sons of the Achaians get wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.801#again after hard work. There is little breathing space in the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.802#You, unwearied, might with a mere cry pile men wearied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.803#back upon their city, and away from the ships and the shelters.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.804#So he spoke, and stirred the feeling in the breast of Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.805#and he went on the run along the ships to the son of Aiakos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.806#Achilleus. But as Patroklos came in his running to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.807#of great Odysseus, where the Achaians had their assembly and dealt out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.808#rights, and where were established their altars to the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.809#there Eurypylos, who had been wounded in the thigh with an arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.810#met him, the illustrious son of Euaimon, limping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.811#away from the battle, and the watery sweat was running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.812#down his shoulders and face, and from the sore wound dark blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.813#continued to drip, and yet the will stayed steady within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.814#And the strong son of Menoitios looked on him in pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.815#and was sorrowful over him, and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.816#'Poor wretches, you leaders and men of counsel among the Danaans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.817#was it your fate then, far from your friends and the land of your fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.818#to glut with your shining fat the running dogs here in Troy land?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.819#But tell me this, my lord Eurypylos grown under God's hand:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.820#will the Achaians somehow be able to hold huge Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.821#or must they now perish beaten down under his spear?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.822#Then Eurypylos who was wounded answered him in turn:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.823#'No longer, illustrious Patroklos, can the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.824#defend themselves, but they will be piled back into their black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.825#For all of these who were before the bravest in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.826#are lying up among the ships with arrow or spear wounds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.827#under the hands of the Trojans whose strength is forever on the uprise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.828#But help save me now at least, leading me away to my black ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.829#and cut the arrow out of my thigh, wash the dark blood running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.830#out of it with warm water, and put kind medicines on it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.831#good ones, which they say you have been told of by Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.832#since Cheiron, most righteous of the Centaurs, told him about them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.833#As for Machaon and Podaleirios, who are healers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.834#I think Machaon has got a wound, and is in the shelters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.835#lying there, and himself is in need of a blameless healer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.836#while the other in the plain is standing the bitter attack of the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.837#Then in turn the strong son of Menoitios spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.838#'But how shall this be, my lord Eurypylos, how shall we do it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.839#I am on my way carrying a message to wise Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.840#given me by Gerenian Nestor, the Achaians' watcher.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.841#But even so I will not leave you in your affliction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.842#He spoke, and holding the shepherd of the host under the arms led him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.843#to his shelter, and a henchman seeing them spread out some ox-hides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.844#and Patroklos laid him there and with a knife cut the sharp tearing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.845#arrow out of his thigh, and washed the black blood running from it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.846#with warm water, and, pounding it up in his hands, laid on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.847#a bitter root to make pain disappear, one which stayed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:11.848#all kinds of pain. And the wound dried, and the flow of blood stopped.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.1#So within the shelter the warlike son of Menoitios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.2#tended stricken Eurypylos, and meanwhile the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.3#and Trojans fought on in massed battle, nor was the Danaans'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.4#ditch going to hold them back nor the wide wall above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.5#they had built for the sake of their ships, and driven a deep ditch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.6#about it, and had not given to the gods grand sacrifices
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.7#so that it might guard their running ships and their masses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.8#of spoil within it. It had been built in despite of the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.9#gods, and therefore it was not to stand firm for a long time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.10#So long as Hektor was still alive, and Achilleus was angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.11#so long as the citadel of lord Priam was a city untaken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.12#for this time the great wall of the Achaians stood firm. But afterwards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.13#when all the bravest among the Trojans had died in the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.14#and many of the Argives had been beaten down, and some left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.15#when in the tenth year the city of Priam was taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.16#and the Argives gone in their ships to the beloved land of their fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.17#then at last Poseidon and Apollo took counsel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.18#to wreck the wall, letting loose the strength of rivers upon it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.19#all the rivers that run to the sea from the mountains of Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.20#Rhesos and Heptaporos, Karesos and Rhodios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.21#Grenikos and Aisepos, and immortal Skamandros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.22#and Simoeis, where much ox-hide armour and helmets were tumbled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.23#in the river mud, and many of the race of the half-god mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.24#Phoibos Apollo turned the mouths of these waters together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.25#and nine days long threw the flood against the wall, and Zeus rained
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.26#incessantly, to break the wall faster and wash it seaward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.27#And the shaker of the earth himself holding in his hands the trident
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.28#guided them, and hurled into the waves all the bastions' strengthening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.29#of logs and stones the toiling Achaians had set in position
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.30#and made all smooth again by the hard-running passage of Helle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.31#and once again piled the great beach under sand, having wrecked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.32#the wall, and turned the rivers again to make their way down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.33#the same channel where before they had run the bright stream of their water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.34#Thus, afterwards, Poseidon and Apollo were minded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.35#to put things in place, but at this time battle and clamour were blazing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.36#about the strong-founded wall and the bastion timbers were thundering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.37#as they were struck, as the Argives broken under Zeus' lashing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.38#were crowded back on their hollow ships, and struggled to get clear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.39#in dread of Hektor, the strong one who drove men to thoughts of panic.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.40#But Hektor, as he had before, fought on like a whirlwind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.41#As when among a pack of hounds and huntsmen assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.42#a wild boar or lion turns at bay in the strength of his fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.43#and the men, closing themselves into a wall about him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.44#stand up to face him, and cast at him with the volleying spears thrown
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.45#from their hands, and in spite of this the proud heart feels not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.46#terror, nor turns to run, and it is his own courage that kills him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.47#and again and again he turns on them trying to break the massed men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.48#and wherever he charges the masses of men break away in front of him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.49#such was Hektor as he went through the battle and rallied his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.50#and drove them on to cross over the ditch, but now the fast-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.51#horses balked at the edge of the lip, and dared not cross, whinnying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.52#loud, since the ditch in its great width frightened them from it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.53#being not easy for them to overleap, nor to walk through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.54#since along the whole length the jut of the overhangs stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.55#on both sides, and the surface of the floor was thickset with pointed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.56#palisades, which the sons of the Achaians had paled there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.57#dense and huge, so as to hold off the rage of attackers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.58#And a horse straining at the strong-wheeled chariot might not easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.59#enter there, but the dismounted were strong in their effort.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.60#And now Poulydamas stood beside bold Hektor, and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.61#'Hektor, and other lords of the Trojans and companions in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.62#we are senseless trying to drive our fast-footed horses over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.63#this ditch. It is hard indeed to cross, and sharp stakes are planted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.64#inside it, and across from these the wall of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.65#There there is no way to get down, no way again to do battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.66#from horses, for the passage is narrow and I think they must be hurt there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.67#For now if Zeus who thunders on high in evil intention
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.68#toward these is destroying them utterly, sending aid to the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.69#this is the way I would wish it, may it happen immediately
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.70#that the Achaians be destroyed here forgotten and far from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.71#Argos; but if they turn again and a backrush comes on us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.72#out of the ships, and we are driven against the deep ditch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.73#then I think no longer could one man to carry a message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.74#get clear to the city, once the Achaians have turned back upon us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.75#Come then, do as I say, let us all be persuaded; let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.76#tell our henchmen to check our horses here by the ditch, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.77#let ourselves, all of us dismounted and armed in our war gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.78#follow Hektor in mass formation. As for the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.79#they will not hold, if the bonds of death are fastened upon them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.80#So spoke Poulydamas, and this counsel of safety pleased Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.81#And at once in all his armour he leapt to the ground from his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.82#and the rest of the Trojans assembled, not mounted behind their horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.83#but all sprang to the ground, when they saw brilliant Hektor had done it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.84#Then each man gave orders to his own charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.85#to check the horses in good order at the edge of the ditch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.86#and the fighters formed apart into groups, then closing together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.87#into five well-ordered battalions followed their leaders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.88#They who went with Hektor and Poulydamas the blameless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.89#these were most numerous, and bravest, and beyond others furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.90#to smash the wall and fight their way among the hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.91#and Kebriones went with them as third man, while by the chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.92#Hektor had left another man, not so good as Kebriones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.93#Paris led the next group with Alkathoös and Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.94#and Helenos, with godlike Deïphobos, led the third group,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.95#sons both of Priam, and Asios was with them as third man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.96#Asios, son of Hyrtakos, whom his tall shining horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.97#had carried over from Arisbe and beside the river Selleëis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.98#The leader of the fourth group was the strong son of Anchises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.99#Aineias, and with him were the two sons of Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.100#Archelochos and Akamas, both skilled in all fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.101#Sarpedon led the far-renowned companions in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.102#and had chosen to go with him Glaukos and warlike Asteropaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.103#since these seemed to him to be marked out as the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.104#of the rest, after himself, but among all he was pre-eminent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.105#Now when these had closed their wrought ox-hide shields together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.106#they charged straight for the Danaans, eagerly, with no thought longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.107#of being held, but rather to hurl themselves on the black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.108#Then the rest of the Trojans and renowned companions in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.109#were willing to follow the order of blameless Poulydamas. Only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.110#Asios, Hyrtakos' son, lord of men, was unwilling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.111#to leave his horses there and a charioteer to attend them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.112#but kept them with him, and so drove on at the fast-running vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.113#poor fool, who by the ships in the pride of his horses and chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.114#was not destined to evade the evil spirits of destruction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.115#nor ever to make his way back again to windy Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.116#Before this the dark-named destiny had shrouded about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.117#through the spear of Idomeneus, proud son of Deukalion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.118#For he sent his horses to the left of the ships, where the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.119#were streaming back from the level ground with horses and chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.120#and this way he drove his chariot and horses, and found there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.121#the leaves not yet pushed home in the gates, nor the long door-bar,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.122#but men were holding them wide apart, on the chance of rescuing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.123#some one of their companions running for the ships from the battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.124#Of a purpose he steered his horses straight there, and his men followed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.125#screaming aloud, since they thought the Achaians no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.126#would hold, but that they would be driven back on their dark ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.127#Fools! since in the gates they found two men of the bravest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.128#high-hearted sons of the spear-fighting Lapithai, one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.129#the son of Peirithoös, powerful Polypoites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.130#and one Leonteus, a man like the murderous god of battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.131#Now these two, who had taken their place in front of the high gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.132#stood there like two oaks who rear their crests in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.133#and through day upon day stand up to the wind and the rainbeat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.134#since their great roots reach far and are gripped in the ground. So
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.135#these two, in the confidence of their strength and their hands' work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.136#stood up to tall Asios advancing upon them, nor gave way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.137#But these, holding up high the tanned leather of their shields, moved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.138#straight in on the strong-built wall with enormous clamour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.139#around Asios their lord and Iamenos and Orestes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.140#and Asios' son Adamas, and Oinomaos and Thoön.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.141#In this time the Lapithai still inside the wall were striving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.142#to stir up the strong-greaved Achaians to defend the vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.143#but among the Danaans, when they saw the Trojans sweeping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.144#on against the wall, a clamour arose, and they gave way;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.145#and the two bursting through the gates fought on in front of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.146#They were in the likeness of two wild boars who in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.147#await a rabble of men and dogs advancing upon them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.148#and as they go tearing slantwise and rip the timber about them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.149#to pieces at the stock, the grinding scream of their teeth sounds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.150#high, until some man hits them with his throw and takes the life from them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.151#such was the grinding scream from the bright bronze covering their chests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.152#struck hard on by spears, for they fought a very strong battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.153#in the confidence of their own strength and the people above them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.154#These flung about them with great stones torn from the strong-founded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.155#bastions, as they fought in defence of themselves, and the shelters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.156#and the fast-running vessels, so that the flung stones dropped to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.157#like snowflakes which the winds' blast whirling the shadowy clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.158#drifts in their abundance along the prospering earth. So
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.159#the missiles flung from the hands of Achaians, and Trojans also,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.160#went showering, and the helms and shields massive in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.161#crashed hollow underneath the impact of rocks like millstones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.162#And now Asios, Hyrtakos' son, groaned aloud and beat on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.163#both thighs with his hands, and spoke aloud in his agony:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.164#'Zeus father, now even you are made utterly a lover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.165#of deception. For I never thought the fighting Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.166#would be able to hold our strength and our hands invincible.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.167#But they, as wasps quick-bending in the middle, or as bees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.168#will make their homes at the side of the rocky way, and will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.169#abandon the hollow house they have made, but stand up to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.170#men who come to destroy them, and fight for the sake of their children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.171#so these, though they are only two, are unwilling to give back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.172#from the gates, until they have killed their men, or are taken.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.173#He spoke, but by such talk did not persuade the heart of Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.174#whose desire it was to extend the glory to Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.175#And now at the various gates various men fought each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.176#It were too much toil for me, as if I were a god, to tell all this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.177#for all about the stone wall the inhuman strength of the fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.178#was rising, and the Argives fought unhappily, yet they must fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.179#on, to defend their ships. And all the gods who were helpers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.180#of the Danaans in the fighting were dejected in spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.181#But the Lapithai fought on and closed in the hateful fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.182#and there the son of Peirithoös, powerful Polypoites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.183#struck Damasos with the spear through the bronze-sided helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.184#and the brazen helmet could not hold, but the bronze spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.185#driven on through smashed the bone apart, and the inward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.186#brain was all spattered forth. So he beat him down in his fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.187#Then he went on to kill Pylon and Ormenos. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.188#Leonteus, the scion of Ares, struck down Antimachos'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.189#son, Hippomachos, with a spear cast into the war belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.190#and afterwards drawing his sharp sword out of the scabbard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.191#made a rush through the crowding men, and struck from close up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.192#Antiphates first, so that he crashed on his back to the ground, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.193#beat down along the prospering earth Menon and Orestes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.194#and Iamenos, all beaten down in rapid succession.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.195#Now as these were stripping their men of the shining armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.196#the fighting men following with Poulydamas and Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.197#who were most numerous, and bravest, and beyond others furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.198#to smash the wall, and set fire to the vessels, these still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.199#were divided in doubt as they stood there at the ditch's edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.200#As they were urgent to cross a bird sign had appeared to them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.201#an eagle, flying high and holding to the left of the people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.202#and carrying in its talons a gigantic snake, blood-coloured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.203#alive still and breathing, it had not forgotten its warcraft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.204#yet, for writhing back it struck the eagle that held it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.205#by chest and neck, so that the eagle let it drop groundward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.206#in pain of the bite, and dashed it down in the midst of the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.207#and itself, screaming high, winged away down the wind's blast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.208#And the Trojans shivered with fear as they looked on the lithe snake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.209#lying in their midst, a portent of Zeus of the aegis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.210#And now Poulydamas stood beside bold Hektor and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.211#'Hektor, somehow in assembly you move ever against me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.212#though I speak excellently, since indeed there is no good reason
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.213#for you, in your skill, to argue wrong, neither in the councils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.214#nor in the fighting, and ever to be upholding your own cause.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.215#Now once more I will speak out the way it seems best to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.216#Let us not go on and fight the Danaans by their ships. I think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.217#it will end as the portent was accomplished, if the bird sign
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.218#that came to the Trojans as we were trying to cross was a true one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.219#an eagle, flying high and holding to the left of the people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.220#and carrying in its talons a gigantic snake, blood-coloured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.221#alive, but let it drop suddenly before winning his own home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.222#and could not finish carrying it back to give to his children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.223#So we, even though in our great strength we break in the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.224#and the wall of the Achaians, and the Achaians give way before us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.225#we shall not take the same ways back from the ships in good order;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.226#since we shall leave many Trojans behind us, whom the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.227#will cut down with the bronze as they fight for themselves by their vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.228#So an interpreter of the gods would answer, one who knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.229#in his mind the truth of portents, and whom the people believed in.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.230#Looking darkly at him tall Hektor of the shining helm answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.231#'Poulydamas, these things that you argue please me no longer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.232#Your mind knows how to contrive a saying better than this one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.233#But if in all seriousness this is your true argument, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.234#it is the very gods who ruined the brain within you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.235#you who are telling me to forget the counsels of thunderous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.236#Zeus, in which he himself nodded his head to me and assented.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.237#But you: you tell me to put my trust in birds, who spread
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.238#wide their wings. I care nothing for these, I think nothing of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.239#nor whether they go by on our right against dawn and sunrise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.240#or go by to the left against the glooming mist and the darkness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.241#No, let us put our trust in the counsel of great Zeus, he who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.242#is lord over all mortal men and all the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.243#One bird sign is best: to fight in defence of our country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.244#Why are you so afraid of war and hostility? Even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.245#though all the rest of us were to be cut down around you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.246#among the Argive ships, you would run no danger of dying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.247#since your heart is not enduring in battle nor a fighter's.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.248#But if you shrink away from the murderous work, or turn back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.249#some other man from the fighting, beguiling him with your arguments,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.250#at once beaten down under my spear you will lose your own life.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.251#He spoke, and led the way, and the rest of them came on after him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.252#with unearthly clamour, and over them Zeus who delights in the thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.253#drove down from among the hills of Ida the blast of a windstorm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.254#which swept the dust straight against the ships. He was mazing the minds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.255#of the Achaians, and giving glory to the Trojans and Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.256#and they in the confidence of the portents shown, and their own strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.257#worked to break down the great wall of the Achaians. They tore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.258#at the projections on the outworks, and broke down the battlements
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.259#and shook with levers the jut of the buttresses the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.260#had stuck in the earth on the outer face to shore their defences.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.261#They tore at these, in hope of breaking down the Achaians'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.262#wall, but now the Danaans did not give way in front of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.263#but they, fencing the battlements with the hides of oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.264#hurled from the wall at the enemy who came on beneath it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.265#The two Aiantes, walking up and down the length of the ramparts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.266#urged the men on, stirring up the warcraft of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.267#and stung them along, using kind words to one, to another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.268#hard ones, whenever they saw a man hang back from the fighting:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.269#'Dear friends, you who are pre-eminent among the Argives, you who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.270#are of middle estate, you who are of low account, since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.271#all of us are not alike in battle, this is work for all now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.272#and you yourselves can see it. Now let no man let himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.273#be turned back upon the ships for the sound of their blustering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.274#but keep forever forward calling out courage to each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.275#So may Olympian Zeus who grips the thunderbolt grant us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.276#a way to the city, when we beat off the attack of our enemies.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.277#Such was their far cry, and they stirred the Achaians' war strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.278#And they, as storms of snow descend to the ground incessant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.279#on a winter day, when Zeus of the counsels, showing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.280#before men what shafts he possesses, brmgs on a snowstorm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.281#and stills the winds asleep in the solid drift, enshrouding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.282#the peaks that tower among the mountains and the shoulders out-jutting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.283#and the low lands with their grasses, and the prospering work of men's hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.284#and the drift falls along the grey sea, the harbours and beaches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.285#and the surf that breaks against it is stilled, and all things elsewhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.286#it shrouds from above, with the burden of Zeus' rain heavy upon it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.287#so numerous and incessant were the stones volleyed from both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.288#some thrown on Trojans, others flung against the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.289#by Trojans, so the whole length of the wall thundered beneath them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.290#And not even then might the Trojans and glorious Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.291#have broken in the gates of the rampart, and the long door-bar,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.292#had not Zeus of the counsels driven his own son, Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.293#upon the Argives, like a lion among horn-curved cattle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.294#Presently he held before him the perfect circle of his shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.295#a lovely thing of beaten bronze, which the bronze-smith hammered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.296#out for him, and on the inward side had stitched ox-hides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.297#in close folds with golden staples clean round the circle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.298#Holding this shield in front of him, and shaking two spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.299#he went onward like some hill-kept lion, who for a long time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.300#has gone lacking meat, and the proud heart is urgent upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.301#to get inside of a close steading and go for the sheepflocks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.302#And even though he finds herdsmen in that place, who are watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.303#about their sheepflocks, armed with spears, and with dogs, even so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.304#he has no thought of being driven from the steading without some attack made,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.305#and either makes his spring and seizes a sheep, or else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.306#himself is hit in the first attack by a spear from a swift hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.307#thrown. So now his spirit drove on godlike Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.308#to make a rush at the wall and break apart the battlements.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.309#And now he spoke in address to Glaukos, son of Hippolochos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.310#'Glaukos, why is it you and I are honoured before others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.311#with pride of place, the choice meats and the filled wine cups
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.312#in Lykia, and all men look on us as if we were immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.313#and we are appointed a great piece of land by the banks of Xanthos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.314#good land, orchard and vineyard, and ploughland for the planting of wheat?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.315#Therefore it is our duty in the forefront of the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.316#to take our stand, and bear our part of the blazing of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.317#so that a man of the close-armoured Lykians may say of us:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.318#"Indeed, these are no ignoble men who are lords of Lykia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.319#these kings of ours, who feed upon the fat sheep appointed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.320#and drink the exquisite sweet wine, since indeed there is strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.321#of valour in them, since they fight in the forefront of the Lykians."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.322#Man, supposing you and I, escaping this battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.323#would be able to live on forever, ageless, immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.324#so neither would I myself go on fighting in the foremost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.325#nor would I urge you into the fighting where men win glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.326#But now, seeing that the spirits of death stand close about us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.327#in their thousands, no man can turn aside nor escape them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.328#let us go on and win glory for ourselves, or yield it to others.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.329#He spoke, nor did Glaukos disobey him nor turn aside from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.330#They, leading the great horde of the Lykians, advanced straight onward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.331#and the son of Peteos, Menestheus, shivered as he saw them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.332#since they came against his bastion and carried disaster upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.333#He scanned the rampart of the Achaians in the hope of seeing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.334#some great chief who could beat back the bane from his company,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.335#and saw the two Aiantes, insatiate of battle, standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.336#on the wall, and Teukros even now coming up from the shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.337#and close by, but he was not able to cry out and make them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.338#hear, so great was the clamour about him as the shouts hit skyward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.339#as shields were battered with missiles, and the helmets crested with horse-hair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.340#and the gates, which all had been slammed shut, and the Trojans standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.341#against them were trying to break them down and force their way in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.342#At once he sent Thoötes off as a runner to Aias:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.343#'Go on the run, brilliant Thoötes, and call Aias here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.344#or better, both Aiantes, since that would be far the best thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.345#that could happen, since here headlong destruction is building against us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.346#Such is the weight of the Lykian lords upon us, who even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.347#before now have shown as deadly men in the strong encounters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.348#But if in their place also hard work and fury have arisen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.349#at least let powerful Telamonian Aias come by himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.350#and let Teukros follow with him, with his craft in the bow's use.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.351#He spoke, nor did the herald disobey when he heard him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.352#but went on the run along the wall of the bronze-armoured Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.353#and came and stood by the two Aiantes, and spoke to them straight out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.354#'Aiantes, leaders of the bronze-armoured Argives: Menestheus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.355#beloved son of Peteos engendered of Zeus, desires you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.356#to go where he is and meet the danger, if only for a little;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.357#both of you for choice, since that would be far the best thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.358#that could happen, since there headlong destruction is building against him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.359#Such is the weight of the Lykian lords upon him, who even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.360#before now have shown as deadly men in the strong encounters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.361#But if in this place also hard fighting and fury have arisen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.362#at least let powerful Telamonian Aias come by himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.363#and let Teukros follow with him, with his craft in the bow's use.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.364#He spoke, and huge Telamonian Aias did not disobey him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.365#but at once called out in winged words to Aias, the son of Oïleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.366#'Aias, now you two, yourself and strong Lykomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.367#must stand your ground and urge on the Danaans to fight strongly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.368#I am going over there to meet the attack, and afterwards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.369#I will come back soon, when I have beaten them back from the others.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.370#So speading Telamonian Aias went away, and with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.371#went Teukros, his brother by the same father, and following them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.372#was Pandion, who carried the curved bow for Teukros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.373#They kept inside the wall as they went, till they came to the bastion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.374#of high-hearted Menestheus, and found men who were hard pressed there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.375#for the strong lords and men of counsel among the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.376#came on against the battlements like a darkening stormwind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.377#and they charged forward to fight with these, and the clamour rose high.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.378#First to kill his man was Telamonian Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.379#It was Sarpedon's companion in arms, high-hearted Epikles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.380#whom he struck with a great jagged stone, that lay at the inside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.381#of the wall, huge, on top of the battlements. A man could not easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.382#hold it, not even if he were very strong, in both hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.383#of men such as men are now, but he heaving it high threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.384#and smashed in the four-sheeted helm, and pounded to pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.385#the bones of the head inside it, so that Epikles dropped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.386#like a diver from the high bastion, and the life left his bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.387#And Teukros with an arrow struck the strong son of Hippolochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.388#Glaukos, as he was swarming aloft the wall's high bastion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.389#where he saw the arm was bare of defence, and stayed his warcraft;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.390#he sprang down from the wall, secretly, for fear some Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.391#might see that he had been hit and vaunt with high words over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.392#Sarpedon, as soon as he was aware that Glaukos had gone back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.393#was downcast, nevertheless he did not forget his warcraft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.394#but striking with his spear at Alkmaon, the son of Thestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.395#stabbed him, then wrenched the spear out, and he following the spear fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.396#on his face, and the armour elaborate with bronze clashed about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.397#And Sarpedon, grabbing in both ponderous hands the battlements,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.398#pulled, and the whole thing came away in his hands, and the rampart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.399#was stripped defenceless above. He had opened a pathway for many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.400#Aias and Teukros aimed at him together, and Teukros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.401#hit him with an arrow in the shining belt that encircled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.402#his chest to hold the man-covering shield, but Zeus brushed the death spirits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.403#from his son, and would not let him be killed there beside the ships' sterns;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.404#and Aias plunging upon him stabbed at the shield, but the spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.405#did not pass clean through. Still, he pounded him back in his fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.406#so that he gave back a little space from the battlement, and yet not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.407#utterly gave way, since his heart was still hopeful of winning glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.408#He whirled about and called aloud to the godlike Lykians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.409#'Lykians, why do you thus let go of your furious valour?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.410#It is a hard thing for me, strong as I am, to break down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.411#the wall, single-handed, and open a path to the vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.412#Come on with me then. This work is better if many do it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.413#So he spoke, and they, awed at the reproach of their leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.414#put on the pressure of more weight around their lord of the counsels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.415#And on the other side the Argives stiffened their battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.416#inside the wall, and a huge fight developed between the two sides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.417#For neither could the powerful Lykians break in the rampart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.418#of the Danaans, and so open a path through to the vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.419#nor had the Danaan spearmen strength to push back the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.420#from the rampart, once they had won to a place close under it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.421#but as two men with measuring ropes in their hands fight bitterly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.422#about a boundary line at the meeting place of two cornfields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.423#and the two of them fight in the strait place over the rights of division,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.424#so the battlements held these armies apart, and across them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.425#they hewed at each other, and at the ox-hide shields strong-circled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.426#guarding men's chests, and at the fluttering straps of the guard-skins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.427#Many were torn in their white flesh by the bronze without pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.428#wherever one of the fighters turning aside laid bare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.429#his back, and many were struck with the spear carried clean through the shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.430#Everywhere the battlements and the bastions were awash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.431#with men's blood shed from both sides, Achaian and Trojan.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.432#But even so they could not drive panic among the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.433#but held evenly as the scales which a careful widow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.434#holds, taking it by the balance beam, and weighs her wool evenly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.435#at either end, working to win a pitiful wage for her children:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.436#so the battles fought by both sides were pulled fast and even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.437#until that time when Zeus gave the greater glory to Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.438#Priam's son, who was first to break into the wall of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.439#For he lifted his voice and called in a piercing cry to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.440#'Rise up, Trojans, breakers of horses, and wreck the ramparts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.441#of the Argives, and let loose the inhuman fire on their vessels.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.442#So he spoke, driving them on, and they all gave ear to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.443#and steered against the wall in a pack, and at once gripping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.444#still their edged spears caught and swarmed up the wall's projections.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.445#Meanwhile Hektor snatched up a stone that stood before the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.446#and carried it along; it was blunt-massed at the base, but the upper
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.447#end was sharp; two men, the best in all a community,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.448#could not easily hoist it up from the ground to a wagon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.449#of men such as men are now, but he alone lifted and shook it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.450#as the son of devious-devising Kronos made it light for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.451#As when a shepherd easily carries the fleece of a wether,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.452#picking it up with one hand, and little is the burden weighting him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.453#so Hektor lifting the stone carried it straight for the door leaves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.454#which filled the gateway ponderously close-fitted together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.455#These were high and twofold, and double door-bars on the inside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.456#overlapping each other closed it, and a single pin-bolt secured them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.457#He came and stood very close and taking a strong wide stance threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.458#at the middle, leaning into the throw, that the cast might not lack
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.459#force, and smashed the hinges at either side, and the stone crashed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.460#ponderously in, and the gates groaned deep, and the door-bars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.461#could not hold, but the leaves were smashed to a wreckage of splinters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.462#under the stone's impact. Then glorious Hektor burst in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.463#with dark face like sudden night, but he shone with the ghastly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.464#glitter of bronze that girded his skin, and carried two spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.465#in his hands. No one could have stood up against him, and stopped him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.466#except the gods, when he burst in the gates; and his eyes flashed fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.467#Whirling, he called out across the battle to the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.468#to climb over the wall, and they obeyed his urgency.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.469#Immediately some swarmed over the wall, while others swept in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.470#through the wrought gateways, and the Danaans scattered in terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:12.471#among their hollow ships, and clamour incessant rose up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.1#WHEN Zeus had driven against the ships the Trojans and Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.2#he left them beside these to endure the hard work and sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.3#of fighting without respite, and himself turned his eyes shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.4#far away, looking out over the land of the Thracian riders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.5#and the Mysians who fight at close quarters, and the proud Hippomolgoi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.6#drinkers of milk, and the Abioi, most righteous of all men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.7#He did not at all now turn his shining eyes upon Troy land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.8#for he had no idea in mind that any one of the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.9#would come down to stand by either Danaans or Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.10#Neither did the powerful shaker of the earth keep blind watch;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.11#for he sat and admired the fighting and the run of the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.12#aloft on top of the highest summit of timbered Samos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.13#the Thracian place; and from there all Ida appeared before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.14#and the city of Priam was plain to see, and the ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.15#There he came up out of the water, and sat, and pitied the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.16#who were beaten by the Trojans, and blamed Zeus for it in bitterness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.17#So presently he came down from the craggy mountain, striding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.18#on rapid feet, and the tall mountains trembled and the timber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.19#under the immortal feet of Poseidon's progress.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.20#He took three long strides forward, and in the fourth came to his goal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.21#Aigai, where his glorious house was built in the waters'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.22#depth, glittering with gold, imperishable forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.23#Going there he harnessed under his chariot his bronze-shod horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.24#flying-footed, with long manes streaming of gold; and he put on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.25#clothing of gold about his own body, and took up the golden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.26#lash, carefully compacted, and climbed up into his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.27#and drove it across the waves. And about him the sea beasts came up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.28#from their deep places and played in his path, and acknowledged their master,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.29#and the sea stood apart before him, rejoicing. The horses winged on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.30#delicately, and the bronze axle beneath was not wetted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.31#The fast-running horses carried him to the ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.32#There is a cave, broad and deep down in the gloom of the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.33#lying midway between Tenedos and Imbros of the high cliffs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.34#There Poseidon the shaker of the earth reined in his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.35#and slipped them from the yoke, and threw fodder immortal before them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.36#so they could eat, and threw around their feet golden hobbles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.37#not to be broken or slipped from, so they would wait there steadfast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.38#for their lord gone. And Poseidon went to the ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.39#But the Trojans, gathered into a pack, like flame, like a stormcloud,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.40#came on after Hektor the son of Priam, raging relentless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.41#roaring and crying as one, and their hopes ran high of capturing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.42#the ships of the Achaians, and killing the best men beside them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.43#all of them. But Poseidon who circles the earth and shakes it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.44#rose up out of the deep water to stir on the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.45#likening himself in form and weariless voice to Kalchas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.46#First he spoke to the Aiantes, who were burning for battle already:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.47#'Aiantes, you two, remembering the spirit of warcraft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.48#and not that of shivering panic, must save the Achaian people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.49#Elsewhere in truth I do not fear the Trojans' invincible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.50#hands, though in full force they have swarmed over our great wall;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.51#since the strong-greaved Achaians will be able to hold the rest of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.52#But I fear most terribly disaster to us in the one place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.53#where that berserk flamelike leads them against us, Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.54#who claims he must be son of Zeus of the high strength. May this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.55#be the message some one of the gods gives your minds to carry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.56#that you stand fast strongly yourselves, urge the rest to stand also.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.57#Thus, hard though he sweeps on, you might stay him beside the fast-running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.58#ships, even though the very Olympian wakes him to battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.59#Poseidon who circles the earth and shakes it spoke, and striking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.60#both of them with his staff filled them with powerful valour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.61#and he made their limbs light, and their feet, and their hands above them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.62#and burst into winged flight himself, like a hawk with quick wings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.63#who from the huge height of an impassable rock lifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.64#leans to flight to pursue some other bird over the wide land;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.65#so Poseidon shaker of the earth broke away from the Aiantes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.66#And of the two swift Aias son of Oïleus was first
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.67#to know him, and spoke therewith to Aias the son of Telamon;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.68#'Aias, since some one of the gods, whose hold is Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.69#has likened himself to the seer, and told us to fight by our vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.70#this is not Kalchas, the bird interpreter of the gods, for I knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.71#easily as he went away the form of his feet, the legs' form
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.72#from behind him. Gods, though gods, are conspicuous. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.73#as for me, the spirit inside my inward breast drives me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.74#all the harder to carry on the war and the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.75#and my feet underneath me are eager and my hands above them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.76#Aias the son of Telamon spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.77#'So for me also now the invincible hands on my spearshaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.78#are furious, my strength is rising, and both feet beneath me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.79#are sweeping me onward, so that I long even for single combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.80#with Hektor, Priam's son, the forever avid of battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.81#Now as these two were saying such things to each other, joyful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.82#in the delight of battle the god had put into their spirits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.83#meanwhile the earth-encircler stirred up the Achaians behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.84#who were cooling the heat of the inward heart back beside their vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.85#for their very limbs were broken with weariness of hard work, and also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.86#discouragement of the heart came over them, as they watched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.87#the Trojans, and how in a mass they had overswarmed the great wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.88#As they saw them the tears dripped from their eyes; they did not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.89#think they could win clear of the evil, but the earth-shaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.90#lightly turning their battalions to strength drove them onward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.91#He came first in encouragement to Teukros and Leïtos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.92#with the fighting Peneleos, and Deïpyros and Thoas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.93#to Meriones and Antilochos, both urgent for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.94#Calling out to these in winged words he rallied them onward:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.95#'Shame, you Argives, young fighting men, since I for my part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.96#have confidence that by fighting you can save our ships from destruction;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.97#but if you yourselves are to go slack from the sorrowful fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.98#now is seen your day to be beaten down by the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.99#Oh for shame! Here is a great strange thing I see with my own eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.100#a terrible thing, and one that I thought never could happen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.101#that the Trojans could come against our ships, they who in time past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.102#were like fugitive deer before us, who in the forests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.103#are spoil for scavengers and wolves and leopards, who scatter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.104#in absolute cowardice, there is no war spirit within them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.105#So before now the Trojans were unwilling to stand up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.106#against the strength and hands of the Achaians, even for a little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.107#but now far from their city they fight by the hollow vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.108#through the weakness of our leader, and the hanging back of our people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.109#who have made their quarrel with him, and will not stand in defence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.110#of the fast-running ships. Instead of this they are killed against them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.111#Yet even though it be utterly true that the son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.112#the hero wide-powerful Agamemnon is guilty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.113#because he did dishonour to Peleus' son, the swift-footed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.114#still there is no way for us now to hang back from the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.115#No, sooner let us heal it, for the hearts of great men can be healed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.116#But you can no longer in honour give way from your fighting valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.117#being all the best men along the host. Even I, for my part,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.118#would not quarrel with any man who hung back from the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.119#because he was a weak thing, but with you my heart must be angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.120#O friends, soon you will bring to pass some still greater evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.121#with this hanging back. Let every one of you plant in his heart's depth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.122#discipline and shamefastness. A big battle rises against you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.123#For Hektor of the great war cry is fighting beside our vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.124#in his power, and has broken our gates and the long door-bar.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.125#So urging them on the earth-encircler stirred up the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.126#and their battalions formed in strength about the two Aiantes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.127#battalions the war god could not find fault with, coming among them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.128#nor Athene lady of storming armies, since there the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.129#formed apart and stood against the Trojans and brilliant Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.130#locking spear by spear, shield against shield at the base, so buckler
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.131#leaned on buckler, helmet on helmet, man against man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.132#and the horse-hair crests along the horns of their shining helmets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.133#touched as they bent their heads, so dense were they formed on each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.134#and the spears shaken from their daring hands made a jagged battle line.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.135#Their thoughts were driving straight ahead in the fury of fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.136#The Trojans came down on them in a pack, and Hektor led them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.137#raging straight forward, like a great rolling stone from a rock face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.138#that a river swollen with winter rain has wrenched from its socket
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.139#and with immense washing broken the hold of the unwilling rock face;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.140#the springing boulder flies on, and the forest thunders beneath it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.141#and the stone runs unwavering on a strong course, till it reaches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.142#the flat land, then rolls no longer for all its onrush;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.143#so Hektor for a while threatened lightly to break through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.144#the shelters and ships of the Achaians and reach the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.145#cutting his way. But when he collided with the dense battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.146#he was stopped, hard, beaten in on himself. The sons of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.147#against him stabbing at him with swords and leaf-headed spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.148#thrust him away from them so that he gave ground backward, staggering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.149#He lifted his voice and called in a piercing cry to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.150#'Trojans, Lykians, Dardanians who fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.151#stand with me. The Achaians will not hold me back for a long time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.152#for all they are building themselves into a bastion against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.153#No, I think they will give back under my spear, if truly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.154#I am driven by the greatest of gods, the thunderous lord of Hera.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.155#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit and strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.156#Among them Deïphobos in high purpose had come striding,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.157#Priam's son, who held the perfect circle of his shield before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.158#moving lightly on his feet as he walked in the shield's protection.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.159#Meriones aimed at him with the shining spear, and threw it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.160#nor missed his mark, but struck the shield on its perfect circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.161#of bull's hide, but the spear did not get through, but sooner
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.162#the long shaft was broken behind the head. Deïphobos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.163#held the bull's-hide shield away from him, his heart frightened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.164#by the spear of wise Meriones, but that hero drew back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.165#into the host of his own companions, deeply angered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.166#for two things, the broken spear and the loss of his battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.167#and went away back to the shelters and ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.168#to bring back a long spear that was left behind in his shelter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.169#But the rest fought on with clamour incessant rising about them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.170#Teukros, son of Telamon, was the first to kill his man, Imbrios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.171#the spearfighter, son of Mentor of the many horses, one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.172#before the coming of the sons of the Achaians lived in Pedaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.173#and had married a bastard daughter of Priam, Medesikaste.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.174#But when the oarswept ships of the Danaans came, he went back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.175#to Ilion, and was a great man among the Trojans, and lived
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.176#at Priam's side, who honoured him as he did his own children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.177#Now the son of Telamon with the long spear stabbed him under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.178#the ear, and wrenched the spear out again, and he dropped like an ash tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.179#which, on the crest of a mountain glittering far about, cut down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.180#with the bronze axe scatters on the ground its delicate leafage;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.181#so he dropped, and the armour elaborate with bronze clashed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.182#about him, and Teukros ran up, eager to strip the armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.183#As he came on Hektor threw at him with the shining javelin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.184#but Teukros with his eyes straight on him avoided the bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.185#by a little, and Hektor struck Amphimachos, son of Aktorian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.186#Kteatos, with a spear in his chest as he swept into battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.187#He fell, thunderously, and his armour clattered upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.188#Then Hektor charged in to tear the helm of great-hearted Amphimachos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.189#from his head where it fitted close on the brows, but Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.190#thrust with the shining spear at Hektor as he came onward;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.191#he could not manage to reach the skin, since this was all shrouded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.192#in the ghastly bronze, but drove at the shield's mass in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.193#and beat him back in great strength so that Hektor gave ground backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.194#from both corpses. These the Achaians dragged out of the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.195#Then Stichios and brilliant Menestheus, lords of the Athenians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.196#carried Amphimachos back among the Achaian people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.197#But the two Aiantes in the fury of their fierce war strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.198#as two lions catch up a goat from the guard of rip-fanged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.199#hounds, and carry it into the density of the underbrush,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.200#holding it high from the ground in the crook of their jaws, so the lordly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.201#two Aiantes lifted Imbrios high and stripped him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.202#of his armour, and the son of Oïleus, in anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.203#for Amphimachos, hewed away his head from the soft neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.204#and threw it spinning like a ball through the throng of fighters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.205#until it came to rest in the dust at the feet of Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.206#Then Poseidon was angered about the heart at his grandson's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.207#slaying in the bitter hostility, so the god went forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.208#on his way among the shelters and ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.209#and stirred the Danaans, and worked disaster against the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.210#Idomeneus the spear-famed encountered him, on his way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.211#from a companion, who had just before come back from the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.212#wounded in the hollow behind the knee by the sharp bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.213#This man his companions carried away. Idomeneus had given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.214#the healers instructions and gone on to his shelter, still burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.215#to face the battle, and now the strong earth-shaker spoke to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.216#Poseidon likened his voice to Thoas, son of Andraimon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.217#lord of the Aitolians over all Pleuron, and headlong
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.218#Kalydon, who was honoured in his countryside as a god is:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.219#'Idomeneus, lord of the Kretans' councils, where are those threats you gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.220#now, that the sons of the Achaians uttered against the Trojans?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.221#Then Idomeneus lord of the Kretans answered him in turn:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.222#'Thoas, no man is responsible for this, so far as
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.223#my thought goes, since all of us understand how to wage war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.224#It is not that heartless fear holds anyone, that a man yielding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.225#to dread emerges out of the evil fighting, but rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.226#this way must be pleasurable to Kronos' son in his great strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.227#that the Achaians must die here forgotten, and far from Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.228#Since you, Thoas, have been before this a man stubborn in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.229#and stirred up another whenever you saw one hang back, so now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.230#also do not give up, and urge on each man as you find him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.231#Then in answer spoke the shaker of the earth, Poseidon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.232#'Idomeneus, may that man who this day wilfully hangs back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.233#from the fighting never win home again out of Troy land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.234#but stay here and be made dogs' delight for their feasting. Come then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.235#take up your armour and go with me. We must speed this action
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.236#together, since we, being two, might bring some advantage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.237#The warcraft even of sad fighters combined turns courage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.238#and you and I would have skill to fight even against good men.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.239#So he spoke and strode on, a god, through the mortals' struggle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.240#Idomeneus, when he came back to his strong-built shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.241#drew his splendid armour over his body, and caught up two spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.242#and went on his way, as a thunderbolt, which the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.243#catching up in his hand shakes from the shining edge of Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.244#flashes as a portent to men and the bright glints shine from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.245#Such was the glitter of bronze that girt his chest in his running.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.246#Close to his shelter there encountered him his strong henchman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.247#Meriones, who was on his way to pick up a bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.248#and bring it back. Idomeneus in his strength spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.249#'Meriones, son of Molos, swift-footed, dearest beloved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.250#companion, why have you come back and left the battle and fighting?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.251#Have you been hit somewhere? Does pain of a spear's head afflict you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.252#Have you come back with someone's message for me? For my part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.253#my desire is to fight, not sit away in the shelters.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.254#Meriones, a thoughtful man, spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.255#'Idomeneus, lord of the counsels of the bronze-armoured Kretans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.256#I am on my way to bring back a spear, if you have any
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.257#left in your shelter. I broke just now the one I was carrying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.258#with a throw made against the shield of haughty Deïphobos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.259#Then Idomeneus lord of the Kretans answered him in turn:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.260#'You will find one spear, and twenty spears, if you want them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.261#standing against the shining inward wall in my shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.262#Trojan spears I win from men that I kill, for my way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.263#is not to fight my battles standing far away from my enemies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.264#Thereby I have spears there, and shields massive in the middle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.265#and helms and corselets are there in all the pride of their shining.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.266#Meriones, a thoughtful man, spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.267#'For me also, beside my shelter and beside my black ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.268#there are many spoils of the Trojans, but not near for me to get them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.269#For I tell you, neither am I one who has forgotten his war strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.270#but among the foremost, along the fighting where men win glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.271#I take my stand, whenever the quarrel of battle arises.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.272#Let my fighting be forgotten by some other bronze-armoured
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.273#Achaian. You are the very one I think must know of it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.274#Then Idomeneus lord of the Kretans answered him in turn:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.275#'I know your valour and what you are. Why need you speak of it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.276#If now beside the ships all the best of us were to assemble
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.277#for a hidden position, and there man's courage is best decided,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.278#where the man who is a coward and the brave man show themselves clearly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.279#the skin of the coward changes colour one way and another,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.280#and the heart inside him has no control to make him sit steady,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.281#but he shifts his weight from one foot to another, then settles firmly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.282#on both feet, and the heart inside his chest pounds violent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.283#as he thinks of the death spirits, and his teeth chatter together:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.284#but the brave man's skin will not change colour, nor is he too much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.285#frightened, once he has taken his place in the hidden position,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.286#but his prayer is to close as soon as may be in bitter division:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.287#and there no man could make light of your battle strength or your hand's work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.288#Even were you to be wounded in your work with spearcast or spearstroke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.289#the weapon would not strike behind your neck, nor in your back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.290#but would be driven straight against the chest or the belly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.291#as you made your way onward through the meeting of champions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.292#But come, let us no longer stand here talking of these things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.293#like children, for fear some man may arrogantly scold us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.294#Go to my shelter and choose for yourself a heavy spear.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.295#So he spoke; Meriones, a match for the rapid war god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.296#went into the shelter rapidly, and took up a bronze spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.297#and with his mind deeply set on battle followed Idomeneus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.298#As manslaughtering Ares is when he strides into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.299#and Terror goes on beside him, his beloved son, the powerful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.300#and dauntless, who frightens even the patient-hearted warrior:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.301#these two come out of Thrace to encounter in arms the Ephyroi
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.302#or the great-hearted Phlegyes, but the two will not listen to prayers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.303#from both sides, but give the glory to one side or the other:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.304#such were Meriones and Idomeneus, leaders of armies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.305#as they went on into the fighting helmed in the bright bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.306#First of the two, Meriones, spoke his word to Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.307#'Deukalides, where are you minded to enter the battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.308#Would it be on the right of the whole array, or in the centre,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.309#or to the left? Since I think that nowhere else in the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.310#are the flowing-haired Achaians overmatched so badly.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.311#Idomeneus lord of the Kretans answered him in turn:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.312#'There are others beside us to defend the ships in the centre,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.313#the two Aiantes, and Teukros, best of all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.314#in archery, and a good man in the close of standing combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.315#They can give Hektor, Priam's son, enough hard hitting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.316#even though he is very strong, and sweeps hard into battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.317#Furious though he is for fighting, it will be very steep work
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.318#for him to win through their irresistible hands and their war strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.319#and fire the ships, unless the son of Kronos in person
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.320#should hurl the blazing firebrand into our fast-running vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.321#Nor would huge Telamonian Aias give way to any man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.322#one who was mortal and ate bread, the yield of Demeter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.323#one who could be broken by the bronze and great stones flung at him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.324#He would not make way for Achilleus who breaks men in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.325#in close combat. For speed of feet none can strive with Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.326#Hold, as you say, for the left of the army, and thus soonest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.327#shall we see whether we win glory or give it to others.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.328#He spoke, and Meriones, a match for the running war god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.329#led the way, till they came to the place in the army he spoke for.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.330#These, as they saw Idomeneus like a flame in his valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.331#himself and his henchman with him in their elaborate war gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.332#they called out across the battle and gathered about him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.333#and an indiscriminate fight rose up by the sterns of the vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.334#And as when under the screaming winds the whirlstorms bluster
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.335#on that day when the dust lies deepest along the pathways
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.336#and the winds in the confusion of dust uplift a great cloud,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.337#such was their indiscriminate battle, and their hearts were furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.338#to slaughter each other with the sharp bronze through the press of the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.339#The battle where men perish shuddered now with the long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.340#man-tearing spears they held in their hands, their eyes were blinded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.341#in the dazzle of the bronze light from the glittering helmets,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.342#from the burnished corselets and the shining shields as men came on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.343#in confusion. That man would have to be very bold-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.344#who could be cheerful and not stricken looking on that struggle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.345#Two powerful sons of Kronos, hearts divided against each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.346#were wreaking bitter agonies on the fighting warriors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.347#since Zeus willed the victory for the Trojans and Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.348#glorifying swift-footed Achilleus, yet not utterly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.349#did he wish the Achaian people to be destroyed before Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.350#but only was giving glory to Thetis and her strong-spirited
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.351#son, while Poseidon emerging unseen from the grey salt water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.352#went among the Argives and stirred them, since he was angered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.353#that they were beaten by the Trojans and blamed Zeus for it bitterly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.354#Indeed, the two were of one generation and a single father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.355#but Zeus was the elder born and knew more. Therefore Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.356#shrank from openly defending them, but secretly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.357#in a man's likeness was forever stirring them up through the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.358#So these two had looped over both sides a crossing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.359#cable of strong discord and the closing of battle, not to be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.360#slipped, not to be broken, which unstrung the knees of many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.361#There Idomeneus, greying though he was, called on the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.362#and charged in upon the Trojans and drove panic among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.363#for he killed Othryoneus, a man who had lived in Kabesos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.364#who was newly come in the wake of the rumour of war, and had asked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.365#Priam for the hand of the loveliest of his daughters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.366#Kassandra, without bride price, but had promised a great work for her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.367#to drive back the unwilling sons of the Achaians from Troy land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.368#and aged Priam had bent his head in assent, and promised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.369#to give her, so Othryoneus fought in the faith of his promises.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.370#Idomeneus aimed at him with the shining spear, and threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.371#and hit him as he came onward with high stride, and the corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.372#of bronze he wore could not hold, the spear fixed in the middle belly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.373#He fell, thunderously, and Idomeneus vaunting cried out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.374#'Othryoneus, I congratulate you beyond all others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.375#if it is here that you will bring to pass what you promised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.376#to Dardanian Priam, who in turn promised you his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.377#See now, we also would make you a promise, and we would fulfil it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.378#we would give you the loveliest of Atreides' daughters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.379#and bring her here from Argos to be your wife, if you joined us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.380#and helped us storm the strong-founded city of Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.381#Come then with me, so we can meet by our seafaring vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.382#about a marriage; we here are not bad matchmakers for you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.383#The hero Idomeneus spoke and dragged him through the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.384#caught by the foot, but now Asios came to stand by him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.385#dismounted, ahead of his horses whom his henchman held ever behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.386#so that they breathed on his shoulders. He was striving in all his fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.387#to strike Idomeneus, but he, too quick with a spearcast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.388#struck him in the gorge underneath the chin, and drove the bronze clean through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.389#He fell, as when an oak goes down or a white poplar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.390#or like a towering pine tree which in the mountains the carpenters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.391#have hewn down with their whetted axes to make a ship timber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.392#So he lay there felled in front of his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.393#roaring, and clawed with his hands at the bloody dust. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.394#the charioteer who was close behind him was stricken in the wits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.395#and shrinking from the hands of the enemy did not have daring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.396#to turn the horses about, but Antilochos stubborn in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.397#pinned him through the middle with a spearstroke, and the corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.398#of bronze he wore could not hold, the spear fixed in the middle belly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.399#so that he tumbled, gasping, out of the strong-wrought chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.400#But for the horses, Antilochos, son of great-hearted Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.401#drove them away from the Trojans among the strong-greaved Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.402#Deïphobos in sorrow for Asios now came close
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.403#in on Idomeneus, and with the bright spear made a cast at him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.404#but Idomeneus with his eyes straight on him avoided the bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.405#since also he was hidden beneath his shield's perfect circle, that shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.406#he carried, hooped in circles of glaring bronze, and the skins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.407#of oxen, fitted with double cross-stays. He was all gathered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.408#together under this, and the brazen spear shot over him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.409#and the shield gave out a hollow clash as the spear glanced from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.410#Yet Deïphobos made no utterly vain cast from his strong hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.411#but struck Hypsenor, son of Hippasos, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.412#in the liver under the midriff, and at once took the strength from his knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.413#And Deïphobos vaunted terribly over him, calling in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.414#'Asios lies not now all unavenged. I think rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.415#as he goes down to Hades of the Gates, the strong one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.416#he will be cheerful at heart, since I have sent him an escort.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.417#He spoke, and sorrow came over the Argives at his vaunting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.418#and beyond others stirred the spirit in wise Antilochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.419#yet sorrowful though he was he did not forget his companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.420#but running stood and bestrode him and covered him under the great shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.421#Thereon Mekisteus, son of Echios, and brilliant Alastor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.422#two staunch companions, stooping beneath it, caught up Hypsenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.423#and carried him, groaning heavily, to the hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.424#Idomeneus did not slacken his great fury, but always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.425#was straining to shroud some one of the Trojans in dark night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.426#or go down crashing himself as he fought the bane from the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.427#There was a man, loved son of illustrious Aisyetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.428#the hero Alkathoös, who was son-in-law of Anchises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.429#and had married the eldest of his daughters, Hippodameia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.430#dear to the hearts of her father and the lady her mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.431#in the great house, since she surpassed all the girls of her own age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.432#for beauty and accomplishments and wit; for which reason
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.433#the man married her who was the best in the wide Troad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.434#But now Poseidon beat him down at the hands of Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.435#for he bewitched his shining eyes, made moveless his bright limbs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.436#so that he could not run backward, neither evade him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.437#but stood like a statue or a tree with leaves towering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.438#motionless, while fighting Idomeneus stabbed at the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.439#of his chest with the spear, and broke the bronze armour about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.440#which in time before had guarded his body from destruction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.441#He cried out then, a great cry, broken, the spear in him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.442#and fell, thunderously, and the spear in his heart was stuck fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.443#but the heart was panting still and beating to shake the butt end
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.444#of the spear. Then and there Ares the huge took his life away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.445#Idomeneus vaunted terribly over him, calling in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.446#'Deïphobos, are we then to call this a worthy bargain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.447#three men killed for one? It was you yourself were so boastful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.448#Strange man. Do you rather come yourself and stand up against me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.449#so you can see what I am like, Zeus' seed, come here to face you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.450#Since Zeus first got by Krete Minos, who cared for his people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.451#and to Minos in turn was born a blameless son, Deukalion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.452#and Deukalion sired me to be lord over many people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.453#in wide Krete, and now my ships have brought me to this place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.454#to be an evil for you and your father and the rest of the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.455#So he spoke, and the heart in Deïphobos was divided,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.456#pondering whether to draw back and find some other high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.457#Trojan to be his companion, or whether to attempt him singly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.458#And in the division of his heart this way seemed best to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.459#to go for Aineias. He found him at the uttermost edge of the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.460#standing, since he was forever angry with brilliant Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.461#because great as he was he did him no honour among his people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.462#Deïphobos came and stood close to him and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.463#'Aineias, lord of the Trojans' counsels, now there is need of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.464#to stand by your brother-in-law, if this bond of kinship touches you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:13.465#Come then, stand by Alkathoös, who was your sister's husband
