urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.236#Put to sleep the shining eyes of Zeus under his brows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.237#as soon as I have lain beside him in love. I will give you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.238#gifts; a lovely throne, imperishable forever,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.239#of gold. My own son, he of the strong arms, Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.240#shall make it with careful skill and make for your feet a footstool
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.241#on which you can rest your shining feet when you take your pleasure.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.242#Then Sleep the still and soft spoke to her in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.243#'Hera, honoured goddess and daughter of mighty Kronos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.244#any other one of the gods, whose race is immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.245#I would lightly put to sleep, even the stream of that River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.246#Okeanos, whence is risen the seed of all the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.247#But I would not come too close to Zeus, the son of Kronos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.248#nor put him to sleep, unless when he himself were to tell me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.249#Before now, it was a favour to you that taught me wisdom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.250#on the day Herakles, the high-hearted son of Zeus, was sailing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.251#from Ilion, when he had utterly sacked the city of the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.252#That time I laid to sleep the brain in Zeus of the aegis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.253#and drifted upon him still and soft, but your mind was devising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.254#evil, and you raised along the sea the blasts of the racking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.255#winds, and on these swept him away to Kos, the strong-founded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.256#with all his friends lost, but Zeus awakened in anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.257#and beat the gods up and down his house, looking beyond all others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.258#for me, and would have sunk me out of sight in the sea from the bright sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.259#had not Night who has power over gods and men rescued me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.260#I reached her in my flight, and Zeus let be, though he was angry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.261#in awe of doing anything to swift Night's displeasure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.262#Now you ask me to do this other impossible thing for you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.263#Then in turn the lady ox-eyed Hera answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.264#'Sleep, why do you ponder this in your heart, and hesitate?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.265#Or do you think that Zeus of the wide brows, aiding the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.266#will be angry as he was angry for his son, Herakles?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.267#Come now, do it, and I will give you one of the younger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.268#Graces for you to marry, and she shall be called your lady;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.269#Pasithea, since all your days you have loved her forever.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.270#So she spoke, and Sleep was pleased and spoke to her in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.271#'Come then! Swear it to me on Styx' ineluctable water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.272#With one hand take hold of the prospering earth, with the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.273#take hold of the shining salt sea, so that all the undergods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.274#who gather about Kronos may be witnesses to us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.275#Swear that you will give me one of the younger Graces,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.276#Pasithea, the one whom all my days I have longed for.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.277#He spoke, nor failed to persuade the goddess Hera of the white arms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.278#and she swore as he commanded, and called by their names on all those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.279#gods who live beneath the Pit, and who are called Titans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.280#Then when she had sworn this, and made her oath a complete thing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.281#the two went away from Lemnos, and the city of Imbros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.282#and mantled themselves in mist, and made their way very lightly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.283#till they came to Ida with all her springs, the mother of wild beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.284#to Lekton, where first they left the water, and went on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.285#over dry land, and with their feet the top of the forest was shaken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.286#There Sleep stayed, before the eyes of Zeus could light on him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.287#and went up aloft a towering pine tree, the one that grew tallest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.288#at that time on Ida, and broke through the close air to the aether.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.289#In this he sat, covered over and hidden by the pine branches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.290#in the likeness of a singing bird whom in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.291#the immortal gods call chalkis, but men call him kymindis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.292#But Hera light-footed made her way to the peak of Gargaros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.293#on towering Ida. And Zeus who gathers the clouds saw her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.294#and when he saw her desire was a mist about his close heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.295#as much as on that time they first went to bed together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.296#and lay in love, and their dear parents knew nothing of it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.297#He stood before her and called her by name and spoke to her: 'Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.298#what is your desire that you come down here from Olympos?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.299#And your horses are not here, nor your chariot, which you would ride in.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.300#Then with false lying purpose the lady Hera answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.301#'I am going to the ends of the generous earth, on a visit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.302#to Okeanos, whence the gods have risen, and Tethys our mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.303#who brought me up kindly in their own house, and cared for me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.304#I shall go to visit these, and resolve their division of discord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.305#since now for a long time they have stayed apart from each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.306#and from the bed of love, since rancour has entered their feelings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.307#In the foothills by Ida of the waters are standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.308#my horses, who will carry me over hard land and water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.309#Only now I have come down here from Olympos for your sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.310#so you will not be angry with me afterwards, if I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.311#have gone silently to the house of deep-running Okeanos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.312#Then in turn Zeus who gathers the clouds answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.313#'Hera, there will be a time afterwards when you can go there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.314#as well. But now let us go to bed and turn to love-making.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.315#For never before has love for any goddess or woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.316#so melted about the heart inside me, broken it to submission,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.317#as now: not that time when I loved the wife of Ixion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.318#who bore me Peirithoös, equal of the gods in counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.319#nor when I loved Akrisios' daughter, sweet-stepping Danaë,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.320#who bore Perseus to me, pre-eminent among all men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.321#nor when I loved the daughter of far-renowned Phoinix, Europa
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.322#who bore Minos to me, and Rhadamanthys the godlike;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.323#not when I loved Semele, or Alkmene in Thebe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.324#when Alkmene bore me a son, Herakles the strong-hearted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.325#while Semele's son was Dionysos, the pleasure of mortals;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.326#not when I loved the queen Demeter of the lovely tresses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.327#not when it was glorious Leto, nor yourself, so much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.328#as now I love you, and the sweet passion has taken hold of me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.329#Then with false lying purpose the lady Hera answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.330#'Most honoured son of Kronos, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.331#If now your great desire is to lie in love together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.332#here on the peaks of Ida, everything can be seen. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.333#what would happen if some one of the gods everlasting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.334#saw us sleeping, and went and told all the other immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.335#of it? I would not simply rise out of bed and go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.336#again, into your house, and such a thing would be shameful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.337#No, if this is your heart's desire, if this is your wish, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.338#there is my chamber, which my beloved son Hephaistos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.339#has built for me, and closed the leaves in the door-posts snugly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.340#We can go back there and lie down, since bed is your pleasure.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.341#Then in turn Zeus who gathers the clouds answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.342#'Hera, do not fear that any mortal or any god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.343#will see, so close shall be the golden cloud that I gather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.344#about us. Not even Helios can look at us through it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.345#although beyond all others his light has the sharpest vision.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.346#So speaking, the son of Kronos caught his wife in his arms. There
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.347#underneath them the divine earth broke into young, fresh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.348#grass, and into dewy clover, crocus and hyacinth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.349#so thick and soft it held the hard ground deep away from them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.350#There they lay down together and drew about them a golden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.351#wonderful cloud, and from it the glimmering dew descended.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.352#So the father slept unshaken on the peak of Gargaron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.353#with his wife in his arms, when sleep and passion had stilled him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.354#but gently Sleep went on the run to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.355#with a message to tell him who circles the earth and shakes it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.356#Poseidon, and stood close to him and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.357#'Poseidon, now with all your heart defend the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.358#and give them glory, though only for a little, while Zeus still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.359#sleeps; since I have mantled a soft slumber about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.360#and Hera beguiled him into sleeping in love beside her.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.361#He spoke so, and went away among the famed races
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.362#of men, and stirred Poseidon even more to defend the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.363#He sprang among their foremost and urged them on in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.364#'Argives, now once more must we give the best of it to Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.365#Priam's son, so he may take our ships and win glory from them?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.366#Such is his thought and such is his prayer, because now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.367#in the anger of his heart stays still among the hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.368#But there will not be too much longing for him, if the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.369#of us can stir ourselves up to stand by each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.370#Come; then, do as I say, let us all be won over; let us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.371#take those shields which are best in all the army and biggest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.372#and put them on, and cover our heads in the complete shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.373#of helmets, and take in our hands our spears that are longest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.374#and go. I myself will lead the way, and I think that no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.375#Hektor, Priam's son, can stand up to us, for all his fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.376#Let the man stubborn in battle who wears a small shield on his shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.377#give it to a worse man, and put on the shield that is bigger.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.378#So he spoke, and they listened hard to him, and obeyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.379#The kings in person marshalled these men, although they were wounded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.380#Tydeus' son, and Odysseus, and Atreus' son Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.381#They went among all, and made them exchange their armour of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.382#and the good fighter put on the good armour, and each gave the worse gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.383#to the worse. Then when in the shining bronze they had shrouded their bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.384#they went forward, and Poseidon the shaker of the earth led them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.385#holding in his heavy hand the stark sword with the thin edge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.386#glittering, as glitters the thunderflash none may close with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.387#by right in sorrowful division, but fear holds all men back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.388#On the other side glorious Hektor ordered the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.389#and now Poseidon of the dark hair and glorious Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.390#strained to its deadliest the division of battle, the one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.391#bringing power to the Trojans, and the god to the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.392#The breaking of the sea washed up to the ships and the shelters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.393#of the Argives. The two sides closed together with a great war cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.394#Not such is the roaring against dry land of the sea's surf
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.395#as it rolls in from the open under the hard blast of the north wind;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.396#not such is the bellowing of fire in its blazing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.397#in the deep places of the hills when it rises inflaming the forest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.398#nor such again the crying voice of the wind in the deep-haired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.399#oaks, when it roars highest in its fury against them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.400#not so loud as now the noise of Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.401#in voice of terror rose as they drove against one another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.402#First glorious Hektor made a cast with his spear at Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.403#since he had turned straight against him, nor missed with his throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.404#but struck, there where over his chest were crossed the two straps,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.405#one for the sword with the silver nails, and one for the great shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.406#These guarded the tenderness of his skin. And Hektor, in anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.407#because his weapon had been loosed from his hand in a vain cast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.408#to avoid death shrank into the host of his own companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.409#But as he drew away huge Telamonian Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.410#caught up a rock; there were many, holding-stones for the fast ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.411#rolled among the feet of the fighters; he caught up one of these
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.412#and hit him in the chest next the throat over his shield rim,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.413#and spun him around like a top with the stroke, so that he staggered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.414#in a circle; as a great oak goes down root-torn under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.415#Zeus father's stroke, and a horrible smell of sulphur uprises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.416#from it, and there is no courage left in a man who stands by
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.417#and looks on, for the thunderstroke of great Zeus is a hard thing;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.418#so Hektor in all his strength dropped suddenly in the dust, let
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.419#fall the spear from his hand, and his shield was beaten upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.420#and the helm, and his armour elaborate with bronze clashed over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.421#Screaming aloud the sons of the Achaians ran forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.422#in hope to drag him away, and threw their volleying javelins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.423#against him, yet no man could stab or cast at the shepherd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.424#of the people; sooner the Trojans' bravest gathered about him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.425#Aineias, and Poulydamas, and brilliant Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.426#Sarpedon, lord of the Lykians, and Glaukos the blameless;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.427#and of the rest no man was heedless of him, but rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.428#sloped the strong circles of their shields over him, while his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.429#caught him in their arms out of the fighting and reached his fast-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.430#horses, where they stood to the rear of the fighting and the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.431#holding their charioteer and the elaborate chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.432#and these carried him, groaning heavily, back toward the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.433#But when they came to the crossing place of the fair-running river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.434#of whirling Xanthos, whose father was Zeus the immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.435#they moved him from behind his horses to the ground, and splashed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.436#water over him. He got his wind again, and his eyes cleared,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.437#and he got up to lean on one knee and vomit a dark clot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:14.438#of blood, then lay back on the ground again, while over both eyes
