urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.121#And there might have been wrought another anger, and bitterness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.122#from Zeus, still greater, more wearisome among the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.123#had not Athene, in her fear for the sake of all gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.124#sprung up and out through the forecourt, left her chair where she was sitting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.125#and taken the helmet off from his head, the shield from his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.126#and snatched out of his heavy hand the bronze spear, and fixed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.127#apart, and then in speech reasoned with violent Ares:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.128#'Madman, mazed of your wits, this is ruin! Your ears can listen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.129#still to reality, but your mind is gone and your discipline.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.130#Do you not hear what the goddess Hera of the white arms tells us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.131#and she coming back even now from Zeus of Olympos?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.132#Do you wish, after running the course of many misfortunes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.133#yourself, still to come back to Olympos under compulsion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.134#though reluctant, and plant seed of great sorrow among the rest of us?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.135#Since he will at once leave the Achaians and the high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.136#Trojans, and come back to batter us on Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.137#and will catch up as they come the guilty one and the guiltless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.138#Therefore I ask of you to give up your anger for your son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.139#By now some other, better of his strength and hands than your son was,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.140#has been killed, or will soon be killed; and it is a hard thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.141#to rescue all the generation and seed of all mortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.142#So she spoke, and seated on a chair violent Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.143#But Hera called to come with her outside the house Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.144#and Iris, who is messenger among the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.145#gods, and spoke to them and addressed them in winged words: 'Zeus wishes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.146#both of you to go to him with all speed, at Ida;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.147#but when you have come there and looked upon Zeus' countenance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.148#then you must do whatever he urges you, and his orders.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.149#So the lady Hera spoke, and once more returning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.150#sat on her throne. They in a flash of speed winged their way onward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.151#They came to Ida with all her springs, the mother of wild beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.152#and found the wide-browed son of Kronos on the height of Gargaron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.153#sitting still, and fragrant cloud gathered in a circle about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.154#These two came into the presence of Zeus the cloud-gatherer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.155#and stood, nor was his heart angry when he looked upon them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.156#seeing they had promptly obeyed the message of his dear lady.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.157#He spoke to Iris first of the two, and addressed her in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.158#'Go on your way now, swift Iris, to the lord Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.159#and give him all this message nor be a false messenger. Tell him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.160#that he must now quit the war and the fighting, and go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.161#among the generations of gods, or into the bright sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.162#And if he will not obey my words, or thinks nothing of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.163#then let him consider in his heart and his spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.164#that he might not, strong though he is, be able to stand up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.165#to my attack; since I say I am far greater than he is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.166#in strength, and elder born; yet his inward heart shrinks not from calling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.167#himself the equal of me, though others shudder before me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.168#He spoke, and swift wind-footed Iris did not disobey him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.169#but went down along the hills of Ida to sacred Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.170#As those times when out of the clouds the snow or the hail whirls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.171#cold beneath the blast of the north wind born in the bright air,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.172#so rapidly in her eagerness winged Iris, the swift one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.173#and stood beside the famed shaker of the earth, and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.174#'I have a certain message for you, dark-haired, earth-encircler,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.175#and came here to bring it to you from Zeus of the aegis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.176#His order is that you quit the war and the fighting, and go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.177#among the generations of gods, or into the bright sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.178#And if you will not obey his words, or think nothing of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.179#his threat is that he himself will come to fight with you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.180#here, strength against strength, but warns you to keep from under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.181#his hands, since he says he is far greater than you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.182#in strength, and elder born. Yet your inward heart shrinks not from calling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.183#yourself the equal of him, though others shudder before him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.184#Then deeply vexed the famed shaker of the earth spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.185#'No, no. Great though he is, this that he has said is too much,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.186#if he will force me against my will, me, who am his equal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.187#in rank. Since we are three brothers born by Rheia to Kronos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.188#Zeus, and I, and the third is Hades, lord of the dead men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.189#All was divided among us three ways, each given his domain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.190#I when the lots were shaken drew the grey sea to live in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.191#forever; Hades drew the lot of the mists and the darkness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.192#and Zeus was allotted the wide sky, in the cloud and the bright air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.193#But earth and high Olympos are common to all three. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.194#I am no part of the mind of Zeus. Let him in tranquillity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.195#and powerful as he is stay satisfied with his third share.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.196#And let him absolutely stop frightening me, as if I were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.197#mean, with his hands. It were better to keep for the sons and the daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.198#he got himself these blusterings and these threats of terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.199#They will listen, because they must, to whatever he tells them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.200#Then in turn swift wind-footed Iris answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.201#'Am I then to carry, o dark-haired, earth-encircler,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.202#this word, which is strong and steep, back to Zeus from you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.203#Or will you change a little? The hearts of the great can be changed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.204#You know the Furies, how they forever side with the elder.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.205#Then in turn the shaker of the earth Poseidon spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.206#'Now this, divine Iris, was a word quite properly spoken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.207#It is a fine thing when a messenger is conscious of justice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.208#But this thing comes as a bitter sorrow to my heart and my spirit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.209#when Zeus tries in words of anger to reprimand one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.210#is his equal in station, and endowed with destiny like his.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.211#Still, this time I will give way, for all my vexation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.212#But I will say this also, and make it a threat in my anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.213#If ever, acting apart from me and Athene the spoiler,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.214#apart from Hera and Hermes and the lord Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.215#he shall spare headlong Ilion, and shall not be willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.216#to take it by storm, and bestow great victory on the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.217#let him be sure, there will be no more healing of our anger.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.218#The shaker of the earth spoke, and left the Achaian people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.219#and went, merging in the sea, and the fighting Achaians longed for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.220#After this Zeus who gathers the clouds spoke to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.221#'Go now, beloved Phoibos, to the side of brazen-helmed Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.222#since by this he who encircles the earth and shakes it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.223#is gone into the bright sea and has avoided the anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.224#that would be ours. In truth, this would have been a fight those other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.225#gods would have heard about, who gather to Kronos beneath us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.226#Now this way it was far better for me, and for himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.227#also, that, for all his vexation before, he gave way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.228#to my hands. We would have sweated before this business was finished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.229#Now yourself take up in your hands the aegis with fluttering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.230#tassels, and shake it hard to scare the Achaian fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.231#Then, striker from afar, let your own concern be glorious Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.232#So long waken the huge strength in him, until the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.233#run in flight, and come to the ships and the crossing of Helle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.234#From there on I myself shall think of the word and the action
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.235#to make the Achaians get wind once more, after their hard fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.236#He spoke so, and Apollo, not disregarding his father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.237#came down along the mountains of Ida in the likeness of a rapid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.238#hawk, the dove's murderer and swiftest of all things flying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.239#He found brilliant Hektor, the son of wise Priam, sitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.240#now, no longer sprawled, as he gathered new strength back into him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.241#and recognized his companions about him. The sweat and hard breathing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.242#had begun to stop, once the will in Zeus of the aegis wakened him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.243#Apollo who works from afar stood beside him, and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.244#'Hektor, son of Priam, why do you sit in such weakness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.245#here apart from the others? Did some disaster befall you?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.246#In his weakness Hektor of the shining helm spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.247#'Who are you, who speak to me face to face, o noblest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.248#of gods? Did you not know how by the Achaians' grounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.249#ships, Aias of the great war cry struck me in the chest with a boulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.250#as I slaughtered his companions, and stayed my furious valour?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.251#Truly, I thought that on this day I would come to the corpses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.252#and the house of the death god, once I had breathed the inward life from me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.253#In turn the lord, the worker from afar, Apollo, spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.254#'Take heart; such an avenger am I whom the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.255#sent down from Ida, to stand by your side and defend you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.256#Phoibos Apollo of the golden sword, who in time before this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.257#also have stood to defend yourself and your sheer citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.258#So come now, and urge on your cavalry in their numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.259#to drive on their horses against the hollow ships. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.260#I shall move on before you and make all the way for the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.261#smooth before them, and bend back the Achaian fighters.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.262#He spoke, and breathed huge strength into the shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.263#As when some stalled horse who has been corn-fed at the manger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.264#breaking free of his rope gallops over the plain in thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.265#to his accustomed bathing place in a sweet-running river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.266#and in the pride of his strength holds high his head and the mane floats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.267#over his shoulders; sure of his glorious strength, the quick knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.268#carry him to the loved places and the pasture of horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.269#so Hektor moving rapidly his feet and his knees went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.270#onward, stirring the horsemen when he heard the god's voice speak.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.271#And as when men who live in the wilds and their dogs have driven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.272#into flight a horned stag or a wild goat. Inaccessible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.273#the rocky cliff or the shadowed forest has covered the quarry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.274#so that the men know it was not their fortune to take him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.275#and now by their clamouring shows in the way a great bearded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.276#lion, and bends them to sudden flight for all their eagerness;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.277#so the Danaans until that time kept always in close chase
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.278#assembled, stabbing at them with swords and leaf-headed spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.279#but when they saw Hektor once more ranging the men's ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.280#they were frightened, and by their feet collapsed all their bravery.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.281#Now Thoas spoke forth among them, the son of Andraimon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.282#far the best of the Aitolians, one skilled in the spear's throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.283#and brave in close fight. In assembly few of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.284#when the young men contended in debate could outdo him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.285#He in kind intention now spoke forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.286#'Can this be? Here is a strange thing I see with my own eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.287#how this Hektor has got to his feet once more, and eluded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.288#the death spirits. I think in each of us the heart had high hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.289#he was killed under the hands of Telamonian Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.290#Now some one of the gods has come to his help and rescued
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.291#Hektor, who has unstrung the knees of so many Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.292#I think he will do it once more now. It is not without Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.293#the deep-thundering that he stands their champion in all this fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.294#Come then, let us do as I say, let us all be persuaded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.295#Let us tell the multitude to make its way back toward the vessels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.296#while we ourselves, who claim we are greatest in all the army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.297#stand, and see if we can face him first, and hold him off from them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.298#with spears lifted against him, and I think for all of his fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.299#his heart will be afraid to plunge into our Danaan company.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.300#So he spoke, and they listened to him with care, and obeyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.301#They who rallied about Aias, the lord Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.302#Teukros, Meriones, and Meges, a man like the war god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.303#closed their order for hard impact, calling on the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.304#to face Hektor and the Trojans. Meanwhile behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.305#the multitude made their way back toward the ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.306#The Trojans came down on them in a pack, and Hektor led them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.307#in long strides, and in front of him went Phoibos Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.308#wearing a mist about his shoulders, and held the tempestuous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.309#terrible aegis, shaggy, conspicuous, that the bronze-smith
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.310#Hephaistos had given Zeus to wear to the terror of mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.311#Gripping this in both hands he led on the Trojan people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.312#But the Argives stood in close order against them, and the battle cry rose up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.313#in a thin scream from either side, the arrows from the bowstrings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.314#jumping, while from violent hands the numerous thrown spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.315#were driven, some deep in the bodies of quick-stirring young men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.316#while many in the space between before they had got to the white skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.317#stood fast in the ground, though they had been straining to reach the bodies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.318#So long as Phoibos Apollo held stilled in his hands the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.319#so long the thrown weapons of both took hold, and men dropped under them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.320#But when he stared straight into the eyes of the fast-mounted Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.321#and shook the aegis, and himself gave a great baying cry, the spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.322#inside them was mazed to hear it, they forgot their furious valour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.323#And they, as when in the dim of the black night two wild beasts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.324#stampede a herd of cattle or big flock of sheep, falling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.325#suddenly upon them, when no herdsman is by, the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.326#fled so in their weakness and terror, since Apollo drove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.327#terror upon them, and gave the glory to the Trojans and Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.328#There man killed man all along the scattered encounter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.329#Hektor first killed Stichios and Arkesilaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.330#one the leader of the bronze-armoured Boiotians, the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.331#trusted companion in arms of great-hearted Menestheus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.332#But Aineias slaughtered Medon and Iasos. Of these
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.333#Medon was a bastard son of godlike Oïleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.334#and therefore brother of Aias, but had made his home in Phylake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.335#away from the land of his fathers, having killed a man, a relation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.336#of Eriopis, his stepmother, the wife of Oileus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.337#Iasos was a leader appointed of the Athenians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.338#and was called the son of Sphelos, the son of Boukolos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.339#Poulydamas killed Mekisteus, and Polites Echios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.340#in the first onfall, and brilliant Agenor cut down Klonios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.341#Paris struck Deïochos from behind at the shoulder's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.342#base, as he ran away through the front ranks, and drove the bronze clean through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.343#While these stripped the armour from their men, meanwhile the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.344#blundering about the deep-dug ditch and the sharp stakes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.345#ran this way and that in terror, forced into their rampart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.346#But Hektor called aloud in a piercing cry to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.347#'Make hard for the ships, let the bloody spoils be. That man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.348#I see in the other direction apart from the vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.349#I will take care that he gets his death, and that man's relations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.350#neither men nor women shall give his dead body the rite of burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.351#In the space before our city the dogs shall tear him to pieces.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.352#So speaking with a whipstroke from the shoulder he lashed on his horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.353#calling across the ranks to the Trojans, who along with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.354#all cried aloud as they steered the horses who pulled their chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.355#with inhuman clamour, and in front of them Phoibos Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.356#easily, kicking them with his feet, tumbled the banked edges
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.357#of the deep ditch into the pit between, and bridged over a pathway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.358#both wide and long, about as long as the force of a spearcast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.359#goes when a man has thrown it to try his strength. They streamed over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.360#in massed formation, with Apollo in front of them holding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.361#the tremendous aegis, and wrecked the bastions of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.362#easily, as when a little boy piles sand by the sea-shore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.363#when in his innocent play he makes sand towers to amuse him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.364#and then, still playing, with hands and feet ruins them and wrecks them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.365#So you, lord Apollo, piled in confusion much hard work
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.366#and painful done by the Argives and drove terror among them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.367#So they reined in and stood fast again beside their ships, calling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.368#aloud upon each other, and to all of the gods, uplifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.369#their hands each man of them cried out his prayers in a great voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.370#and beyond others Gerenian Nestor, the Achaians' watcher,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.371#prayed, reaching out both arms to the starry heavens:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.372#'Father Zeus, if ever in wheat-deep Argos one of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.373#burning before you the rich thigh pieces of sheep or ox prayed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.374#he would come home again, and you nodded your head and assented,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.375#remember this, Olympian, save us from the day without pity;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.376#let not the Achaians be beaten down like this by the Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.377#So he spoke in prayer, and Zeus of the counsels thundered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.378#a great stroke, hearing the prayer of the old man, the son of Neleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.379#But the Trojans, hearing the thunderstroke of Zeus of the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.380#remembered even more their warcraft, and sprang on the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.381#They, as when the big waves on the sea wide-wandering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.382#wash across the walls of a ship underneath the leaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.383#force of the wind, which particularly piles up the big waves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.384#so the Trojans with huge clamour went over the rampart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.385#and drove their horses to fight alongside the grounded vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.386#with leaf-headed spears, some at close quarters, others from their horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.387#But the Achaians climbing high on their black ships fought from them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.388#with long pikes that lay among the hulls for sea fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.389#shrouded about the heads in bronze that was soldered upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.390#Meanwhile Patroklos, all the time the Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.391#were fighting on both sides of the wall, far away from the fast ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.392#had sat all this time in the shelter of courtly Eurypylos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.393#and had been entertaining him with words and applying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.394#medicines that would mitigate the black pains to the sore wound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.395#But when he saw the Trojans were sweeping over the rampart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.396#and the outcry and the noise of terror rose from the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.397#Patroklos groaned aloud then and struck himself on both thighs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.398#with the flats of his hands and spoke a word of lamentation:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.399#'Eurypylos, much though you need me I cannot stay here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.400#longer with you. This is a big fight that has arisen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.401#Now it is for your henchman to look after you, while I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.402#go in haste to Achilleus, to stir him into the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.403#Who knows if, with God helping, I might trouble his spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.404#by entreaty, since the persuasion of a friend is a strong thing.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.405#As he was speaking his feet carried him away. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.406#the Achaians stood steady against the Trojan attack, but they could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.407#beat the enemy, fewer as they were, away from their vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.408#nor again had the Trojans strength to break the battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.409#of the Danaans, and force their way into the ships and the shelters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.410#But as a chalkline straightens the cutting of a ship's timber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.411#in the hands of an expert carpenter, who by Athene's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.412#inspiration is well versed in all his craft's subtlety,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.413#so the battles fought by both sides were pulled fast and even.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.414#Now by the ships others fought in their various places
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.415#but Hektor made straight for glorious Aias. These two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.416#were fighting hard for a single ship, and neither was able,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.417#Hektor to drive Aias off the ship, and set fire to it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.418#nor Aias to beat Hektor back, since the divinity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.419#drove him. Shining Aias struck with the spear Kaletor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.420#Klytios' son, in the chest as he brought fire to the vessel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.421#He fell, thunderously, and the torch dropped from his hand. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.422#Hektor, when his eyes were aware of his cousin fallen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.423#in the dust in front of the black ship, uplifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.424#his voice in a great cry called to the Trojans and Lykians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.425#'Trojans, Lykians, Dardanians who fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.426#do not anywhere in this narrow place give way from the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.427#but stand by the son of Klytios, do not let the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.428#strip the armour from him, fallen where the ships are assembled.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.429#So he spoke, and made a cast at Aias with the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.430#spear, but missed him and struck the son of Mastor, Lykophron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.431#henchman of Aias from Kythera who had been living
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.432#with him; for he had killed a man in sacred Kythera.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.433#Hektor struck him in the head above the ear with the sharp bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.434#as he stood next to Aias, so that Lykophron sprawling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.435#dropped from the ship's stern to the ground, and his strength was broken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.436#And Aias shuddered at the sight, and spoke to his brother:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.437#'See, dear Teukros, our true companion, the son of Mastor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.438#is killed, who came to us from Kythera and in our household
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.439#was one we honoured as we honoured our beloved parents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.440#Now great-hearted Hektor has killed him. Where are your arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.441#of sudden death, and the bow that Phoibos Apollo gave you?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.442#He spoke, and Teukros heard and came running to stand beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.443#holding in his hand the backstrung bow and the quiver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.444#to hold arrows, and let go his hard shots against the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.445#First he struck down Kleitos, the glorious son of Peisenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.446#and companion of Poulydamas, proud son of Panthoös.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.447#Now Kleitos held the reins, and gave all his care to the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.448#driving them into that place where the most battalions were shaken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.449#for the favour of Hektor and the Trojans, but the sudden evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.450#came to him, and none for all their desire could defend him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.451#for the painful arrow was driven into his neck from behind him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.452#He fell out of the chariot, and the fast-footed horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.453#shied away, rattling the empty car; but Poulydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.454#their master saw it at once, and ran first to the heads of the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.455#He gave them into the hands of Astynoös, Protiaon's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.456#son, with many orders to be watchful and hold the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.457#close; then himself went back into the ranks of the champions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.458#But Teukros picked up another arrow for bronze-helmed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.459#Hektor, and would have stopped his fighting by the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.460#had he hit him during his bravery and torn the life from him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.461#but he was not hidden from the close purpose of Zeus, who was guarding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.462#Hektor, and denied that glory to Telamonian Teukros;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.463#who broke in the unfaulted bow the close-twisted sinew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.464#as Teukros drew it against him, so the bronze-weighted arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.465#went, as the bow dropped out of his hands, driven crazily sidewise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.466#And Teukros shuddered at the sight, and spoke to his brother:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.467#'See now, how hard the divinity cuts across the intention
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.468#in all our battle, who struck the bow out of my hand, who has broken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.469#the fresh-twisted sinew of the bowstring I bound on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.470#this morning, so it would stand the succession of springing arrows.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.471#Then in turn huge Telamonian Aias answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.472#'Dear brother, then let your bow and your showering arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.473#lie, now that the god begrudging the Danaans wrecked them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.474#But take a long spear in your hands, a shield on your shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.475#and close with the Trojans, and drive on the rest of your people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.476#Let them not, though they have beaten us, easily capture
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.477#our strong-benched ships. We must remember the frenzy of fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.478#He spoke, and Teukros put away the bow in his shelter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.479#and threw across his shoulders the shield of the fourfold ox-hide.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.480#Over his mighty head he set the well-fashioned helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.481#with the horse-hair crest, and the plumes nodded terribly above it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.482#Then he caught up a powerful spear, edged with sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.483#and went on his way, running fast, and stood beside Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.484#But Hektor, when he saw how the arrows of Teukros were baffled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.485#lifted his voice in a great cry to the Trojans and Lykians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.486#'Trojans, Lykians, Dardanians who fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.487#be men now, dear friends, remember your furious valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.488#along the hollow ships, since I have seen with my own eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.489#how by the hand of Zeus their bravest man's arrows were baffled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.490#Easily seen is the strength that is given from Zeus to mortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.491#either in those into whose hands he gives the surpassing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.492#glory, or those he diminishes and will not defend them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.493#as now he diminishes the strength of the Argives, and helps us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.494#Fight on then by the ships together. He who among you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.495#finds by spear thrown or spear thrust his death and destiny,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.496#let him die. He has no dishonour when he dies defending
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.497#his country, for then his wife shall be saved and his children afterwards,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.498#and his house and property shall not be damaged, if the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.499#must go away with their ships to the beloved land of their fathers.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.500#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit and strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.501#But Aias on the other side called to his companions:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.502#'Shame, you Argives; here is the time of decision, whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.503#we die, or live on still and beat back ruin from our vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.504#Do you expect, if our ships fall to helm-shining Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.505#you will walk each of you back dryshod to the land of your fathers?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.506#Do you not hear how Hektor is stirring up all his people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.507#how he is raging to set fire to our ships? He is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.508#inviting you to come to a dance. He invites you to battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.509#For us there can be no design, no purpose, better than this one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.510#to close in and fight with the strength of our hands at close quarters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.511#Better to take in a single time our chances of dying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.512#or living, than go on being squeezed in the stark encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.513#right up against our ships, as now, by men worse than we are.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.514#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit and strength in each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.515#There Hektor killed the son of Perimedes, Schedios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.516#lord of the men of Phokis; but Aias killed Laodamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.517#leader of the foot-soldiers, and shining son of Antenor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.518#Then Poulydamas stripped Otos of Kyllene, companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.519#to Meges, Phyleus' son, and a lord among the great-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.520#Epeians. Meges seeing it lunged at him, but Poulydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.521#bent down and away, so that Meges missed him. Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.522#would not let Panthoös' son go down among the front fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.523#but Meges stabbed with the spear the middle of the chest of Kroismos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.524#He fell, thunderously, and Meges was stripping the armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.525#from his shoulders, but meanwhile Dolops lunged at him, Lampos'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.526#son, a man crafty with the spear and strongest of the sons born
