urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.733#'Friends and fighting men of the Danaans, henchmen of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.734#be men now, dear friends, remember your furious valour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.735#Do we think there are others who stand behind us to help us?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.736#Have we some stronger wall that can rescue men from perdition?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.737#We have no city built strong with towers lying near us, within which
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.738#we could defend ourselves and hold off this host that matches us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.739#We hold position in this plain of the close-armoured Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.740#bent back against the sea, and far from the land of our fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.741#Salvation's light is in our hands' work, not the mercy of battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.742#He spoke, and came forward with his sharp spear, raging for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.743#And whenever some Trojan crashed against the hollow ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.744#with burning fire, who sought to wake the favour of Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.745#Aias would wait for him and then stab with the long pike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:15.746#and so from close up wounded twelve in front of the vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.1#So they fought on both sides for the sake of the strong-benched vessel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.2#Meanwhile Patroklos came to the shepherd of the people, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.3#and stood by him and wept warm tears, like a spring dark-running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.4#that down the face of a rock impassable drips its dim water;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.5#and swift-footed brilliant Achilleus looked on him in pity,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.6#and spoke to him aloud and addressed him in winged words: 'Why then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.7#are you crying like some poor little girl, Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.8#who runs after her mother and begs to be picked up and carried,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.9#and clings to her dress, and holds her back when she tries to hurry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.10#and gazes tearfully into her face, until she is picked up?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.11#You are like such a one, Patroklos, dropping these soft tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.12#Could you have some news to tell, for me or the Myrmidons?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.13#Have you, and nobody else, received some message from Phthia?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.14#Yet they tell me Aktor's son Menoitios lives still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.15#and Aiakos' son Peleus lives still among the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.16#If either of these died we should take it hard. Or is it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.17#the Argives you are mourning over, and how they are dying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.18#against the hollow ships by reason of their own arrogance?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.19#Tell me, do not hide it in your mind, and so we shall both know.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.20#Then groaning heavily, Patroklos the rider, you answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.21#'Son of Peleus, far greatest of the Achaians, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.22#do not be angry; such grief has fallen upon the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.23#For all those who were before the bravest in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.24#are lying up among the ships with arrow or spear wounds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.25#The son of Tydeus, strong Diomedes, was hit by an arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.26#and Odysseus has a pike wound, and Agamemnon the spear-famed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.27#and Eurypylos has been wounded in the thigh with an arrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.28#And over these the healers skilled in medicine are working
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.29#to cure their wounds. But you, Achilleus; who can do anything
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.30#with you? May no such anger take me as this that you cherish!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.31#Cursed courage. What other man born hereafter shall be advantaged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.32#unless you beat aside from the Argives this shameful destruction?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.33#Pitiless: the rider Peleus was never your father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.34#nor Thetis was your mother, but it was the grey sea that bore you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.35#and the towering rocks, so sheer the heart in you is turned from us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.36#But if you are drawing back from some prophecy known in your own heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.37#and by Zeus' will your honoured mother has told you of something,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.38#then send me out at least, let the rest of the Myrmidon people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.39#follow me, and I may be a light given to the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.40#Give me your armour to wear on my shoulders into the fighting;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.41#so perhaps the Trojans might think I am you, and give way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.42#from their attack, and the fighting sons of the Achaians get wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.43#again after hard work. There is little breathing space in the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.44#We unwearied might with a mere cry pile men wearied
