urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.48#But now, deeply troubled, swift-footed Achilleus answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.49#'Ah, Patroklos, illustrious, what is this you are saying?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.50#I have not any prophecy in mind that I know of;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.51#there is no word from Zeus my honoured mother has told me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.52#but this thought comes as a bitter sorrow to my heart and my spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.53#when a man tries to foul one who is his equal, to take back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.54#a prize of honour, because he goes in greater authority.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.55#This is a bitter thought to me; my desire has been dealt with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.56#roughly. The girl the sons of the Achaians chose out for my honour,
