urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.390#and in the ravines of their water-courses rip all the hillsides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.391#and dash whirling in huge noise down to the blue sea, out of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.392#the mountains headlong, so that the works of men are diminished;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.393#so huge rose the noise from the horses of Troy in their running.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.394#But Patroklos, when he had cut away their first battalions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.395#turned back to pin them against the ships, and would not allow them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.396#to climb back into their city though they strained for it, but sweeping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.397#through the space between the ships, the high wall, and the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.398#made havoc and exacted from them the blood price for many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.399#There first of all he struck with the shining spear Pronoös
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.400#in the chest where it was left bare by the shield, and unstrung his limbs' strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.401#He fell, thunderously, and Patroklos in his next outrush
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.402#at Thestor, Enops' son, who huddled inside his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.403#shrunk back, he had lost all his nerve, and from his hands the reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.404#slipped--Patroklos coming close up to him stabbed with a spear-thrust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.405#at the right side of the jaw and drove it on through the teeth, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.406#hooked and dragged him with the spear over the rail, as a fisherman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.407#who sits out on the jut of a rock with line and glittering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.408#bronze hook drags a fish, who is thus doomed, out of the water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.409#So he hauled him, mouth open to the bright spear, out of the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.410#and shoved him over on his face, and as he fell the life left him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.411#Next he struck Erylaos, as he swept in, with a great stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.412#in the middle of the head, and all the head broke into two pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.413#inside the heavy helmet, and he in the dust face downward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.414#dropped while death breaking the spirit drifted about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.415#Afterwards with Erymas, Amphoteros, and Epaltes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.416#Tlepolemos Damastor's son, Echios and Pyris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.417#Ipheus and Euippos, and Argeas' son Polymelos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.418#all these he felled to the bountiful earth in rapid succession.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.419#But Sarpedon, when he saw his free-girt companions going
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.420#down underneath the hands of Menoitios' son Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.421#called aloud in entreaty upon the godlike Lykians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.422#'Shame, you Lykians, where are you running to? You must be fierce now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.423#for I myself will encounter this man, so I may find out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.424#who this is who has so much strength and has done so much evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.425#to the Trojans, since many and brave are those whose knees he has unstrung.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.426#He spoke, and sprang to the ground in all his arms from the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.427#and on the other side Patroklos when he saw him leapt down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.428#from his chariot. They as two hook-clawed beak-bent vultures
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.429#above a tall rock face, high-screaming, go for each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.430#so now these two, crying aloud, encountered together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.431#And watching them the son of devious-devising Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.432#was pitiful, and spoke to Hera, his wife and his sister:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.433#'Ah me, that it is destined that the dearest of men, Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.434#must go down under the hands of Menoitios' son Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.435#The heart in my breast is balanced between two ways as I ponder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.436#whether I should snatch him out of the sorrowful battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.437#and set him down still alive in the rich country of Lykia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.438#or beat him under at the hands of the son of Menoitios.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.439#In turn the lady Hera of the ox eyes answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.440#'Majesty, son of Kronos, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.441#Do you wish to bring back a man who is mortal, one long since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.442#doomed by his destiny, from ill-sounding death and release him?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.443#Do it, then; but not all the rest of us gods shall approve you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.444#And put away in your thoughts this other thing I tell you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.445#if you bring Sarpedon back to his home, still living,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.446#think how then some other one of the gods might also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.447#wish to carry his own son out of the strong encounter;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.448#since around the great city of Priam are fighting many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.449#sons of the immortals. You will waken grim resentment among them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.450#No, but if he is dear to you, and your heart mourns for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.451#then let him be, and let him go down in the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.452#underneath the hands of Patroklos, the son of Menoitios;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.453#but after the soul and the years of his life have left him, then send
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.454#Death to carry him away, and Sleep, who is painless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.455#until they come with him to the countryside of broad Lykia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.456#where his brothers and countrymen shall give him due burial
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.457#with tomb and gravestone. Such is the privilege of those who have perished.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.458#She spoke, nor did the father of gods and men disobey her;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.459#yet he wept tears of blood that fell to the ground, for the sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.460#of his beloved son, whom now Patroklos was presently
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.461#to kill, by generous Troy and far from the land of his fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.462#Now as these two advancing had come close to each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.463#there Patroklos threw first at glorious Thrasymelos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.464#who was the strong henchman of lord Sarpedon, and struck him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.465#in the depth of the lower belly, and unstrung his limbs' strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.466#Sarpedon with the second throw then missed with the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.467#spear, but the spear fixed in the right shoulder of Pedasos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.468#the horse, who screamed as he blew his life away, and went down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.469#in shrill noise into the dust, and the life spirit flittered from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.470#The other horses shied apart, the yoke creaked, the guide reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.471#were fouled together as the trace horse lay in the dust beside them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.472#but at this spear-famed Automedon saw what he must do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.473#and wrenching out the long-edged sword from beside his big thigh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.474#in a flashing stroke and without faltering cut loose the trace horse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.475#and the other horses were straightened out, and pulled in the guide reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.476#and the two heroes came together in the heart-perishing battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.477#Once again Sarpedon threw wide with a cast of his shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.478#spear, so that the pointed head overshot the left shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.479#of Patroklos; and now Patroklos made the second cast with the brazen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.480#spear, and the shaft escaping his hand was not flung vainly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.481#but struck where the beating heart is closed in the arch of the muscles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.482#He fell, as when an oak goes down or a white poplar,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.483#or like a towering pine tree which in the mountains the carpenters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.484#have hewn down with their whetted axes to make a ship-timber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.485#So he lay there felled in front of his horses and chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.486#roaring, and clawed with his hands at the bloody dust; or as
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.487#a blazing and haughty bull in a huddle of shambling cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.488#when a lion has come among the herd and destroys him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.489#dies bellowing under the hooked claws of the lion, so now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.490#before Patroklos the lord of the shield-armoured Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.491#died raging, and called aloud to his beloved companion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.492#'Dear Glaukos, you are a fighter among men. Now the need comes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.493#hardest upon you to be a spearman and a bold warrior.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.494#Now, if you are brave, let bitter warfare be dear to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.495#First you must go among all men who are lords of the Lykians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.496#everywhere, and stir them up to fight for Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.497#and then you yourself also must fight for me with the bronze spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.498#For I shall be a thing of shame and a reproach said of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.499#afterwards, all your days forever, if the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.500#strip my armour here where I fell by the ships assembled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.501#But hold strongly on and stir up all the rest of our people.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.502#He spoke, and as he spoke death's end closed over his nostrils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.503#and eyes, and Patroklos stepping heel braced to chest dragged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.504#the spear out of his body, and the midriff came away with it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.505#so that he drew out with the spearhead the life of Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.506#and the Myrmidons close by held in the hard-breathing horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.507#as they tried to bolt away, once free of their master's chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.508#But when he heard the voice a hard sorrow came upon Glaukos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.509#and the heart was stirred within him, and he could not defend Sarpedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.510#He took his arm in his hand and squeezed it, since the wound hurt him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.511#where Teukros had hit him with an arrow shot as he swept in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.512#on the high wall, and fended destruction from his companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.513#He spoke in prayer to him who strikes from afar, Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.514#'Hear me, my lord. You are somewhere in the rich Lykian countryside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.515#or here in Troy, and wherever you are you can listen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.516#to a man in pain, as now this pain has descended upon me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.517#For see, I have this strong wound on me, and my arm on both sides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.518#is driven with sharp pains about, my blood is not able
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.519#to dry and stop running, my shoulder is aching beneath it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.520#I cannot hold my spear up steady, I cannot go forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.521#to fight against the enemy. And the best of men has perished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.522#Sarpedon, son of Zeus; who will not stand by his children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.523#No, but you at least, my lord, make well this strong wound;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.524#and put the pains to sleep, give me strength, so that I may call out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.525#to my companions, the Lykians, and stir them to fight on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.526#and I myself do battle over the fallen body.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.527#So he spoke in prayer, and Phoibos Apollo heard him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.528#At once he made the pains stop, and dried away from the hard wound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.529#the dark running of blood, and put strength into his spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.530#And Glaukos knew in his heart what was done, and was happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.531#that the great god had listened to his prayer. And first of all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.532#he roused toward battle all the men who were lords of the Lykians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.533#going everywhere among them, to fight for Sarpedon;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.534#afterwards he ranged in long strides among the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.535#by Poulydamas the son of Panthoös and brilliant Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.536#and went to Aineias and to Hektor of the brazen helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.537#and stood near them and addressed them in winged words: 'Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.538#now you have utterly forgotten your armed companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.539#who for your sake, far from their friends and the land of their fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.540#are wearing their lives away, and you will do nothing to help them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.541#Sarpedon has fallen, the lord of the shield-armoured Lykians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.542#who defended Lykia in his strength and the right of his justice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.543#Now brazen Ares has struck him down by the spear of Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.544#Then, friends, stand beside me, let the thought be shame in your spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.545#that they might strip away his arms, and dishonour his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.546#these Myrmidons, in anger for all the Danaans perished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.547#those whom we Lykians have killed with the spear by the swift ships.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.548#He spoke, and the Trojans were taken head to heel with a sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.549#untakeable, not to be endured, since he was their city's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.550#stay, always, though he was an outlander, and many people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.551#came with him, but he was the best of them all in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.552#always. They went straight for the Danaans, raging, and Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.553#led them, in anger for Sarpedon. Meanwhile the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.554#roused to the savage heart of Patroklos, the son of Menoitios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.555#First he spoke to the Aiantes, who were burning for battle already:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.556#'Aiantes, now your desire must be to defend yourselves, and be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.557#such as you were among men before, or even more valiant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.558#The man is fallen who first scaled the wall of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.559#Sarpedon. If only we could win and dishonour his body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.560#and strip the armour from his shoulders, and kill with the pitiless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.561#bronze some one of his companions who fight to defend him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.562#He spoke, and they likewise grew furious in their defence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.563#and when they on either side had made massive their battalions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.564#Trojans and Lykians, and Myrmidons and Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.565#they clashed together in battle over the perished body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.566#howling terribly, with a high crash of the men in their armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.567#while Zeus swept ghastly night far over the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.568#that over his dear son might be deadly work in the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.569#First the Trojans shouldered back the glancing-eyed Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.570#when a man, and not the worst of the Myrmidons, was struck down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.571#son of high-hearted Agakles, Epeigeus the brilliant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.572#He was one who was lord before in strong-founded Boudeion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.573#but now, since he had happened to kill his high-born cousin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.574#had come suppliant to Peleus and to Thetis the silver-footed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.575#and these sent him to follow Achilleus, who broke men in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.576#to Ilion of the horses and the battle against the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.577#As he caught at a dead man glorious Hektor hit him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.578#with a stone in the head, and all the head broke into two pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.579#inside the heavy helmet, and he in the dust face downward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.580#dropped, while death breaking the spirit drifted about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.581#And the sorrow took hold of Patroklos for his fallen companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.582#He steered his way through the ranks of the front fighters, like a flying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.583#hawk who scatters into flight the daws and the starlings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.584#So straight for the Lykians, o lord of horses, Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.585#you swept, and for the Trojans, heart angered for your companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.586#Now he struck Sthenelaos, beloved son of Ithaimenes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.587#in the neck with a stone, and broke the tendons loose from about it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.588#The champions of Troy gave back then, and glorious Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.589#As far as goes the driving cast of a slender javelin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.590#which a man throws making trial of his strength, either in a contest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.591#or else in battle, under the heart-breaking hostilities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.592#so far the Trojans gave way with the Achaians pushing them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.593#But Glaukos was first, lord of the shield-armoured Lykians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.594#to turn again, and killed Bathykles the great-hearted, beloved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.595#son of Chalkon, who had dwelled in his home in Hellas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.596#conspicuous for wealth and success among all the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.597#It was he whom Glaukos stabbed in the middle of the chest, turning
