urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.606#Meriones struck him by jaw and ear, and at once the life spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.607#fled from his limbs, and the hateful darkness closed in about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.608#But Aineias threw his bronze spear at Meriones, hoping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.609#to hit him as he came forward under his shield's covering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.610#but Meriones with his eyes straight on him avoided the bronze spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.611#For he bent forward, and behind his back the long spearshaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.612#was driven into the ground so that the butt end was shaken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.613#on the spear. Then and there Ares the huge took the force from it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.614#[so that the vibrant shaft of Aineias was driven groundward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.615#since it had been thrown in a vain cast from his big hand].
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.616#But Aineias was angered in his spirit, and called out to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.617#'Meriones, though you are a dancer my spear might have stopped you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.618#now and for all time, if only I could have hit you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.619#Then in turn Meriones the spear-famed answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.620#'Aineias, strong fighter though you are, it would be hard for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.621#to quench the strength of every man who might come against you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.622#and defend himself, since you also are made as a mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.623#But if I could throw and hit you with the sharp bronze in the middle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.624#then strong as you are and confident in your hands' work, you might
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.625#give the glory to me, and your soul to Hades of the horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.626#He spoke, but the fighting son of Menoitios reprimanded him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.627#'Meriones, when you are a brave fighter, why say such things?--
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.628#See, dear friend, the Trojans will not give back from the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.629#for hard words spoken. Sooner the ground will cover them. Warfare's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.630#finality lies in the work of hands, that of words in counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.631#It is not for us now to pile up talk, but to fight in battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.632#He spoke, and led the way, and the other followed, a mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.633#like a god. As the tumult goes up from men who are cutting
