urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.793#Apollo now struck away from his head the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.794#four-horned and hollow-eyed, and under the feet of the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.795#it rolled clattering, and the plumes above it were defiled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.796#by blood and dust. Before this time it had not been permitted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.797#to defile in the dust this great helmet crested in horse-hair;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.798#rather it guarded the head and the gracious brow of a godlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.799#man, Achilleus; but now Zeus gave it over to Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.800#to wear on his head, Hektor whose own death was close to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.801#And in his hands was splintered all the huge, great, heavy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.802#iron-shod, far-shadowing spear, and away from his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.803#dropped to the ground the shield with its shield sling and its tassels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.804#The lord Apollo, son of Zeus, broke the corselet upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.805#Disaster caught his wits, and his shining body went nerveless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.806#He stood stupidly, and from close behind his back a Dardanian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.807#man hit him between the shoulders with a sharp javelin:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.808#Euphorbos, son of Panthoös, who surpassed all men of his own age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.809#with the throwing spear, and in horsemanship and the speed of his feet. He
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.810#had already brought down twenty men from their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.811#since first coming, with his chariot and his learning in warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.812#He first hit you with a thrown spear, o rider Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.813#nor broke you, but ran away again, snatching out the ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.814#from your body, and lost himself in the crowd, not enduring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.815#to face Patroklos, naked as he was, in close combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.816#Now Patroklos, broken by the spear and the god's blow, tried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.817#to shun death and shrink back into the swarm of his own companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.818#But Hektor, when he saw high-hearted Patroklos trying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.819#to get away, saw how he was wounded with the sharp javelin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.820#came close against him across the ranks, and with the spear stabbed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.821#in the depth of the belly and drove the bronze clean through. He fell,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.822#thunderously, to the horror of all the Achaian people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.823#As a lion overpowers a weariless boar in wild combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.824#as the two fight in their pride on the high places of a mountain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.825#over a little spring of water, both wanting to drink there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.826#and the lion beats him down by force as he fights for his breath, so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.827#Hektor, Priam's son, with a close spear-stroke stripped the life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.828#from the fighting son of Menoitios, who had killed so many,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.829#and stood above him, and spoke aloud the winged words of triumph:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.830#'Patroklos, you thought perhaps of devastating our city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.831#of stripping from the Trojan women the day of their liberty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.832#and dragging them off in ships to the beloved land of your fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.833#Fool! When in front of them the running horses of Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.834#strained with their swift feet into the fighting, and I with my own spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.835#am conspicuous among the fighting Trojans, I who beat from them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.836#the day of necessity. For you, here the vultures shall eat you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.837#Wretch! Achilleus, great as he was, could do nothing to help you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.838#When he stayed behind, and you went, he must have said much to you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.839#"Patroklos, lord of horses, see that you do not come back to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.840#and the hollow ships, until you have torn in blood the tunic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.841#of manslaughtering Hektor about his chest." In some such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.842#manner he spoke to you, and persuaded the fool's heart in you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.843#And now, dying, you answered him, o rider Patroklos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.844#'Now is your time for big words, Hektor. Yours is the victory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.845#given by Kronos' son, Zeus, and Apollo, who have subdued me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.846#easily, since they themselves stripped the arms from my shoulders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.847#Even though twenty such as you had come in against me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.848#they would all have been broken beneath my spear, and have perished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.849#No, deadly destiny, with the son of Leto, has killed me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.850#and of men it was Euphorbos; you are only my third slayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.851#And put away in your heart this other thing that I tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.852#You yourself are not one who shall live long, but now already
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.853#death and powerful destiny are standing beside you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.854#to go down under the hands of Aiakos' great son, Achilleus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.855#He spoke, and as he spoke the end of death closed in upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.856#and the soul fluttering free of his limbs went down into Death's house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.857#mourning her destiny, leaving youth and manhood behind her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.858#Now though he was a dead man glorious Hektor spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.859#'Patroklos, what is this prophecy of my headlong destruction?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.860#Who knows if even Achilleus, son of lovely-haired Thetis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.861#might before this be struck by my spear, and his own life perish?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.862#He spoke, and setting his heel upon him wrenched out the bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.863#from the wound, then spurned him away on his back from the spear. Thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.864#armed with the spear he went on, aiming a cast at Automedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.865#the godlike henchman for the swift-footed son of Aiakos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.866#with the spear as he was carried away by those swift and immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:16.867#horses the gods had given as shining gifts to Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.1#As Patroklos went down before the Trojans in the hard fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.2#he was not unseen by Atreus' son, warlike Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.3#who stalked through the ranks of the champions, helmed in the bright bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.4#and bestrode the body, as over a first-born calf the mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.5#cow stands lowing, she who has known no children before this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.6#So Menelaos of the fair hair stood over Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.7#and held the spear and the perfect circle of his shield before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.8#raging to cut down any man who might come forth against him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.9#Nor did the fall of blameless Patroklos pass unattended
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.10#by Panthoös' son of the strong ash spear, Euphorbos, who standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.11#close to face him spoke a word to warlike Menelaos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.12#'Son of Atreus, Menelaos, illustrious, leader of armies:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.13#give way, let the bloody spoils be, get back from this body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.14#since before me no one of the Trojans, or renowned companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.15#struck Patroklos down with the spear in the strong encounter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.16#Thereby let me win this great glory among the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.17#before I hit you and strip the sweetness of life away from you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.18#Deeply stirred, Menelaos of the fair hair answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.19#'Father Zeus, it is not well for the proud man to glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.20#Neither the fury of the leopard is such, not such is the lion's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.21#nor the fury of the devastating wild boar, within whose breast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.22#the spirit is biggest and vaunts in the pride of his strength, is so great
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.23#as goes the pride in these sons of Panthoös of the strong ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.24#Yet even the strength of Hyperenor, breaker of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.25#had no joy of his youth when he stood against me and taunted me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.26#and said that among all the Danaans I was the weakest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.27#in battle. Yet I think that his feet shall no more carry him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.28#back, to pleasure his beloved wife and his honoured parents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.29#So I think I can break your strength as well, if you only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.30#stand against me. No, but I myself tell you to get back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.31#into the multitude, not stand to face me, before you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.32#take some harm. Once a thing has been done, the fool sees it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.33#He spoke so, but did not persuade Euphorbos, who answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.34#'Then, lordly Menelaos, you must now pay the penalty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.35#for my brother, whom you killed, and boast that you did it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.36#and made his wife a widow in the depth of a young bride chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.37#and left to his parents the curse of lamentation and sorrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.38#Yet I might stop the mourning of these unhappy people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.39#if I could carry back to them your head, and your armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.40#and toss them into Panthoös' hands, and to Phrontis the lovely.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.41#No, this struggle shall not go long untested between us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.42#nor yet unfought, whether it prove our strength or our terror.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.43#He spoke, and stabbed Menelaos' shield in its perfect circle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.44#nor did the bronze break its way through, but the spearhead bent back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.45#in the strong shield. And after him Atreus' son, Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.46#made his prayer to father Zeus and lunged with the bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.47#and as he was drawing back caught him in the pit of the gullet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.48#and leaned in on the stroke in the confidence of his strong hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.49#and clean through the soft part of the neck the spearpoint was driven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.50#He fell, thunderously, and his armour clattered upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.51#and his hair, lovely as the Graces, was splattered with blood, those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.52#braided locks caught waspwise in gold and silver. As some
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.53#slip of an olive tree strong-growing that a man raises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.54#in a lonely place, and drenched it with generous water, so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.55#it blossoms into beauty, and the blasts of winds from all quarters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.56#tremble it, and it bursts into pale blossoming. But then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.57#a wind suddenly in a great tempest descending upon it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.58#wrenches it out of its stand and lays it at length on the ground; such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.59#was Euphorbos of the strong ash spear, the son of Panthoös,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.60#whom Menelaos Atreides killed, and was stripping his armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.61#As when in the confidence of his strength some lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.62#hill-reared snatches the finest cow in a herd as it pastures;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.63#first the lion breaks her neck caught fast in the strong teeth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.64#then gulps down the blood and all the guts that are inward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.65#savagely, as the dogs and the herdsmen raise a commotion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.66#loudly about him, but from a distance, and are not willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.67#to go in and face him, since the hard green fear has hold of them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.68#so no heart in the breast of any Trojan had courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.69#to go in and face glorious Menelaos. Then easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.70#the son of Atreus might have taken the glorious armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.71#from Panthoös' son, only Phoibos Apollo begrudged him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.72#and stirred up Hektor, a match for the running war god, against him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.73#in semblance of a man, the leader of the Kikones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.74#Mentes, and spoke aloud to him, and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.75#'While you, Hektor, run after what can never be captured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.76#the horses of valiant Aiakides; they are difficult horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.77#for mortal man to manage, or even to ride behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.78#for all except Achilleus, who was born of an immortal mother;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.79#meanwhile Menelaos, the warlike son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.80#stands over Patroklos and has killed the best man of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.81#Euphorbos, Panthoös' son, and stopped his furious valour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.82#So he spoke, and went back, a god, to the mortals' struggle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.83#But bitter sorrow closed over Hektor's heart in its darkness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.84#He looked about then across the ranks, and at once was aware
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.85#of the two men, one stripping the glorious armour, the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.86#sprawled on the ground, and blood running from the gash of the spear-thrust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.87#He stalked through the ranks of the champions helmed in the bright bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.88#with a shrill scream, and looking like the flame of Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.89#weariless. Nor did Atreus' son fail to hear the sharp cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.90#Deeply troubled, he spoke to his own great-hearted spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.91#'Ah me; if I abandon here the magnificent armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.92#and Patroklos, who has fallen here for the sake of my honour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.93#shall not some one of the Danaans, seeing it, hold it against me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.94#Yet if I fight, alone as I am, the Trojans and Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.95#for shame, shall they not close in, many against one, about me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.96#Hektor of the shining helm leads all of the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.97#here. Then why does my own heart within me debate this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.98#When a man, in the face of divinity, would fight with another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.99#whom some god honours, the big disaster rolls sudden upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.100#Therefore, let no Danaan seeing it hold it against me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.101#if I give way before Hektor, who fights from God. Yet if somewhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.102#I could only get some word of Aias of the great war cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.103#we two might somehow go, and keep our spirit of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.104#even in the face of divinity, if we might win the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.105#for Peleïd Achilleus. It would be our best among evils.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.106#Now as he was pondering this in his heart and his spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.107#meanwhile the ranks of the Trojans came on, and Hektor led them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.108#and Menelaos backed away from them and left the dead man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.109#but kept turning on his way like some great bearded lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.110#when dogs and men drive him off from a steading with weapons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.111#and shouts, and in the breast of the lion the strong heart of valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.112#freezes, and he goes reluctant away from the fenced ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.113#So fair-haired Menelaos moved from Patroklos, but turning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.114#stood fast when he had got back to the swarm of his own companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.115#and looked all about for huge Aias, the son of Telamon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.116#and saw soon where he was, at the left of the entire battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.117#encouraging his companions and urging them into the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.118#since Phoibos Apollo had smitten them all with unearthly terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.119#He went on the run, and presently stood beside him and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.120#'This way, Aias, we must make for fallen Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.121#to try if we can carry back to Achilleus the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.122#which is naked; Hektor of the shining helm has taken his armour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.123#So he spoke, and stirred the spirit in valiant Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.124#who strode among the champions, fair-haired Menelaos with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.125#But Hektor, when he had stripped from Patroklos the glorious armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.126#dragged at him, meaning to cut his head from his shoulders with the sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.127#to haul off the body and give it to the dogs of Troy; but meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.128#Aias came near him, carrying like a wall his shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.129#and Hektor drew back to the company of his own companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.130#and sprang to his chariot, but handed over the beautiful armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.131#to the Trojans, to take back to the city and to be his great glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.132#Now Aias covering the son of Menoitios under his broad shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.133#stood fast, like a lion over his young, when the lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.134#is leading his little ones along, and men who are hunting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.135#come upon them in the forest. He stands in the pride of his great strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.136#hooding his eyes under the cover of down-drawn eyelids.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.137#Such was Aias as he bestrode the hero Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.138#while on the other side Atreus' son, warlike Menelaos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.139#stood fast, feeding still bigger the great sorrow within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.140#But Glaukos, lord of the Lykian men, the son of Hippolochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.141#looked at Hektor, scowling, and laid a harsh word upon him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.142#'Hektor, splendid to look at, you come far short in your fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.143#That fame of yours, high as it is, belongs to a runner.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.144#Take thought now how to hold fast your town, your citadel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.145#by yourself, with those your people who were born in Ilion;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.146#since no Lykian will go forth now to fight with the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.147#for the sake of your city, since after all we got no gratitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.148#for our everlasting hard struggle against your enemies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.149#How then, o hard-hearted, shall you save a worse man in all your
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.150#company, when you have abandoned Sarpedon, your guest-friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.151#and own companion, to be the spoil and prey of the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.152#who was of so much use to you, yourself and your city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.153#while he lived? Now you have not the spirit to keep the dogs from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.154#Therefore now, if any of the Lykian men will obey me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.155#we are going home, and the headlong destruction of Troy shall be manifest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.156#For if the Trojans had any fighting strength that were daring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.157#and unshaken, such as comes on men who, for the sake of their country,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.158#have made the hard hateful work come between them and their enemies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.159#we could quickly get the body of Patroklos inside Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.160#If, dead man though he be, he could be brought into the great city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.161#of lord Priam, if we could tear him out of the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.162#the Argives must at once give up the beautiful armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.163#of Sarpedon, and we could carry his body inside Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.164#Such is the man whose henchman is killed. He is far the greatest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.165#of the Argives by the ships, and his men fight hard at close quarters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.166#No, but you could not bring yourself to stand up against Aias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.167#of the great heart, nor to look at his eyes in the clamour of fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.168#men, nor attack him direct, since he is far better than you are.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.169#Looking darkly at him tall Hektor of the shining helm answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.170#'Glaukos, why did a man like you speak this word of annoyance?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.171#I am surprised. I thought that for wits you surpassed all others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.172#of those who dwell in Lykia where the soil is generous; and yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.173#now I utterly despise your heart for the thing you have spoken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.174#when you said I cannot stand in the face of gigantic Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.175#I am not one who shudders at attack and the thunder of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.176#But always the mind of Zeus is a stronger thing than a man's mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.177#He terrifies even the warlike man, he takes away victory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.178#lightly, when he himself has driven a man into battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.179#Come here, friend, and watch me at work; learn, standing beside me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.180#whether I shall be a coward all day, as you proclaim me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.181#or whether I stop some Danaan, for all of his fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.182#from his fighting strength and from the defence of fallen Patroklos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.183#So speaking he called afar in a great voice to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.184#'Trojans, Lykians, Dardanians who fight at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.185#be men now, dear friends, remember your furious valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.186#while I am putting on the beautiful armour of blameless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.187#Achilleus, which I stripped from Patroklos the strong when I killed him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.188#So spoke Hektor of the shining helm, and departed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.189#from the hateful battle, and running caught up with his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.190#very soon, since he went on quick feet, and they had not gone far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.191#carrying the glorious armour of Peleus' son toward the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.192#He stood apart from the sorrowful fighting, and changed his armour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.193#and gave what he had worn to the fighting Trojans to carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.194#to sacred Ilion, and himself put on that armour immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.195#of Peleïd Achilleus, which the Uranian gods had given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.196#to his loved father; and he in turn grown old had given it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.197#to his son; but a son who never grew old in his father's armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.198#When Zeus who gathers the clouds saw him, apart from the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.199#arming himself in the battle gear of godlike Peleïdes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.200#he stirred his head and spoke to his own spirit: 'Ah, poor wretch!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.201#There is no thought of death in your mind now, and yet death stands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.202#close beside you as you put on the immortal armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.203#of a surpassing man. There are others who tremble before him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.204#Now you have killed this man's dear friend, who was strong and gentle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.205#and taken the armour, as you should not have done, from his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.206#and head. Still for the present I will invest you with great strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.207#to make up for it that you will not come home out of the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.208#nor Andromache take from your hands the glorious arms of Achilleus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.209#He spoke, the son of Kronos, and nodded his head with the dark brows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.210#The armour was fitted to Hektor's skin, and Ares the dangerous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.211#war god entered him, so that the inward body was packed full
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.212#of force and fighting strength. He went onward calling in a great voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.213#to his renowned companions in arms, and figured before them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.214#flaming in the battle gear of great-hearted Peleion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.215#He ranged their ranks, and spoke a word to encourage each captain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.216#to Mesthles and Glaukos, to Thersilochos and Medon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.217#Deisenor and Hippothoös and Asteropaios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.218#to Phorkys and Chromios and the bird interpreter Ennomos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.219#and stirring all of these forward called to them in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.220#'Hear me, you numberless hordes of companions who live at our borders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.221#It was not for any desire nor need of a multitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.222#that man by man I gathered you to come here from your cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.223#but so that you might have good will to defend the innocent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.224#children of the Trojans, and their wives, from the fighting Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.225#With such a purpose I wear out my own people for presents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.226#and food, wherewith I make strong the spirit within each one of you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.227#Therefore a man must now turn his face straight forward, and perish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.228#or survive. This is the sweet invitation of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.229#That man of you who drags Patroklos, dead as he is, back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.230#among Trojans, breakers of horses, and Aias gives way before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.231#I will give him half the spoils for his portion, and keep half
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.232#for myself, and his glory shall be as great as mine is.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.233#So he spoke, and they lifted their spears and went straight for the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.234#who felt their weight, and inside each man the spirit was hopeful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.235#to get the body away from Telamonian Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.236#Fools! Since over the dead man he tore the life out of many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.237#Then Aias himself spoke to Menelaos of the great war cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.238#'Illustrious Menelaos, dear friend, I no longer have hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.239#that even you and I can win back out of the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.240#My fear is not so much for the dead body of Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.241#who presently must glut the dogs and the birds of Troy, so much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.242#as I fear for my own head, my life, and what may befall it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.243#and for yours, since this cloud of war is darkened on all things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.244#this Hektor, while for you and me sheer death is emerging.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.245#Come then, call the great men of the Danaans, if one might hear you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.246#He spoke, and Menelaos of the great war cry obeyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.247#He lifted his voice and called in a piercing cry to the Danaans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.248#'Friends, o leaders and men of counsel among the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.249#you that beside Agamemnon and Menelaos, the two sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.250#of Atreus, drink the community's wine and give, each man, his orders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.251#to the people; and from Zeus the respect and honour attend you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.252#It is hard for me to discriminate among you each man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.253#who is a leader, so big is the bitter fight that has blazed up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.254#Then let a man come of his own accord, think it shameful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.255#that Patroklos be given to the dogs of Troy to delight them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.256#He spoke, and swift Aias son of Oïleus was sharp to hear him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.257#and was first to come running along the battle, and join him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.258#and after him Idomeneus, and Idomeneus' companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.259#Meriones, a match for the murderous lord of battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.260#But what man could tell forth from his heart the names of the others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.261#all who after these waked the war strength of the Achaians?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.262#The Trojans came down on them in a pack, and Hektor led them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.263#As when at the outpouring place of a rain-glutted river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.264#the huge surf of the sea roars against the current, out-jutting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.265#beaches thunder aloud to the backwash of the salt water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.266#with such a bellow the Trojans came on, but now the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.267#stood fast about the son of Menoitios, in a single courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.268#and fenced beneath their bronze-armoured shields, while the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.269#drifted across the glitter of their helmets a deepening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.270#mist; since before this time he had not hated Menoitios'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.271#son, while he lived yet and was Achilleus' companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.272#and loathed now that he should become the spoil of the hated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.273#Trojans' dogs, and stirred his companions on to defend him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.274#First the Trojans shouldered back the glancing-eyed Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.275#who abandoned the body and ran for terror, nor did the high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.276#Trojans take any with their spears, for all of their striving,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.277#but dragged at the dead man, only the Achaians were not long destined
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.278#to fail him, since they were pulled around in sudden speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.279#by Aias, who for his beauty and the work of his hands surpassed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.280#all other Danaans, after the blameless son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.281#He steered through the front fighters in pride of strength like a savage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.282#wild boar, who among the mountains easily scatters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.283#the dogs and strong young men when he turns at bay in the valley.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.284#So now the son of haughty Telamon, glorious Aias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.285#turned to charge and easily scatter the Trojan battalions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.286#who had taken their stand bestriding Patroklos, in high hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.287#of dragging him off to their own city, and so winning honour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.288#Indeed, Hippothoös, glorious son of Pelasgian Lethos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.289#was trying to drag him by the foot through the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.290#by fastening the sling of his shield round the ankle tendons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.291#for the favour of Hektor and the Trojans, but the sudden evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.292#came to him, and none for all their desire could defend him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.293#The son of Telamon, sweeping in through the mass of the fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.294#struck him at close quarters through the brazen cheeks of his helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.295#and the helm crested with horse-hair was riven about the spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.296#to the impact of the huge spear and the weight of the hand behind it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.297#and the brain ran from the wound along the spear by the eye-hole,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.298#bleeding. There his strength was washed away, and from his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.299#he let fall to the ground the foot of great-hearted Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.300#to lie there, and himself collapsed prone over the dead man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.301#far away from generous Larisa, and he could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.302#render again the care of his dear parents; he was short-lived,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.303#beaten down beneath the spear of high-hearted Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.304#Again Hektor threw at Aias with the shining javelin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.305#but Aias with his eyes straight on him avoided the bronze spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.306#by a little, and Hektor struck Schedios, the son of high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.307#Iphitos and far the best of the Phokians, one who lived
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.308#in his home in famous Panopeus and was lord over many people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.309#He struck him fair beneath the collar-bone, and the pointed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.310#bronze head tore clean through and came out by the base of the shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.311#He fell, thunderously, and his armour clattered upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.312#But Aias in turn cut at Phorkys, the wise son of Phainops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.313#in the middle of the belly as he stood over fallen Hippothoös,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.314#and broke the hollow of the corselet, so that the entrails spurted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.315#from the bronze, and he went down clawing the dust in his fingers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.316#The champions of Troy gave back then, and glorious Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.317#and the Argives gave a great cry and dragged back the bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.318#of Hippothoös and Phorkys, and eased the armour from their shoulders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.319#Then, once more, might the Trojans have climbed back into Ilion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.320#wall, subdued by terror before the warlike Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.321#and the Argives, even beyond Zeus' destiny, might have won glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.322#by their own force and strength, had not Apollo in person
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.323#stirred on Aineias; he had assumed the form of the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.324#Periphas, Epytos' son, growing old in his herald's office
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.325#by Aineias' aged father, and a man whose thoughts were of kindness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.326#In the likeness of this man Zeus' son Apollo spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.327#'Aineias, how could you be the men to defend sheer Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.328#even against a god's will, as I have seen other men do it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.329#in the confidence of their own force and strength, their own manhood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.330#and their own numbers, though they had too few people for it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.331#But now Zeus wishes the victory far rather for our side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.332#than the Danaans', only yourselves keep blenching and will not fight them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.333#So he spoke, but Aineias knew far-striking Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.334#as he looked him straight in the face, and called in a great voice to Hektor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.335#'Hektor, and you other lords of the Trojans and their companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.336#here is a shameful thing! We are climbing back into Ilion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.337#wall, subdued by terror before the warlike Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.338#Yet see, some one of the gods is standing beside me, and tells me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.339#that Zeus the supreme counsellor lends his weight to our fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.340#Therefore we must go straight for the Danaans, so that they may not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.341#carry thus easily back to their ships the fallen Patroklos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.342#He spoke, and with a long leap stood far before the front fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.343#and the Trojans turned and held their ground against the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.344#And now Aineias killed Leiokritos, with a spear-thrust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.345#the son of Arisbas and noble companion of Lykomedes;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.346#but as he fell the warrior Lykomedes pitied him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.347#and stood close in, and made a cast with the shining javelin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.348#and struck Apisaon, son of Hippasos, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.349#in the liver under the midriff, and the strength of his knees was broken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.350#He was one who had come from Paionia of the rich soil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.351#and was best of her men in fighting next to Asteropaios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.352#As this man fell, warlike Asteropaios pitied him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.353#and he in turn drove forward eager to fight with the Danaans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.354#but was not able to do it, for they, standing about Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.355#fenced him behind their shields on all sides, and held their spears out-thrust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.356#For Aias ranged their whole extent with his numerous orders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.357#and would not let any man give back from the body, nor let one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.358#go out and fight by himself far in front of the other Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.359#but made them stand hard and fast about him and fight at close quarters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.360#Such were the orders of gigantic Aias. The ground ran
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.361#with red blood, the dead men dropped one after another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.362#from the ranks alike of Trojans and their mighty companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.363#and Danaans also, since these fought not without bloodletting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.364#but far fewer of them went down, since they ever remembered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.365#always to stand massed and beat sudden death from each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.366#So they fought on in the likeness of fire, nor would you have thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.367#the sun was still secure in his place in the sky, nor the moon, since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.368#the mist was closed over all that part of the fight where the bravest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.369#stood about Patroklos, the fallen son of Menoitios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.370#Now elsewhere the rest of the Trojans and strong-greaved Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.371#fought naturally in the bright air, with the sun's sharp glitter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.372#everywhere about them, no cloud was showing anywhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.373#on earth nor on the mountains. They fought their battle by intervals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.374#standing each well off at a distance, avoiding the painful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.375#shots from the other side; but they in the middle were suffering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.376#distress in the mist and the fighting, with the cruel bronze wearing them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.377#These men were the bravest, but there were two men of glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.378#Thrasymedes and Antilochos, who had not yet heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.379#how Patroklos the blameless had been killed, but still thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.380#he was alive and fighting in the first shock with the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.381#But these two, watching against death or flight in their company,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.382#fought their separate battle, since such was their order from Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.383#as he was urging them forth from the black ships into the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.384#So for these daylong the hard bitterness of the wearing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.385#battle rose. With the ever-relentless sweat and the weariness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.386#knees, legs, and feet that supported from underneath each fighter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.387#their hands and eyes also were running wet as they fought on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.388#over the brave henchman of swift-footed Aiakides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.389#As when a man gives the hide of a great ox, a bullock,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.390#drenched first deep in fat, to all his people to stretch out;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.391#the people take it from him and stand in a circle about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.392#and pull, and presently the moisture goes and the fat sinks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.393#in, with so many pulling, and the bull's hide is stretched out level;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.394#so the men of both sides in a cramped space tugged at the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.395#in both directions; and the hearts of the Trojans were hopeful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.396#to drag him away to Ilion, those of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.397#to get him back to the hollow ships. And about him a savage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.398#struggle arose. Not Ares who rallies men, not Athene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.399#watching this fight could have scorned it, not even in some strong anger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.400#such was the wicked work of battle for men and for horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.401#Zeus strained tight above Patroklos that day. But the brilliant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.402#Achilleus did not yet know at all that Patroklos had fallen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.403#Since now the men were fighting far away from the fast ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.404#under the Trojan wall, and Achilleus had no expectation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.405#that Patroklos was dead, but thought he was alive and close under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.406#the gates, and would come back. He had not thought that Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.407#would storm the city without himself, nor with himself either;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.408#for often he had word from his mother, not known to mortals;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.409#she was ever telling him what was the will of great Zeus; but this time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.410#his mother did not tell Achilleus of all the evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.411#that had been done, nor how his dearest companion had perished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.412#So they about the body gripping their headed spears kept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.413#inexorably close together, and slaughtered on both sides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.414#And such would be the saying of some bronze-armoured Achaian:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.415#'Friends, there is no glory for us if we go back again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.416#to our hollow ships, but here and now let the black earth open
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.417#gaping for all; this would soon be far better for us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.418#if we give up this man to the Trojans, breakers of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.419#to take away to their own city and win glory from him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.420#And such in turn would be the cry of some high-hearted Trojan:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.421#'O friends, though it be destined for all of us to be killed here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.422#over this man, still none of us must give ground from the fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.423#Thus a man would speak, and stir the spirit in each one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.424#of his fellowship. So they fought on, and the iron tumult
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.425#went up into the brazen sky through the barren bright air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.426#But the horses of Aiakides standing apart from the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.427#wept, as they had done since they heard how their charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.428#had fallen in the dust at the hands of murderous Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.429#In truth Automedon, the powerful son of Diores,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.430#hit them over and over again with the stroke of the flying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.431#lash, or talked to them, sometimes entreating them, sometimes threatening.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.432#They were unwilling to go back to the wide passage of Helle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.433#and the ships, or back into the fighting after the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.434#but still as stands a grave monument which is set over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.435#the mounded tomb of a dead man or lady, they stood there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.436#holding motionless in its place the fair-wrought chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.437#leaning their heads along the ground, and warm tears were running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.438#earthward from underneath the lids of the mourning horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.439#who longed for their charioteer, while their bright manes were made dirty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.440#as they streamed down either side of the yoke from under the yoke pad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.441#As he watched the mourning horses the son of Kronos pitied them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.442#and stirred his head and spoke to his own spirit: 'Poor wretches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.443#why then did we ever give you to the lord Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.444#a mortal man, and you yourselves are immortal and ageless?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.445#Only so that among unhappy men you also might be grieved?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.446#Since among all creatures that breathe on earth and crawl on it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.447#there is not anywhere a thing more dismal than man is.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.448#At least the son of Priam, Hektor, shall not mount behind you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.449#in the carefully wrought chariot. I will not let him. Is it not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.450#enough for him that he has the armour and glories in wearing it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.451#But now I will put vigour into your knees and your spirits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.452#so that you bring back Automedon out of the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.453#safe to the hollow ships; since I shall still give the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.454#the glory of killing, until they win to the strong-benched vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.455#until the sun goes down and the blessed darkness comes over.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.456#So spoke Zeus, and breathed great vigour into the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.457#and they shaking the dust from their manes to the ground lightly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.458#carried the running chariot among the Achaians and Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.459#Automedon fought from them, though grieving for his companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.460#He would dash in, like a vulture among geese, with his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.461#and lightly get away out of the Trojans' confusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.462#and lightly charge in again in pursuit of a great multitude,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.463#and yet could kill no men when he swept in in chase of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.464#He had no way while he was alone in a separate chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.465#to lunge with the spear and still keep in hand his fast-running horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.466#But at last there was one of his companions who laid eyes upon him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.467#Alkimedon, the son of Laerkes, descended from Haimon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.468#He stood behind the chariot and called to Automedon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.469#'Automedon, what god put this unprofitable purpose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.470#into your heart, and has taken away the better wits, so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.471#you are trying to fight the Trojans in the first shock of encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.472#by yourself, since your companion has been killed, and Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.473#glories in wearing Aiakides' armour on his own shoulders?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.474#In turn Automedon answered him, the son of Diores:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.475#'Alkimedon, which other of the Achaians could handle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.476#the management and the strength of immortal horses as you can,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.477#were it not Patroklos, the equal of the immortals in counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.478#while he lived? Now death and fate have closed in upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.479#Therefore take over from me the whip and the glittering guide reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.480#while I dismount from behind the horses, so I may do battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.481#He spoke, and Alkimedon vaulted up to the charging chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.482#and quickly gathered up the reins and the lash in his hands, while
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.483#Automedon sprang down. But glorious Hektor saw them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.484#and immediately spoke to Aineias, who stood close beside him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.485#'Aineias, lord of the counsels of the bronze-armoured Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.486#I see before us the horses of swift-footed Aiakides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.487#who appear now in the fighting with weak charioteers. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.488#I could be hopeful of their capture, if you were willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.489#in heart to go with me. If we two went forth against them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.490#they would not dare to stand their ground and do battle against us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.491#He spoke, and the strong son of Anchises did not disobey him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.492#The two went strongly forward, hooding their shoulders in well-tanned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.493#and stubborn hides of oxen with deep bronze beaten upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.494#Along with these went Chromios and godlike Aretos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.495#both together, and the spirit within each had high hopes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.496#of killing the men and driving away the strong-necked horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.497#poor fools, who were not going to come back from Automedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.498#without the shedding of blood; and he with a prayer to Zeus father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.499#was filled about the darkening heart with war-strength and courage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.500#and spoke now to Alkimedon his trusted companion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.501#'Alkimedon, no longer check the horses back from me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.502#but keep them breathing right against my back. I have no thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.503#that I can stand up to the strength of Hektor the son of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.504#Sooner, I think, he will kill us and mount behind the mane-floating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.505#horses of Achilleus, and scatter the ranks of the Argive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.506#fighting men; or else himself go down in the first rush.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.507#He spoke, and called to the two Aiantes and Menelaos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.508#'Aiantes, lords of the Argives, and Menelaos, we call you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.509#to leave the dead man in the care of those who are fittest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.510#to stand bestriding him and fend off the ranks of the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.511#while you beat back the day without pity from us who are living.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.512#For Hektor and Aineias, the greatest men of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.513#are leaning the weight of their charge this way through the sorrowful battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.514#Yet all these are things that are lying upon the gods' knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.515#I myself will cast; and Zeus will look after the issue.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.516#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far-shadowed, and threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.517#and struck the shield of Aretos on its perfect circle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.518#nor could the shield hold off the spear, but the bronze smashed clean through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.519#and was driven on through the belt to the deep of the belly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.520#As when a strong-grown man with sharp axe in his hands chops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.521#at an ox, ranger of the fields, behind the horns, cutting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.522#all the way through the sinew, and the ox springing forward topples,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.523#so Aretos sprang forward, then toppled back, and sharp-driven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.524#into the depth of his belly the quivering spear unstrung him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.525#Then Hektor made a cast with the shining spear at Automedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.526#but he, keeping his eyes straight on him, avoided the bronze spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.527#For he bent forward, and behind his back the long spearshaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.528#was driven into the ground so that the butt end was shaken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.529#on the spear. Then and there Ares the huge took the force from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.530#And now they would have gone for each other with swords at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.531#had not the two Aiantes driven strongly between them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.532#who came on through the battle at the call of their companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.533#and in fear before them Hektor and Aineias and godlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.534#Chromios gave ground back and away once more, leaving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.535#Aretos lying there where he was with a wound in his vitals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.536#Then Automedon, a match for the running god of battles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.537#stripped the armour, and spoke a word of boasting above him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.538#'Now I have put a little sorrow from my heart for Patroklos'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.539#death, although the man I killed was not great as he was.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.540#So he spoke, and took up the bloody war spoils and laid them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.541#inside the chariot, and himself mounted it, the blood running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.542#from hands and feet, as on some lion who has eaten a bullock.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.543#Once again over Patroklos was close drawn a strong battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.544#weary and sorrowful, and Athene from the sky descending
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.545#waked the bitter fighting, since Zeus of the wide brows sent her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.546#down to stir the Danaans, for now his purpose had shifted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.547#As when in the sky Zeus strings for mortals the shimmering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.548#rainbow, to be a portent and sign of war, or of wintry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.549#storm, when heat perishes, such storm as stops mortals'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.550#work upon the face of the earth, and afflicts their cattle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.551#so Athene shrouded in the shimmering cloud about her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.552#merged among the swarming Achaians, and wakened each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.553#And first she spoke, stirring him on, to the son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.554#strong Menelaos, since he was the one who was standing close to her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.555#She likened hereself in form and weariless voice to Phoinix:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.556#'Menelaos, this will be a thing of shame, a reproach said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.557#of you, if under the wall of the Trojans the dogs in their fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.558#can mutilate the staunch companion of haughty Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.559#But hold strongly on, and stir up all the rest of your people.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.560#Then in turn Menelaos of the great war cry answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.561#'Phoinix, my father, aged and honoured, if only Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.562#would give me such strength, and hold the volleying missiles off from me!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.563#So for my part I would be willing to stand by Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.564#and defend him, since in his death he hurt my heart greatly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.565#Yet Hektor holds still the awful strength of a fire, nor falters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.566#in raging with the bronze spear, since Zeus is giving him glory.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.567#So he spoke, and the goddess grey-eyed Athene was happy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.568#that first among all the divinities his prayer had bespoken her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.569#She put strength into the man's shoulders and knees, inspiring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.570#in his breast the persistent daring of that mosquito
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.571#who though it is driven hard away from a man's skin, even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.572#so, for the taste of human blood, persists in biting him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.573#With such daring she darkened to fullness the heart inside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.574#He stood over Patroklos, and made a cast with the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.575#spear. There was one among the Trojans, Podes, Eëtion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.576#son, a rich man and good, whom Hektor prized above others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.577#in the countryside, since he was his friend and ate at his table.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.578#Now fair-haired Menelaos struck this man, at the war belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.579#as he swept away in flight, and drove the bronze spear clean through it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.580#He fell, thunderously, and Atreus' son Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.581#dragged the body away from the Trojans among his companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.582#But now Apollo came and stood beside Hektor, and stirred him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.583#assuming the shape of Phainops, Asios' son, who among all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.584#guest friends was dearest to Hektor, and lived at home in Abydos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.585#In the likeness of this man far-striking Apollo spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.586#'Hektor, what other Achaian now shall be frightened before you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.587#See, you have shrunk before Menelaos, who in times before this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.588#was a soft spearfighter; and now he has gone taking off single-handed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.589#a body from among the Trojans. He has killed your trusted companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.590#valiant among the champions, Podes, the son of Eëtion.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.591#He spoke, and the dark cloud of sorrow closed over Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.592#He took his way among the champions helmed in the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.593#bronze. And now the son of Kronos caught up the betasselled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.594#glaring aegis, and shrouded Ida in mists. He let go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.595#a lightning flash and a loud thunderstroke, shaking the mountain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.596#gave victory to the Trojans, and terrified the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.597#First to begin the flight was Peneleos the Boiotian.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.598#For he, turning always toward the attack, was hit in the shoulder's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.599#end, a slight wound, but the spear of Poulydamas, who had thrown it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.600#from a stance very close to him, had grated the bone's edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.601#Then Hektor wounded in the hand by the wrist Leïtos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.602#the son of great-hearted Alektryon, and halted his warcraft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.603#and he drew back staring about him since his spirit had hope no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.604#of holding a spear steady in his hand to fight with the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.605#Now as Hektor made a rush for Leïtos, Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.606#struck him on the corselet over the chest by the nipple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.607#but the long shaft was broken behind the head, and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.608#shouted. Now Hektor made a cast at Deukalian Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.609#as he stood in his chariot, and missed him by only a little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.610#but struck the follower and charioteer of Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.611#Koiranos, who had come with him from strong-founded Lyktos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.612#Now Idomeneus at the first had come on foot, leaving the oarswept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.613#ships, and now would have given the Trojans a mighty triumph,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.614#had not Koiranos swiftly come up with the fast-running horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.615#came as light to the other and beat from him the day without pity,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.616#but himself lost his life at the hands of manslaughtering Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.617#who hit him under the jaw by the ear, and the spearshaft pushed out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.618#his teeth by the roots from the base, and split the tongue through the middle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.619#He toppled from the chariot, with the reins on the ground scattered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.620#but Meriones leaning down caught these up in his own hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.621#from the surface of the plain, and called aloud to Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.622#'Lash them now, until you can get back to our fast ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.623#You see yourself there is no more strength left in the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.624#So he spoke, and Idomeneus whipped the mane-floating horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.625#back to the hollow ships, with fear fallen upon his spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.626#Nor was it unseen by great-hearted Aias how Zeus shifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.627#the strength of the fighting toward the Trojans, nor by Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.628#First of the two to speak was huge Telamonian Aias:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.629#'Shame on it! By now even one with a child's innocence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.630#could see how father Zeus himself is helping the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.631#The weapons of each of these take hold, no matter who throws them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.632#good fighter or bad, since Zeus is straightening all of them equally,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.633#while ours fall to the ground and are utterly useless. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.634#let us deliberate with ourselves upon the best counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.635#how at the same time to rescue the dead body, and also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.636#win back ourselves, and bring joy to our beloved companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.637#who look our way and sorrow for us, and believe no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.638#that the fury of manslaughtering Hektor, his hands irresistible,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.639#can be held, but must be driven on to the black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.640#But there should be some companion who could carry the message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.641#quickly to Peleus' son, since I think he has not yet heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.642#the ghastly news, how his beloved companion has fallen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.643#Yet I cannot make out such a man among the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.644#since they are held in the mist alike, the men and their horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.645#Father Zeus, draw free from the mist the sons of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.646#make bright the air, and give sight back to our eyes; in shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.647#daylight destroy us, if to destroy us be now your pleasure.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.648#He spoke thus, and as he wept the father took pity upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.649#and forthwith scattered the mist and pushed the darkness back from them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.650#and the sun blazed out, and all the battle was plain before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.651#Now Aias spoke to him of the great war cry, Menelaos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.652#'Look hard, illustrious Menelaos, if you can discover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.653#Antilochos still living, the son of great-hearted Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.654#and send him out to run with a message to wise Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.655#how one who was far the dearest of his companions has fallen.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.656#He spoke, and Menelaos of the great war cry obeyed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.657#and went on his way, as from a mid-fenced ground some lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.658#who has been harrying dogs and men, but his strength is worn out;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.659#they will not let him tear out the fat of the oxen, watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.660#nightlong against him, and he in his hunger for meat closes in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.661#but can get nothing of what he wants, for the raining javelins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.662#thrown from the daring hands of the men beat ever against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.663#and the flaming torches, and these he balks at for all of his fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.664#and with the daylight goes away, disappointed of desire;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.665#so Menelaos of the great war cry went from Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.666#much unwilling, and was afraid for him, lest the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.667#under pressure of fear might leave him as spoil for the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.668#and had much to urge on Meriones and the Aiantes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.669#'Aiantes, o lords of the Argives, and you, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.670#now let each one of you remember unhappy Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.671#who was gentle, and understood how to be kindly toward all men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.672#while he lived. Now death and fate have closed in upon him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.673#So spoke fair-haired Menelaos, and went away from them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.674#peering about on all sides, like an eagle, who, as men say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.675#sees most sharply of all winged creatures under the heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.676#and lofty though he hover the cowering hare, the swift-footed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.677#escapes not his sight as he crouches in the shaggy bush, but the eagle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.678#plunges suddenly to grab him and tear the life from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.679#So now in you, Menelaos, illustrious, the eyes shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.680#circled everywhere your swarming hordes of companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.681#if the man might see anywhere Nestor's son, still living,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.682#and saw soon where he was, at the left of the entire battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.683#encouraging his companions and urging them into the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.684#Menelaos the fair-haired stood beside him and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.685#'Antilochos, turn this way, illustrious, and hear from me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.686#the ghastly message of a thing I wish never had happened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.687#You can see for yourself, I think, already, from watching,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.688#how the god is wheeling disaster against the Danaans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.689#and how the Trojans are winning. The best of the Achaians has fallen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.690#Patroklos, and a huge loss is inflicted upon the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.691#Run then quickly to Achilleus, by the ships of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.692#and tell him. He might in speed win back to his ship the dead body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.693#which is naked. Hektor of the shining helm has taken his armour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.694#So he spoke, and Antilochos hated his word as he listened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.695#He stayed for a long time without a word, speechless, and his eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.696#filled with tears, the springing voice was held still within him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.697#yet even so he neglected not Menelaos' order
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.698#but went on the run, handing his war gear to a blameless companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.699#Laodokos, who had turned nearby his single-foot horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.700#Now as his feet carried him, weeping, out of the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.701#with his message of evil for the son of Peleus, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.702#so now, Menelaos, the spirit in you, illustrious,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.703#wished not to defend his stricken companions, after Antilochos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.704#was gone from them, and his loss wrought greatly upon the Pylians;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.705#rather he sent Thrasymedes the brilliant over to help them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.706#while he himself went back again to the hero Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.707#running, and took his place beside the Aiantes, and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.708#'Now I have sent the man you spoke of back to the fast ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.709#on his way to swift-footed Achilleus, yet think not even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.710#he can come now, for all his great anger with Hektor the brilliant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.711#There is no way he could fight bare of armour against the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.712#We by ourselves must deliberate upon the best counsel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.713#how at the same time to rescue the dead body, and also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.714#ourselves escape death and destiny from the clamouring Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.715#Then in turn huge Telamonian Aias answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.716#'All you have said, renowned Menelaos, is fair and orderly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.717#But come: you and Meriones stoop and shoulder the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.718#at once, and carry it out of the hard fighting. Behind you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.719#we two shall fight off the Trojans and glorious Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.720#we, who have the same name, the same spirit, and who in times past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.721#have stood fast beside each other in the face of the bitter war god.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.722#He spoke, and they caught the body from the ground in their arms, lifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.723#him high with a great heave, and the Trojan people behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.724#shouted aloud as they saw the Achaians lifting the dead man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.725#and made a rush against them like dogs, who sweep in rapidly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.726#on a wounded wild boar, ahead of the young men who hunt him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.727#and for the moment race in raging to tear him to pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.728#until in the confidence of his strength he turns on them, at bay,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.729#and they give ground and scatter for fear one way and another;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.730#so the Trojans until that time kept always in close chase
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.731#assembled, stabbing at them with swords and leaf-headed spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.732#but every time the two Aiantes would swing round to face them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.733#and stand fast, the colour of their skin changed, and no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.734#could any endure to sweep in further and fight for the body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:17.735#So these, straining, carried the dead man out of the battle
