urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.178#Up, then, lie here no longer; let shame come into your heart, lest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.179#Patroklos become sport for the dogs of Troy to worry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.180#your shame, if the body goes from here with defilement upon it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.181#Then in turn Achilleus of the swift feet answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.182#'Divine Iris, what god sent you to me with a message?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.183#Then in turn swift wind-footed Iris spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.184#'Hera sent me, the honoured wife of Zeus; but the son of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.185#Kronos, who sits on high, does not know this, nor any other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.186#immortal, of all those who dwell by the snows of Olympos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.187#Then in answer to her spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.188#'How shall I go into the fighting? They have my armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.189#And my beloved mother told me I must not be armoured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.190#not before with my own eyes I see her come back to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.191#She promised she would bring magnificent arms from Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.192#Nor do I know of another whose glorious armour I could wear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.193#unless it were the great shield of Telamonian Aias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.194#But he himself wears it, I think, and goes in the foremost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.195#of the spear-fight over the body of fallen Patroklos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.196#Then in turn swift wind-footed Iris spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.197#'Yes, we also know well how they hold your glorious armour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.198#But go to the ditch, and show yourself as you are to the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.199#if perhaps the Trojans might be frightened, and give way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.200#from their attack, and the fighting sons of the Achaians get wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.201#again after hard work. There is little breathing space in the fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.202#So speaking Iris of the swift feet went away from him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.203#but Achilleus, the beloved of Zeus, rose up, and Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.204#swept about his powerful shoulders the fluttering aegis;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.205#and she, the divine among goddesses, about his head circled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.206#a golden cloud, and kindled from it a flame far-shining.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.207#As when a flare goes up into the high air from a city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.208#from an island far away, with enemies fighting about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.209#who all day long are in the hateful division of Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.210#fighting from their own city, but as the sun goes down signal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.211#fires blaze out one after another, so that the glare goes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.212#pulsing high for men of the neighbouring islands to see it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.213#in case they might come over in ships to beat off the enemy;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.214#so from the head of Achilleus the blaze shot into the bright air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.215#He went from the wall and stood by the ditch, nor mixed with the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.216#Achaians, since he followed the close command of his mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.217#There he stood, and shouted, and from her place Pallas Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.218#gave cry, and drove an endless terror upon the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.219#As loud as comes the voice that is screamed out by a trumpet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.220#by murderous attackers who beleaguer a city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.221#so then high and clear went up the voice of Aiakides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.222#But the Trojans, when they heard the brazen voice of Aiakides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.223#the heart was shaken in all, and the very floating-maned horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.224#turned their chariots about, since their hearts saw the coming afflictions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.225#The charioteers were dumbfounded as they saw the unwearied dangerous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.226#fire that played above the head of great-hearted Peleion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.227#blazing, and kindled by the goddess grey-eyed Athene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.228#Three times across the ditch brilliant Achilleus gave his great cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.229#and three times the Trojans and their renowned companions were routed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.230#There at that time twelve of the best men among them perished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.231#upon their own chariots and spears. Meanwhile the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.232#gladly pulled Patroklos out from under the missiles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.233#and set him upon a litter, and his own companions about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.234#stood mourning, and along with them swift-footed Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.235#went, letting fall warm tears as he saw his steadfast companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.236#lying there on a carried litter and torn with the sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.237#the man he had sent off before with horses and chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.238#into the fighting; who never again came home to be welcomed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.239#Now the lady Hera of the ox eyes drove the unwilling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.240#weariless sun god to sink in the depth of the Ocean,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.241#and the sun went down, and the brilliant Achaians gave over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.242#their strong fighting, and the doubtful collision of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.243#The Trojans on the other side moved from the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.244#in their turn, and unyoked their running horses from under the chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.245#and gathered into assembly before taking thought for their supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.246#They stood on their feet in assembly, nor did any man have the patience
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.247#to sit down, but the terror was on them all, seeing that Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.248#had appeared, after he had stayed so long from the difficult fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.249#First to speak among them was the careful Poulydamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.250#Panthoös' son, who alone of them looked before and behind him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.251#He was companion to Hektor, and born on the same night with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.252#but he was better in words, the other with the spear far better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.253#He in kind intention toward all stood forth and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.254#'Now take careful thought, dear friends; for I myself urge you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.255#to go back into the city and not wait for the divine dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.256#in the plain beside the ships. We are too far from the wall now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.257#While this man was still angry with great Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.258#for all that time the Achaians were easier men to fight with.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.259#For I also used then to be one who was glad to sleep out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.260#near their ships, and I hoped to capture the oarswept vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.261#But now I terribly dread the swift-footed son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.262#So violent is the valour in him, he will not be willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.263#to stay here in the plain, where now Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.264#from either side sunder between them the wrath of the war god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.265#With him, the fight will be for the sake of our city and women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.266#Let us go into the town; believe me; thus it will happen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.267#For this present, immortal night has stopped the swift-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.268#son of Peleus, but if he catches us still in this place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.269#tomorrow, and drives upon us in arms, a man will be well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.270#aware of him, be glad to get back into sacred Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.271#the man who escapes; there will be many Trojans the vultures
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.272#and dogs will feed on. But let such a word be out of my hearing!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.273#If all of us will do as I say, though it hurts us to do it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.274#this night we will hold our strength in the market place, and the great walls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.275#and the gateways, and the long, smooth-planed, close-joined gate timbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.276#that close to fit them shall defend our city. Then, early
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.277#in the morning, under dawn, we shall arm ourselves in our war gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.278#and take stations along the walls. The worse for him, if he endeavours
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.279#to come away from the ships and fight us here for our city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.280#Back he must go to his ships again, when he wears out the strong necks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.281#of his horses, driving them at a gallop everywhere by the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.282#His valour will not give him leave to burst in upon us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.283#nor sack our town. Sooner the circling dogs will feed on him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.284#Then looking darkly at him Hektor of the shining helm spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.285#'Poulydamas, these things that you argue please me no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.286#when you tell us to go back again and be cooped in our city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.287#Have you not all had your glut of being fenced in our outworks?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.288#There was a time when mortal men would speak of the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.289#of Priam as a place with much gold and much bronze. But now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.290#the lovely treasures that lay away in our houses have vanished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.291#and many possessions have been sold and gone into Phrygia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.292#and into Maionia the lovely, when great Zeus was angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.293#But now, when the son of devious-devising Kronos has given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.294#me the winning of glory by the ships, to pin the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.295#on the sea, why, fool, no longer show these thoughts to our people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.296#Not one of the Trojans will obey you. I shall not allow it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.297#Come, then, do as I say and let us all be persuaded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.298#Now, take your supper by positions along the encampment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.299#and do not forget your watch, and let every man be wakeful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.300#And if any Trojan is strongly concerned about his possessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.301#let him gather them and give them to the people, to use them in common.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.302#It is better for one of us to enjoy them than for the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.303#In the morning, under dawn, we shall arm ourselves in our war gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.304#and waken the bitter god of war by the hollow vessels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.305#If it is true that brilliant Achilleus is risen beside their
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.306#ships, then the worse for him if he tries it, since I for my part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.307#will not run from him out of the sorrowful battle, but rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.308#stand fast, to see if he wins the great glory, or if I can win it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.309#The war god is impartial. Before now he has killed the killer.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.310#So spoke Hektor, and the Trojans thundered to hear him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.311#fools, since Pallas Athene had taken away the wits from them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.312#They gave their applause to Hektor in his counsel of evil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.313#but none to Poulydamas, who had spoken good sense before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.314#They took their supper along the encampment. Meanwhile the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.315#mourned all night in lamentation over Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.316#Peleus' son led the thronging chant of their lamentation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.317#and laid his manslaughtering hands over the chest of his dear friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.318#with outbursts of incessant grief. As some great bearded lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.319#when some man, a deer hunter, has stolen his cubs away from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.320#out of the close wood; the lion comes back too late, and is anguished,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.321#and turns into many valleys quartering after the man's trail
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.322#on the chance of finding him, and taken with bitter anger;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.323#so he, groaning heavily, spoke out to the Myrmidons:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.324#'Ah me. It was an empty word I cast forth on that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.325#when in his halls I tried to comfort the hero Menoitios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.326#I told him I would bring back his son in glory to Opous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.327#with Ilion sacked, and bringing his share of war spoils allotted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.328#But Zeus does not bring to accomplishment all thoughts in men's minds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.329#Thus it is destiny for us both to stain the same soil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.330#here in Troy; since I shall never come home, and my father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.331#Peleus the aged rider, will not welcome me in his great house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.332#nor Thetis my mother, but in this place the earth will receive me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.333#But seeing that it is I, Patroklos, who follow you underground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.334#I will not bury you till I bring to this place the armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.335#and the head of Hektor, since he was your great-hearted murderer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.336#Before your burning pyre I shall behead twelve glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.337#children of the Trojans, for my anger over your slaying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.338#Until then, you shall lie where you are in front of my curved ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.339#and beside you women of Troy and deep-girdled Dardanian women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.340#shall sorrow for you night and day and shed tears for you, those whom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.341#you and I worked hard to capture by force and the long spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.342#in days when we were storming the rich cities of mortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.343#So speaking brilliant Achilleus gave orders to his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.344#to set a great cauldron across the fire, so that with all speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.345#they could wash away the clotted blood from Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.346#They set up over the blaze of the fire a bath-water cauldron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.347#and poured water into it and put logs underneath and kindled them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.348#The fire worked on the swell of the cauldron, and the water heated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.349#But when the water had come to a boil in the shining bronze, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.350#they washed the body and anointed it softly with olive oil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.351#and stopped the gashes in his body with stored-up unguents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.352#and laid him on a bed, and shrouded him in a thin sheet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.353#from head to foot, and covered that over with a white mantle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.354#Then all night long, gathered about Achilleus of the swift feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.355#the Myrmidons mourned for Patroklos and lamented over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.356#But Zeus spoke to Hera, who was his wife and his sister:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.357#'So you have acted, then, lady Hera of the ox eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.358#You have roused up Achilleus of the swift feet. It must be then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.359#that the flowing-haired Achaians are born of your own generation.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.360#Then the goddess the ox-eyed lady Hera answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.361#'Majesty, son of Kronos, what sort of thing have you spoken?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.362#Even one who is mortal will try to accomplish his purpose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.363#for another, though he be a man and knows not such wisdom as we do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.364#As for me then, who claim I am highest of all the goddesses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.365#both ways, since I am eldest born and am called your consort,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.366#yours, and you in turn are lord over all the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.367#how could I not weave sorrows for the men of Troy, when I hate them?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.368#Now as these two were saying things like this to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.369#Thetis of the silver feet came to the house of Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.370#imperishable, starry, and shining among the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.371#built in bronze for himself by the god of the dragging footsteps.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.372#She found him sweating as he turned here and there to his bellows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.373#busily, since he was working on twenty tripods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.374#which were to stand against the wall of his strong-founded dwelling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.375#And he had set golden wheels underneath the base of each one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.376#so that of their own motion they could wheel into the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.377#gathering, and return to his house: a wonder to look at.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.378#These were so far finished, but the elaborate ear handles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.379#were not yet on. He was forging these, and beating the chains out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.380#As he was at work on this in his craftsmanship and his cunning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.381#meanwhile the goddess Thetis the silver-footed drew near him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.382#Charis of the shining veil saw her as she came forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.383#she, the lovely goddess the renowned strong-armed one had married.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.384#She came, and caught her hand and called her by name and spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.385#'Why is it, Thetis of the light robes, you have come to our house now?
