urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.585#But they, before they could get their teeth in, turned back from the lions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.586#but would come and take their stand very close, and bayed, and kept clear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.587#And the renowned smith of the strong arms made on it a meadow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.588#large and in a lovely valley for the glimmering sheepflocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.589#with dwelling places upon it, and covered shelters, and sheepfolds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.590#And the renowned smith of the strong arms made elaborate on it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.591#a dancing floor, like that which once in the wide spaces of Knosos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.592#Daidalos built for Ariadne of the lovely tresses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.593#And there were young men on it and young girls, sought for their beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.594#with gifts of oxen, dancing, and holding hands at the wrist. These
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.595#wore, the maidens long light robes, but the men wore tunics
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.596#of finespun work and shining softly, touched with olive oil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.597#And the girls wore fair garlands on their heads, while the young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.598#carried golden knives that hung from sword-belts of silver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.599#At whiles on their understanding feet they would run very lightly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.600#as when a potter crouching makes trial of his wheel, holding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.601#it close in his hands, to see if it will run smooth. At another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.602#time they would form rows, and run, rows crossing each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.603#And around the lovely chorus of dancers stood a great multitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.604#happily watching. And among them sang an inspired singer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.605#playing his lyre, while with them two acrobats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.606#led the measures of song and dance revolving among them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.607#He made on it the great strength of the Ocean River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.608#which ran around the uttermost rim of the shield's strong structure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.609#Then after he had wrought this shield, which was huge and heavy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.610#he wrought for him a corselet brighter than fire in its shining,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.611#and wrought him a helmet, massive and fitting close to his temples,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.612#lovely and intricate work, and laid a gold top-ridge along it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.613#and out of pliable tin wrought him leg-armour. Thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.614#when the renowned smith of the strong arms had finished the armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.615#he lifted it and laid it before the mother of Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.616#And she like a hawk came sweeping down from the snows of Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:18.617#and carried with her the shining armour, the gift of Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.1#Now Dawn the yellow-robed arose from the river of Ocean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.2#to carry her light to men and to immortals. And Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.3#came to the ships and carried with her the gifts of Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.4#She found her beloved son lying in the arms of Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.5#crying shrill, and his companions in their numbers about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.6#mourned. She, shining among divinities, stood there beside them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.7#She clung to her son's hand and called him by name and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.8#'My child, now, though we grieve for him, we must let this man lie
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.9#dead, in the way he first was killed through the gods' designing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.10#Accept rather from me the glorious arms of Hephaistos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.11#so splendid, and such as no man has ever worn on his shoulders.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.12#The goddess spoke so, and set down the armour on the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.13#before Achilleus, and all its elaboration clashed loudly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.14#Trembling took hold of all the Myrmidons. None had the courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.15#to look straight at it. They were afraid of it. Only Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.16#looked, and as he looked the anger came harder upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.17#and his eyes glittered terribly under his lids, like sunflare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.18#He was glad, holding in his hands the shining gifts of Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.19#But when he had satisfied his heart with looking at the intricate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.20#armour, he spoke to his mother and addressed her in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.21#'My mother, the god has given me these weapons; they are such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.22#as are the work of immortals. No mortal man could have made them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.23#Therefore now I shall arm myself in them. Yet I am sadly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.24#afraid, during this time, for the warlike son of Menoitios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.25#that flies might get into the wounds beaten by bronze in his body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.26#and breed worms in them, and these make foul the body, seeing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.27#that the life is killed in him, and that all his flesh may be rotted.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.28#In turn the goddess Thetis the silver-footed answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.29#'My child, no longer let these things be a care in your mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.30#I shall endeavour to drive from him the swarming and fierce things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.31#those flies, which feed upon the bodies of men who have perished;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.32#and although he lie here till a year has gone to fulfilment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.33#still his body shall be as it was, or firmer than ever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.34#Go then and summon into assembly the fighting Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.35#and unsay your anger against Agamemnon, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.36#and arm at once for the fighting, and put your war strength upon you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.37#She spoke so, and drove the strength of great courage into him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.38#and meanwhile through the nostrils of Patroklos she distilled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.39#ambrosia and red nectar, so that his flesh might not spoil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.40#But he, brilliant Achilleus, walked along by the sea-shore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.41#crying his terrible cry, and stirred up the fighting Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.42#And even those who before had stayed where the ships were assembled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.43#they who were helmsmen of the ships and handled the steering oar,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.44#they who were stewards among the ships and dispensers of rations,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.45#even these came then to assembly, since now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.46#had appeared, after staying so long from the sorrowful battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.47#And there were two who came limping among them, henchmen of Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.48#both, Tydeus' son the staunch in battle, and brilliant Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.49#leaning on spears, since they had the pain of their wounds yet upon them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.50#and came and took their seats in the front rank of those assembled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.51#And last of them came in the lord of men Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.52#with a wound on him, seeing that Koön, the son of Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.53#had stabbed him with the bronze edge of the spear in the strong encounter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.54#But now, when all the Achaians were in one body together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.55#Achilleus of the swift feet stood up before them and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.56#'Son of Atreus, was this after all the better way for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.57#both, for you and me, that we, for all our hearts' sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.58#quarrelled together for the sake of a girl in soul-perishing hatred?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.59#I wish Artemis had killed her beside the ships with an arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.60#on that day when I destroyed Lyrnessos and took her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.61#For thus not all these too many Achaians would have bitten
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.62#the dust, by enemy hands, when I was away in my anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.63#This way was better for the Trojans and Hektor; yet I think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.64#the Achaians will too long remember this quarrel between us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.65#Still, we will let all this be a thing of the past, though it hurts us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.66#and beat down by constraint the anger that rises inside us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.67#Now I am making an end of my anger. It does not become me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.68#unrelentingly to rage on. Come, then! The more quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.69#drive on the flowing-haired Achaians into the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.70#so that I may go up against the Trojans, and find out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.71#if they still wish to sleep out beside the ships. I think rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.72#they will be glad to rest where they are, whoever among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.73#gets away with his life from the fury of our spears' onset.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.74#He spoke, and the strong-greaved Achaians were pleasured to hear him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.75#and how the great-hearted son of Peleus unsaid his anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.76#Now among them spoke forth the lord of men Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.77#from the place where he was sitting, and did not stand up among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.78#'Fighting men and friends, o Danaans, henchmen of Ares:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.79#it is well to listen to the speaker, it is not becoming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.80#to break in on him. This will be hard for him, though he be able.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.81#How among the great murmur of people shall anyone listen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.82#or speak either? A man, though he speak very clearly, is baffled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.83#I shall address the son of Peleus; yet all you other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.84#Argives listen also, and give my word careful attention.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.85#This is the word the Achaians have spoken often against me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.86#and found fault with me in it, yet I am not responsible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.87#but Zeus is, and Destiny, and Erinys the mist-walking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.88#who in assembly caught my heart in the savage delusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.89#on that day I myself stripped from him the prize of Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.90#Yet what could I do? It is the god who accomplishes all things.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.91#Delusion is the elder daughter of Zeus, the accursed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.92#who deludes all; her feet are delicate and they step not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.93#on the firm earth, but she walks the air above men's heads
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.94#and leads them astray. She has entangled others before me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.95#Yes, for once Zeus even was deluded, though men say
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.96#he is the highest one of gods and mortals. Yet Hera
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.97#who is female deluded even Zeus in her craftiness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.98#on that day when in strong wall-circled Thebe Alkmene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.99#was at her time to bring forth the strength of Herakles. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.100#Zeus spoke forth and made a vow before all the immortals:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.101#"Hear me, all you gods and all you goddesses: hear me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.102#while I speak forth what the heart within my breast urges.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.103#This day Eileithyia of women's child-pains shall bring forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.104#a man to the light who, among the men sprung of the generation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.105#of my blood, shall be lord over all those dwelling about him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.106#Then in guileful intention the lady Hera said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.107#"You will be a liar, not put fulfilment on what you have spoken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.108#Come, then, lord of Olympos, and swear before me a strong oath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.109#that he shall be lord over all those dwelling about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.110#who this day shall fall between the feet of a woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.111#that man who is born of the blood of your generation." So Hera
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.112#spoke. And Zeus was entirely unaware of her falsehood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.113#but swore a great oath, and therein lay all his deception.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.114#But Hera in a flash of speed left the horn of Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.115#and rapidly came to Argos of Achaia, where she knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.116#was the mighty wife of Sthenelos, descended of Perseus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.117#And she was carrying a son, and this was the seventh month for her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.118#but she brought him sooner into the light, and made him premature,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.119#and stayed the childbirth of Alkmene, and held back the birth pangs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.120#She went herself and spoke the message to Zeus, son of Kronos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.121#"Father Zeus of the shining bolt, I will tell you a message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.122#for your heart. A great man is born, who will be lord over the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.123#Eurystheus, son of Sthenelos, of the seed of Perseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.124#your generation. It is not unfit that he should rule over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.125#the Argives." She spoke, and the sharp sorrow struck at his deep heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.126#He caught by the shining hair of her head the goddess Delusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.127#in the anger of his heart, and swore a strong oath, that never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.128#after this might Delusion, who deludes all, come back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.129#to Olympos and the starry sky. So speaking, he whirled her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.130#about in his hand and slung her out of the starry heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.131#and presently she came to men's establishments. But Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.132#would forever grieve over her each time that he saw his dear son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.133#doing some shameful work of the tasks that Eurystheus set him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.134#So I in my time, when tall Hektor of the shining helm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.135#was forever destroying the Argives against the sterns of their vessels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.136#could not forget Delusion, the way I was first deluded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.137#But since I was deluded and Zeus took my wits away from me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.138#I am willing to make all good and give back gifts in abundance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.139#Rise up, then, to the fighting and rouse the rest of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.140#Here am I, to give you all those gifts, as many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.141#as brilliant Odysseus yesterday went to your shelter and promised.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.142#Or if you will, hold back, though you lean hard into the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.143#while my followers take the gifts from my ship and bring them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.144#to you, so you may see what I give to comfort your spirit.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.145#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.146#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.147#the gifts are yours to give if you wish, and as it is proper,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.148#or to keep with yourself. But now let us remember our joy in warcraft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.149#immediately, for it is not fitting to stay here and waste time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.150#nor delay, since there is still a big work to be done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.151#So can a man see once more Achilleus among the front fighters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.152#with the bronze spear wrecking the Trojan battalions. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.153#let each of you remember this and fight his antagonist.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.154#Then in answer to him spoke resourceful Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.155#'Not that way, good fighter that you are, godlike Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.156#Do not drive the sons of the Achaians on Ilion when they are hungry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.157#to fight against the Trojans, since not short will be the time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.158#of battle, once the massed formations of men have encountered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.159#together, with the god inspiring fury in both sides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.160#Rather tell the men of Achaia here by their swift ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.161#to take food and wine, since these make fighting fury and warcraft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.162#For a man will not have strength to fight his way forward all day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.163#long until the sun goes down if he is starved for food. Even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.164#though in his heart he be very passionate for the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.165#yet without his knowing it his limbs will go heavy, and hunger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.166#and thirst will catch up with him and cumber his knees as he moves on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.167#But when a man has been well filled with wine and with eating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.168#and then does battle all day long against the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.169#why, then the heart inside him is full of cheer, nor do his limbs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.170#get weary, until all are ready to give over the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.171#Come then, tell your men to scatter and bid them get ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.172#a meal; and as for the gifts, let the lord of men Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.173#bring them to the middle of our assembly so all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.174#can see them before their eyes, so your own heart may be pleasured.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.175#And let him stand up before the Argives and swear an oath to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.176#that he never entered into her bed and never lay with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.177#as is natural for people, my lord, between men and women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.178#And by this let the spirit in your own heart be made gracious.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.179#After that in his own shelter let him appease you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.180#with a generous meal, so you will lack nothing of what is due you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.181#And you, son of Atreus, after this be more righteous to another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.182#man. For there is no fault when even one who is a king
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.183#appeases a man, when the king was the first one to be angry.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.184#Then in turn the lord of men Agamemnon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.185#'Hearing what you have said, son of Laertes, I am pleased with you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.186#Fairly have you gone through everything and explained it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.187#And all this I am willing to swear to, and my heart urges me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.188#and I will not be foresworn before the gods. Let Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.189#stay here the while, though he lean very hard toward the work of the war god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.190#and remain the rest of you all here assembled, until the gifts come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.191#back from my shelter and while we cut our oaths of fidelity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.192#And for you yourself, Odysseus, I give you this errand, this order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.193#that you choose out excellent young men of all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.194#and bring the gifts back here from my ship, all that you promised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.195#yesterday to Achilleus, and bring the women back also.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.196#And in the wide host of the Achaians let Talthybios make ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.197#a boar for me, and dedicate it to Zeus and Helios.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.198#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.199#'Son of Atreus, most lordly and king of men, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.200#at some other time rather you should busy yourself about these things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.201#when there is some stopping point in the fighting, at some time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.202#when there is not so much fury inside of my heart. But now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.203#as things are they lie there torn whom the son of Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.204#Hektor has beaten down, since Zeus was giving him glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.205#and then you urge a man to eating. No, but I would now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.206#drive forward the sons of the Achaians into the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.207#starving and unfed, and afterwards when the sun sets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.208#make ready a great dinner, when we have paid off our defilement.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.209#But before this, for me at least, neither drink nor food shall
