urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.214#but blood does, and slaughter, and the groaning of men in the hard work.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.215#Then in answer to him spoke resourceful Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.216#'Son of Peleus, Achilleus, far greatest of the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.217#you are stronger than I am and greater by not a little
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.218#with the spear, yet I in turn might overpass you in wisdom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.219#by far, since I was born before you and have learned more things.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.220#Therefore let your heart endure to listen to my words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.221#When there is battle men have suddenly their fill of it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.222#when the bronze scatters on the ground the straw in most numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.223#and the harvest is most thin, when Zeus has poised his balance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.224#Zeus, who is administrator to men in their fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.225#There is no way the Achaians can mourn a dead man by denying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.226#the belly. Too many fall day by day, one upon another,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.227#and how could anyone find breathing space from his labour?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.228#No, but we must harden our hearts and bury the man who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.229#dies, when we have wept over him on the day, and all those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.230#who are left about from the hateful work of war must remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.231#food and drink, so that afterwards all the more strongly
