urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.274#wished that death should befall great numbers of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.275#Go now and take your dinner, so we may draw on the battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.276#So he spoke, and suddenly broke up the assembly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.277#Now these scattered away each man to his own ship. Meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.278#the great-hearted Myrmidons disposed of the presents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.279#They went on their way carrying them to the ship of godlike Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.280#and stowed the gifts in the shelters, and let the women be settled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.281#while proud henchmen drove the horses into Achilleus' horse-herd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.282#And now, in the likeness of golden Aphrodite, Briseis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.283#when she saw Patroklos lying torn with sharp bronze, folding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.284#him in her arms cried shrilly above him and with her hands tore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.285#at her breasts and her soft throat and her beautiful forehead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.286#The woman like the immortals mourning for him spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.287#'Patroklos, far most pleasing to my heart in its sorrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.288#I left you here alive when I went away from the shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.289#but now I come back, lord of the people, to find you have fallen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.290#So evil in my life takes over from evil forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.291#The husband on whom my father and honoured mother bestowed me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.292#I saw before my city lying torn with the sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.293#and my three brothers, whom a single mother bore with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.294#and who were close to me, all went on one day to destruction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.295#And yet you would not let me, when swift Achilleus had cut down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.296#my husband, and sacked the city of godlike Mynes, you would not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.297#let me sorrow, but said you would make me godlike Achilleus'
