urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.299#to Phthia, and formalize my marriage among the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.300#Therefore I weep your death without ceasing. You were kind always.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.301#So she spoke, lamenting, and the women sorrowed around her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.302#grieving openly for Patroklos, but for her own sorrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.303#each. But the lords of Achaia were gathered about Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.304#beseeching him to eat, but he with a groan denied them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.305#'I beg of you, if any dear companion will listen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.306#to me, stop urging me to satisfy the heart in me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.307#with food and drink, since this strong sorrow has come upon me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.308#I will hold out till the sun goes down and endure, though it be hard.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.309#So he spoke, and caused the rest of the kings to scatter;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.310#but the two sons of Atreus stayed with him, and brilliant Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.311#and Nestor, and Idomeneus, and the aged charioteer, Phoinix,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.312#comforting him close in his sorrow, yet his heart would not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.313#be comforted, till he went into the jaws of the bleeding battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.314#Remembering Patroklos he sighed much for him, and spoke aloud:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.315#'There was a time, ill fated, o dearest of all my companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.316#when you yourself would set the desirable dinner before me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.317#quickly and expertly, at the time the Achaians were urgent
