urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.338#So he spoke, mourning, and the elders lamented around him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.339#remembering each those he had left behind in his own halls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.340#The son of Kronos took pity on them as he watched them mourning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.341#and immediately spoke in winged words to Athene:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.342#'My child, have you utterly abandoned the man of your choice?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.343#Is there no longer deep concern in your heart for Achilleus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.344#Now he has sat down before the steep horned ships and is mourning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.345#for his own beloved companion, while all the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.346#have gone to take their dinner, but he is fasting and unfed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.347#Go then to him and distil nectar inside his chest, and delicate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.348#ambrosia, so the weakness of hunger will not come upon him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.349#Speaking so, he stirred Athene, who was eager before this,
