urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.377#in a desolate steading, as the mariners are carried unwilling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.378#by storm winds over the fish-swarming sea, far away from their loved ones;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.379#so the light from the fair elaborate shield of Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.380#shot into the high air. And lifting the helm he set it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.381#massive upon his head, and the helmet crested with horse-hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.382#shone like a star, the golden fringes were shaken about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.383#which Hephaistos had driven close along the horn of the helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.384#And brilliant Achilleus tried himself in his armour, to see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.385#if it fitted close, and how his glorious limbs ran within it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.386#and the armour became as wings and upheld the shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.387#Next he pulled out from its standing place the spear of his father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.388#huge, heavy, thick, which no one else of all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.389#could handle, but Achilleus alone knew how to wield it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.390#the Pelian ash spear which Cheiron had brought to his father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.391#from high on Pelion, to be death for fighters in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.392#Automedon and Alkimos, in charge of the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.393#yoked them, and put the fair breast straps about them, and forced the bits home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.394#between their jaws, and pulled the reins back against the compacted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.395#chariot seat, and one, Automedon, took up the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.396#whip caught close in his hand and vaulted up to the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.397#while behind him Achilleus helmed for battle took his stance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.398#shining in all his armour like the sun when he crosses above us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.399#and cried in a terrible voice on the horses of his father:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.400#'Xanthos, Balios, Bay and Dapple, famed sons of Podarge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.401#take care to bring in another way your charioteer back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.402#to the company of the Danaans, when we give over fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.403#not leave him to lie fallen there, as you did to Patroklos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.404#Then from beneath the yoke the gleam-footed horse answered him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.405#Xanthos, and as he spoke bowed his head, so that all the mane
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.406#fell away from the pad and swept the ground by the cross-yoke;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.407#the goddess of the white arms, Hera, had put a voice in him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.408#'We shall still keep you safe for this time, o hard Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.409#And yet the day of your death is near, but it is not we
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.410#who are to blame, but a great god and powerful Destiny.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.411#For it was not because we were slow, because we were careless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.412#that the Trojans have taken the armour from the shoulders of Patroklos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.413#but it was that high god, the child of lovely-haired Leto,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.414#who killed him among the champions and gave the glory to Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.415#But for us, we two could run with the blast of the west wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.416#who they say is the lightest of all things; yet still for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.417#there is destiny to be killed in force by a god and a mortal.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.418#When he had spoken so the Furies stopped the voice in him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.419#but deeply disturbed, Achilleus of the swift feet answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.420#'Xanthos, why do you prophesy my death? This is not for you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.421#I myself know well it is destined for me to die here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.422#far from my beloved father and mother. But for all that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.423#I will not stop till the Trojans have had enough of my fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:19.424#He spoke, and shouting held on in the foremost his single-foot horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.1#So these now, the Achaians, beside the curved ships were arming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.2#around you, son of Peleus, insatiate of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.3#while on the other side at the break of the plain the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.4#armed. But Zeus, from the many-folded peak of Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.5#told Themis to summon all the gods into assembly. She went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.6#everywhere, and told them to make their way to Zeus' house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.7#There was no river who was not there, except only Ocean,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.8#there was not any one of the nymphs who live in the lovely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.9#groves, and the springs of rivers and grass of the meadows, who came not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.10#These all assembling into the house of Zeus cloud gathering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.11#took places among the smooth-stone cloister walks which Hephaistos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.12#had built for Zeus the father by his craftsmanship and contrivance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.13#So they were assembled within Zeus' house; and the shaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.14#of the earth did not fail to hear the goddess, but came up among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.15#from the sea, and sat in the midst of them, and asked Zeus of his counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.16#'Why, lord of the shining bolt, have you called the gods to assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.17#once more? Are you deliberating Achaians and Trojans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.18#For the onset of battle is almost broken to flame between them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.19#In turn Zeus who gathers the clouds spoke to him in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.20#'You have seen, shaker of the earth, the counsel within me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.21#and why I gathered you. I think of these men though they are dying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.22#Even so, I shall stay here upon the fold of Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.23#sitting still, watching, to pleasure my heart. Meanwhile all you others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.24#go down, wherever you may go among the Achaians and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.25#and give help to either side, as your own pleasure directs you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.26#For if we leave Achilleus alone to fight with the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.27#they will not even for a little hold off swift-footed Peleion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.28#For even before now they would tremble whenever they saw him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.29#and now, when his heart is grieved and angered for his companion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.30#death, I fear against destiny he may storm their fortress.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.31#So spoke the son of Kronos and woke the incessant battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.32#and the gods went down to enter the fighting, with purposes opposed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.33#Hera went to the assembled ships with Pallas Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.34#and with Poseidon who embraces the earth, and with generous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.35#Hermes, who within the heart is armed with astute thoughts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.36#Hephaistos went the way of these in the pride of his great strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.37#limping, and yet his shrunken legs moved lightly beneath him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.38#But Ares of the shining helm went over to the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.39#and with him Phoibos of the unshorn hair, and the lady of arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.40#Artemis, and smiling Aphrodite, Leto, and Xanthos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.41#Now in the time when the gods were still distant from the mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.42#so long the Achaians were winning great glory, since now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.43#showed among them, who had stayed too long from the sorrowful fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.44#But the Trojans were taken every man in the knees with trembling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.45#and terror, as they looked on the swift-footed son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.46#shining in all his armour, a man like the murderous war god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.47#But after the Olympians merged in the men's company
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.48#strong Hatred, defender of peoples, burst out, and Athene bellowed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.49#standing now beside the ditch dug at the wall's outside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.50#and now again at the thundering sea's edge gave out her great cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.51#while on the other side Ares in the likeness of a dark stormcloud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.52#bellowed, now from the peak of the citadel urging the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.53#sharply on, now running beside the sweet banks of Simoeis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.54#So the blessed gods stirring on the opponents drove them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.55#together, and broke out among themselves the weight of their quarrel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.56#From high above the father of gods and men made thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.57#terribly, while Poseidon from deep under them shuddered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.58#all the illimitable earth, the sheer heads of the mountains.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.59#And all the feet of Ida with her many waters were shaken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.60#and all her crests, and the city of Troy, the ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.61#Aïdoneus, lord of the dead below, was in terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.62#and sprang from his throne and screamed aloud, for fear that above him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.63#he who circles the land, Poseidon, might break the earth open
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.64#and the houses of the dead lie open to men and immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.65#ghastly and mouldering, so the very gods shudder before them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.66#such was the crash that sounded as the gods came driving together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.67#in wrath. For now over against the lord Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.68#Phoibos Apollo took his stand with his feathered arrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.69#and against Enyalios the goddess grey-eyed Athene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.70#Against Hera stood the lady of clamour, of the golden distaff,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.71#of the showering arrows, Artemis, sister of the far striker.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.72#Opposite Leto stood the strong one, generous Hermes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.73#and against Hephaistos stood the great deep-eddying river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.74#who is called Xanthos by the gods, but by mortals Skamandros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.75#Thus gods went on to encounter gods; and meanwhile Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.76#was straining to plunge into the combat opposite Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.77#Priam's son, since beyond all others his anger was driving him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.78#to glut with his blood Ares the god who fights under the shield's guard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.79#But it was Aineias whom Apollo defender of people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.80#drove straight against Peleion, and inspired vast power within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.81#Zeus' son Apollo made his voice like that of Lykaon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.82#Priam's son, and assumed his appearance, and spoke to Aineias:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.83#'Aineias, lord of the Trojans' counsels. Where are those threats gone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.84#which as you drank your wine you made before Troy's kings, solemnly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.85#that you would match your battle strength with Peleian Achilleus?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.86#In turn Aineias spoke to him in answer: 'Lykaon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.87#son of Priam, why do you urge me on against my will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.88#to fight in the face of Peleus' son and his too great fury?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.89#Since this will not be the first time I stand up against swift-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.90#Achilleus, but another time before now he drove me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.91#with the spear from Ida, when he came there after our cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.92#the time he sacked Lyrnessos and Pedasos. But Zeus rescued me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.93#when he put strength inside me and made my knees quick. Otherwise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.94#I should have gone down at Achilleus' hands, and those of Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.95#who goes before him and makes light before him, who then was urging
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.96#him on with the brazen spear to destroy Leleges and Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.97#Thereby it is not for any man to fight with Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.98#There is always some one of the gods with him to beat death from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.99#Without this, even, his spear wings straight to its mark, nor gives out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.100#until it has gone through a man's body. But if the god only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.101#would pull out even the issue of war, he would not so easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.102#win, not even though he claims to be made all of bronze.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.103#In turn the lord the son of Zeus Apollo spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.104#'Hero, then make your prayer, you also, to the everlasting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.105#gods, since they say that you yourself are born of Zeus' daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.106#Aphrodite, but Achilleus was born of a lesser goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.107#Aphrodite being daughter of Zeus, Thetis of the sea's ancient.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.108#Carry your weariless bronze straight against him, let him by no means
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.109#turn you back by blustering words and his threats of terror.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.110#So speaking, he inspired enormous strength in the shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.111#who strode on his way among the champions helmed in the bright bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.112#nor did Hera of the white arms fail to see the son of Anchises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.113#as he went through the thronging men to face the son of Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.114#and drew the other immortals about her and spoke to them, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.115#'Poseidon and Athene, now take counsel between you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.116#and within your hearts as to how these matters shall be accomplished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.117#Here is Aineias gone helmed in the shining bronze against
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.118#Peleus' son, and it was Phoibos Apollo who sent him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.119#Come then, we must even go down ourselves and turn him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.120#back from here, or else one of us must stand by Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.121#and put enormous strength upon him, and let him not come short
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.122#in courage, but let him know that they love him who are the highest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.123#of the immortals, but those who before now fended the fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.124#of war, as now, from the Trojans are as wind and nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.125#For all of us have come down from Olympos to take our part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.126#in this battle, so nothing may be done to him by the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.127#on this day. Afterwards he shall suffer such things as Destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.128#wove with the strand of his birth that day he was born to his mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.129#But if Achilleus does not hear all this from gods' voices
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.130#he will be afraid, when a god puts out his strength against him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.131#in the fighting. It is hard for gods to be shown in their true shape.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.132#In turn Poseidon the shaker of the earth answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.133#'Hera, do not be angry without purpose. It does not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.134#become you, since I at least would not have the rest of us gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.135#encounter in battle, since indeed we are far too strong for them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.136#Let us then go away and sit down together off the path
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.137#at a viewing place, and let the men take care of their fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.138#Only if Ares begins to fight, or Phoibos Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.139#or if they hold Achilleus back and will not let him fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.140#then at once they will have a quarrel with us on their hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.141#in open battle. But soon, I think, when they have fought with us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.142#they will get back to Olympos and the throng of the other gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.143#beaten back by the overmastering strength of our hands.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.144#So he spoke, Poseidon of the dark hair, and led the way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.145#to the stronghold of godlike Herakles, earth-piled on both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.146#a high place, which the Trojans and Pallas Athene had built him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.147#as a place of escape where he could get away from the Sea Beast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.148#when the charging monster drove him away to the plain from the seashore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.149#There Poseidon and the gods who were with him sat down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.150#and gathered a breakless wall of cloud to darken their shoulders;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.151#while they of the other side sat down on the brows of the sweet bluffs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.152#around you, lord Apollo, and Ares sacker of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.153#So they on either side took their places, deliberating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.154#counsels, reluctant on both sides to open the sorrowful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.155#attack. But Zeus sitting on high above urged them on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.156#But all the plain was filled and shining with bronze of the mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.157#their men and horses, and underneath their feet the earth staggered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.158#as they swept together. Two men far greater than all the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.159#were coming to encounter, furious to fight with each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.160#Aineias, the son of Anchises, and brilliant Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.161#First of the two Aineias had strode forth in menace, tossing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.162#his head beneath the heavy helm, and he held the stark shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.163#in front of his chest, and shook the brazen spear. From the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.164#side the son of Peleus rose like a lion against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.165#the baleful beast, when men have been straining to kill him, the county
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.166#all in the hunt, and he at the first pays them no attention
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.167#but goes his way, only when some one of the impetuous young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.168#has hit him with the spear he whirls, jaws open, over his teeth foam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.169#breaks out, and in the depth of his chest the powerful heart groans;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.170#he lashes his own ribs with his tail and the flanks on both sides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.171#as he rouses himself to fury for the fight, eyes glaring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.172#and hurls himself straight onward on the chance of killing some one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.173#of the men, or else being killed himself in the first onrush.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.174#So the proud heart and fighting fury stirred on Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.175#to go forward in the face of great-hearted Aineias.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.176#Now as these in their advance had come close to each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.177#first of the two to speak was swift-footed brilliant Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.178#'Aineias, why have you stood so far forth from the multitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.179#against me? Does the desire in your heart drive you to combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.180#in hope you will be lord of the Trojans, breakers of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.181#and of Priam's honour. And yet even if you were to kill me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.182#Priam would not because of that rest such honour on your hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.183#He has sons, and he himself is sound, not weakened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.184#Or have the men of Troy promised you a piece of land, surpassing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.185#all others, fine ploughland and orchard for you to administer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.186#if you kill me? But I think that killing will not be easy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.187#Another time before this, I tell you, you ran from my spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.188#Or do you not remember when, apart from your cattle, I caught you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.189#alone, and chased you in the speed of your feet down the hills of Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.190#headlong, and that time as you ran you did not turn to look back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.191#Then you got away into Lyrnessos, but I went after you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.192#and stormed that place, with the help of Athene and of Zeus father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.193#and took the day of liberty away from their women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.194#and led them as spoil, but Zeus and the other gods saved you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.195#I think they will not save you now, as your expectation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.196#tells you they will. No, but I myself urge you to get back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.197#into the multitude, not stand to face me, before you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.198#take some harm. Once a thing has been done, the fool sees it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.199#Then in turn Aineias spoke to him and made his answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.200#'Son of Peleus, never hope by words to frighten me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.201#as if I were a baby. I myself understand well enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.202#how to speak in vituperation and how to make insults.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.203#You and I know each other's birth, we both know our parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.204#since we have heard the lines of their fame from mortal men; only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.205#I have never with my eyes seen your parents, nor have you seen mine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.206#For you, they say you are the issue of blameless Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.207#and that your mother was Thetis of the lovely hair, the sea's lady;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.208#I in turn claim I am the son of great-hearted Anchises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.209#but that my mother was Aphrodite; and that of these parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.210#one group or the other will have a dear son to mourn for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.211#this day. Since I believe we will not in mere words, like children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.212#meet, and separate and go home again out of the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.213#Even so, if you wish to learn all this and be certain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.214#of my genealogy: there are plenty of men who know it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.215#First of all Zeus who gathers the clouds had a son, Dardanos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.216#who founded Dardania, since there was yet no sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.217#made a city in the plain to be a centre of peoples,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.218#but they lived yet in the underhills of Ida with all her waters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.219#Dardanos in turn had a son, the king, Erichthonios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.220#who became the richest of mortal men, and in his possession
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.221#were three thousand horses who pastured along the low grasslands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.222#mares in their pride with their young colts; and with these the North Wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.223#fell in love as they pastured there, and took on upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.224#the likeness of a dark-maned stallion, and coupled with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.225#and the mares conceiving of him bore to him twelve young horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.226#Those, when they would play along the grain-giving tilled land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.227#would pass along the tassels of corn and not break the divine yield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.228#but again, when they played across the sea's wide ridges
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.229#they would run the edge of the wave where it breaks on the grey salt water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.230#Erichthonios had a son, Tros, who was lord of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.231#and to Tros in turn there were born three sons unfaulted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.232#Ilos and Assarakos and godlike Ganymedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.233#who was the loveliest born of the race of mortals, and therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.234#the gods caught him away to themselves, to be Zeus' wine-pourer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.235#for the sake of his beauty, so he might be among the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.236#Ilos in turn was given a son, the blameless Laomedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.237#and Laomedon had sons in turn, Tithonos and Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.238#Lampos, Klytios and Hiketaon, scion of Ares;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.239#but Assarakos had Kapys, and Kapys' son was Anchises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.240#and I am Anchises' son, and Priam's is Hektor the brilliant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.241#Such is the generation and blood I claim to be born from.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.242#Zeus builds up and Zeus diminishes the strength in men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.243#the way he pleases, since his power is beyond all others'.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.244#But come, let us no longer stand here talking of these things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.245#like children, here in the space between the advancing armies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.246#For there are harsh things enough that could be spoken against us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.247#both, a ship of a hundred locks could not carry the burden.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.248#The tongue of man is a twisty thing, there are plenty of words there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.249#of every kind, the range of words is wide, and their variance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.250#The sort of thing you say is the thing that will be said to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.251#But what have you and I to do with the need for squabbling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.252#and hurling insults at each other, as if we were two wives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.253#who when they have fallen upon a heart-perishing quarrel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.254#go out in the street and say abusive things to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.255#much true, and much that is not, and it is their rage that drives them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.256#You will not by talking turn me back from the strain of my warcraft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.257#not till you have fought to my face with the bronze. Come on then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.258#and let us try each other's strength with the bronze of our spearheads.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.259#He spoke, and on the terrible grim shield drove the ponderous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.260#pike, so that the great shield moaned as it took the spearhead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.261#The son of Peleus with his heavy hand held the shield away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.262#from him, in fright, since he thought the far-shadowing spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.263#of great-hearted Aineias would lightly be driven through it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.264#Fool, and the heart and spirit in him could not understand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.265#how the glorious gifts of the gods are not easily broken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.266#by mortal men, how such gifts will not give way before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.267#Nor this time could the ponderous spear of war-wise Aineias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.268#smash the shield, since the gold stayed it, the god's gift. Indeed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.269#he did drive the spear through two folds, but there were three left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.270#still, since the god of the dragging feet had made five folds on it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.271#two of bronze on the outside and on the inside two of tin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.272#and between them the single gold, and in this the ash spear was held fast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.273#After him Achilleus let go his spear far shadowing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.274#and struck the shield of Aineias along its perfect circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.275#at the utter rim where the circle of bronze ran thinnest about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.276#and the oxhide was laid thinnest there. The Pelian ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.277#crashed clean through it there, and the shield cried out as it went through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.278#Aineias shrank down and held the shield away and above him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.279#in fright, and the spear went over his back and crashed its way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.280#to the ground, and fixed there, after tearing apart two circles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.281#of the man-covering shield. But Aineias, free of the long spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.282#stood still, and around his eyes gathered the enormous emotion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.283#and fear, that the weapon had fixed so close to him. Now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.284#drew his tearing sword and swept in fury upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.285#crying a terrible cry, but Aineias now in his hand caught
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.286#up a stone, a huge thing which no two men could carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.287#such as men are now, but by himself he lightly hefted it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.288#And there Aineias would have hit him with the stone as he swept in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.289#on helm or shield, which would have fended the bitter death from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.290#and Peleus' son would have closed with the sword and stripped the life from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.291#had not the shaker of the earth Poseidon sharply perceived all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.292#and immediately spoken his word out among the immortals:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.293#'Ah me; I am full of sorrow for great-hearted Aineias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.294#who must presently go down to death, overpowered by Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.295#because he believed the words of Apollo, the far ranging;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.296#poor fool, since Apollo will do nothing to keep grim death from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.297#But why does this man, who is guiltless, suffer his sorrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.298#for no reason, for the sake of others' unhappiness, and always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.299#he gives gifts that please them to the gods who hold the wide heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.300#But come, let us ourselves get him away from death, for fear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.301#the son of Kronos may be angered if now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.302#kills this man. It is destined that he shall be the survivor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.303#that the generation of Dardanos shall not die, without seed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.304#obliterated, since Dardanos was dearest to Kronides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.305#of all his sons that have been born to him from mortal women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.306#For Kronos' son has cursed the generation of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.307#and now the might of Aineias shall be lord over the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.308#and his sons' sons, and those who are born of their seed hereafter.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.309#In turn the lady of the ox eyes, Hera, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.310#'Shaker of the earth, you yourself must decide in your own heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.311#about Aineias, whether to rescue him or to let him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.312#go down, for all his strength, before Peleus' son, Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.313#For we two, Pallas Athene and I, have taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.314#numerous oaths and sworn them in the sight of all the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.315#never to drive the day of evil away from the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.316#not even when all the city of Troy is burned in the ravening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.317#fire, on that day when the warlike sons of the Achaians burn it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.318#When he had heard this, the shaker of the earth Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.319#went on his way through the confusion of spears and the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.320#and came to where Aineias was, and renowned Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.321#There quickly he drifted a mist across the eyes of one fighter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.322#Achilleus, Peleus' son, and from the shield of Aineias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.323#of the great heart pulled loose the strong bronze-headed ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.324#and laid it down again before the feet of Achilleus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.325#but Aineias he lifted high from the ground, and slung him through the air
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.326#so that many ranks of fighting men, many ranks of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.327#were overvaulted by Aineias, hurled by the god's hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.328#He landed at the uttermost edge of the tossing battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.329#where the Kaukonians were arming them for the order of fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.330#And Poseidon, shaker of the earth, came and stood very near him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.331#and spoke to him and addressed him in winged words: 'Aineias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.332#which one of the gods is it who urges you to such madness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.333#that you fight in the face of Peleus' son, against his high courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.334#though he is both stronger than you and dearer to the immortals?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.335#Give back rather, whenever you find yourself thrown against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.336#lest beyond your fate you go down into the house of the death god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.337#But once Achilleus has fulfilled his death and his destiny,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.338#then take courage, and go on, and fight with their foremost,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.339#since there shall be no other Achaian able to kill you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.340#He spoke, and left him there, when he had told him all this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.341#and at once scattered the mist away from the eyes of Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.342#that the gods had sent, and now he looked with his eyes, and saw largely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.343#and in disgust spoke then to his own great-hearted spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.344#'Can this be? Here is a strange thing I see with my own eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.345#Here is my spear lying on the ground, but I can no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.346#see the man, whom I was charging in fury to kill him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.347#Aineias was then one beloved of the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.348#gods. I thought what he said was ineffectual boasting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.349#Let him go. He will not again have daring to try me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.350#in battle, since even now he was glad to escape my onset.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.351#Come! I must urge on the Danaans whose delight is in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.352#and go on to face the rest of the Trojans, and see what they can do.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.353#He spoke, and leapt back into the ranks, and urged each man on:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.354#'No longer stand away from the Trojans, o great Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.355#but let each one go to face his man, furious to fight him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.356#It is a hard thing for me, for all my great strength, to harry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.357#the flight of men in such numbers or to fight with all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.358#Not Ares, who is a god immortal, not even Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.359#could take the edge of such masses of men and fight a way through them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.360#But what I can do with hands and feet and strength I tell you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.361#I will do, and I shall not hang back even a little
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.362#but go straight on through their formation, and I think that no man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.363#of the Trojans will be glad when he comes within my spear's range.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.364#He spoke, urging them on, but glorious Hektor called out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.365#in a great voice to the Trojans, and was minded to face Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.366#'Do not be afraid of Peleion, o high-hearted Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.367#I myself could fight in words against the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.368#but with the spear it were hard, since they are far stronger than we are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.369#Even Achilleus will not win achievement of everything
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.370#he says. Part he will accomplish, but part shall be baulked halfway done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.371#I am going to stand against him now, though his hands are like flame,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.372#and his heart like the shining of iron.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.373#He spoke, urging the Trojans, and they lifted their spears to face them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.374#Their fury gathered into bulk and their battle cry rose up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.375#But now Phoibos Apollo stood by Hektor and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.376#'Hektor, do not go out all alone to fight with Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.377#but wait for him in the multitude and out of the carnage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.378#lest he hit you with the spear or the stroke of the sword from close in.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.379#He spoke, and Hektor plunged back into the swarm of the fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.380#men, in fear, when he heard the voice of the god speaking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.381#But Achilleus, gathering the fury upon him, sprang on the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.382#with a ghastly cry, and the first of them he killed was Iphition
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.383#the great son of Otrynteus and a lord over numbers of people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.384#born of a naiad nymph to Otrynteus, sacker of cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.385#under the snows of Tmolos in the rich countryside of Hydë.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.386#Great Achilleus struck him with the spear as he came in fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.387#in the middle of the head, and all the head broke into two pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.388#He fell, thunderously. Great Achilleus vaunted above him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.389#'Lie there, Otrynteus' son, most terrifying of all men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.390#Here is your death, but your generation was by the lake waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.391#of Gyge, where is the allotted land of your fathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.392#by fish-swarming Hyllos and the whirling waters of Hermos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.393#He spoke, vaunting, but darkness shrouded the eyes of the other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.394#and the running rims of Achaian chariots cut him to pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.395#in the van of the onrush. Next, after him, facing Demoleon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.396#lord defender of battle and son of Antenor, Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.397#stabbed him in the temple through the brazen sides of the helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.398#and the brazen helmet could not hold, but the bronze spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.399#driven on through smashed the bone apart, and the inward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.400#brain was all spattered forth. So he beat him down in his fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.401#Next he stabbed with a spear-stroke in the back Hippodamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.402#as he fled away before him and sprang from behind his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.403#He blew his life away, bellowing, as when a bull
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.404#bellows as he is dragged for Poseidon, lord of Helike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.405#and the young men drag him. In such bulls the earth shaker glories.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.406#Such was his bellowing as the proud spirit flitted from his bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.407#Next he went with the spear after godlike Polydoros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.408#Priam's son, whom his father would not let go into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.409#because he was youngest born of all his sons to him, and also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.410#the most beloved, and in speed of his feet outpassed all the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.411#But now, in his young thoughtlessness and display of his running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.412#he swept among the champions until thus he destroyed his dear life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.413#For as he shot by swift-footed brilliant Achilleus hit him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.414#with a spear thrown in the middle of the back where the clasps of the war belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.415#were golden and came together at the joining halves of the corselet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.416#The spearhead held its way straight on and came out by the navel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.417#and he dropped, moaning, on one knee as the dark mist gathered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.418#about him, and sagged, and caught with his hands at his bowels in front of him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.419#But now when Hektor saw Polydoros, his own brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.420#going limp to the ground and catching his bowels in his hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.421#the mist closed about his eyes also, he could stand no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.422#to turn there at a distance, but went out to face Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.423#hefting his sharp spear, like a flame. Seeing him Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.424#balanced his spear in turn, and called out to him, and challenged him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.425#'Here is the man who beyond all others has troubled my anger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.426#who slaughtered my beloved companion. Let us no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.427#shrink away from each other along the edgeworks of battle.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.428#He spoke, and looking darkly at brilliant Hektor spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.429#'Come nearer, so that sooner you may reach your appointed destruction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.430#But with no fear Hektor of the shining helm answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.431#'Son of Peleus, never hope by words to frighten me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.432#as if I were a baby. I myself understand well enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.433#how to speak in vituperation and how to make insults.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.434#I know that you are great and that I am far weaker than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.435#Still, all this lies upon the knees of the gods; and it may be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.436#that weaker as I am I might still strip the life from you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.437#with a cast of the spear, since my weapon too has been sharp before this.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.438#He spoke, and balanced the spear and let it fly. But Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.439#blew against it and turned it back from renowned Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.440#with an easy blast. It came back again to glorious Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.441#and dropped to the ground in front of his feet. Meanwhile Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.442#made a furious charge against him, raging to kill him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.443#with a terrible cry, but Phoibos Apollo caught up Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.444#easily, since he was a god, and wrapped him in thick mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.445#Three times swift-footed brilliant Achilleus swept in against him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.446#with the brazen spear. Three times his stroke went into the deep mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.447#But as a fourth time, like something more than a man, he charged in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.448#Achilleus with a terrible cry called in winged words after him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.449#'Once again now you escaped death, dog. And yet the evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.450#came near you, but now once more Phoibos Apollo has saved you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.451#he to whom you must pray when you go into the thunder of spears thrown.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.452#Yet I may win you, if I encounter you ever hereafter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.453#if beside me also there is some god who will help me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.454#Now I must chase whoever I can overtake of the others.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.455#He spoke, and with the spear full in the neck stabbed Dryops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.456#so that he dropped in front of his feet. He left him to lie there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.457#and with a spear thrown against the knee stopped the charge of Demouchos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.458#Philetor's son, a huge man and powerful. After the spearcast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.459#with an inward plunge of the great sword he took the life from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.460#Then Achilleus swooping on Dardanos and Laogonos, sons both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.461#of Bias, dashed them to the ground from behind their horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.462#one with a spearcast, one with a stroke of the sword from close up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.463#Now Tros, Alastor's son: he had come up against Achilleus'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.464#knees, to catch them and be spared and his life given to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.465#if Achilleus might take pity upon his youth and not kill him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.466#fool, and did not see there would be no way to persuade him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.467#since this was a man with no sweetness in his heart, and not kindly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.468#but in a strong fury; now Tros with his hands was reaching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.469#for the knees, bent on supplication, but he stabbed with his sword at the liver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.470#so that the liver was torn from its place, and from it the black blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.471#drenched the fold of his tunic and his eyes were shrouded in darkness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.472#as the life went. Next from close in he thrust at Moulios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.473#with the pike at the ear, so the bronze spearhead pushed through and came out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.474#at the other ear. Now he hit Echeklos the son of Agenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.475#with the hilted sword, hewing against his head in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.476#so all the sword was smoking with blood, and over both eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.477#closed the red death and the strong destiny. Now Deukalion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.478#was struck in the arm, at a place in the elbow where the tendons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.479#come together. There through the arm Achilleus transfixed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.480#with the bronze spearhead, and he, arm hanging heavy, waited
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.481#and looked his death in the face. Achilleus struck with the sword's edge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.482#at his neck, and swept the helmed head far away, and the marrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.483#gushed from the neckbone, and he went down to the ground at full length.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.484#Now he went on after the blameless son of Peires,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.485#Rhigmos, who had come over from Thrace where the soil is rich. This man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.486#he stabbed in the middle with the spear, and the spear stuck fast in his belly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.487#He dropped from the chariot, but as Areïthoös his henchman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.488#turned the horses away Achilleus stabbed him with the sharp spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.489#in the back, and thrust him from the chariot. And the horses bolted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.490#As inhuman fire sweeps on in fury through the deep angles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.491#of a drywood mountain and sets ablaze the depth of the timber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.492#and the blustering wind lashes the flame along, so Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.493#swept everywhere with his spear like something more than a mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.494#harrying them as they died, and the black earth ran blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.495#Or as when a man yokes male broad-foreheaded oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.496#to crush white barley on a strong-laid threshing floor, and rapidly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.497#the barley is stripped beneath the feet of the bellowing oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.498#so before great-hearted Achilleus the single-foot horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.499#trampled alike dead men and shields, and the axle under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.500#the chariot was all splashed with blood and the rails which encircled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.501#the chariot, struck by flying drops from the feet of the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.502#from the running rims of the wheels. The son of Peleus was straining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:20.503#to win glory, his invincible hands spattered with bloody filth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.1#BUT when they came to the crossing place of the fair-running river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.2#of whirling Xanthos, a stream whose father was Zeus the immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.3#there Achilleus split them and chased some back over the flat land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.4#toward the city, where the Achaians themselves had stampeded in terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.5#on the day before, when glorious Hektor was still in his fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.6#Along this ground they were streaming in flight; but Hera let fall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.7#a deep mist before them to stay them. Meanwhile the other half
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.8#were crowded into the silvery whirls of the deep-running river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.9#and tumbled into it in huge clamour, and the steep-running water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.10#sounded, and the banks echoed hugely about them, as they out-crying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.11#tried to swim this way and that, spun about in the eddies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.12#As before the blast of a fire the locusts escaping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.13#into a river swarm in air, and the fire unwearied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.14#blazes from a sudden start, and the locusts huddle in water;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.15#so before Achilleus the murmuring waters of Xanthos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.16#the deep-whirling were filled with confusion of men and of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.17#But heaven-descended Achilleus left his spear there on the bank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.18#leaning against the tamarisks, and leapt in like some immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.19#with only his sword, but his heart was bent upon evil actions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.20#and he struck in a circle around him. The shameful sound of their groaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.21#rose as they were struck with the sword, and the water was reddened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.22#with blood. As before a huge-gaping dolphin the other fishes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.23#escaping cram the corners of a deepwater harbour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.24#in fear, for he avidly eats up any he can catch;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.25#so the Trojans along the course of the terrible river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.26#shrank under the bluffs. He, when his hands grew weary with killing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.27#chose out and took twelve young men alive from the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.28#to be vengeance for the death of Patroklos, the son of Menoitios.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.29#These, bewildered with fear like fawns, he led out of the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.30#and bound their hands behind them with thongs well cut out of leather,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.31#with the very belts they themselves wore on their ingirt tunics,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.32#and gave them to his companions to lead away to the hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.33#then himself whirled back, still in a fury to kill men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.34#And there he came upon a son of Dardanian Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.35#as he escaped from the river, Lykaon, one whom he himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.36#had taken before and led him unwilling from his father's gardens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.37#on a night foray. He with the sharp bronze was cutting young branches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.38#from a fig tree, so that they could make him rails for a chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.39#when an unlooked-for evil thing came upon him, the brilliant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.40#Achilleus, who that time sold him as slave in strong-founded Lemnos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.41#carrying him there by ship, and the son of Jason paid for him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.42#from there a guest and friend who paid a great price redeemed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.43#Eëtion of Imbros, and sent him to shining Arisbe;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.44#and from there he fled away and came to the house of his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.45#For eleven days he pleasured his heart with friends and family
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.46#after he got back from Lemnos, but on the twelfth day once again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.47#the god cast him into the hands of Achilleus, who this time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.48#was to send him down unwilling on his way to the death god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.49#Now as brilliant swift-footed Achilleus saw him and knew him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.50#naked and without helm or shield, and he had no spear left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.51#but had thrown all these things on the ground, being weary and sweating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.52#with the escape from the river, and his knees were beaten with weariness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.53#disturbed, Achilleus spoke to his own great-hearted spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.54#'Can this be? Here is a strange thing that my eyes look on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.55#Now the great-hearted Trojans, even those I have killed already,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.56#will stand and rise up again out of the gloom and the darkness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.57#as this man has come back and escaped the day without pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.58#though he was sold into sacred Lemnos; but the main of the grey sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.59#could not hold him, though it holds back many who are unwilling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.60#But come now, he must be given a taste of our spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.61#so that I may know inside my heart and make certain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.62#whether he will come back even from there, or the prospering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.63#earth will hold him, she who holds back even the strong man.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.64#So he pondered, waiting, and the other in terror came near him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.65#in an agony to catch at his knees, and the wish in his heart was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.66#to get away from the evil death and the dark fate. By this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.67#brilliant Achilleus held the long spear uplifted above him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.68#straining to stab, but he under-ran the stroke and caught him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.69#by the knees, bending, and the spear went over his back and stood fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.70#in the ground, for all its desire to tear a man's flesh. Lykaon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.71#with one hand had taken him by the knees in supplication
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.72#and with the other held and would not let go of the edged spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.73#and spoke aloud to him and addressed him in winged words: 'Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.74#I am at your knees. Respect my position, have mercy upon me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.75#I am in the place, illustrious, of a suppliant who must be honoured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.76#for you were the first beside whom I tasted the yield of Demeter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.77#on that day you captured me in the strong-laid garden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.78#and took me away from my father and those near me, and sold me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.79#away into sacred Lemnos, and a hundred oxen I fetched you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.80#My release was ransom three times as great; and this is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.81#the twelfth dawn since I came back to Ilion, after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.82#much suffering. Now again cursed destiny has put me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.83#in your hands; and I think I must be hated by Zeus the father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.84#who has given me once more to you, and my mother bore me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.85#to a short life, Laothoë, daughter of aged Altes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.86#Altes, lord of the Leleges, whose delight is in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.87#and holds headlong Pedasos on the river Satnioeis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.88#His daughter was given to Priam, who had many wives beside her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.89#We are two who were born to her. You will have cut the throats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.90#of both, since one you beat down in the forefront of the foot-fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.91#Polydoros the godlike, with a cast of the sharp spear. This time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.92#the evil shall be mine in this place, since I do not think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.93#I shall escape your hands, since divinity drove me against them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.94#Still, put away in your heart this other thing I say to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.95#Do not kill me. I am not from the same womb as Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.96#he who killed your powerful and kindly companion.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.97#So the glorious son of Priam addressed him, speaking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.98#in supplication, but heard in turn the voice without pity:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.99#'Poor fool, no longer speak to me of ransom, nor argue it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.100#In the time before Patroklos came to the day of his destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.101#then it was the way of my heart's choice to be sparing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.102#of the Trojans, and many I took alive and disposed of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.103#Now there is not one who can escape death, if the gods send
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.104#him against my hands in front of Ilion, not one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.105#of all the Trojans and beyond others the children of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.106#So, friend, you die also. Why all this clamour about it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.107#Patroklos also is dead, who was better by far than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.108#Do you not see what a man I am, how huge, how splendid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.109#and born of a great father, and the mother who bore me immortal?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.110#Yet even I have also my death and my strong destiny,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.111#and there shall be a dawn or an afternoon or a noontime
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.112#when some man in the fighting will take the life from me also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.113#either with a spearcast or an arrow flown from the bowstring.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.114#So he spoke, and in the other the knees and the inward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.115#heart went slack. He let go of the spear and sat back, spreading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.116#wide both hands; but Achilleus drawing his sharp sword struck him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.117#beside the neck at the collar-bone, and the double-edged sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.118#plunged full length inside. He dropped to the ground, face downward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.119#and lay at length, and the black blood flowed, and the ground was soaked with it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.120#Achilleus caught him by the foot and slung him into the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.121#to drift, and spoke winged words of vaunting derision over him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.122#'Lie there now among the fish, who will lick the blood away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.123#from your wound, and care nothing for you, nor will your mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.124#lay you on the death-bed and mourn over you, but Skamandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.125#will carry you spinning down to the wide bend of the salt water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.126#And a fish will break a ripple shuddering dark on the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.127#as he rises to feed upon the shining fat of Lykaon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.128#Die on, all; till we come to the city of sacred Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.129#you in flight and I killing you from behind; and there will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.130#be any rescue for you from your silvery-whirled strong-running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.131#river, for all the numbers of bulls you dedicate to it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.132#and drown single-foot horses alive in its eddies. And yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.133#even so, die all an evil death, till all of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.134#pay for the death of Patroklos and the slaughter of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.135#whom you killed beside the running ships, when I was not with them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.136#He spoke, but the anger was rising now in the heart of the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.137#and he pondered in his heart as to how he could stop the labour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.138#of brilliant Achilleus, and fend destruction away from the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.139#And now with the spear far shadowing in his hands Peleus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.140#was springing, furious to kill him, on Asteropaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.141#the son of Pelegon; who in turn was born of the wide-running river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.142#Axios, and of Periboia, eldest of the daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.143#of Akessamenos, for she lay in love with the deep-whirling river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.144#Against this man Achilleus rose up, and he came out to face him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.145#from the river, holding two spears, for Xanthos had inspired valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.146#into his heart, in anger for the slaughter of the young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.147#whom Achilleus had slain beside his waters and taken no pity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.148#Now as these two in their advance encountered together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.149#first of the two to speak was swift-footed brilliant Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.150#'What man are you, and whence, who dare stand up to my onset?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.151#Since unhappy are those whose sons match warcraft against me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.152#Then in turn the glorious son of Pelegon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.153#'High-hearted son of Peleus, why ask of my generation?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.154#I am from Paionia far away, where the soil is generous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.155#and lead the men of Paionia with long spears; and this for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.156#is the eleventh day since I arrived in Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.157#For my generation, it is from the broad waters of Axios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.158#Axios, who floods the land with the loveliest waters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.159#His son was Pelegon the spear-famed; but men say I am Pelegon's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.160#son; now, glorious Achilleus, we shall fight together.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.161#So he spoke, challenging, and brilliant Achilleus uplifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.162#the Pelian ash spear, but the warrior Asteropaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.163#threw with both spears at the same time, being ambidextrous.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.164#With the one spear he hit the shield but could not altogether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.165#break through the shield, since the gold stayed it that the god had given.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.166#With the other spear he struck Achilleus on the right forearm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.167#and grazed it so that the blood gushed out in a dark cloud, and the spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.168#overpassed him and fixed in the ground, straining to reach his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.169#Throwing second Achilleus let fly at Asteropaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.170#with the straight-flying ash spear in a fury to kill him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.171#but missed his man and hit the high bank, so that the ash spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.172#was driven half its length and stuck in the bank of the river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.173#But the son of Peleus, drawing from beside his thigh the sharp sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.174#sprang upon him in fury; and Asteropaios could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.175#with his heavy hand wrench Achilleus' ash spear free of the river-bank.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.176#Three times he struggled straining to wrench it clear, and three times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.177#gave over the effort, and now for the fourth time he was bending
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.178#over the ash spear of Aiakides, trying to break it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.179#but before this Achilleus took his life with the sword from close up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.180#for he struck him in the belly next the navel, and all his guts poured
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.181#out on the ground, and a mist of darkness closed over both eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.182#as he gasped life out, and springing upon his chest Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.183#stripped his armour away and spoke in triumph above him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.184#'Lie so: it is hard even for those sprung of a river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.185#to fight against the children of Kronos, whose strength is almighty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.186#You said you were of the generation of the wide-running river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.187#but I claim that I am of the generation of great Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.188#The man is my father who is lord over many Myrmidons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.189#Peleus, Aiakos' son, but Zeus was the father of Aiakos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.190#And as Zeus is stronger than rivers that run to the sea, so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.191#the generation of Zeus is made stronger than that of a river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.192#For here is a great river beside you, if he were able
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.193#to help; but it is not possible to fight Zeus, son of Kronos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.194#Not powerful Acheloios matches his strength against Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.195#not the enormous strength of Ocean with his deep-running waters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.196#Ocean, from whom all rivers are and the entire sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.197#and all springs and all deep wells have their waters of him, yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.198#even Ocean is afraid of the lightning of great Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.199#and the dangerous thunderbolt when it breaks from the sky crashing.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.200#So he spoke, and pulled the bronze spear free of the river bluff
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.201#and left him there, when he had torn the heart of life from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.202#sprawled in the sands and drenched in the dark water. And about
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.203#Asteropaios the eels and the other fish were busy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.204#tearing him and nibbling the fat that lay by his kidneys.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.205#But Achilleus went on after the Paionians crested with horse-hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.206#who had scattered in fear along the banks of the eddying river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.207#when they had seen their greatest man in the strong encounter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.208#gone down by force under the sword and the hands of Peleïdes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.209#There he killed Thersilochos and Astypylos and Mydon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.210#Mnesos and Thrasios, and Ainios and Ophelestes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.211#Now swift Achilleus would have killed even more Paionians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.212#except that the deep-whirling river spoke to him in anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.213#and in mortal likeness, and the voice rose from the depth of the eddies:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.214#'O Achilleus, your strength is greater, your acts more violent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.215#than all men's; since always the very gods are guarding you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.216#If the son of Kronos has given all Trojans to your destruction,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.217#drive them at least out of me to the plain, and there work your havoc.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.218#For the loveliness of my waters is crammed with corpses, I cannot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.219#find a channel to cast my waters into the bright sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.220#since I am congested with the dead men you kill so brutally.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.221#Let me alone, then; lord of the people, I am confounded.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.222#Then in answer to him spoke Achilleus of the swift feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.223#'All this, illustrious Skamandros, shall be as you order.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.224#But I will not leave off my killing of the proud Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.225#until I have penned them inside their city, and attempted Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.226#strength against strength, until he has killed me or I have killed him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.227#He spoke, and like something more than mortal swept down on the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.228#And now the deep-whirling river called aloud to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.229#'Shame, lord of the silver bow, Zeus' son; you have not kept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.230#the counsels of Kronion, who very strongly ordered you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.231#to stand by the Trojans and defend them, until the sun setting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.232#at last goes down and darkens all the generous ploughland.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.233#He spoke: and spear-famed Achilleus leapt into the middle water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.234#with a spring from the bluff, but the river in a boiling surge was upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.235#and rose making turbulent all his waters, and pushed off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.236#the many dead men whom Achilleus had killed piled in abundance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.237#in the stream; these, bellowing like a bull, he shoved out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.238#on the dry land, but saved the living in the sweet waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.239#hiding them under the huge depths of the whirling current.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.240#And about Achilleus in his confusion a dangerous wave rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.241#up, and beat against his shield and pushed it. He could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.242#brace himself with his feet, but caught with his hands at an elm tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.243#tall and strong grown, but this uptorn by the roots and tumbling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.244#ripped away the whole cliff and with its dense tangle of roots stopped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.245#the run of the lovely current and fallen full length in the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.246#dammed the very stream. Achilleus uprising out of the whirlpool
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.247#made a dash to get to the plain in the speed of his quick feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.248#in fear, but the great god would not let him be, but rose on him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.249#in a darkening edge of water, minded to stop the labour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.250#of brilliant Achilleus and fend destruction away from the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.251#The son of Peleus sprang away the length of a spearcast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.252#running with the speed of the black eagle, the marauder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.253#who is at once the strongest of flying things and the swiftest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.254#In the likeness of this he sped away, on his chest the bronze armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.255#clashed terribly, and bending away to escape from the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.256#he fled, but the river came streaming after him in huge noise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.257#And as a man running a channel from a spring of dark water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.258#guides the run of the water among his plants and his gardens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.259#with a mattock in his hand and knocks down the blocks in the channel;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.260#in the rush of the water all the pebbles beneath are torn loose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.261#from place, and the water that has been dripping suddenly jets on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.262#in a steep place and goes too fast even for the man who guides it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.263#so always the crest of the river was overtaking Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.264#for all his speed of foot, since gods are stronger than mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.265#And every time swift-footed brilliant Achilleus would begin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.266#to turn and stand and fight the river, and try to discover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.267#if all the gods who hold the wide heaven were after him, every
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.268#time again the enormous wave of the sky-fed river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.269#would strike his shoulders from above. He tried, in his desperation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.270#to keep a high spring with his feet, but the river was wearing his knees out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.271#as it ran fiercely beneath him and cut the ground from under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.272#his feet. Peleïdes groaned aloud, gazing into the wide sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.273#'Father Zeus, no god could endure to save me from the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.274#who am so pitiful. And what then shall become of me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.275#It is not so much any other Uranian god who has done this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.276#but my own mother who beguiled me with falsehoods, who told me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.277#that underneath the battlements of the armoured Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.278#I should be destroyed by the flying shafts of Apollo.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.279#I wish now Hektor had killed me, the greatest man grown in this place.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.280#A brave man would have been the slayer, as the slain was a brave man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.281#But now this is a dismal death I am doomed to be caught in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.282#trapped in a big river as if I were a boy and a swineherd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.283#swept away by a torrent when he tries to cross in a rainstorm.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.284#So he spoke, and Poseidon and Athene swiftly came near him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.285#and stood beside him with their shapes in the likeness of mortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.286#and caught him hand by hand and spoke to him in assurance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.287#First of them to speak was the shaker of the earth, Poseidon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.288#'Do not be afraid, son of Peleus, nor be so anxious,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.289#such are we two of the gods who stand beside you to help you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.290#by the consent of Zeus, myself and Pallas Athene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.291#Thereby it is not your destiny to be killed by the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.292#but he shall be presently stopped, and you yourself shall behold it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.293#'But we also have close counsel to give you, if you will believe us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.294#Do not let stay your hands from the collision of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.295#until you have penned the people of Troy, those who escape you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.296#inside the famed wall of Ilion. Then when you have taken Hektor's life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.297#go back again to the ships. We grant you the winning of glory.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.298#So speaking the two went back again among the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.299#but Achilleus went on, and the urgency of the gods strongly stirred him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.300#into the plain. But the river filled with an outrush of water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.301#and masses of splendid armour from the young men who had perished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.302#floated there, and their bodies, but against the hard drive of the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.303#straight on he kept a high spring with his feet, and the river wide running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.304#could not stop him now, since he was given great strength by Athene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.305#But Skamandros did not either abate his fury, but all the more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.306#raged at Peleion, and high uplifting the wave of his waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.307#gathered it to a crest, and called aloud upon Simoeis:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.308#'Beloved brother, let even the two of us join to hold back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.309#the strength of a man, since presently he will storm the great city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.310#of lord Priam. The Trojans cannot stand up to him in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.311#But help me beat him off with all speed, and make full your currents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.312#with water from your springs, and rouse up all of your torrents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.313#and make a big wave rear up and wake the heavy confusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.314#and sound of timbers and stones, so we can stop this savage man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.315#who is now in his strength and rages in fury like the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.316#For I say that his strength will not be enough for him nor his beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.317#nor his arms in their splendour, which somewhere deep down under the waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.318#shall lie folded under the mud; and I will whelm his own body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.319#deep, and pile it over with abundance of sands and rubble
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.320#numberless, nor shall the Achaians know where to look for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.321#his bones to gather them, such ruin will I pile over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.322#And there shall his monument be made, and he will have no need
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.323#of any funeral mound to be buried in by the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.324#He spoke, and rose against Achilleus, turbulent, boiling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.325#to a crest, muttering in foam and blood and dead bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.326#until the purple wave of the river fed from the bright sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.327#lifted high and caught in its waters the son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.328#But Hera, greatly fearing for Achilleus, cried in a loud voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.329#lest he be swept away in the huge deep-eddying river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.330#and at once thereafter appealed to her own dear son, Hephaistos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.331#'Rise up, god of the dragging feet, my child; for we believe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.332#that whirling Xanthos would be fit antagonist for you in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.333#Go now quickly to the help of Achilleus, make shine a great flame
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.334#while I raise up and bring in out of the sea a troublesome
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.335#storm of the west wind and the whitening south wind, a storm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.336#that will burn the heads of the Trojans and burn their armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.337#carrying the evil flame, while you by the banks of Xanthos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.338#set fire to the trees and throw fire on the river himself, and do not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.339#by any means let him turn you with winning words or revilements.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.340#Do not let your fury be stopped until such time as
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.341#I lift my voice and cry to you. Then stay your weariless burning.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.342#Hera spoke, and Hephaistos set on them an inhuman fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.343#First he kindled a fire in the plain and burned the numerous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.344#corpses that lay there in abundance, slain by Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.345#and all the plain was parched and the shining water was straitened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.346#As when the north wind of autumn suddenly makes dry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.347#a garden freshly watered and makes glad the man who is tending it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.348#so the entire flat land was dried up with Hephaistos burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.349#the dead bodies. Then he turned his flame in its shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.350#into the river. The elms burned, the willows and tamarisks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.351#the clover burned and the rushes and the galingale, all those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.352#plants that grew in abundance by the lovely stream of the river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.353#The eels were suffering and the fish in the whirl of the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.354#who leaped out along the lovely waters in every direction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.355#in affliction under the hot blast of resourceful Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.356#The strength of the river was burning away; he gave voice and called out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.357#by name: 'Hephaistos, not one of the gods could stand up against you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.358#I for one could not fight the flame of a fire like this one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.359#Leave your attack. Brilliant Achilleus can capture the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.360#of the Trojans, now, for me. What have I to do with this quarrel?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.361#He spoke, blazing with fire, and his lovely waters were seething.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.362#And as a cauldron that is propped over a great fire boils up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.363#dancing on its whole circle with dry sticks burning beneath it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.364#as it melts down the fat of swine made tender, so Xanthos'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.365#lovely streams were burned with the fire, and the water was boiling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.366#and would not flow along but was stopped under stress of the hot blast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.367#strongly blown by resourceful Hephaistos. And now the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.368#cried out to Hera in the winged words of strong supplication:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.369#'Hera, why did your son assault me to trouble my waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.370#beyond others'? It is not so much I who have done anything against you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.371#as all the rest of the gods who stand by to help the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.372#Now indeed I will leave off, if such is your order,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.373#but let him leave off too, I will swear you a promise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.374#not ever to drive the day of evil away from the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.375#not even when all the city of Troy is burned in the ravening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.376#fire, on that day when the warlike sons of the Achaians burn it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.377#Now when the goddess of the white arms, Hera, had heard this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.378#immediately she spoke to her own dear son, Hephaistos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.379#'Hephaistos, hold, my glorious child, since it is not fitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.380#to batter thus an immortal god for the sake of mortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.381#So she spoke, and Hephaistos quenched his inhuman fire. Now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.382#the lovely waters ran their ripples back in the channel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.383#But when the strength of Xanthos had been beaten, these two gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.384#rested, since Hera, for all she was still angry, restrained them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.385#But upon the other gods descended the wearisome burden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.386#of hatred, and the wind of their fury blew from division,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.387#and they collided with a grand crash, the broad earth echoing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.388#and the huge sky sounded as with trumpets. Zeus heard it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.389#from where he sat on Olympos, and was amused in his deep heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.390#for pleasure, as he watched the gods' collision in conflict.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.391#Thereafter they stood not long apart from each other, for Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.392#began it, the shield-stabber, and rose up against Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.393#with the brazen spear in his hand, and spoke a word of revilement:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.394#'Why once more, you dogfly, have you stirred up trouble among the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.395#with the blast of your blown fury, and the pride of your heart driving you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.396#Do you not remember how you set on Diomedes, Tydeus'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.397#son, to spear me, and yourself laying hold of the far-seen pike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.398#pushed it straight into me and tore my skin in its beauty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.399#So now I am minded to pay you back for all you have done me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.400#He spoke, and stabbed against the ghastly aegis with fluttering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.401#straps, which gives way not even before the bolt of Zeus' lightning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.402#There blood-dripping Ares made his stab with the long spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.403#but Athene giving back caught up in her heavy hand a stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.404#that lay in the plain, black and rugged and huge, one which men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.405#of a former time had set there as boundary mark of the cornfield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.406#With this she hit furious Ares in the neck, and unstrung him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.407#He spread over seven acres in his fall, and his hair dragged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.408#in the dust, and his armour clashed. But Pallas Athene laughing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.409#stood above him and spoke to him in the winged words of triumph:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.410#'You child; you did not think even this time how much stronger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.411#I can claim I am than you, when you match your fury against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.412#Therefore you are paying atonement to your mother's furies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.413#since she is angry and wishes you ill, because you abandoned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.414#the Achaians, and have given your aid to the insolent Trojans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.415#She spoke, and turned the shining of her eyes away. But taking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.416#Ares by the hand the daughter of Zeus, Aphrodite,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.417#led him away, groaning always, his strength scarce gathered back into him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.418#But now, as the goddess of the white arms, Hera, noticed her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.419#immediately she spoke to Pallas Athene her winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.420#'For shame now, Atrytone, daughter of Zeus of the aegis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.421#Here again is this dogfly leading murderous Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.422#out of the fighting and through the confusion. Quick, go after her!'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.423#She spoke, and Athene swept in pursuit, heart full of gladness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.424#and caught up with her and drove a blow at her breasts with her ponderous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.425#hand, so that her knees went slack and the heart inside her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.426#Those two both lay sprawled on the generous earth. But Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.427#stood above them and spoke to them in the winged words of triumph:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.428#'Now may all who bring their aid to the Trojans be in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.429#such case as these, when they do battle with the armoured Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.430#as daring and as unfortunate, as now Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.431#came companion in arms to Ares, and faced my fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.432#So we should long ago have rested after our fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.433#once having utterly stormed the strong-founded city of Ilion.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.434#She spoke, and the goddess of the white arms, Hera, smiled on her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.435#But now the powerful shaker of the earth spoke to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.436#'Phoibos, why do you and I stand yet apart. It does not suit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.437#when the others have begun, and it were too shameful if without fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.438#we go back to the brazen house of Zeus on Olympos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.439#Begin, you; you are younger born than I; it is not well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.440#for me to, since I am elder born than you, and know more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.441#Young fool, what a mindless heart you have. Can you not even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.442#now remember all the evils we endured here by Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.443#you and I alone of the gods, when to proud Laomedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.444#we came down from Zeus and for a year were his servants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.445#for a stated hire, and he told us what to do, and to do it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.446#Then I built a wall for the Trojans about their city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.447#wide, and very splendid, so none could break into their city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.448#but you, Phoibos, herded his shambling horn-curved cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.449#along the spurs of Ida with all her folds and her forests.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.450#But when the changing seasons brought on the time for our labour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.451#to be paid, then headstrong Laomedon violated and made void
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.452#all our hire, and sent us away, and sent threats after us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.453#For he threatened to hobble our feet and to bind our arms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.454#to carry us away for slaves in the far-lying islands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.455#He was even going to strip with bronze the ears from both of us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.456#Then you and I took our way back with hearts full of anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.457#and wrath for our hire which he promised us and would not accomplish it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.458#Yet to his people you give now your grace, and you will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.459#try with us to bring destruction on the insolent Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.460#evil and complete, with their honoured wives and their children.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.461#In turn the lord who strikes from afar, Apollo, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.462#'Shaker of the earth, you would have me be as one without prudence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.463#if I am to fight even you for the sake of insignificant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.464#mortals, who are as leaves are, and now flourish and grow warm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.465#with life, and feed on what the ground gives, but then again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.466#fade away and are dead. Therefore let us with all speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.467#give up this quarrel and let the mortals fight their own battles.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.468#He spoke so and turned away, for he was too modest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.469#to close and fight in strength of hand with his father's brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.470#But his sister, Artemis of the wild, the lady of wild beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.471#scolded him bitterly and spoke a word of revilement:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.472#'You run from him, striker from afar. You have yielded Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.473#the victory entire. He can brag, where nothing has happened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.474#Fool, then why do you wear that bow, which is wind and nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.475#Let me not hear you in the halls of my father boasting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.476#ever again, as you did before among the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.477#that you could match your strength in combat against Poseidon.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.478#So she spoke, but Apollo who strikes from afar said nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.479#to her; but the august consort of Zeus, full of anger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.480#scolded the lady of showering arrows in words of revilement:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.481#'How have you had the daring, you shameless hussy, to stand up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.482#and face me? It will be hard for you to match your strength with mine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.483#even if you wear a bow, since Zeus has made you a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.484#among women, and given you leave to kill any at your pleasure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.485#Better for you to hunt down the ravening beasts in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.486#and deer of the wilds, than try to fight in strength with your betters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.487#But if you would learn what fighting is, come on. You will find out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.488#how much stronger I am when you try to match strength against me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.489#She spoke, and caught both of her arms at the wrists in her left hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.490#and with her right hand stripped away the bow from her shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.491#then with her own bow, smiling, boxed her ears as Artemis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.492#tried to twist away, and the flying arrows were scattered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.493#She got under and free and fled in tears, as a pigeon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.494#in flight from a hawk wings her way into some rock-hollow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.495#and a cave, since it was not destiny for the hawk to catch her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.496#So she left her archery on the ground, and fled weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.497#Meanwhile the Guide, Argeïphontes, addressed him to Leto:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.498#'Leto, I will not fight with you; since it is a hard thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.499#to come to blows with the brides of Zeus who gathers the clouds. No,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.500#sooner you may freely speak among the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.501#gods, and claim that you were stronger than I, and beat me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.502#So he spoke, but Leto picked up the curved bow and the arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.503#which had fallen in the turn of the dust one way and another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.504#When she had taken up the bow she went back to her daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.505#But the maiden came to the bronze-founded house on Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.506#of Zeus, and took her place kneeling at the knees of her father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.507#and the ambrosial veil trembled about her. Her father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.508#Kronides caught her against him, and laughed softly, and questioned her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.509#'Who now of the Uranian gods, dear child, has done such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.510#things to you, rashly, as if you were caught doing something wicked?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.511#Artemis sweet-garlanded lady of clamours answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.512#'It was your wife, Hera of the white arms, who hit me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.513#father, since hatred and fighting have fastened upon the immortals.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.514#Now as these two were talking thus to each other, meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.515#Phoibos Apollo went into the sacred city of Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.516#since he was concerned for the wall of the strong-founded city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.517#lest the Danaans storm it on that day, before they were fated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.518#The rest of the gods who live forever went back to Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.519#some in anger and others glorying greatly, and sat down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.520#at the side of their father the dark-misted. Meanwhile Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.521#was destroying alike the Trojans themselves and their single-foot horses;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.522#and as when smoke ascending goes up into the wide sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.523#from a burning city, with the anger of the gods let loose upon it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.524#which inflicted labour upon them all, and sorrow on many,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.525#so Achilleus inflicted labour and sorrow upon the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.526#The aged Priam had taken his place on the god-built bastion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.527#and looked out and saw gigantic Achilleus, where before him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.528#the Trojans fled in the speed of their confusion, no war strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.529#left them. He groaned and descended to the ground from the bastion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.530#and beside the wall set in motion the glorious guards of the gateway;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.531#'Hold the gates wide open in your hands, so that our people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.532#in their flight can get inside the city, for here is Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.533#close by, stampeding them, and I think there will be disaster.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.534#But once they are crowded inside the city and get wind again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.535#shut once more the door-leaves closely fitted together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.536#I am afraid this ruinous man may spring into our stronghold.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.537#He spoke, and they spread open the gates and shoved back the door bars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.538#and the gates opening let in daylight. Meanwhile Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.539#sprang out to meet them, so that he could fend off destruction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.540#from the Trojans, who, straight for the city and the lift of the rampart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.541#dusty from the plain and throats rugged with thirst, fled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.542#away, and Achilleus followed fiercely with the spear, strong madness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.543#forever holding his heart and violent after his glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.544#There the sons of the Achaians might have taken gate-towering Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.545#had not Phoibos Apollo sent on them brilliant Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.546#a man who was the son of Antenor, blameless and powerful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.547#He drove courage into his heart, and stood there beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.548#in person, so as to beat the dragging death spirits from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.549#and leaned there on an oak tree with close mist huddled about him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.550#When Agenor was aware of Achilleus, sacker of cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.551#he stood fast, but the heart was a storm in him as he waited,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.552#and deeply disturbed he spoke to his own great-hearted spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.553#'Ah me! if I run away before the strength of Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.554#in the way that others are stampeded in terror before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.555#he will catch me even so and cut my throat like a coward's.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.556#But if I leave these men to be driven in flight by Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.557#Peleus' son, and run on my feet in another direction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.558#away from the wall to the plain of Ilion, until I come to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.559#the spurs of Ida, and take cover there within the undergrowth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.560#then in the evening, when I have bathed in the river, and washed off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.561#the sweat, I could make my way back again to Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.562#Yet still, why does the heart within me debate on these things?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.563#This way, he might see me as I started to the plain from the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.564#and go in pursuit, and in the speed of his feet overtake me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.565#Then there will be no way to escape death and the death spirits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.566#He is too strong, his strength is beyond all others'. But then if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.567#I go out in front of the city and stand fast against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.568#I think even his body might be torn by the sharp bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.569#There is only one life in him, and people say he is mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.570#It is only that Zeus, the son of Kronos, is granting him glory.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.571#He spoke, and gathered himself to await Achilleus, and in him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.572#the fighting heart was urgent for the encounter of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.573#But as a leopard emerges out of her timbered cover
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.574#to face the man who is hunting her, and takes no terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.575#in her heart nor thought of flight when she hears them baying against her;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.576#and even though one be too quick for her with spear thrust or spear thrown
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.577#stuck with the shaft though she be she will not give up her fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.578#fury, till she has closed with one of them or is overthrown;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.579#so the son of proud Antenor, brilliant Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.580#was unwilling to run away until he had tested Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.581#but held the perfect circle of his shield in front of him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.582#and with the spear aimed at him and cried out in a great voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.583#'You must have hoped within your heart, o shining Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.584#on this day to storm the city of the proud Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.585#You fool! There is much hard suffering to be done for its winning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.586#since there are many of us inside, and men who are fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.587#who will stand before our beloved parents, our wives and our children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.588#to defend Ilion; but in this place you will find your destiny,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.589#for all you are so headlong and so bold a warrior.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.590#He spoke, and from his heavy hand let fly with the sharp spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.591#and struck him in the leg below the knee, nor entirely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.592#missed him, and taking the spear the greave of new-wrought tin clattered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.593#horribly, and back from the struck greave the bronze rebounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.594#without getting through, but the gift of the god defended Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.595#After him Peleus' son made his spring at godlike Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.596#but Apollo would no further grant him the winning of glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.597#but caught Agenor away closing him in a dense mist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.598#and sent him to make his way quietly out of the battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.599#Then by deception he kept Peleion away from the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.600#The striker from afar likened himself in all ways to Agenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.601#and stood there before his feet, and Achilleus sprang in chase of him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.602#in the speed of his feet; for the time he chased him across the wheat-bearing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.603#plain, turning him toward the deep whirls of the river Skamandros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.604#as he ran a little in front; with the trick Apollo beguiled him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.605#so that he hoped ever by running to catch up with him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.606#all this time the rest of the Trojans fled in a body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.607#gladly into the town, and the city was filled with their swarming.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.608#They dared no longer outside the wall and outside the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.609#to wait for each other and find out which one had got away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.610#and who had died in the battle, so hastily were they streaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:21.611#into the city, each man as his knees and feet could rescue him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.1#So along the city the Trojans, who had run like fawns, dried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.2#the sweat off from their bodies and drank and slaked their thirst, leaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.3#along the magnificent battlements. Meanwhile the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.4#sloping their shields across their shoulders came close to the rampart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.5#But his deadly fate held Hektor shackled, so that he stood fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.6#in front of Ilion and the Skaian gates. Now Phoibos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.7#Apollo spoke aloud to Peleion: 'Why, son of Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.8#do you keep after me in the speed of your feet, being mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.9#while I am an immortal god? Even yet you have not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.10#seen that I am a god, but strain after me in your fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.11#Now hard fighting with the Trojans whom you stampeded means nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.12#to you. They are crowded in the city, but you bent away here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.13#You will never kill me. I am not one who is fated.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.14#Deeply vexed Achilleus of the swift feet spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.15#'You have balked me, striker from afar, most malignant of all gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.16#when you turned me here away from the rampart, else many Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.17#would have caught the soil in their teeth before they got back into Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.18#Now you have robbed me of great glory, and rescued these people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.19#lightly, since you have no retribution to fear hereafter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.20#Else I would punish you, if only the strength were in me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.21#He spoke, and stalked away against the city, with high thoughts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.22#in mind, and in tearing speed, like a racehorse with his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.23#who runs lightly as he pulls the chariot over the flat land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.24#Such was the action of Achilleus in feet and quick knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.25#The aged Priam was the first of all whose eyes saw him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.26#as he swept across the flat land in full shining, like that star
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.27#which comes on in the autumn and whose conspicuous brightness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.28#far outshines the stars that are numbered in the night's darkening,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.29#the star they give the name of Orion's Dog, which is brightest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.30#among the stars, and yet is wrought as a sign of evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.31#and brings on the great fever for unfortunate mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.32#Such was the flare of the bronze that girt his chest in his running.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.33#The old man groaned aloud and with both hands high uplifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.34#beat his head, and groaned amain, and spoke supplicating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.35#his beloved son, who there still in front of the gateway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.36#stood fast in determined fury to fight with Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.37#The old man stretching his hands out called pitifully to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.38#'Hektor, beloved child, do not wait the attack of this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.39#alone, away from the others. You might encounter your destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.40#beaten down by Peleion, since he is far stronger than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.41#A hard man: I wish he were as beloved of the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.42#as loved by me. Soon he would lie dead, and the dogs and the vultures
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.43#would eat him, and bitter sorrow so be taken from my heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.44#He has made me desolate of my sons, who were brave and many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.45#He killed them, or sold them away among the far-lying islands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.46#Even now there are two sons, Lykaon and Polydoros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.47#whom I cannot see among the Trojans pent up in the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.48#sons Laothoëa princess among women bore to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.49#But if these are alive somewhere in the army, then I can
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.50#set them free for bronze and gold; it is there inside, since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.51#Altes the aged and renowned gave much with his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.52#But if they are dead already and gone down to the house of Hades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.53#it is sorrow to our hearts, who bore them, myself and their mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.54#but to the rest of the people a sorrow that will be fleeting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.55#beside their sorrow for you, if you go down before Achilleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.56#Come then inside the wall, my child, so that you can rescue
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.57#the Trojans and the women of Troy, neither win the high glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.58#for Peleus' son, and yourself be robbed of your very life. Oh, take
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.59#pity on me, the unfortunate still alive, still sentient
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.60#but ill-starred, whom the father, Kronos' son, on the threshold of old age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.61#will blast with hard fate, after I have looked upon evils
