urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.227#and likened herself in form and weariless voice to Deïphobos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.228#She came now and stood close to him and addressed him in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.229#'Dear brother, indeed swift-footed Achilleus is using you roughly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.230#and chasing you on swift feet around the city of Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.231#Come on, then; let us stand fast against him and beat him back from us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.232#Then tall Hektor of the shining helm answered her: 'Deïphobos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.233#before now you were dearest to me by far of my brothers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.234#of all those who were sons of Priam and Hekabe, and now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.235#I am minded all the more within my heart to honour you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.236#you who dared for my sake, when your eyes saw me, to come forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.237#from the fortifications, while the others stand fast inside them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.238#Then in turn the goddess grey-eyed Athene answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.239#'My brother, it is true our father and the lady our mother, taking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.240#my knees in turn, and my companions about me, entreated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.241#that I stay within, such was the terror upon all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.242#But the heart within me was worn away by hard sorrow for you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.243#But now let us go straight on and fight hard, let there be no sparing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.244#of our spears, so that we can find out whether Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.245#will kill us both and carry our bloody war spoils back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.246#to the hollow ships, or will himself go down under your spear.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.247#So Athene spoke and led him on by beguilement.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.248#Now as the two in their advance were come close together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.249#first of the two to speak was tall helm-glittering Hektor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.250#'Son of Peleus, I will no longer run from you, as before this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.251#I fled three times around the great city of Priam, and dared not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.252#stand to your onfall. But now my spirit in turn has driven me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.253#to stand and face you. I must take you now, or I must be taken.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.254#Come then, shall we swear before the gods? For these are the highest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.255#who shall be witnesses and watch over our agreements.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.256#Brutal as you are I will not defile you, if Zeus grants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.257#to me that I can wear you out, and take the life from you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.258#But after I have stripped your glorious armour, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.259#I will give your corpse back to the Achaians. Do you do likewise.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.260#Then looking darkly at him swift-footed Achilleus answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.261#'Hektor, argue me no agreements. I cannot forgive you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.262#As there are no trustworthy oaths between men and lions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.263#nor wolves and lambs have spirit that can be brought to agreement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.264#but forever these hold feelings of hate for each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.265#so there can be no love between you and me, nor shall there be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.266#oaths between us, but one or the other must fall before then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.267#to glut with his blood Ares the god who fights under the shield's guard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.268#Remember every valour of yours, for now the need comes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.269#hardest upon you to be a spearman and a bold warrior.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.270#There shall be no more escape for you, but Pallas Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.271#will kill you soon by my spear. You will pay in a lump for all those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.272#sorrows of my companions you killed in your spear's fury.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.273#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far shadowed, and threw it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.274#but glorious Hektor kept his eyes on him, and avoided it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.275#for he dropped, watchful, to his knee, and the bronze spear flew over his shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.276#and stuck in the ground, but Pallas Athene snatched it, and gave it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.277#back to Achilleus, unseen by Hektor shepherd of the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.278#But now Hektor spoke out to the blameless son of Peleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.279#'You missed; and it was not, o Achilleus like the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.280#from Zeus that you knew my destiny; but you thought so; or rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.281#you are someone clever in speech and spoke to swindle me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.282#to make me afraid of you and forget my valour and war strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.283#You will not stick your spear in my back as I run away from you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.284#but drive it into my chest as I storm straight in against you;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.285#if the god gives you that; and now look out for my brazen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.286#spear. I wish it might be taken full length in your body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.287#And indeed the war would be a lighter thing for the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.288#if you were dead, seeing that you are their greatest affliction.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.289#So he spoke, and balanced the spear far shadowed, and threw it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.290#and struck the middle of Peleïdes' shield, nor missed it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.291#but the spear was driven far back from the shield, and Hektor was angered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.292#because his swift weapon had been loosed from his hand in a vain cast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.293#He stood discouraged, and had no other ash spear; but lifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.294#his voice he called aloud on Deïphobos of the pale shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.295#and asked him for a long spear, but Deïphobos was not near him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.296#And Hektor knew the truth inside his heart, and spoke aloud:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.297#'No use. Here at last the gods have summoned me deathward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.298#I thought Deïphobos the hero was here close beside me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.299#but he is behind the wall and it was Athene cheating me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.300#and now evil death is close to me, and no longer far away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.301#and there is no way out. So it must long since have been pleasing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.302#to Zeus, and Zeus' son who strikes from afar, this way; though before this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.303#they defended me gladly. But now my death is upon me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.304#Let me at least not die without a struggle, inglorious,
