urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.349#from your head, not if they bring here and set before me ten times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.350#and twenty times the ransom, and promise more in addition,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.351#not if Priam son of Dardanos should offer to weigh out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.352#your bulk in gold; not even so shall the lady your mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.353#who herself bore you lay you on the death-bed and mourn you:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.354#no, but the dogs and the birds will have you all for their feasting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.355#Then, dying, Hektor of the shining helmet spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.356#'I know you well as I look upon you, I know that I could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.357#persuade you, since indeed in your breast is a heart of iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.358#Be careful now; for I might be made into the gods' curse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.359#upon you, on that day when Paris and Phoibos Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.360#destroy you in the Skaian gates, for all your valour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.361#He spoke, and as he spoke the end of death closed in upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.362#and the soul fluttering free of the limbs went down into Death's house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.363#mourning her destiny, leaving youth and manhood behind her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.364#Now though he was a dead man brilliant Achilleus spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.365#'Die: and I will take my own death at whatever time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.366#Zeus and the rest of the immortals choose to accomplish it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.367#He spoke, and pulled the brazen spear from the body, and laid it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.368#on one side, and stripped away from the shoulders the bloody
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.369#armour. And the other sons of the Achaians came running about him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.370#and gazed upon the stature and on the imposing beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.371#of Hektor; and none stood beside him who did not stab him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.372#and thus they would speak one to another, each looking at his neighbour:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.373#'See now, Hektor is much softer to handle than he was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.374#when he set the ships ablaze with the burning firebrand.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.375#So as they stood beside him they would speak, and stab him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.376#But now, when he had despoiled the body, swift-footed brilliant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.377#Achilleus stood among the Achaians and addressed them in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.378#'Friends, who are leaders of the Argives and keep their counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.379#since the gods have granted me the killing of this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.380#who has done us much damage, such as not all the others together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.381#have done, come, let us go in armour about the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.382#to see if we can find out what purpose is in the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.383#whether they will abandon their high city, now that this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.384#has fallen, or are minded to stay, though Hektor lives no longer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.385#Yet still, why does the heart within me debate on these things?
