urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.463#she stopped, staring, on the wall; and she saw him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.464#being dragged in front of the city, and the running horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.465#dragged him at random toward the hollow ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.466#The darkness of night misted over the eyes of Andromache.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.467#She fell backward, and gasped the life breath from her, and far off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.468#threw from her head the shining gear that ordered her headdress,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.469#the diadem and the cap, and the holding-band woven together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.470#and the circlet, which Aphrodite the golden once had given her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.471#on that day when Hektor of the shining helmet led her forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.472#from the house of Eëtion, and gave numberless gifts to win her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.473#And about her stood thronging her husband's sisters and the wives of his brothers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.474#and these, in her despair for death, held her up among them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.475#But she, when she breathed again and the life was gathered back into her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.476#lifted her voice among the women of Troy in mourning:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.477#'Hektor, I grieve for you. You and I were born to a single
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.478#destiny, you in Troy in the house of Priam, and I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.479#in Thebe, underneath the timbered mountain of Plakos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.480#in the house of Eëtion, who cared for me when I was little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.481#ill-fated he, I ill-starred. I wish he had never begotten me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.482#Now you go down to the house of Death in the secret places
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.483#of the earth, and left me here behind in the sorrow of mourning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.484#a widow in your house, and the boy is only a baby
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.485#who was born to you and me, the unfortunate. You cannot help him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.486#Hektor, any more, since you are dead. Nor can he help you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.487#Though he escape the attack of the Achaians with all its sorrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.488#yet all his days for your sake there will be hard work for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.489#and sorrows, for others will take his lands away from him. The day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.490#of bereavement leaves a child with no agemates to befriend him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.491#He bows his head before every man, his cheeks are bewept, he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.492#goes, needy, a boy among his father's companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.493#and tugs at this man by the mantle, that man by the tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.494#and they pity him, and one gives him a tiny drink from a goblet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.495#enough to moisten his lips, not enough to moisten his palate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.496#But one whose parents are living beats him out of the banquet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.497#hitting him with his fists and in words also abuses him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.498#"Get out, you! Your father is not dining among us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.499#And the boy goes away in tears to his widowed mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.500#Astyanax, who in days before on the knees of his father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.501#would eat only the marrow or the flesh of sheep that was fattest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.502#And when sleep would come upon him and he was done with his playing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.503#he would go to sleep in a bed, in the arms of his nurse, in a soft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.504#bed, with his heart given all its fill of luxury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.505#Now, with his dear father gone, he has much to suffer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.506#he, whom the Trojans have called Astyanax, lord of the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.507#since it was you alone who defended the gates and the long walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.508#But now, beside the curving ships, far away from your parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.509#the writhing worms will feed, when the dogs have had enough of you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.510#on your naked corpse, though in your house there is clothing laid up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.511#that is fine-textured and pleasant, wrought by the hands of women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.512#But all of these I will burn up in the fire's blazing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.513#no use to you, since you will never be laid away in them;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.514#but in your honour, from the men of Troy and the Trojan women.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:22.515#So she spoke, in tears; and the women joined in her mourning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.1#So they were mourning through the city. Meanwhile, the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.2#after they had made their way back to their ships and the Hellespont,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.3#scattered, the rest of them, each man to his own ship. Except
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.4#Achilleus would not allow the Myrmidons to be scattered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.5#but called out to his companions whose delight was in battle:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.6#'Myrmidons, you of the fast horses, my steadfast companions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.7#we must not yet slip free of the chariots our single-foot horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.8#but with these very horses and chariots we must drive close up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.9#to Patroklos and mourn him, since such is the privilege of the perished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.10#Then, when we have taken full satisfaction from the sorrowful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.11#dirge, we shall set our horses free, and all of us eat here.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.12#He spoke, and all of them assembled moaned, and Achilleus led them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.13#Three times, mourning, they drove their horses with flowing manes about
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.14#the body, and among them Thetis stirred the passion for weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.15#The sands were wet, and the armour of men was wet with their tears. Such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.16#was their longing after Patroklos, who drove men to thoughts of terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.17#Peleus' son led the thronging chant of their lamentation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.18#and laid his manslaughtering hands over the chest of his dear friend:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.19#'Good-bye, Patroklos. I hail you even in the house of the death god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.20#All that I promised you in time past I am accomplishing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.21#that I would drag Hektor here and give him to the dogs to feed on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.22#raw, and before your burning pyre to behead twelve glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.23#children of the Trojans for my anger over your slaying.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.24#He spoke, and thought of shameful treatment for glorious Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.25#He laid him on his face in the dust by the bier of Menoitios'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.26#son. Meanwhile the others took off each man his glittering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.27#brazen armour, and all unyoked their proud neighing horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.28#and sat down in their thousands beside the ship of swift-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.29#Aiakides, who set the funeral feast in abundance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.30#before them; and many shining oxen were slaughtered with the stroke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.31#of the iron, and many sheep and bleating goats and numerous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.32#swine with shining teeth and the fat abundant upon them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.33#were singed and stretched out across the flame of Hephaistos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.34#The blood ran and was caught in cups all around the dead man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.35#But now the kings of the Achaians brought the swift-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.36#lord, the son of Peleus, to great Agamemnon, hardly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.37#persuading him, since his heart was still angered for his companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.38#When these had made their way to the shelter of Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.39#straightway they gave orders to the heralds, the clear crying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.40#to set a great cauldron over the fire, if so they might persuade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.41#the son of Peleus to wash away the filth of the bloodstains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.42#but he denied them stubbornly and swore an oath on it:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.43#'No, before Zeus, who is greatest of gods and the highest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.44#there is no right in letting water come near my head, until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.45#I have laid Patroklos on the burning pyre, and heaped the mound over him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.46#and cut my hair for him, since there will come no second sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.47#like this to my heart again while I am still one of the living.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.48#Then let us now give way to the gloomy feast; and with the dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.49#cause your people to rise, o lord of men Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.50#and bring in timber and lay it by, with all that is fitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.51#for the dead man to have when he goes down under the gloom and the darkness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.52#so that with the more speed the unwearying fire may burn him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.53#away from our eyes, and the people turn back to that which they must do.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.54#So he spoke, and they listened well to him and obeyed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.55#and in speed and haste they got the dinner ready, and each man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.56#feasted, nor was any men's hunger denied a fair portion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.57#But when they had put aside their desire for eating and drinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.58#they went away to sleep, each man into his own shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.59#but along the beach of the thunderous sea the son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.60#lay down, groaning heavily, among the Myrmidon numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.61#in a clear place where the waves washed over the beach; and at that time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.62#sleep caught him and was drifted sweetly about him, washing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.63#the sorrows out of his mind, for his shining limbs were grown weary
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.64#indeed, from running in chase of Hektor toward windy Ilion;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.65#and there appeared to him the ghost of unhappy Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.66#all in his likeness for stature, and the lovely eyes, and voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.67#and wore such clothing as Patroklos had worn on his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.68#The ghost came and stood over his head and spoke a word to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.69#'You sleep, Achilleus; you have forgotten me; but you were not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.70#careless of me when I lived, but only in death. Bury me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.71#as quickly as may be, let me pass through the gates of Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.72#The souls, the images of dead men, hold me at a distance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.73#and will not let me cross the river and mingle among them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.74#but I wander as I am by Hades' house of the wide gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.75#And I call upon you in sorrow, give me your hand; no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.76#shall I come back from death, once you give me my rite of burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.77#No longer shall you and I, alive, sit apart from our other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.78#beloved companions and make our plans, since the bitter destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.79#that was given me when I was born has opened its jaws to take me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.80#And you, Achilleus like the gods, have your own destiny;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.81#to be killed under the wall of the prospering Trojans. There is one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.82#more thing I will say, and ask of you, if you will obey me:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.83#do not have my bones laid apart from yours, Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.84#but with them, just as we grew up together in your house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.85#when Menoitios brought me there from Opous, when I was little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.86#and into your house, by reason of a baneful manslaying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.87#on that day when I killed the son of Amphidamas. I was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.88#a child only, nor intended it, but was angered over a dice game.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.89#There the rider Peleus took me into his own house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.90#and brought me carefully up, and named me to be your henchman.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.91#Therefore, let one single vessel, the golden two-handled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.92#urn the lady your mother gave you, hold both our ashes.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.93#Then in answer to him spoke swift-footed Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.94#'How is it, o hallowed head of my brother, you have come back to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.95#here, and tell me all these several things? Yet surely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.96#I am accomplishing all, and I shall do as you tell me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.97#But stand closer to me, and let us, if only for a little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.98#embrace, and take full satisfaction from the dirge of sorrow.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.99#So he spoke, and with his own arms reached for him, but could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.100#take him, but the spirit went underground, like vapour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.101#with a thin cry, and Achilleus started awake, staring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.102#and drove his hands together, and spoke, and his words were sorrowful:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.103#'Oh, wonder! Even in the house of Hades there is left something,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.104#a soul and an image, but there is no real heart of life in it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.105#For all night long the phantom of unhappy Patroklos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.106#stood over me in lamentation and mourning, and the likeness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.107#to him was wonderful, and it told me each thing I should do.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.108#So he spoke, and stirred in all of them the passion of mourning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.109#and Dawn of the rose fingers showed on them as still they mourned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.110#about the forlorn body. Now powerful Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.111#gave order for men and mules to assemble from all the shelters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.112#and bring in timber, and a great man led them in motion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.113#Meriones, the henchman of courtly Idomeneus. These then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.114#went out and in their hands carried axes to cut wood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.115#and ropes firmly woven, and their mules went on ahead of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.116#They went many ways, uphill, downhill, sidehill and slantwise;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.117#but when they came to the spurs of Ida with all her well springs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.118#they set to hewing with the thin edge of bronze and leaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.119#their weight to the strokes on towering-leafed oak trees that toppled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.120#with huge crashing; then the Achaians splitting the timbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.121#fastened them to the mules and these with their feet tore up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.122#the ground as they pulled through the dense undergrowth to the flat land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.123#All the woodcutters carried logs themselves; such was the order
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.124#of Meriones, the henchman of courtly Idomeneus. These then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.125#threw down their burdens in order along the beach, where Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.126#had chosen place for a huge grave mound, for himself and Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.127#Then when on all sides they had thrown down abundance of timber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.128#they sat down where they were, assembled. And now Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.129#gave order at once to the Myrmidons, whose delight was in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.130#to belt themselves in bronze and each man to yoke his horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.131#to the chariot. And they rose up and got into their armour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.132#and stepped up, charioteer and sideman, into the chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.133#with the horsemen in front, and behind them came on a cloud of foot-soldiers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.134#by thousands; and in the midst his companions carried Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.135#They covered all the corpse under the locks of their hair, which they cut off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.136#and dropped on him, and behind them brilliant Achilleus held the head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.137#sorrowing, for this was his true friend he escorted toward Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.138#When these had come to the place Achilleus had spoken of to them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.139#they laid him down, and quickly piled up abundant timber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.140#And now brilliant swift-footed Achilleus remembered one more thing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.141#He stood apart from the pyre and cut off a lock of fair hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.142#which he had grown long to give to the river Spercheios, and gazing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.143#in deep distress out over the wine-blue water, he spoke forth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.144#'Spercheios, it was in vain that Peleus my father vowed to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.145#that there, when I had won home to the beloved land of my fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.146#I would cut my hair for you and make you a grand and holy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.147#sacrifice of fifty rams consecrate to the waters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.148#of your springs, where is your holy ground and your smoking altar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.149#So the old man vowed, but you did not accomplish his purpose.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.150#Now, since I do not return to the beloved land of my fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.151#I would give my hair into the keeping of the hero Patroklos.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.152#He spoke, and laid his hair in the hands of his beloved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.153#companion, and stirred in all of them the passion of mourning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.154#And now the light of the sum would have set on their lamentation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.155#had not Achilleus soon stood by Agamemnon and spoken:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.156#'Son of Atreus, beyond others the people of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.157#will obey your words. There can be enough, even in mourning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.158#Now cause them to scatter from the fire and bid them make ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.159#their dinner; and we, who are most nearly concerned with the dead man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.160#shall do this work; except only let the leaders stay near us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.161#Then the lord of men, Agamemnon, when he had heard this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.162#at once caused the people to disperse among the balanced ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.163#but the close mourners stayed by the place and piled up the timber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.164#and built a pyre a hundred feet long this way and that way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.165#and on the peak of the pyre they laid the body, sorrowful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.166#at heart; and in front of it skinned and set in order numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.167#of fat sheep and shambling horn-curved cattle; and from all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.168#great-hearted Achilleus took the fat and wrapped the corpse in it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.169#from head to foot, and piled up the skinned bodies about it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.170#Then he set beside him two-handled jars of oil and honey
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.171#leaning them against the bier, and drove four horses with strong necks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.172#swiftly aloft the pyre with loud lamentation. And there were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.173#nine dogs of the table that had belonged to the lord Patroklos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.174#Of these he cut the throats of two, and set them on the pyre;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.175#and so also killed twelve noble sons of the great-hearted Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.176#with the stroke of bronze, and evil were the thoughts in his heart against them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.177#and let loose the iron fury of the fire to feed on them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.178#Then he groaned, and called by name on his beloved companion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.179#'Good-bye, Patroklos. I hail you even in the house of the death god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.180#For all that I promised you in time past I am accomplishing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.181#Here are twelve noble sons of the great-hearted Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.182#whom the fire feeds on, all, as it feeds on you. But I will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.183#give Hektor, Priam's son, to the fire, but the dogs, to feast on.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.184#So he spoke his threat. But the dogs did not deal with Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.185#for Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus, drove the dogs back from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.186#by day and night, and anointed him with rosy immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.187#oil, so Achilleus, when he dragged him about, might not tear him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.188#And Phoibos Apollo brought down a darkening mist about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.189#from the sky to the plain, and covered with it all the space that was taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.190#by the dead man, to keep the force of the sum from coming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.191#first, and wither his body away by limbs and sinews.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.192#But the pyre of dead Patroklos would not light. Then swift-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.193#brilliant Achilleus thought of one more thing that he must do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.194#He stood apart from the pyre and made his prayer to the two winds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.195#Boreas and Zephyros, north wind and west, and promised them splendid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.196#offerings, and much outpouring from a golden goblet entreated them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.197#to come, so that the bodies might with best speed burn in the fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.198#and the timber burst into flame. And Iris, hearing his prayer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.199#went swiftly as messenger to the winds for him. Now the winds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.200#assembled within the house of storm-blowing Zephyros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.201#were taking part in a feast, and Iris paused in her running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.202#and stood on the stone doorsill; but they, when their eyes saw her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.203#sprang to their feet, and each one asked her to sit beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.204#But she refused to be seated and spoke her word to them: 'I must not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.205#sit down. I am going back to the running waters of Ocean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.206#and the Aithiopians' land, where they are making grand sacrifice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.207#to the immortals; there I, too, shall partake of the sacraments.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.208#But Achilleus' prayer is that Boreas and blustering Zephyros
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.209#may come to him, and he promises them splendid offerings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.210#so that you may set ablaze the funeral pyre, whereon lies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.211#Patroklos, with all Achaians mourning about him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.212#She spoke so, and went away, and they with immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.213#clamour rose up, and swept the clouds in confusion before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.214#They came with a sudden blast upon the sea, and the waves rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.215#under the whistling wind. They came to the generous Troad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.216#and hit the pyre, and a huge inhuman blaze rose, roaring.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.217#Nightlong they piled the flames on the funeral pyre together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.218#and blew with a screaming blast, and nightlong swift-footed Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.219#from a golden mixing-bowl, with a two-handled goblet in his hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.220#drew the wine and poured it on the ground and drenched the ground with it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.221#and called upon the soul of unhappy Patroklos. And as
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.222#a father mourns as he burns the bones of a son, who was married
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.223#only now, and died to grieve his unhappy parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.224#so Achilleus was mourning as he burned his companion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.225#bones, and dragged himself by the fire in close lamentation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.226#At that time when the dawn star passes across earth, harbinger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.227#of light, and after him dawn of the saffron mantle is scattered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.228#across the sea, the fire died down and the flames were over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.229#The winds took their way back toward home again, crossing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.230#the Thracian water, and it boiled with a moaning swell as they crossed it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.231#The son of Peleus turned aside and away from the burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.232#and lay down exhausted, and sweet sleep rose upon him. But now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.233#they who were with the son of Atreus assembled together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.234#and the sound and murmur of their oncoming wakened Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.235#who straightened himself and sat upright and spoke a word to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.236#'Son of Atreus, and you other greatest of all the Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.237#first put out with gleaming wine the pyre that is burning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.238#all that still has on it the fury of fire; and afterwards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.239#we shall gather up the bones of Patroklos, the son of Menoitios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.240#which we shall easily tell apart, since they are conspicuous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.241#where he lay in the middle of the pyre and the others far from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.242#at the edge burned, the men indiscriminately with the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.243#And let us lay his bones in a golden jar and a double
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.244#fold of fat, until I myself enfold him in Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.245#And I would have you build a grave mound which is not very great
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.246#but such as will be fitting, for now; afterwards, the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.247#can make it broad and high--such of you Achaians as may be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.248#left to survive me here by the benched ships, after I am gone.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.249#So he spoke, and they did as swift-footed Peleion told them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.250#First with gleaming wine they put out the pyre that was burning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.251#as much as was still aflame, and the ashes dropped deep from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.252#Then they gathered up the white bones of their gentle companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.253#weeping, and put them into a golden jar with a double
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.254#fold of fat, and laid it away in his shelter, and covered it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.255#with a thin veil; then laid out the tomb and cast down the holding walls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.256#around the funeral pyre, then heaped the loose earth over them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.257#and piled the tomb, and turned to go away. But Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.258#held the people there, and made them sit down in a wide assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.259#and brought prizes for games out of his ships, cauldrons and tripods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.260#and horses and mules and the powerful high heads of cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.261#and fair-girdled women and grey iron. First of all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.262#he set forth the glorious prizes for speed of foot for the horsemen;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.263#a woman faultless in the work of her hands to lead away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.264#and a tripod with ears and holding twenty-two measures
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.265#for the first prize; and for the second he set forth a six-year-old
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.266#unbroken mare who carried a mule foal within her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.267#Then for the third prize he set forth a splendid unfired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.268#cauldron, which held four measures, with its natural gloss still upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.269#For the fourth place he set out two talents' weight of gold, and for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.270#the fifth place set forth an unfired jar with two handles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.271#He stood upright and spoke his word out among the Argives:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.272#'Son of Atreus and all you other strong-greaved Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.273#these prizes are in the place of games and wait for the horsemen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.274#Now if we Achaians were contending for the sake of some other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.275#hero, I myself should take the first prize away to my shelter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.276#You know how much my horses surpass in their speed all others;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.277#yes, for they are immortal horses, and Poseidon gave them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.278#to Peleus my father, who in turn gave them into my hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.279#But I stay here at the side, and my single-foot horses stay with me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.280#such is the high glory of the charioteer they have lost,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.281#the gentle one, who so many times anointed their manes with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.282#soft olive oil, after he had washed them in shining water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.283#Therefore these two horses stand here and grieve, and their manes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.284#are swept along the ground as they stand with hearts full of sorrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.285#But take, the rest of you, places in the field, whichever Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.286#has confidence in his horses and his compacted chariot.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.287#So spoke the son of Peleus, and the swift riders gathered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.288#Far the first to rise up was the lord of men Eumelos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.289#own son of Admetos, who surpassed in horsemanship. After
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.290#him rose up the son of Tydeus, strong Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.291#and led under the yoke the Trojan horses whom he had taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.292#by force from Aineias, but Aineias himself was saved by Apollo.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.293#After him rose the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.294#the sky-descended, and led beneath the yoke the swift horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.295#Aithe, Agamemnon's mare, and his own Podargos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.296#Echepolos, son of Anchises, gave her to Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.297#as a gift, so as not to have to go with him to windy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.298#but stay where he was and enjoy himself, since Zeus had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.299#great wealth, and he made his home in the wide spaces of Sikyon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.300#This mare, who was straining hard for the race, Menelaos harnessed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.301#Fourth to order his horses with flowing manes was Antilochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.302#the glorious son of Nestor, Neleus' son, the high-hearted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.303#lord, and fast-running horses out of the breed of Pylos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.304#pulled his chariot, and his father standing close beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.305#gave well-intentioned advice to his own good understanding:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.306#'Antilochos, you are young indeed, but Zeus and Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.307#have loved you and taught you horsemanship in all of its aspects.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.308#Therefore there is no great need to instruct you; you yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.309#know well how to double the turning-post. Yet in this race your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.310#should run slowest. Therefore I think your work will be heavy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.311#The horses of these men are faster, but they themselves do not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.312#understand any more than you of the science of racing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.313#Remember then, dear son, to have your mind full of every
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.314#resource of skill, so that the prizes may not elude you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.315#The woodcutter is far better for skill than he is for brute strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.316#It is by skill that the sea captain holds his rapid ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.317#on its course, though torn by winds, over the wine-blue water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.318#By skill charioteer outpasses charioteer. He
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.319#who has put all his confidence in his horses and chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.320#and recklessly makes a turn that is loose one way or another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.321#finds his horses drifting out of the course and does not control them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.322#But the man, though he drive the slower horses, who takes his advantage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.323#keeps his eye always on the post and turns tight, ever watchful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.324#pulled with the ox-hide reins on the course, as in the beginning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.325#and holds his horses steady in hand, and watches the leader.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.326#I will give you a clear mark and you cannot fail to notice it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.327#There is a dry stump standing up from the ground about six feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.328#oak, it may be, or pine, and not rotted away by rain-water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.329#and two white stones are leaned against it, one on either side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.330#at the joining place of the ways, and there is smooth driving around it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.331#Either it is the grave-mark of someone who died long ago,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.332#or was set as a racing goal by men who lived before our time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.333#Now swift-footed brilliant Achilleus has made it the turning-post.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.334#You must drive your chariot and horses so as to hug this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.335#and yourself, in the strong-fabricated chariot, lean over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.336#a little to the left of the course, and as for your right horse, whip him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.337#and urge him along, slackening your hands to give him his full rein,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.338#but make your left-hand horse keep hard against the turning-post
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.339#so that the hub's edge of your fashioned wheel will seem to be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.340#touching it, yet take care not really to brush against it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.341#for, if so, you might damage your horses and break your chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.342#and that will be a thing of joy for the others, and a failure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.343#for you. So, dear son, drive thoughtfully and be watchful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.344#For if you follow the others but get first by the turning-post,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.345#there is none who could sprint to make it up, nor close you, nor pass you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.346#not if the man behind you were driving the great Arion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.347#the swift horse of Adrestos, whose birth is from the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.348#or Laomedon's horses, who were the pride of those raised in this country.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.349#So spoke Nestor the son of Neleus, and turned back to his place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.350#and sat down, having talked to his son of each stage in the contest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.351#Fifth to order his horses with flowing manes was Meriones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.352#They climbed to the chariots and deposited the lots. Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.353#shook them, and the first to fall out was that of Antilochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.354#Nestor's son, and strong Eumelos drew next after him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.355#and after him the son of Atreus, Menelaos the spear-famed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.356#Meriones drew the next lane to drive, and the last for the driving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.357#of horses was drawn by far the best of them all, Diomedes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.358#They stood in line for the start, and Achilleus showed them the turn-post
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.359#far away on the level plain, and beside it he stationed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.360#a judge, Phoinix the godlike, the follower of his father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.361#to mark and remember the running and bring back a true story.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.362#Then all held their whips high-lifted above their horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.363#then struck with the whip thongs and in words urged their horses onward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.364#into speed. Rapidly they made their way over the flat land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.365#and presently were far away from the ships. The dust lifting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.366#clung beneath the horses' chests like cloud or a stormwhirl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.367#Their manes streamed along the blast of the wind, the chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.368#rocking now would dip to the earth who fosters so many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.369#and now again would spring up clear of the ground, and the drivers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.370#stood in the chariots, with the spirit beating in each man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.371#with the strain to win, and each was calling aloud upon his own
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.372#horses, and the horses flew through the dust of the flat land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.373#But as the rapid horses were running the last of the race-course
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.374#back, and toward the grey sea, then the mettle of each began to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.375#show itself, and the field of horses strung out, and before long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.376#out in front was the swift-stepping team of the son of Pheres,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.377#Eumelos, and after him the stallions of Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.378#the Trojan horses, not far behind at all, but close on him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.379#for they seemed forever on the point of climbing his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.380#and the wind of them was hot on the back and on the broad shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.381#of Eumelos. They lowered their heads and flew close after him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.382#And now he might have passed him or run to a doubtful decision,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.383#had not Phoibos Apollo been angry with Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.384#Tydeus' son, and dashed the shining whip from his hands, so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.385#that the tears began to stream from his eyes, for his anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.386#as he watched how the mares of Eumelos drew far ahead of him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.387#while his own horses ran without the whip and were slowed. Yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.388#Athene did not fail to see the foul play of Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.389#on Tydeus' son. She swept in speed to the shepherd of the people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.390#and gave him back his whip, and inspired strength into his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.391#Then in her wrath she went on after the son of Admetos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.392#and she, a goddess, smashed his chariot yoke, and his horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.393#ran on either side of the way, the pole dragged, and Eumelos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.394#himself was sent spinning out beside the wheel of the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.395#so that his elbows were all torn, and his mouth, and his nostrils,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.396#and his forehead was lacerated about the brows, and his eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.397#filled with tears, and the springing voice was held fast within him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.398#Then the son of Tydeus, turning his single-foot horses to pass him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.399#went far out in front of the others, seeing that Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.400#had inspired strength in his horses and to himself gave the glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.401#After him came the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.402#But Antilochos cried out aloud to his father's horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.403#'Come on, you two. Pull, as fast as you can! I am not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.404#trying to make you match your speed with the speed of those others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.405#the horses of Tydeus' valiant son, to whom now Athene
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.406#has granted speed and to their rider has given the glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.407#But make your burst to catch the horses of the son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.408#nor let them leave you behind, for fear Aithe who is female
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.409#may shower you in mockery. Are you falling back, my brave horses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.410#For I will tell you this, and it will be a thing accomplished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.411#There will be no more care for you from the shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.412#Nestor, but he will slaughter you out of hand with the edge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.413#of bronze, if we win the meaner prize because you are unwilling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.414#Keep on close after him and make all the speed you are able.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.415#I myself shall know what to do and contrive it, so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.416#we get by in the narrow place of the way. He will not escape me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.417#So he spoke, and they fearing the angry voice of their master
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.418#ran harder for a little while, and presently after this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.419#battle-stubborn Antilochos saw where the hollow way narrowed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.420#There was a break in the ground where winter water had gathered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.421#and broken out of the road, and made a sunken place all about.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.422#Menelaos shrinking from a collision of chariots steered there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.423#but Antilochos also turned out his single-foot horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.424#from the road, and bore a little way aside, and went after him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.425#and the son of Atreus was frightened and called out aloud to Antilochos:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.426#'Antilochos, this is reckless horsemanship. Hold in your horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.427#The way is narrow here, it will soon be wider for passing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.428#Be careful not to crash your chariot and wreck both of us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.429#So he spoke, but Antilochos drove on all the harder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.430#with a whiplash for greater speed, as if he had never heard him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.431#As far as is the range of a discus swung from the shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.432#and thrown by a stripling who tries out the strength of his young manhood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.433#so far they ran even, but then the mares of Atreides gave way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.434#and fell back, for he of his own will slackened his driving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.435#for fear that in the road the single-foot horses might crash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.436#and overturn the strong-fabricated chariots, and the men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.437#themselves go down in the dust through their hard striving for victory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.438#But Menelaos of the fair hair called to him in anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.439#'Antilochos, there is no other man more cursed than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.440#Damn you. We Achaians lied when we said you had good sense.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.441#Even so, you will not get this prize without having to take oath.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.442#He spoke, and lifted his voice and called aloud to his horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.443#'Never hold back now, never stop, for all your hearts are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.444#sorrowful. The feet of these and their knees will weary
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.445#before yours do, seeing that the youth is gone from those horses.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.446#So he spoke, and they fearing the angry voice of their master
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.447#ran the harder, and soon were close up behind the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.448#Now the Argives who sat in their assembly were watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.449#the horses, and the horses flew through the dust of the flat land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.450#Idomeneus, lord of the Kretans, was first to make out the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.451#for he sat apart from the others assembled, and higher up, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.452#he could see all ways, and from far off he heard Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.453#calling, and knew him, and made out one horse ahead of the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.454#who was conspicuous, all red, except on his forehead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.455#there was a white mark, round, like the full moon. Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.456#rose to his feet upright and spoke his word out to the Argives:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.457#'Friends, who are leaders of the Argives and keep their counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.458#am I the only one who can see the horses, or can you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.459#also? It seems to me there are other horses leading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.460#and I make out another charioteer. The mares of Eumelos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.461#must have come to grief somewhere in the plain, who led on the way out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.462#for those I saw running out in front as they made the turn-post
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.463#I can see no longer anywhere, though I watch and though my eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.464#look everywhere about the plain of Troy. But it must be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.465#that the reins got away from the charioteer, or he could not hold them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.466#well in hand at the goal and failed to double the turn-post.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.467#There I think he must have been thrown out and his chariot broken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.468#and the mares bolted away with the wildness upon their spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.469#But you also stand up and look for yourselves; I cannot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.470#well make out, but it seems to me the man who is leading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.471#is an Aitolian by birth, but lord of the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.472#the son of Tydeus, breaker of horses, strong Diomedes.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.473#Swift Aias, son of Oïleus, spoke shamefully to him in anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.474#'Idomeneus, what was all this windy talk? The light-footed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.475#horses are still far where they sweep over the great plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.476#You are not by so much the youngest among the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.477#nor do the eyes in your head see so much sharper than others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.478#But forever you are windy with your words, and you should not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.479#be a windy speaker. There are others here better than you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.480#The horses who are in front are the same as before, and they are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.481#those of Eumelos, and he stands holding the reins behind them.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.482#The lord of the Kretans answered him to his face in anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.483#'Aias, surpassing in abuse, yet stupid, in all else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.484#you are worst of the Argives with that stubborn mind of yours. Come then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.485#let us put up a wager of a tripod or cauldron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.486#and make Agamemnon, son of Atreus, witness between us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.487#as to which horses lead. And when you pay, you will find out.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.488#So he spoke, and swift Aias, son of Oïleus, was rising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.489#up, angry in turn, to trade hard words with him. And now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.490#the quarrel between the two of them would have gone still further,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.491#had not Achilleus himself risen up and spoken between them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.492#'No longer now, Aias and Idomeneus, continue
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.493#to exchange this bitter and evil talk. It is not becoming.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.494#If another acted so, you yourselves would be angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.495#Rather sit down again among those assembled and watch for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.496#the horses, and they in their strain for victory will before long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.497#be here. Then you each can see for himself, and learn which
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.498#of the Argives horses have run first and which have run second.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.499#He spoke, and now Tydeus' son in his rapid course was close on them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.500#and he lashed them always with the whipstroke from the shoulder. His horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.501#still lifted their feet light and high as they made their swift passage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.502#Dust flying splashed always the charioteer, and the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.503#that was overlaid with gold and tin still rolled hard after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.504#the flying feet of the horses, and in their wake there was not much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.505#trace from the running rims of the wheels left in the thin dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.506#The horses came in running hard. Diomedes stopped them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.507#in the middle of where the men were assembled, with the dense sweat starting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.508#and dripping to the ground from neck and chest of his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.509#He himself vaulted down to the ground from his shining chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.510#and leaned his whip against the yoke. Nor did strong Sthenelos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.511#delay, but made haste to take up the prizes, and gave the woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.512#to his high-hearted companions to lead away and the tripod
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.513#with ears to carry, while Diomedes set free the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.514#After him Neleian Antilochos drove in his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.515#having passed Menelaos, not by speed but by taking advantage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.516#But even so Menelaos held his fast horses close on him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.517#As far as from the wheel stands the horse who is straining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.518#to pull his master with the chariot over the flat land;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.519#the extreme hairs in the tail of the horse brush against the running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.520#rim of the wheel, and he courses very close, there is not much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.521#space between as he runs a great way over the flat land;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.522#by so much Menelaos was left behind by Antilochos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.523#the blameless. At first he was left behind the length of a discus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.524#thrown, but was overhauling him fast, with Aithe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.525#of the fair mane, Agamemnon's mare, putting on a strong burst.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.526#If both of them had had to run the course any further,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.527#Menelaos would have passed him, and there could have been no argumen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.528#But Meriones, strong henchman of Idomeneus, was left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.529#a spearcast's length behind by glorious Menelaos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.530#For his horses with splendid manes were slowest of all, and likewise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.531#he himself was of least account for the racing of chariots.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.532#Last and behind them all came in the son of Admetos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.533#dragging his fine chariot and driving his horses before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.534#and seeing this, brilliant swift-footed Achilleus took pity upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.535#and stood forth among the Argives and spoke to them all in winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.536#'The best man is driving his single-foot horses in last.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.537#Come then, we must give some kind of prize, and well he deserves it;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.538#second prize; let first place go to the son of Tydeus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.539#So he spoke, and all gave approval to what he was urging,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.540#and he would have given him the horse, since all the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.541#approved, had not Antilochos, son of great-hearted Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.542#stood up to answer Peleid Achilleus, and argue:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.543#'Achilleus, I shall be very angry with you if you accomplish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.544#what you have said. You mean to take my prize away from me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.545#with the thought in mind that his chariot fouled and his running horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.546#but he himself is great. He should have prayed to the immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.547#gods. That is why he came in last of all in the running.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.548#But if you are sorry for him and he is dear to your liking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.549#there is abundant gold in your shelter, and there is bronze there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.550#and animals, and there are handmaidens and single-foot horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.551#You can take from these, and give him afterwards a prize still greater
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.552#than mine, or now at once, and have the Achaians applaud you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.553#But the mare I will not give up, and the man who wants her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.554#must fight me for her with his hands before he can take her.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.555#So he spoke, but brilliant swift-footed Achilleus, favouring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.556#Antilochos, smiled, since he was his beloved companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.557#and answered him and addressed him in winged words: 'Antilochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.558#if you would have me bring some other thing out of my dwelling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.559#as special gift for Eumelos, then for your sake I will do it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.560#I will give him that corselet I stripped from Asteropaios;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.561#it is bronze, but there is an overlay circled about it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.562#in shining tin. It will be a gift that will mean much to him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.563#He spoke, and told Automedon, his beloved companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.564#to bring it out of the shelter, and he went away, and brought it back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.565#and put it in Eumelos' hands. And he accepted it joyfully.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.566#But now Menelaos, heart full of bitterness, stood up among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.567#in relentless anger against Antilochos, and the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.568#put the staff into his hand and gave the call for the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.569#to be silent. And he stood forth, a man like a god, and spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.570#'Antilochos, you had good sense once. See what you have done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.571#You have defiled my horsemanship, you have fouled my horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.572#by throwing your horses in their way, though yours were far slower.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.573#Come then, o leaders of the Argives and their men of counsel:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.574#judge between the two of us now; and without favour;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.575#so that no man of the bronze-armoured Achaians shall say of us:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.576#"Menelaos using lies and force against Antilochos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.577#went off with the mare he won, for his horses were far slower
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.578#but he himself was greater in power and degree." Or rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.579#come, I myself will give the judgment, and I think no other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.580#man of the Danaans can call it in question, for it will be right.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.581#Antilochos, beloved of Zeus, come here. This is justice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.582#Stand in front of your horses and chariot, and in your hand take
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.583#up the narrow whip with which you drove them before, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.584#lay your hand on the horses and swear by him who encircles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.585#the earth and shakes it you used no guile to baffle my chariot.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.586#Then in turn Antilochos of the good counsel answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.587#'Enough now. For I, my lord Menelaos, am younger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.588#by far than you, and you are the greater and go before me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.589#You know how greedy transgressions flower in a young man, seeing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.590#that his mind is the more active but his judgment is lightweight. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.591#I would have your heart be patient with me. I myself will give you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.592#the mare I won, and if there were something still greater you asked for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.593#out of my house, I should still be willing at once to give it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.594#to you, beloved of Zeus, rather than all my days
