urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.598#was softened, as with dew the ears of corn are softened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.599#in the standing corn growth of a shuddering field. For you also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.600#the heart, o Menelaos, was thus softened within you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.601#He spoke to him aloud and addressed him in winged words: 'Antilochos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.602#I myself, who was angry, now will give way before you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.603#since you were not formerly loose-minded or vain. It is only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.604#that this time your youth got the better of your intelligence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.605#Beware another time of playing tricks on your betters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.606#Any other man of the Achaians might not have appeased me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.607#But you have suffered much for me, and done much hard work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.608#and your noble father, too, and your brother for my sake. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.609#I will be ruled by your supplication. I will even give you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.610#the mare, though she is mine, so that these men too may be witnesses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.611#that the heart is never arrogant nor stubborn within me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.612#He spoke, and gave Antilochos' companion, Noëmon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.613#the mare to lead away, and himself took the glittering cauldron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.614#Fourth, in the order he had driven, Meriones took up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.615#the two talents' weight of gold. But the fifth prize, the two-handled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.616#jar, was left. Achilleus carried it through the assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.617#of the Argives, and gave it to Nestor, and stood by and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.618#'This, aged sir, is yours to lay away as a treasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.619#in memory of the burial of Patroklos; since never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.620#again will you see him among the Argives. I give you this prize
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.621#for the giving; since never again will you fight with your fists nor wrestle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.622#nor enter again the field for the spear-throwing, nor race
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.623#on your feet; since now the hardship of old age is upon you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.624#He spoke, and put it in the hands of Nestor, who took it
