urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.657#He stood upright and spoke his word out among the Argives:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.658#'Son of Atreus, and all you other strong-greaved-Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.659#we invite two men, the best among you, to contend for these prizes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.660#with their hands up for the blows of boxing. He whom Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.661#grants to outlast the other, and all the Achaians witness it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.662#let him lead away the hard-working jenny to his own shelter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.663#The beaten man shall take away the two-handled goblet.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:23.664#He spoke, and a man huge and powerful, well skilled in boxing,
