urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.58#But Hektor was mortal, and suckled at the breast of a woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.59#while Achilleus is the child of a goddess, one whom I myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.60#nourished and brought up and gave her as bride to her husband
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.61#Peleus, one dear to the hearts of the immortals, for you all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.62#went, you gods, to the wedding; and you too feasted among them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.63#and held your lyre, o friend of the evil, faithless forever.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.64#In turn Zeus who gathers the clouds spoke to her in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.65#'Hera, be not utterly angry with the gods, for there shall not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.66#be the same pride of place given both. Yet Hektor also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.67#was loved by the gods, best of all the mortals in Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.68#I loved him too. He never failed of gifts to my liking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.69#Never yet has my altar gone without fair sacrifice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.70#the smoke and the savour of it, since that is our portion of honour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.71#The stealing of him we will dismiss, for it is not possible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.72#to take bold Hektor secretly from Achilleus, since always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.73#his mother is near him night and day; but it would be better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.74#if one of the gods would summon Thetis here to my presence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.75#so that I can say a close word to her, and see that Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.76#is given gifts by Priam and gives back the body of Hektor.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.77#He spoke, and Iris storm-footed sprang away with the message,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.78#and at a point between Samos and Imbros of the high cliffs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.79#plunged in the dark water, and the sea crashed moaning about her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.80#She plummeted to the sea floor like a lead weight which, mounted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.81#along the horn of an ox who ranges the fields, goes downward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.82#and takes death with it to the raw-ravening fish. She found Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.83#inside the hollow of her cave, and gathered about her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.84#sat the rest of the sea goddesses, and she in their midst
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.85#was mourning the death of her blameless son, who so soon was destined
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.86#to die in Troy of the rich soil, far from the land of his fathers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.87#Iris the swift-foot came close beside her and spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.88#'Rise, Thetis. Zeus whose purposes are infinite calls you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.89#In turn Thetis the goddess, the silver-footed, answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.90#'What does he, the great god, want with me? I feel shamefast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.91#to mingle with the immortals, and my heart is confused with sorrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.92#But I will go. No word shall be in vain, if he says it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.93#So she spoke, and shining among the divinities took up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.94#her black veil, and there is no darker garment. She went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.95#on her way, and in front of her rapid wind-footed Iris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.96#guided her, and the wave of the water opened about them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.97#They stepped out on the dry land and swept to the sky. There they found
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.98#the son of Kronos of the wide brows, and gathered about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.99#sat all the rest of the gods, the blessed, who live forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.100#She sat down beside Zeus father, and Athene made a place for her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.101#Hera put into her hand a beautiful golden goblet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.102#and spoke to her to comfort her, and Thetis accepting drank from it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.103#The father of gods and men began the discourse among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.104#'You have come to Olympos, divine Thetis, for all your sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.105#with an unforgotten grief in your heart. I myself know this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.106#But even so I will tell you why I summoned you hither.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.107#For nine days there has risen a quarrel among the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.108#over the body of Hektor, and Achilleus, stormer of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.109#They keep urging clear-sighted Argeïphontes to steal the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.110#but I still put upon Achilleus the honour that he has, guarding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.111#your reverence and your love for me into time afterwards. Go then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.112#in all speed to the encampment and give to your son this message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.113#tell him that the gods frown upon him, that beyond all other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.114#immortals I myself am angered that in his heart's madness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.115#he holds Hektor beside the curved ships and did not give him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.116#back. Perhaps in fear of me he will give back Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.117#Then I will send Iris to Priam of the great heart, with an order
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.118#to ransom his dear son, going down to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.119#and bringing gifts to Achilleus which might soften his anger.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.120#He spoke and the goddess silver-foot Thetis did not disobey him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.121#but descended in a flash of speed from the peaks of Olympos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.122#and made her way to the shelter of her son, and there found him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.123#in close lamentation, and his beloved companions about him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.124#were busy at their work and made ready the morning meal, and there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.125#stood a great fleecy sheep being sacrificed in the shelter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.126#His honoured mother came close to him and sat down beside him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.127#and stroked him with her hand and called him by name and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.128#'My child, how long will you go on eating your heart out in sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.129#and lamentation, and remember neither your food nor going
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.130#to bed? It is a good thing even to lie with a woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.131#in love. For you will not be with me long, but already
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.132#death and powerful destiny stand closely above you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.133#But listen hard to me, for I come from Zeus with a message.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.134#He says that the gods frown upon you, that beyond all other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.135#immortals he himself is angered that in your heart's madness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.136#you hold Hektor beside the curved ships and did not redeem him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.137#Come, then, give him up and accept ransom for the body.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.138#Then in turn Achilleus of the swift feet answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.139#'So be it. He can bring the ransom and take off the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.140#if the Olympian himself so urgently bids it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.141#So, where the ships were drawn together, the son and his mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.142#conversed at long length in winged words. But the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.143#stirred Iris to go down to sacred Ilion, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.144#'Go forth, Iris the swift, leaving your place on Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.145#and go to Priam of the great heart within Ilion, tell him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.146#to ransom his dear son, going down to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.147#and bringing gifts to Achilleus which might soften his anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.148#alone, let no other man of the Trojans go with him, but only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.149#let one elder herald attend him, one who can manage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.150#the mules and the easily running wagon, so he can carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.151#the dead man, whom great Achilleus slew, back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.152#Let death not be a thought in his heart, let him have no fear;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.153#such an escort shall I send to guide him, Argeïphontes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.154#who shall lead him until he brings him to Achilleus. And after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.155#he has brought him inside the shelter of Achilleus, neither
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.156#will the man himself kill him, but will hold back all the others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.157#for he is no witless man nor unwatchful, nor is he wicked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.158#but will in all kindness spare one who comes to him as a suppliant.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.159#He spoke, and storm-footed Iris swept away with the message
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.160#and came to the house of Priam. There she found outcry and mourning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.161#The sons sitting around their father inside the courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.162#made their clothes sodden with their tears, and among them the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.163#sat veiled, beaten into his mantle. Dung lay thick
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.164#on the head and neck of the aged man, for he had been rolling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.165#in it, he had gathered and smeared it on with his hands. And his daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.166#all up and down the house and the wives of his sons were mourning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.167#as they remembered all those men in their numbers and valour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.168#who lay dead, their lives perished at the hands of the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.169#The messenger of Zeus stood beside Priam and spoke to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.170#in a small voice, and yet the shivers took hold of his body:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.171#'Take heart, Priam, son of Dardanos, do not be frightened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.172#I come to you not eyeing you with evil intention
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.173#but with the purpose of good toward you. I am a messenger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.174#of Zeus, who far away cares much for you and is pitiful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.175#The Olympian orders you to ransom Hektor the brilliant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.176#to bring gifts to Achilleus which may soften his anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.177#alone, let no other man of the Trojans go with you, but only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.178#let one elder herald attend you, one who can manage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.179#the mules and the easily running wagon, so he can carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.180#the dead man, whom great Achilleus slew, back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.181#Let death not be a thought in your heart, you need have no fear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.182#such an escort shall go with you to guide you, Argeïphontes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.183#who will lead you till he brings you to Achilleus. And after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.184#he has brought you inside the shelter of Achilleus, neither
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.185#will the man himself kill you but will hold back all the others;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.186#for he is no witless man nor unwatchful, nor is he wicked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.187#but will in all kindness spare one who comes to him as a suppliant.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.188#So Iris the swift-footed spoke and went away from him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.189#Thereupon he ordered his sons to make ready the easily rolling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.190#mule wagon, and to fasten upon it the carrying basket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.191#He himself went into the storeroom, which was fragrant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.192#and of cedar, and high-ceilinged, with many bright treasures inside it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.193#He called out to Hekabe his wife, and said to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.194#'Dear wife, a messenger came to me from Zeus on Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.195#that I must go to the ships of the Achaians and ransom my dear son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.196#bringing gifts to Achilleus which may soften his anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.197#Come then, tell me. What does it seem best to your own mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.198#for me to do? My heart, my strength are terribly urgent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.199#that I go there to the ships within the wide army of the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.200#So he spoke, and his wife cried out aloud, and answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.201#'Ah me, where has that wisdom gone for which you were famous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.202#in time before, among outlanders and those you rule over?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.203#How can you wish to go alone to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.204#before the eyes of a man who has slaughtered in such numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.205#such brave sons of yours? The heart in you is iron. For if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.206#he has you within his grasp and lays eyes upon you, that man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.207#who is savage and not to be trusted will not take pity upon you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.208#nor have respect for your rights. Let us sit apart in our palace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.209#now, and weep for Hektor, and the way at the first strong Destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.210#spun with his life line when he was born, when I gave birth to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.211#that the dogs with their shifting feet should feed on him, far from his parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.212#gone down before a stronger man; I wish I could set teeth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.213#in the middle of his liver and eat it. That would be vengeance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.214#for what he did to my son; for he slew him when he was no coward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.215#but standing before the men of Troy and the deep-girdled women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.216#of Troy, with no thought in his mind of flight or withdrawal.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.217#In turn the aged Priam, the godlike, answered her saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.218#'Do not hold me back when I would be going, neither yourself be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.219#a bird of bad omen in my palace. You will not persuade me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.220#If it had been some other who ordered me, one of the mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.221#one of those who are soothsayers, or priests, or diviners,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.222#I might have called it a lie and we might rather have rejected it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.223#But now, for I myself heard the god and looked straight upon her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.224#I am going, and this word shall not be in vain. If it is my destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.225#to die there by the ships of the bronze-armoured Achaians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.226#then I wish that. Achilleus can slay me at once, with my own son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.227#caught in my arms, once I have my fill of mourning above him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.228#He spoke, and lifted back the fair covering of his clothes-chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.229#and from inside took out twelve robes surpassingly lovely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.230#and twelve mantles to be worn single, as many blankets,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.231#as many great white cloaks, also the same number of tunics.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.232#He weighed and carried out ten full talents of gold, and brought forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.233#two shining tripods, and four cauldrons, and brought out a goblet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.234#of surpassing loveliness that the men of Thrace had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.235#when he went to them with a message, but now the old man spared not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.236#even this in his halls, so much was it his heart's desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.237#to ransom back his beloved son. But he drove off the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.238#all from his cloister walks, scolding them with words of revilement:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.239#'Get out, you failures, you disgraces. Have you not also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.240#mourning of your own at home that you come to me with your sorrows?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.241#Is it not enought that Zeus, son of Kronos, has given me sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.242#in losing the best of my sons? You also shall be aware of this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.243#since you will be all the easier for the Achaians to slaughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.244#now he is dead. But, for myself, before my eyes look
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.245#upon this city as it is destroyed and its people are slaughtered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.246#my wish is to go sooner down to the house of the death god.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.247#He spoke, and went after the men with a stick, and they fled outside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.248#before the fury of the old man. He was scolding his children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.249#and cursing Helenos, and Paris, Agathon the brilliant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.250#Pammon and Antiphonos, Polites of the great war cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.251#Deïphobos and Hippothoös and proud Dios. There were nine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.252#sons to whom now the old man gave orders and spoke to them roughly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.253#'Make haste, wicked children, my disgraces. I wish all of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.254#had been killed beside the running ships in the place of Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.255#Ah me, for my evil destiny. I have had the noblest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.256#of sons in Troy, but I say not one of them is left to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.257#Mestor like a god and Troilos whose delight was in horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.258#and Hektor, who was a god among men, for he did not seem like
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.259#one who was child of a mortal man, but of a god. All these
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.260#Ares has killed, and all that are left me are the disgraces,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.261#the liars and the dancers, champions of the chorus, the plunderers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.262#of their own people in their land of lambs and kids. Well then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.263#will you not get my wagon ready and be quick about it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.264#and put all these things on it, so we can get on with our journey?'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.265#So he spoke, and they in terror at the old man's scolding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.266#hauled out the easily running wagon for mules, a fine thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.267#new-fabricated, and fastened the carrying basket upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.268#They took away from its peg the mule yoke made of boxwood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.269#with its massive knob, well fitted with guiding rings, and brought forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.270#the yoke lashing (together with the yoke itself) of nine cubits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.271#and snugged it well into place upon the smooth-polished wagon-pole
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.272#at the foot of the beam, then slipped the ring over the peg, and lashed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.273#with three turns on either side to the knob, and afterwards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.274#fastened it all in order and secured it under a hooked guard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.275#Then they carried out and piled into the smooth-polished mule wagon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.276#all the unnumbered spoils to be given for the head of Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.277#then yoked the powerful-footed mules who pulled in the harness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.278#and whom the Mysians gave once as glorious presents to Priam;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.279#but for Priam they led under the yoke those horses the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.280#himself had kept, and cared for them at his polished manger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.281#Now in the high house the yoking was done for the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.282#and Priam, men both with close counsels in their minds. And now came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.283#Hekabe with sorrowful heart and stood close beside them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.284#carrying in her right hand the kind, sweet wine in a golden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.285#goblet, so that before they went they might pour a drink-offering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.286#She stood in front of the horses, called Priam by name and spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.287#'Here, pour a libation to Zeus father, and pray you may come back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.288#home again from those who hate you, since it seems the spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.289#within you drives you upon the ships, though I would not have it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.290#Make your prayer then to the dark-misted, the son of Kronos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.291#on Ida, who looks out on all the Troad, and ask him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.292#for a bird of omen, a rapid messenger, which to his own mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.293#is dearest of all birds and his strength is the biggest, one seen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.294#on the right, so that once your eyes have rested upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.295#you can trust in him and go to the ships of the fast-mounted Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.296#But if Zeus of the wide brows will not grant you his own messenger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.297#then I, for one, would never urge you on nor advise you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.298#to go to the Argive ships, for all your passion to do it.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.299#Then in answer to her again spoke Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.300#'My lady, I will not disregard this wherein you urge me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.301#It is well to lift hands to Zeus and ask if he will have mercy.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.302#The old man spoke, and told the housekeeper who attended them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.303#to pour unstained water over his hands. She standing beside them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.304#and serving them held the washing-bowl in her hands, and a pitcher.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.305#He washed his hands and took the cup from his wife. He stood up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.306#in the middle of the enclosure, and prayed, and poured the wine out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.307#looking up into the sky, and gave utterance and spoke, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.308#'Father Zeus, watching over us from Ida, most high, most honoured:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.309#grant that I come to Achilleus for love and pity; but send me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.310#a bird of omen, a rapid messenger which to your own mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.311#is dearest of all birds and his strength is biggest, one seen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.312#on the right, so that once my eyes have rested upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.313#I may trust in him and go to the ships of the fast-mounted Danaans.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.314#So he spoke in prayer, and Zeus of the counsels heard him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.315#Straightway he sent down the most lordly of birds, an eagle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.316#the dark one, the marauder, called as well the black eagle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.317#And as big as is the build of the door to a towering chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.318#in the house of a rich man, strongly fitted with bars, of such size
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.319#was the spread of his wings on either side. He swept through the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.320#appearing on the right hand, and the people looking upon him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.321#were uplifted and the hearts made glad in the breasts of all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.322#Now in urgent haste the old man mounted into his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.323#and drove out through the forecourt and the thundering close. Before him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.324#the mules hauled the wagon on its four wheels, Idaios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.325#the sober-minded driving them, and behind him the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.326#came on as the old man laid the lash upon them and urged them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.327#rapidly through the town, and all his kinsmen were following
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.328#much lamenting, as if he went to his death. When the two men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.329#had gone down through the city, and out, and come to the flat land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.330#the rest of them turned back to go to Ilion, the sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.331#and the sons-in-law. And Zeus of the wide brows failed not to notice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.332#the two as they showed in the plain. He saw the old man and took pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.333#upon him, and spoke directly to his beloved son, Hermes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.334#'Hermes, for to you beyond all other gods it is dearest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.335#to be man's companion, and you listen to whom you will, go now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.336#on your way, and so guide Priam inside the hollow ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.337#of the Achaians, that no man shall see him, none be aware of him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.338#of the other Danaans, till he has come to the son of Peleus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.339#He spoke, nor disobeyed him the courier, Argeïphontes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.340#Immediately he bound upon his feet the fair sandals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.341#golden and immortal, that carried him over the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.342#as over the dry land of the main abreast of the wind's blast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.343#He caught up the staff, with which he mazes the eyes of those mortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.344#whose eyes he would maze, or wakes again the sleepers. Holding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.345#this in his hands, strong Argeïphontes winged his way onward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.346#until he came suddenly to Troy and the Hellespont, and there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.347#walked on, and there took the likeness of a young man, a noble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.348#with beard new grown, which is the most graceful time of young manhood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.349#Now when the two had driven past the great tomb of Ilos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.350#they stayed their mules and horses to water them in the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.351#for by this time darkness had descended on the land; and the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.352#made out Hermes, who was coming toward them at a short distance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.353#He lifted his voice and spoke aloud to Priam: 'Take thought,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.354#son of Dardanos. Here is work for a mind that is careful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.355#I see a man; I think he will presently tear us to pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.356#Come then, let us run away with our horses, or if not, then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.357#clasp his knees and entreat him to have mercy upon us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.358#So he spoke, and the old man's mind was confused, he was badly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.359#frightened, and the hairs stood up all over his gnarled body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.360#and he stood staring, but the kindly god himself coming closer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.361#took the old man's hand, and spoke to him and asked him a question
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.362#'Where, my father, are you thus guiding your mules and horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.363#through the immortal night while other mortals are sleeping?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.364#Have you no fear of the Achaians whose wind is fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.365#who hate you, who are your enemies, and are near? For if one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.366#of these were to see you, how you are conveying so many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.367#treasures through the swift black night, what then could you think of?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.368#You are not young yourself, and he who attends you is aged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.369#for beating off any man who might pick a quarrel with you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.370#But I will do you no harm myself, I will even keep off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.371#another who would. You seem to me like a beloved father.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.372#In answer to him again spoke aged Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.373#'Yes, in truth, dear child, all this is much as you tell me;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.374#yet still there is some god who has held his hand above me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.375#who sent such a wayfarer as you to meet me, an omen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.376#of good, for such you are by your form, your admired beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.377#and the wisdom in your mind. Your parents are fortunate in you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.378#Then in turn answered him the courier Argeïphontes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.379#'Yes, old sir, all this that you said is fair and orderly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.380#But come, tell me this thing and recite it to me accurately.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.381#Can it be you convey these treasures in all their numbers and beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.382#to outland men, so that they can be still kept safe for you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.383#Or are all of you by now abandoning sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.384#in fear, such a one was he who died, the best man among you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.385#your son; who was never wanting when you fought against the Achaians.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.386#In answer to him again spoke aged Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.387#'But who are you, o best of men, and who are your parents?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.388#Since you spoke of my ill-starred son's death, and with honour.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.389#Then in turn answered him the courier Argeïphontes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.390#'You try me out, aged sir. You ask me of glorious Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.391#whom many a time my eyes have seen in the fighting where men win
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.392#glory, as also on that time when he drove back the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.393#on their ships and kept killing them with the stroke of the sharp bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.394#and we stood by and wondered at him; for then Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.395#would not let us fight by reason of his anger at Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.396#For I am Achilleus' henchman, and the same strong-wrought vessel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.397#brought us here; and I am a Myrmidon, and my father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.398#is Polyktor; a man of substance, but aged, as you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.399#He has six sons beside, and I am the seventh, and I shook
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.400#lots with the others, and it was my lot to come on this venture.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.401#But now I have come to the plain away from the ships, for at daybreak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.402#the glancing-eyed Achaians will do battle around the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.403#They chafe from sitting here too long, nor have the Achaians'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.404#kings the strength to hold them back as they break for the fighting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.405#In answer to him again spoke aged Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.406#'If then you are henchman to Peleïd Achilleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.407#come, tell me the entire truth, and whether my son lies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.408#still beside the ships, or whether by now he has been hewn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.409#limb from limb and thrown before the dogs by Achilleus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.410#Then in turn answered him the courier Argeïphontes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.411#'Aged sir, neither have any dogs eaten him, nor have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.412#the birds, but he lies yet beside the ship of Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.413#at the shelters, and as he was; now here is the twelfth dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.414#he has lain there, nor does his flesh decay, nor do worms feed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.415#on him, they who devour men who have fallen in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.416#It is true, Achilleus drags him at random around his beloved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.417#companion's tomb, as dawn on dawn appears, yet he cannot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.418#mutilate him; you yourself can see when you go there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.419#how fresh with dew he lies, and the blood is all washed from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.420#nor is there any corruption, and all the wounds have been closed up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.421#where he was struck, since many drove the bronze in his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.422#So it is that the blessed immortals care for your son, though
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.423#he is nothing but a dead man; because in their hearts they loved him.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.424#He spoke, and the old man was made joyful and answered him, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.425#'My child, surely it is good to give the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.426#their due gifts; because my own son, if ever I had one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.427#never forgot in his halls the gods who live on Olympos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.428#Therefore they remembered him even in death's stage. Come, then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.429#accept at my hands this beautiful drinking-cup, and give me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.430#protection for my body, and with the gods' grace be my escort
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.431#until I make my way to the shelter of the son of Peleus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.432#In turn answered him the courier Argeïphontes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.433#'You try me out, aged sir, for I am young, but you will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.434#persuade me, telling me to accept your gifts when Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.435#does not know. I fear him at heart and have too much reverence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.436#to rob him. Such a thing might be to my sorrow hereafter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.437#But I would be your escort and take good care of you, even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.438#till I came to glorious Argos in a fast ship or following
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.439#on foot, and none would fight you because he despised your escort.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.440#The kind god spoke, and sprang up behind the horses and into
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.441#the chariot, and rapidly caught in his hands the lash and the guide reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.442#and breathed great strength into the mules and horses. Now after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.443#they had got to the fortifications about the ships, and the ditch, there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.444#were sentries, who had just begun to make ready their dinner,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.445#but about these the courier Argeïphontes drifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.446#sleep, on all, and quickly opened the gate, and shoved back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.447#the door-bars, and brought in Priam and the glorious gifts on the wagon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.448#But when they had got to the shelter of Peleus' son: a towering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.449#shelter the Myrmidons had built for their king, hewing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.450#the timbers of pine, and they made a roof of thatch above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.451#shaggy with grass that they had gathered out of the meadows;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.452#and around it made a great courtyard for their king, with hedgepoles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.453#set close together; the gate was secured by a single door-piece
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.454#of pine, and three Achaians could ram it home in its socket
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.455#and three could pull back and open the huge door-bar; three other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.456#Achaians, that is, but Achilleus all by himself could close it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.457#At this time Hermes, the kind god, opened the gate for the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.458#and brought in the glorious gifts for Peleus' son, the swift-footed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.459#and dismounted to the ground from behind the horses, and spoke forth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.460#'Aged sir, I who came to you am a god immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.461#Hermes. My father sent me down to guide and go with you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.462#But now I am going back again, and I will not go in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.463#before the eyes of Achilleus, for it would make others angry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.464#for an immortal god so to face mortal men with favour.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.465#But go you in yourself and clasp the knees of Peleion
