urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.476#with eating and drinking, and the table still stood by. Tall Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.477#came in unseen by the other men and stood close beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.478#and caught the knees of Achilleus in his arms, and kissed the hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.479#that were dangerous and manslaughtering and had killed so many
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.480#of his sons. As when dense disaster closes on one who has murdered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.481#a man in his own land, and he comes to the country of others,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.482#to a man of substance, and wonder seizes on those who behold him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.483#so Achilleus wondered as he looked on Priam, a godlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.484#man, and the rest of them wondered also, and looked at each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.485#But now Priam spoke to him in the words of a suppliant:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.486#'Achilleus like the gods, remember your father, one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.487#is of years like mine, and on the door-sill of sorrowful old age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.488#And they who dwell nearby encompass him and afflict him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.489#nor is there any to defend him against the wrath, the destruction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.490#Yet surely he, when he hears of you and that you are still living,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.491#is gladdened within his heart and all his days he is hopeful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.492#that he will see his beloved son come home from the Troad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.493#But for me, my destiny was evil. I have had the noblest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.494#of sons in Troy, but I say not one of them is left to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.495#Fifty were my sons, when the sons of the Achaians came here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.496#Nineteen were born to me from the womb of a single mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.497#and other women bore the rest in my palace; and of these
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.498#violent Ares broke the strength in the knees of most of them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.499#but one was left me who guarded my city and people, that one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.500#you killed a few days since as he fought in defence of his country,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.501#Hektor; for whose sake I come now to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.502#to win him back from you, and I bring you gifts beyond number.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.503#Honour then the gods, Achilleus, and take pity upon me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.504#remembering your father, yet I am still more pitiful;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.505#I have gone through what no other mortal on earth has gone through;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.506#I put my lips to the hands of the man who has killed my children.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.507#So he spoke, and stirred in the other a passion of grieving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.508#for his own father. He took the old man's hand and pushed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.509#gently away, and the two remembered, as Priam sat huddled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.510#at the feet of Achilleus and wept close for manslaughtering Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.511#and Achilleus wept now for his own father, now again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.512#for Patroklos. The sound of their mourning moved in the house. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.513#when great Achilleus had taken full satisfaction in sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.514#and the passion for it had gone from his mind and body, thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.515#he rose from his chair, and took the old man by the hand, and set him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.516#on his feet again, in pity for the grey head and the grey beard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.517#and spoke to him and addressed him in winged words: 'Ah, unlucky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.518#surely you have had much evil to endure in your spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.519#How could you dare to come alone to the ships of the Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.520#and before my eyes, when I am one who have killed in such numbers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.521#such brave sons of yours? The heart in you is iron. Come, then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.522#and sit down upon this chair, and you and I will even let
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.523#our sorrows lie still in the heart for all our grieving. There is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.524#any advantage to be won from grim lamentation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.525#Such is the way the gods spun life for unfortunate mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.526#that we live in unhappiness, but the gods themselves have no sorrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.527#There are two urns that stand on the door-sill of Zeus. They are unlike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.528#for the gifts they bestow: an urn of evils, an urn of blessings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.529#If Zeus who delights in thunder mingles these and bestows them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.530#on man, he shifts, and moves now in evil, again in good fortune.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.531#But when Zeus bestows from the urn of sorrows, he makes a failure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.532#of man, and the evil hunger drives him over the shining
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.533#earth, and he wanders respected neither of gods nor mortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.534#Such were the shining gifts given by the gods to Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.535#from his birth, who outshone all men beside for his riches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.536#and pride of possession, and was lord over the Myrmidons. Thereto
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.537#the gods bestowed an immortal wife on him, who was mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.538#But even on him the god piled evil also. There was not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.539#any generation of strong sons born to him in his great house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.540#but a single all-untimely child he had, and I give him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.541#no care as he grows old, since far from the land of my fathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.542#I sit here in Troy, and bring nothing but sorrow to you and your children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.543#And you, old sir, we are told you prospered once; for as much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.544#as Lesbos, Makar's hold, confines to the north above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.545#and Phrygia from the north confines, and enormous Hellespont,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.546#of these, old sir, you were lord once in your wealth and your children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.547#But now the Uranian gods brought us, an affliction upon you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.548#forever there is fighting about your city, and men killed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.549#But bear up, nor mourn endlessly in your heart, for there is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.550#anything to be gained from grief for your son; you will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.551#bring him back; sooner you must go through yet another sorrow.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.552#In answer to him again spoke aged Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.553#'Do not, beloved of Zeus, make me sit on a chair while Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.554#lies yet forlorn among the shelters; rather with all speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.555#give him back, so my eyes may behold him, and accept the ransom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.556#we bring you, which is great. You may have joy of it, and go back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.557#to the land of your own fathers, since once you have permitted me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.558#to go on living myself and continue to look on the sunlight.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.559#Then looking darkly at him spoke swift-footed Achilleus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.560#'No longer stir me up, old sir. I myself am minded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.561#to give Hektor back to you. A messenger came to me from Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.562#my mother, she who bore me, the daughter of the sea's ancient.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.563#I know you, Priam, in my heart, and it does not escape me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.564#that some god led you to the running ships of the Achaians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.565#For no mortal would dare come to our encampment, not even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.566#one strong in youth. He could not get by the pickets, he could not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.567#lightly unbar the bolt that secures our gateway. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.568#you must not further make my spirit move in my sorrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.569#for fear, old sir, I might not let you alone in my shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.570#suppliant as you are; and be guilty before the god's orders.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.571#He spoke, and the old man was frightened and did as he told him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.572#The son of Peleus bounded to the door of the house like a lion,
