urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.582#called out to his serving-maids to wash the body and anoint it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.583#all over; but take it first aside, since otherwise Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.584#might see his son and in the heart's sorrow not hold in his anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.585#at the sight, and the deep heart in Achilleus be shaken to anger;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.586#that he might not kill Priam and be guilty before the god's orders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.587#Then when the serving-maids had washed the corpse and anointed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.588#with olive oil, they threw a fair great cloak and a tunic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.589#about him, and Achilleus himself lifted him and laid him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.590#on a litter, and his friends helped him lift it to the smooth-polished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.591#mule wagon. He groaned then, and called by name on his beloved companion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.592#'Be not angry with me, Patroklos, if you discover,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.593#though you be in the house of Hades, that I gave back great Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.594#to his loved father, for the ransom he gave me was not unworthy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.595#I will give you your share of the spoils, as much as is fitting.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.596#So spoke great Achilleus and went back into the shelter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.597#and sat down on the elaborate couch from which he had risen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.598#against the inward wall, and now spoke his word to Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.599#'Your son is given back to you, aged sir, as you asked it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.600#He lies on a bier. When dawn shows you yourself shall see him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.601#as you take him away. Now you and I must remember our supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.602#For even Niobe, she of the lovely tresses, remembered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.603#to eat, whose twelve children were destroyed in her palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.604#six daughters, and six sons in the pride of their youth, whom Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.605#killed with arrows from his silver bow, being angered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.606#with Niobe, and shaft-showering Artemis killed the daughters;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.607#because Niobe likened herself to Leto of the fair colouring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.608#and said Leto had borne only two, she herself had borne many;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.609#but the two, though they were only two, destroyed all those others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.610#Nine days long they lay in their blood, nor was there anyone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.611#to bury them, for the son of Kronos made stones out of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.612#the people; but on the tenth day the Uranian gods buried them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.613#But she remembered to eat when she was worn out with weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.614#And now somewhere among the rocks, in the lonely mountains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.615#in Sipylos, where they say is the resting place of the goddesses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.616#who are nymphs, and dance beside the waters of Acheloios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.617#there, stone still, she broods on the sorrows that the gods gave her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.618#Come then, we also, aged magnificent sir, must remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.619#to eat, and afterwards you may take your beloved son back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.620#to Ilion, and mourn for him; and he will be much lamented.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.621#So spoke fleet Achilleus and sprang to his feet and slaughtered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.622#a gleaming sheep, and his friends skinned it and butchered it fairly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.623#and cut up the meat expertly into small pieces, and spitted them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.624#and roasted all carefully and took off the pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.625#Automedon took the bread and set it out on the table
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.626#in fair baskets, while Achilleus served the meats. And thereon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.627#they put their hands to the good things that lay ready before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.628#But when they had put aside their desire for eating and drinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.629#Priam, son of Dardanos, gazed upon Achilleus, wondering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.630#at his size and beauty, for he seemed like an outright vision
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.631#of gods. Achilleus in turn gazed on Dardanian Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.632#and wondered, as he saw his brave looks and listened to him talking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.633#But when they had taken their fill of gazing one on the other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.634#first of the two to speak was the aged man, Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.635#'Give me, beloved of Zeus, a place to sleep presently, so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.636#we may even go to bed and take the pleasure of sweet sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.637#For my eyes have not closed underneath my lids since that time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.638#when my son lost his life beneath your hands, but always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.639#I have been grieving and brooding over my numberless sorrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.640#and wallowed in the muck about my courtyard's enclosure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.641#Now I have tasted food again and have let the gleaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.642#wine go down my throat. Before, I had tasted nothing.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.643#He spoke, and Achilleus ordered his serving-maids and companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.644#to make a bed in the porch's shelter and to lay upon it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.645#fine underbedding of purple, and spread blankets above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.646#and fleecy robes to be an over-all covering. The maid-servants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.647#went forth from the main house, and in their hands held torches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.648#and set to work, and presently had two beds made. Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.649#of the swift feet now looked at Priam and said, sarcastic:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.650#'Sleep outside, aged sir and good friend, for fear some Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.651#might come in here on a matter of counsel, since they keep coming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.652#and sitting by me and making plans; as they are supposed to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.653#But if one of these come through the fleeting black night should notice you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.654#he would go straight and tell Agamemnon, shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.655#and there would be delay in the ransoming of the body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.656#But come, tell me this and count off for me exactly
