urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.658#Tell me, so I myself shall stay still and hold back the people.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.659#In answer to him again spoke aged Priam the godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.660#'If you are willing that we accomplish a complete funeral
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.661#for great Hektor, this, Achilleus, is what you could do and give
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.662#me pleasure. For you know surely how we are penned in our city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.663#and wood is far to bring in from the hills, and the Trojans are frightened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.664#badly. Nine days we would keep him in our palace and mourn him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.665#and bury him on the tenth day, and the people feast by him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.666#and on the eleventh day we would make the grave-barrow for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.667#and on the twelfth day fight again; if so we must do.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.668#Then in turn swift-footed brilliant Achilleus answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.669#'Then all this, aged Priam, shall be done as you ask it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.670#I will hold off our attack for as much time as you bid me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.671#So he spoke, and took the aged king by the right hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.672#at the wrist, so that his heart might have no fear. Then these two,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.673#Priam and the herald who were both men of close counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.674#slept in the place outside the house, in the porch's shelter;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.675#but Achilleus slept in the inward corner of the strong-built shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.676#and at his side lay Briseis of the fair colouring.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.677#Now the rest of the gods and men who were lords of chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.678#slept nightlong, with the easy bondage of slumber upon them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.679#only sleep had not caught Hermes the kind god, who pondered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.680#now in his heart the problem of how to escort King Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.681#from the ships and not be seen by the devoted gate-wardens.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.682#He stood above his head and spoke a word to him, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.683#'Aged sir, you can have no thought of evil from the way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.684#you sleep still among your enemies now Achilleus has left you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.685#unharmed. You have ransomed now your dear son and given much for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.686#But the sons you left behind would give three times as much ransom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.687#for you, who are alive, were Atreus' son Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.688#to recognize you, and all the other Achaians learn of you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.689#He spoke, and the old man was afraid, and wakened his herald,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.690#and lightly Hermes harnessed for them the mules and the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.691#and himself drove them through the encampment. And no man knew of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.692#But when they came to the crossing-place of the fair-running river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.693#of whirling Xanthos, a stream whose father was Zeus the immortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.694#there Hermes left them and went away to the height of Olympos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.695#and dawn, she of the yellow robe, scattered over all earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.696#and they drove their horses on to the city with lamentation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.697#and clamour, while the mules drew the body. Nor was any other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.698#aware of them at the first, no man, no fair-girdled woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.699#only Kassandra, a girl like Aphrodite the golden,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.700#who had gone up to the height of the Pergamos. She saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.701#her dear father standing in the chariot, his herald and crier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.702#with him. She saw Hektor drawn by the mules on a litter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.703#She cried out then in sorrow and spoke to the entire city:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.704#'Come, men of Troy and Trojan women; look upon Hektor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.705#if ever before you were joyful when you saw him come back living
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.706#from battle; for he was a great joy to his city, and all his people.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.707#She spoke, and there was no man left there in all the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.708#nor woman, but all were held in sorrow passing endurance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.709#They met Priam beside the gates as he brought the dead in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.710#First among them were Hektor's wife and his honoured mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.711#who tore their hair, and ran up beside the smooth-rolling wagon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.712#and touched his head. And the multitude, wailing, stood there about them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.713#And now and there in front of the gates they would have lamented
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.714#all day till the sun went down and let fall their tears for Hektor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.715#except that the old man spoke from the chariot to his people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.716#'Give me way to get through with my mules; then afterwards
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.717#you may sate yourselves with mourning, when I have him inside the palace.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.718#So he spoke, and they stood apart and made way for the wagon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.719#And when they had brought him inside the renowned house, they laid him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.720#then on a carved bed, and seated beside him the singers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.721#who were to lead the melody in the dirge, and the singers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.722#chanted the song of sorrow, and the women were mourning beside them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.723#Andromache of the white arms led the lamentation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.724#of the women, and held in her arms the head of manslaughtering Hektor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.725#'My husband, you were lost young from life, and have left me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.726#a widow in your house, and the boy is only a baby
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.727#who was born to you and me, the unhappy. I think he will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.728#come of age, for before then head to heel this city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.729#will be sacked, for you, its defender, are gone, you who guarded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.730#the city, and the grave wives, and the innocent children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.731#wives who before long must go away in the hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.732#and among them I shall also go, and you, my child, follow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.733#where I go, and there do much hard work that is unworthy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.734#of you, drudgery for a hard master; or else some Achaian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.735#will take you by hand and hurl you from the tower into horrible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.736#death, in anger because Hektor once killed his brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.737#or his father, or his son; there were so many Achaians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.738#whose teeth bit the vast earth, beaten down by the hands of Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.739#Your father was no merciful man in the horror of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.740#Therefore your people are grieving for you all through their city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.741#Hektor, and you left for your parents mourning and sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.742#beyond words, but for me passing all others is left the bitterness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.743#and the pain, for you did not die in bed, and stretch your arms to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.744#nor tell me some last intimate word that I could remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.745#always, all the nights and days of my weeping for you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.746#So she spoke in tears, and the women were mourning about her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.747#Now Hekabe led out the thronging chant of their sorrow:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.748#'Hektor, of all my sons the dearest by far to my spirit;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.749#while you still lived for me you were dear to the gods, and even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.750#in the stage of death they cared about you still. There were others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.751#of my sons whom at times swift-footed Achilleus captured,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.752#and he would sell them as slaves far across the unresting salt water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.753#into Samos, and Imbros, and Lemnos in the gloom of the mists. You,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.754#when he had taken your life with the thin edge of the bronze sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.755#he dragged again and again around his beloved companion's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.756#tomb, Patroklos', whom you killed, but even so did not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.757#bring him back to life. Now you lie in the palace, handsome
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.758#and fresh with dew, in the likeness of one whom he of the silver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.759#bow, Apollo, has attacked and killed with his gentle arrows.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.760#So she spoke, in tears, and wakened the endless mourning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.761#Third and last Helen led the song of sorrow among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.762#'Hektor, of all my lord's brothers dearest by far to my spirit:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.763#my husband is Alexandros, like an immortal, who brought me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.764#here to Troy; and I should have died before I came with him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.765#and here now is the twentieth year upon me since I came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.766#from the place where I was, forsaking the land of my fathers. In this time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.767#I have never heard a harsh saying from you, nor an insult.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.768#No, but when another, one of my lord's brothers or sisters, a fair-robed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.769#wife of some brother, would say a harsh word to me in the palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.770#or my lord's mother--but his father was gentle always, a father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.771#indeed--then you would speak and put them off and restrain them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.772#by your own gentleness of heart and your gentle words. Therefore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.773#I mourn for you in sorrow of heart and mourn myself also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.774#and my ill luck. There was no other in all the wide Troad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.775#who was kind to me, and my friend; all others shrank when they saw me.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.776#So she spoke in tears, and the vast populace grieved with her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.777#Now Priam the aged king spoke forth his word to his people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.778#'Now, men of Troy, bring timber into the city, and let not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.779#your hearts fear a close ambush of the Argives. Achilleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.780#promised me, as he sent me on my way from the black ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.781#that none should do us injury until the twelfth dawn comes.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.782#He spoke, and they harnessed to the wagons their mules and their oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.783#and presently were gathered in front of the city. Nine days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.784#they spent bringing in an endless supply of timber. But when
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.785#the tenth dawn had shone forth with her light upon mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.786#they carried out bold Hektor, weeping, and set the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.787#aloft a towering pyre for burning. And set fire to it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.788#But when the young dawn showed again with her rosy fingers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.789#the people gathered around the pyre of illustrious Hektor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.790#But when all were gathered to one place and assembled together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.791#first with gleaming wine they put out the pyre that was burning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.792#all where the fury of the fire still was in force, and thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.793#the brothers and companions of Hektor gathered the white bones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.794#up, mourning, as the tears swelled and ran down their cheeks. Then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.795#they laid what they had gathered up in a golden casket
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.796#and wrapped this about with soft robes of purple, and presently
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.797#put it away in the hollow of the grave, and over it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.798#piled huge stones laid close together. Lightly and quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.799#they piled up the grave-barrow, and on all sides were set watchmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.800#for fear the strong-greaved Achaians might too soon set upon them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.801#They piled up the grave-barrow and went away, and thereafter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.802#assembled in a fair gathering and held a glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.803#feast within the house of Priam, king under God's hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.wheng:24.804#Such was their burial of Hektor, breaker of horses.